source_text: common foods for the highlanders kaicolo. the frog is not to be confused with the introduced and very common toad (boto) which has become a nuisance in the wet zone. syn. boto (ni viti). dresu, dresuka, dresulaka v. to tear (paper, cloth, sail of a sailboat). kadresu torn. dresulaka v. to tear forcefully.
v., n. noisy heated argument (here likened to the tearing of a coconut husk), fierce
(boxing, rugby).
n . clay suitable for pottery, mud suitable treatment of human hair ;
v. to stress (the importance of something).
(eng. bandage)v. to bandage. ivadreti n. bandage. ssyn. vadreti-taka.

. adj . ripe, ready for eating (usually fruit, including breadfruit). vakadreutaka to ripen fruit (leaving it in sun, or enclosing in bags). veidreu children's game of touch and chase, often played in the water. boi dreudreu smells ripe. fij ian do not necessarily prefer very ripe fruit, and will often reject it if there is any bruise or any insect damage. dreu . (nait.) n. banana. naitasiri was a major producer of bananas for export as organised by the british. after independence this export industry died due to failure of responsible marketing with quality control. dreu ! familiar, informal and friendly form of address between people of nadroga and cakaudrove, often used between men and women, with a smile. macuata people use the more full expression draka dreu! meaning sweet lip s!

adj . futile, ineffectual, ineffective, unsuccessful (person, plan of action, remedy, medicine). something that does not work . applied to a person, dreve suggests someone who cannot do anything right.
the effort is futile, ineffective. drevula n. edible starkly white shellfish, small, round, polinices albumen. syn. (west) tidre.
(medical) a patchy, whitish discoloration of skin .

. n. sea cucumber, bêche-de-mer, of genera holothuria, bohadschia, actinopyga or thelanota spp. most fijians themselves eat only the sandfish dairo, usually raw. this species and other types they sell
all over its body) and dri vula (bohadschia sp.). noting that tiny fish come out from the dri vula, some fij ians believe that this sea cucumber is giving birth to ika sa which later becomes a fairly
and eat. some say the dri vula is mother to the moray-like eel called tunatuna. dri vula is whitish, similar to dairo but much bigger, and has pronounced teats. wai ni dri soup made

and cooked in fresh water for half an hour. (red or bright orange sticky strands are not to be used.) natewa people have traditionally prepared black dri for the tui wailevu, the loaloa is gutted, cleaned, cut into pieces and wrapped in plantain leaves. that is left to rot for four nights. it stinks

it is boiled and then eaten by the tui with great relish. sili dri to gather dri, to dive to collect dri. syn. (nadro.) ki. idiom: volitaki dri n. (slang) prostitute, volitaka dri v. to go around as a prostitute. implication is

a woman ’s private parts may be symbolized by a sea cucumber. literally the reference is to sell (volitaka) sea cucumber. idiom: volitaki kai koso same meaning as above, implying a resemblance of the kai koso shellfish (arca sp.) with a woman ’s private parts.

trade in bêche-de-mer had begun by , boomed in the s but was finished around . european ship s sold in manila for the market in china and the ships returned home with silk, tea and sugar. a minor trade continues today on a modest scale, individual fij ians diving and selling to chinese merchants who export it.

. v. to bounce off, rebound (ball, wood chip), ricochet. idiom: sa dri yani "over to you people", said by a person who finishes telling a story. someone should respond and take over with another yarn , or a response.
. n. waimaro highlanders of colo east on viti levu island, known earlier as fierce black warriors,

loa, black like some dri (sea cucumber, see above) and extremely agile to dart here and there in fighting, as implied in the rebounding suggested by the verb dri (see above). dri thus has double meaning.

adj . plump, fully filled out, as a woman ’s breasts, or the body of a baby or young person. this is thought to be a positive feature. drigi, drigita v. to bump into (people, animals). drigita yani push one's way into the crowd. veidrigiti too crowded in. veidrigidrigi so crowded, people bumping into one another (as of people on dance floor). osodrigi crowded with people moving about.
. adj . bald. ulu drika bald-headed (no hair at all). syn. cou.
. (rewa, colo east) n. or adj . cold (of person feeling it). sa vakadrikai au na cagi. the wind has given me a chill, has chilled me.
adj . smooth, sleek, usually of the skin.
adj . very black, almost a shiny black (of person), like a black (loa) sea cucumber (dri). fijians are
conscious of skin-colour differences among people and often comment on it. fair-skinned

are often favoured. dark-skinned indigenous fijians often originally accepted lightskinned polynesian (and sometimes europeans) as their chieftains and ancestral spirits. however, dri loa has been a proud reference to viti levu highlanders of super-tribe waimaro, feared warriors, darkskinned of melanesian origin. proudly, they consider themselves the “real fijians”, kai viti dina.

loli n. bêche-de-mer species, actinopyga miliaris, of commerical value. dark brown, lighter below, long thin papillae, average cm, depths - meters, found at reefs, sandy lagoons. round, cylindrical body, ball-shaped when disturbed.

n. a certain itchy, fungal affliction of the skin with pimples or blisters, sometimes said to be ringworm. fij ians have believed drimi can come from the wind, from the spirits themselves, or from witchcraft, in which case it can be fatal. e dua e cakava tiko na kemu drimi. someone is causing
drimi illness. natively, virtually all illness was thought to be caused by someone casting a spell
and a few other “fij ian sicknesses” (tauvimate vakaviti) such as raberabe, and sau. some of the problems might be psychogenic. syn. drimu. see baubau.

qala n. a small bird, scarlet robin, petroica multicolor, on fiji’s four largest islands, a red-breasted robin. also found in savai ’i and upolu in samoa. males especially have a starkly red breast with dark head.
. adj . bald. see cou, ulu drika.

. adj . as in mata drisi, having haggard features or complexion, often with bloodshot eyes. this is thought to be from poor life-style, such as excessive drinking, staying up late at night. drisi . n., v. to whistle sharply , as if to attract attention, like the call of the kula, the collared lory, phygis solitarius. in various parts of fiji the kula bird is referred to as the drisi (or) drusi. formerly it was valued for the red feathers, especially by tongans who collected it in fij i, especially for trading to samoa. tongans engaged many fij ians in this effort. driti, dritia . v. to cut off (cloth from a roll of cloth), tear off (leaves of a plant, usually for food or medicine). e dua na isulu driti a length of cloth.
. n. an edible leafy vegetable, amaranthus sp,, named from the action of tearing off the leaves. amaranthus spp. also go by the names of tubua and moca. aboriginal intro. sold at markets.

adj . wide-eyed, as in mata driu. can be natural or by emotion. e driu na matana niu vakaraitaka vua. he/she was wide-eyed when i showed it to him/her. driva, drivata (lau) v. to steal. dau drivadriva habitual crook.
n. a small black edible, salt-water mussel modiola lithophaga.
v. to run away, flee. dro vakayawa run far away. dro vata kei au run away with me. dro mai vei

run to me (words of a popular song). dro vua run to him. idiom: dro bula get out alive, survive. idiom: o sa dro tiko ena loma ni yaloka. you can't get away (just running around in circles), lit. run away inside an egg.

(bible) n. refuge for an escaping person, hiding place, referring to the koro ni drodro of the old testament, cities of refuge for israelites. drodro, drodrova v. to flow, to flow to or over, usually a river, ditch , canal, sweat, some heavy leakage.
flow plentifully.
n. rainbow. lagi sky. idiom: vakasiri drodrolagi very fast, lit. as a rainbow might jump. e vakasiri drodrolagi mai na waqavuka. the aeroplane is coming in fast.
(na lewe ni yago-na) v. to have a muscle cramp . vakadrodro, vakadrodroya v. to cause to flow, usually water or electricity, as in putting in a water conduit, or an electric line.
n. deep soft mud. syn. lolobo. see soso.
v. to escape, run away from (person, thing, a fight). drovaki koya run away from him. sa dro vakai koya. he ran away by himself.

v. to escape, run away with (person, thing). e rau sa veidrotaki they () ran away together, eloped. syn. veicavu. traditionally, most marriages were arranged. lovers by choice have usually had to elope, arranging afterwards for “forgiveness” (bulubulu) by bringing gifts (whale-teeth, mats) to the woman ’s family.
n. current, flow (of liquid), wake of a boat or ship . drodro, drodroga v. to flow with the current (of person or thing). drodro, drodrova v. to flow (of liquid), against or toward.

(or) drogadroga adj . hoarse (of voice). some stories relate that this word gives rise to the name of nadroga province but the place-name existed earlier, inland. droga-oso n. (medical) congested lungs, “flu”, influenza.
n. third finger, ring finger of the human hand. fijians reckon this as the fourth finger na ikava ni qaqaloniligana. syn. idaradara ni mama. mama n . ring.
v . to rise, erect, of penis. syn. drui, bula (in this context).
(eng.) n. drawing (picture). fij ians anciently developed none of the graphic arts except the use of

for designs on barkcloth, and men painting their faces in stark colours, preparatory to war. now there are some gifted graphic artists. idrodroini n. graphic arts. droini, droini-taka (eng.) v. to draw (picture). dau droini n. artist (pictorial).

. raw, not cooked (any food). butadroka undercooked (of any food) and by extension, inexperienced of a person. idiom: droka i wai usually of children, reluctant to get into the water and bathe. idiom: adi droka na bogi young women who are active in the night. droka . fresh, as in wai droka fresh water.
adj ., n. green (colour), usually of vegetation but can be fish, (but not water or the sea),
(uncured) of firewood, timber. modern tendency is to use this word for anything green as perceived by europeans, if it were an ab stract colour defined as part of the colour sprectrum. fijians had
developed the notion of abstract colours as such. their names of colours were always associated with specific obj ects. idiom: mata drokadroka fresh, gleaming face, youthful face, baby-face.

n., adj . almost mature, of coconut, with flesh fully formed but not hard, usually with green-skin husk or very light tan . skin inside the shell is light tan, not yet darkened. it is a good stage if one is eating the meat as an improvised meal. the water is still drinkable, not so laxative as water of the completely mature coconut. drokai may also mean mature but not yet soft-ripe, of a fruit like guava (introduced). syn. kade.

adj . usually said of a child who has not bathed frequently or properly. droku . v. to join in the singing as a back-up to the lead singer, as with a chorus. see camana. dro(k)u . (vanua levu) sated, had enough to eat. syn. mamau. drolo adj . very muddy, especially of watery mud. syn. drodrolu, soso; words based on lobo refer to very sticky mud. the word drola was used for the name of a coastal bay of nacula island in the far west of fiji, and it implies murky water, there caused by brown algae. here a branch of super-tribe vusaratu
and call their chief the tui drola and drola became the name of their tribe. closely related is

such sloshy mud. highlanders using the title tui indicates an earlier close contact with verata and tongan influence. tongans did use viti levu highlanders as mercenary warriors, slaves, and collectors of red kula feathers for trade to samoa. there is a village vaimaro (= waimaro) in vava’u, tonga. drolo, droloka v. to “work”, massage heavily , muscles that are cramped. see dro.
adj . lacking any body hair (vuti-na).
adj . . soggy, water-soaked of overcooked root crops.
adj . . out of tune, of a singing voice.
yellow. also refers to the disease yellow j aundice or yellow of an egg. may be synonymous with dromodromoa.

adj . yellow, or lightly orange-yellow as in dried turmeric (cago ni viti) or the dried mace (= aril, in botanical terms) of nutmeg. dromu, dromuca v. to sink below in water. vakadromuca to push it under water. sa dromu na mata-nisiga the sun has set. ena vula sa dromu during last month, some time last month. idiom: sa dromu

he/she is getting old. lit. his/her sun is setting. idiom: dromu na vula, dromu vata kei na kena kalokalo. lit. the moon sets and its star sets with it, meaning the death of one person can quickly bring on the death of a spouse, close relative or associate.
(ni siga) n. sunset, setting of the sun. dromucaka, dromutaka v. to submerge (something) in a liquid, usually water.

n. bottom end of the yam, a soft part that is eaten rather than being used as planting material. kobe-na, the middle part of the yam is eaten or, for the outside that has skin, may be planted. that is
n. edible white or colourless j ellyfish, the “upside-down jellyfish”, that must be cooked in hot

eaten . this sting in made innocuous by hot water. this is a special food for the chiefs of verata. (blue j ellyfish is to be avoided). drose is also a common food of hawkbill turtles. canu drose gather j ellyfish. cassiopea spp. syn. (kadavu) drodro, (lau) yalove.
hoarse (of voice). syn. droga.
n. pennant, ensign, flag. na drotini ni peritania the british ensign. syn. kuila flag, now usually referring to a national flag.
. "a variety of seaweed, ulva sp ., ulvaceae, giving its name to the province of cakaudrove",
to capell. it is more likely that the cakaudrove name derives from a native species of the ginger family.
. (cakau . & nadro.) n. a native ginger, zingiber sp. in different parts of fij i, different species of

bear this name. one of the main species bearing this name is geanthus cevuga, a tall ginger with fragrant large white flowers used in garlands and to scent coconut oil, a species also called cevuga though that name also may refer to alpinia purpurata.
. n. a type of edible sea-hare.
adj . good looking. drovidrovili very good looking, of a person.

. n. double, twins. drua-i-valu (or, in cakaudrove) drua vesi male twins. drua tabua female twins. drua dadakulaci boy and girl twins. drua-i-tolu triplets. rau drua o seru kei op eti. seru and opeti are twins.

. v. large type of double-hulled ship built in southern lau during the s. the invention was samoan, the carving mostly tongan, and the timber fijian vesi, much of it from kabara or fulaga. the last one was the ratu finau, tui nayau, built at fulaga in -. the rusa i vanua was built at fulanga island and sailed to lakeba island, feet in length, with a deck x feet, six feet from keel
three trips to tonga, returned to cakobau, was feet long by feet wide with mast to feet. crew of men. after cakobau died, it was returned to taveuni and left to rot. very few drua
when british administration became well established.

. duplication or replication of a syllable (tago) in the formation of a word, such as ruarua meaning “both” from the word rua “two”. school-teachers invented this term to help describe fijian grammar while avoiding the use of english words. drua-balavu (or) druadina refers to replications that have two

(tagoirua), as in ilakolako, or three syllables (tagoitolu) as in qiqiqi. if only a single syllable is repeated, as in rorogo, the replication is known as a short one: drualeka. drudru, drudruga v. to slit and remove outer skin with inner bark of shrub, such as mulberry, in production of bark-cloth (masi), wild hibiscus (vau) for fibre, cinnamon bark for quills, and skin of cassava, preparatory to cooking. also to remove bark from plants like qatima, urena lobata, to obtain cordage. drudru na kulina me wa. remove the skin to make cordage. also may refer to skinning of animals.
adj . dull-witted, of a person.
adj . tasteless, off-flavour, of water that is stale, brackish, not clean and fresh, or of the juice of some fruits such as melon, mango, pineapple when they are off-flavour.

n. windpipe of throat, bronchial tube(s). drugudrugu(a) ad. smelly (person, place, thing). drugu, druguta v. to add bass voice(s), chorus, to the singing lead. na idrugu the chorus. druguta! join in ! (the chorus). laga sere to lead off a song.
. to fail, lose (game, fight). vakadruka to defeat. vakadrukai defeated. druka . by extension, idiomatically , to be amazed, astonished, dumbfounded. vakadrukai e na kena levu
at the amount of it. au sa druka ena nomu yaloqaqa. i am astonished by your bravery .
amazing.
adj . stupid, awkward, inept.

harsh loud whistle to catch someone ’s attention. druti, drutia, drutilaka v. pull off leaves of grass, trees, as for making fij i medicines, or pulling out weeds by hand. may also apply to a rope snapping from a forceful pull. often used of children or two women fighting, pulling the hair aggressively. idiom: drutia v . to dash off to escape suddenly .
(nait.) v. to nip, pull our grass or weeds, and may extend to cleaning lawn around house or cleaning a garden.
v. weeding, pulling of weeds by hand, drutilaka if done forcefully .
. one (as a cardinal number). e dua, rua, tolu one, two, three. e dua na drau one hundred. e
one person (a person, some person). e dua ga one only. duadua unique, exceptional, special. duabau (or) dua bulu unique, only one.
. the indefinite article a. e dua na nomu isele? do you have a knife?
. someone. sa lako mai e dua. someone came. dua mada e taki mai! someone pour a drink.

alone as one person. yadua each. vakayadua each one (by him/her/itself). idiom: dua mai keri! “your turn !” (to speak , tell a story, entertain the group). this is said by someone who has just finished telling a yarn.

vakadua ever, once and for all, permanently. sa oti vakadua. it is completely finished. sega vakadua! never ! sega . . . vakadua never. vakacegu vakadua died (polite term). lako vakadua gone permanently, forever. vosa vakadua n. chief justice.
adj . unique, one of a kind. na luvedrau duabau their () only child. syn. duabulu.
adj . unique, single, only one. e dua bulu ga. it is unique. syn. duabau.
adj . unique, exceptional, best.

o! a call to announce one's arrival outside a house, wishing to enter. it should be done from a respectful distance. the response is o i dua! for the visitor to enter. several people inside may add to
adj . strange, different (usually not good), unfamiliar, not the same.
(roman catholic) n . holy trinity. syn. lewe tolu vakalou.
adj . united. vakaduavata-taka v . to unite. dubi, dubia, dubilaka v. to punch with the fist. e dua na idubi n. a punch.
. adj . brave in the sense of standing out, willing to express opinions or fight by onself.

. adj ., n. inflated (balloon, tyre), heaped up, high and full (gravel pile, mountain), swollen, swelled out, protruding (cheeks, stomach , breasts). gusu dudu sullen. sucu dudu protruding breasts (woman). dudu i wai protruding into the water (or sea). ulu dudu protruding brow (usually of a person). na dudu n. the protuberance.
. (rewa) adj ., n . deaf. elswhere the word is usually didivara or didi.
adj . difficult (of person), sullen and uncooperative.
n. or v. rumbling sound (sea, pigeon, human's deep voice). sa dugu mai na domo i seru ni sa yaco

seru's voice deepened as he became a youth. vadugu usually refers to the sound of the sea on the reef. idiom: dugu ga na saqa lala lierally , the empty vessel makes a deep resounding sound, an anglicism
from the english idiom, suggesting that the person who has nothing useful to say makes the most noise.
. (archaic) n. death or severe disability resulting from too close a contact with a chief; magical
a chief, an awesome power mentioned by a. c. reid (tovata, part , p. ), as the probable source of the name of tugua island, in ha’apai, tonga, residence of the sacred tamaha, and part
chief, tu ’i ha’ateiho. mara kapaiwai (the early one) visited the tamaha and revived the connection between tugua and his native island moala.
target_text: of the estate of fale fisi

source_text: . (or) dugudugua adj . somewhat soiled or sullied with age and wear, dusty (house, car, object,
a person, physically). in describing objects, this is not always negative. sa rui dugudugua na nomu vakasama. you have developed a dirty mind.

v. to make formal request for a woman in marriage. this has usually involved the presentation of a whale tooth with ceremony by the family making the proposal, not the prospective husband himself. duguca mai na yalewa. syn. vosaki. dugu, duguna v. to heap up (clothes, gravel, fruit).

particle implying separateness, difference, various, each one, both, individually. era dui dro. they all ran off in different direction. dui tamata yadua e kila na nona itavi. each person knows what he has to do. dui yalona tu na tamata. people have their own different way of thinking. ko viti e dui tu ga na kena turaga. fij i has various chieftains (not only one). seru, op eti, semesa kei na dui watidratou. seru, opeti, semesa and their respective wives. duikaikai people of various different origins (british, chinese, fijian, indian for example). duiroka variously coloured, variegated. dui yaloyalo of a different mind, with different feelings, said of people. idiom: dui tu tu each one located in a separate place. idiom: dui tau tau of individual things, fallen in several disparate places (fruit from a tree, parts of a car from a crash). idiom: dui mate ga ena nona ucu ni vatu. the implication is that each person is ready to die defending his home territory. in fact, practically no fijian tribe has ever lived for any great length of time in any one place. on the basis of ratu sukuna’s research, virtually no tribe continued living in the place (yavutu) where it was formed. nonetheless, a close attachment to the land is quickly formed. here the notion is that when cornered, a fij ian will fight to the death.
adj ., n. difference, different, separate. duidui mai na ka oqo mai vei na ka oqori. this thing is
from that thing. sa duidui o seru. seru is different from all others. na kena duidui the difference
v. to differentiate, discriminate, show prejudice.
adj . having independent, different and divisive ways, non-conformist who is indifferent or opposed to the group norms.
adj . and n. dirty, dirt. sa rui duka na yalomu. you have a dirty mind. it is an anglicism to apply this word to the mind. to earlier fijians, dirt was just physical dirt.
v. to soil, to dirty.
adj . very dirty (but can be cleaned). me kakua ni dukadukali nomu ivakarau. don't develop bad habits. syn. dukaveluvelu.

adj ., n. extremely dirty disgustingly dirty . duki, dukia v. to slap, clap the water making a sound, usually to direct fish into a net or trap . dula! hush ! (affectionate, consoling, for babies, loved ones). after the fact, dula implies that the baby has been quieted. dula, dulaka . v. to extend, raise (hand, arm, weapon, tool). dulaka na ligamu raise up your hand (arm). it is a modernism to say, in literal translation from english, “raise the hand” laveta na ligamu. dula, dulaka . v. to give an order to do something. sa dulaka na turaga ni koro na ka me caka. the village administrator ordered the things to be done.

(archaic) n. fijian nose-flute (bitu vakatagi or bitu ceguvi), now known only in the museum, and in a few coastal areas, unknown in the highlands. fij ians never had any romantic music; that concept is polynesian. ramacake was legendary player on makogai island whose music attracted the women of bau. they looked for him in lomaiviti, and he, being very shy, misdirected them to avoid them finding him. he thought himself ugly, possibly due to leprosy.
n. ear-wax. savata na dule ni daligamu. clean out the wax from your ear. dulu, duluka (vulgar) v. to fornicate, have sexual intercourse. veidulu fornication. syn., cai, caita. see veiyacovi.
n. (archaic) ten bundles of dalo at a formal presentation ceremony. for such occasions,

of the goods used this traditional number system, in this case, so many tens of bundles of dalo. some fij ians consider this to amount to be of the taro tubers, assuming ten in each bundle. in fact, it is approximate. dulumi . n . tree-stump.

. adj . bald-headed. a person with a bald shaved head may be referred to as being tasi dulumi. syn. cou. dumu, dumuka v. to open out (umbrella, boat-sail), also, to pick certain fruit by hand or with a long
to poke tree-fruit (usually poke the fruit-stem) to bring down fruit (breadfruit, mango, kavika , dawa, oranges). the implication is of lifting up and then taking down. me dumu na taunamu let down
(closing it). also applied to opening the shutter windows, hinged at the top, common
n. edible j ellyfish. it is boiled, netrostoma sp. syn. drose. (note that na ivolavosa vakaviti, page , considers dumudumu-kuro distinct from drose and, unlike drose, not eaten.
n. river eel. three main types are the diria (clear-water eel), the badamu (mud eel), and the

(rock eel). there is also a moray eel in the rivers, that is not usually eaten, and has a very nasty bite; see dararikai, above. laki ta duna go catching eels. they are caught by hand, or by handnet, or light fishing line. bait used is a shelled shrimp or tiny fish (its natural food), or guts from another eel ; worms may be used in daytime. with a line, one patiently lets the eel swallow the bait deeply, then pulls it in easily. the eel is subdued by hitting or cutting its tail, not its head, for the tail is the motive force. in catching by hand, the fingers are inserted into the gills, or directly into the mouth, pushing in hard. to attempt to pull out the finger too soon results in a very painful, injured finger. the

are deeply raspy (not like a snake's) and are very effective at removing skin painfully. eels are edible, but in some areas of the mainland it is an aquatic totem, and is not eaten. eels breed in the sea, the young transformed into transparent “glass eels” when they encounter fresh water, become

in colour and, known in english as elvers, they migrate upstream in the rivers, even against forceful currents. (the migration is described by paddy ryan, author of fij i ’s natural heritage.) syn. (west) tuna.
adj . disrespectful, a term not much used.
. v. sit up, straighten up or stand up, make an upward movement. duri mada lai kauta mai na ka
get up and bring that thing here. duri cake! straighten up in a sitting posture, or stand up ! depending on context. duri vakadodonu! stand up straight ! gone duriduri baby who has just learned
(but not walk). duri . v. to set up, as of a fallen fence post, a flagpole, telephone pole, house-post.
v. set it up (bottle fallen over, a club or business that is being established). vakaduria e dua
(anglicism) v. to establish a business.

(ni liga-na) n. elbow. syn. duru ni liga, ilokiloki ni liga. duru-na . n. knee (person, animal). tekiduru v. to kneel. idiom: ucu mai duru unbelievable, tall tale (lit. like a nose growing out of the knee). duru-na . n. vertical post (house, telephone pole), keel (boat). syn. (polyn.) bou. idiom: duruvesi n. key supporter, mainstay (person.) vesi is a “noble” wood.
. prefix or suffix , as in duruliu prefix, durumuri suffix, words invented by language teachers who try to avoid direct usage of english.
n. delicious vegetable, "fiji asparagus", saccharum edule. duruka vulavula white duruka , grows
duruka, grows best on somewhat drier ground, and is prone to rot (due to rain penetrating the "husks"), yields twice a year, around march or april and again in november. the fruits of red duruka

smaller and in texture are drier than white duruka . duruka is perhaps best cooked by grilling over embers, or simmered in coconut cream. also eaten raw, sliced in salads, by resident europeans. dusi, dusimaka v . to point (as with the finger), to indicate, point out. dusi, dusia v. to indicate, point, to point at. dusivaka vei koya na ka me kau mai. indicate to him the thing that is to be brought here. dusia na sala point the way (the path, or figuratively, the way to do something). syn. (west, rewa, kadavu, lau) duci.
n. indicator, indication, instructions, guidelines, suggestions, and by extension, idusidusi ni
index finger (anciently, only a chief might point with the finger). ivola dusidusi n. book or pamphlet of instructions, guidebook, or more simply one may simply say idusidusi.
v. put together (of two or more things, people, ideas) to be as one. can be two adjoining pieces of
to be treated as one, tables placed together vakaduta vata put them together. me rau duta. consider them as one. to match up two.
to compare. ni veidutaitaki na isau ni dovu kei na isau ni yaqona . . . when the price of
is compared to the price of yaqona . . . me veidutataki to match up (two or more things that go together, as sometimes requested in a school exam paper.)
n. wooden "anvil" on which barkcloth is beaten (samu) to j oin the pieces and smooth it out. it is a
sound in some outlying coastal villages. kuveti n. stencil for applying a pattern design on bark-cloth .

(or) tuva n., v. plant(s) used to poison fish, the roots pounded and placed in a cloth-like sac, especially tephrosia sp., pittosporum spp. and derris trifoliata, coastal shrub with pale pink flowers, rich in natural pyrethrum. what has been called duva ni niukini (new guinea duva), introduced, is d . malac censis. the poisoned fish are perfectly edible. they float to the surface. curiously , crustaceans are not

the poison. the poison itself is fatal to human if consumed, as evidenced by a case of a suicide. leaves are also macerated and used to heal wounds, applied externally . vakaduva na wai poison the water (with duva). by extension, duva can refer to black magic: kemu duva sa caka tiko.

against you. modernly, fijians may use dangerous agricultural chemicals (often stolen) to poison fish and prawns that they sell by the side of the road. duva, duvana v. to apply poison deliberately, either to fish (see above) or humans. duvani poisoned, of fish or humans. poison for humans was usually mixed in with yaqona to be drunk by the unsuspecting victim. poisons used included the duva kalou, pittosporum, five species, fish poisons, and in the naitasiri highlands, lobau brugmansia suevolens, poison for humans, these days more commonly known as davui or angel ’s trumpet, introduced shrub closely related to datura, jimson weed, a known intoxicant. also mavu ni toga, again a human poison, antiaris toxicaria, moraceae, a not very common tree
crimson flowers. i have noted it in tailevu, perhaps an introduction via tonga. this taxon

many of the poisons used for centuries in southeast asia. the fiji variety is somewhat less toxic than some of the asian ones. in fiji a poison would only have to disable a person. a club to the head could finish the job.
n. uterus, womb. syn. kato ni gone.

n. fijian medical problem of women when the womb has seemed to descend. this is adjusted manually by an older woman, and is often done while the patient is seated in water. one uses the verb sili for this action, as if bathing. sa tarai na nona duvu. her uterus has been manipulated.
as used in vuniduvu, this refers to a composer of traditional exhibition dances (meke). this is a very

position. people formally request the composer to compose a meke for them. he composes, trains those people, and then transmits it so that it “belongs” to that group. no other people should perform that meke without persmission. the composer is well rewarded. syn. daunivucu.
is pronounced just as the e in the english words end or bell.
. in (or) at (only when the speaker is located at that place). e suva in suva (speaker in suva).
. particle in front of some words that indicate location or direction (sometimes it is written as part of
. particle that may appear in front of numbers, or quantities: e tolu three. e so some. e so tale some more. e vica ? how many?

. particle that may appear in front of some words indicating time: edaidai today. vaka-edaidai current, modern, of these times; e naica ? when? ena bogi at night. ena gauna ni ivalu in time of war. ena noa yesterday. ena mataka ni mataka tomorrow morning. ena mataka tomorrow. again, an official grammarian insists on joining the e with the na. actual custom varies greatly.

. particle in front of pronouns especially when the pronoun is the subj ect of the sentence, or begins the sentence, as in: e ratou = eratou, e ra = era. properly this e should be attached, not separated, according to the modern rules imposed by cabinet decision.
. particle with other meanings, such as concerning, about, for, over, on, with. a. concerning, for.
isau ni kakana angry about the price of food. yabaki tolu ena butako three years (prison) for theft. b. on. rogoca na qito ena walesi listen to the game on the radio (wireless). c. with . laki
ena veivuke ni sikolasivi. go to school with the help of a scholarship. again, fiji ’s official grammarian now joins the e to the na.
(eng.) ethanol, much spoken of as vegetable fuel of the future.
. (lau) v. to squat on one's heels.
. v. to shift without raising (a thing such as a pot on a stove), shift without rising (a person, as when
closer to a food-mat). a duck is thought to walk in this way: sa ece tiko yani na ga. the duck is waddling away.
. (cakau.) v. to sit at rest.
. (cakau.) alone. oi au ece (or) kece. i alone.
we (many). eda kila ni da cala . we (many) know that we are wrong.
we (two people). also kedaru.
we (several), abbrev. tou. also kedatou.
today syn. nikua.
(eng.) n . editor.

(or) e ke here, most properly eke. eke ga right here.
(roman catholic) the roman catholic church.
(or) i keri there (where you are), most properly ekeri.
(eng.) n. hectare (. acres).
adj . disgusting, “yuk”, as in eki na boto mate the dead toad is “yuk”.

(vanua levu) n. woman ’s private parts. syn. tele. the word may be used freely in most of cakaudrove, but not in bua. elei! (vanua levu) interj ection of lament, rej ection or disgust. oilei is the more common word throughout fiji.
n. (eng.) elephant. none in fiji but historically there had been correspondence with u.s. government as to the possible use of elephants as work animals. syn. elef adi.
(eng.) n. hell. eli, elica . v. to combine two or more food ingredients (in a pot). eli, elica . v. to remove (something). elica na buka remove some of the burning firewood. syn, talaca.
(eng.) n. helicopter.
(eng.) amen. syn. ameni.

(or) e na in, or in the, or during, as in ena vula sa oti during last month. ena rua na siga in two days. preferred spelling by official grammarian is ena though many educators disagree very strongly.
tomorrow.

(or) evereli (eng.) n. april. the p is more common in lau, cakaudrove. the v is used more often in tailevu, naitasiri, ra. eqe v. to walk in a lop-sided way, with unequal balance between the two legs. may be due to one or more
they (many) or he/she (of high chief).

(or) ira below, as opposed to e cake, above. this applies to relative height but ira may refer to the west, downwind of the speaker’s location. similarly e cake may refer to an upwind direction or uphill direction.
(or) e ratou they (few), properly eratou.
(interj ection) declining to answer, i am not sure, do not know.
(eng.) ace, as in a deck of cards.
(eng.) n. escort, usually as a guard for people of great importance. esikote-taka to escort, accompany, a dignitary on official mission.
(eng., methodist) formal estimate of financial needs of a local church for the coming year.
and planning is then given as to how these funds can be sourced and what the congregation should be asked to contribute.
(or) e so some, as in mai na veivanua e so, in some countries. used at the beginning of an expression it is perhaps more customary to separate the spelling, as e so na tamata some people.
(eng.) n. extreme unction as last rites for a dying roman catholic.

(eng.) aide-de-camp, formerly serving the governor. may be heard as tikoqe. eu! interjection of pain, or of rej ection, disgust, especially in response to something said, or something offered. as with most expressions, this may be said in j est. one sometimes hears u!
(or) e vei where (as a question).
(eng.) n . april. syn. ep ereli.
v. to grow big, espec. of the body.
n. a seaside tree, hernandia peltata or h . nymphaeifolia, hernandiaceae, the inner bark often used as an abortifacient. (scientific tests on rats indicate no such effect - r.g.)
is no letter f in mainland fijian languages. it is the polynesian equivalent of the fij ian v in

and has been introduced by tongans on the smaller islands, especially in lau. some english or tongan words with f are now sometimes pronounced with that letter. the letter v is sometimes used in place of an f, except for distinctly lauan words or for some adaptions of english words.
(eng.) father, form of address for roman catholic priest.

(lau) treat the hair with lime (lase) as conditioning. “faiba” or “fibre” (eng.) n. fibreglass boat, usually open-topped, operated by an outboard engine. in some places this has replaced the wooden punt and and small cutters used for short trips.

(or) ifaele (eng.) n. file. f ailetaka v. to file, fijians' way of sharpening knives. bush knives (cane knives) are made of soft steel that can be sharpened readily by frequent filing. knife-filing justifies resting between bouts of hard work cutting weeds, grass.
(eng.) n. final (in sports), referring to the last championship game. semi-f ainala semi-finals. can be used as a verb as well as noun.
(lau) v. to sit cross-legged, as done by men.
(lau, from togan f aiva) n. expertise, special skill from experience.
(lau) n. spokesman-protocol officer for lauan chief. the equiv. of matanivanua among mainland fijians. sometimes pronounced vaka.

(tonga) n. spontaneous giving of gifts during dances, or functions of two different groups of people, often a man ’s shirt. may include money slipped into the clothes of dancers, flour sprinkled on their head. syn. tibivuru.
(lau) v. to do, to make, bauan cakava.
. (eng.) n. flour. along with rice and cassava, this is now a main staple starch foods of fij ians,
it is much less nutritious. these introduced starches have been cheaper than traditional root crops and are less perishable. flour is used for many fried breakfast foods.
. (eng., lau) a starch food treated as kakana dina, “true food”, such as taro or yam, cooked in
at meals with a garnish (icoi), or at breakfast with tea. because of the shortage of
starch-foods in the smaller islands of lau, store-bought flour is mixed with grated cassava and coconut as a basic food.

(lau) n. house. traditional lauan houses follow tongan style with rounded ends, rather than appearing strictly rectangular. syn. vale. (west) were, sue. “fale fisi” (tonga) n. the clan ha’a fale fisi, of the tongan royal family, as founded by tapu ’osi, the

lakeba, a waciwaci chief who married sinaitakala i langileka, tu ’i tonga fefine, daughter of th tele’a, tu ’i tonga. the narewadamu are true kailakeba, early chiefs of lakeba, replaced ultimately by the vuanirewa people of the tui nayau who retain a separate but similar affiliation with
a royal wife from the sacred, royal island of tungua in tonga. tui naosara settled on nayau and his two sons were the first vuanirewa.
(eng., lau) n. family.
(eng.) n. funnel. faqa! (interj ection) cheat ! (in playing, usually marbles).
(bib.) n . pharisee.
(lau) n. lauan chiefly serving-bowl especially for kava, the rim inlaid with pearl shell, and
twelve legs instead the the four legs that are more common elsewhere in fij i. the artefact is tongan in concept. vakaf atu (or) vakavatu as an anglicism, may also refer to a very wealthy person.

(rotuma) n . traditional sweet pudding with thick coconut cream, sometimes sold in the public market. the starch basis has been mostly taro, sometimes yam. (yams rarely used in fij ian sweet puddings).
(or) veverueri (eng.) february. fika . (eng., lau) adj . to be smart, clever, adept.

(lau): meca i a f ika ga, or meca qo na f ika ga. literally , “the thing is to think it through”, more figuratively, “(things will be done) by hook or by crook”. fika . (eng.) v . to calculate. fika . (eng.) n . arithmetic, figure.
(eng.) v. to calculate a total (isoqoni) in arithmetic.
subtraction na musumusu. musu e rua sa tolu. five minus two is three.
addition sosoqoni. kei na rua sa vitu. five plus two is seven.
multiplication na vakalevutaki. vakarua sa tini. five times two is ten.

division na wasewase. wase rua sa lima. ten divided by two is five. “fire!” (slang) pron. “faiya!”, go ahead ! begin ! let’s go ! "fifty cents " (eng, slang) a very vulgar taunt, meaning "coward", implying a loose rectum as large as a fifty-cents coin.

(eng.) n. movie film or photographic film. fiu . (lau, tongan “fihu”) n. a type of very fine white woven sleeping mat. fiu . (lau, tongan “fiu”) tired, worn out, done in, fed up. syn. oca. “fix”-taka v. to arrange, to set up, to iron out (a problem), to fix. “fix”, “fix”-taka v. to try to win over a woman, with a desire to make love, arrange intercourse with or for someone. au na qai f ixtaka a dua na nomu. i will get you a partner for making love.
(eng.) n . fox, and may refer to someone cunning like a fox. slang: yalewa f okisi prostitute.
(eng.) v. to assemble in a formal group, “fall in”, of soldiers, or children assembled at school.
(eng.) n. foreman .
. (eng.) n. form (to be filled out). vakalewena na f omu. fill out the form.
. (eng.) n. form, as a class of secondary school that in fiji can extend through form seven, in preparation for possible tertiary education.
(tonga) sinnet fly whisk as used by chieftains.
(eng.) floor. syn. buturara.
a soft ng, as in going, fling. it is not pronounced like the ng in anger. in western viti levu, gwa may replace the ga, as in gwata for gata (snake), or tagwane for tagane (man) in eastern fij i.

source_text: . n. duck. ga ni vatu peregrine falcon, rather rare in fiji. ga loa (or) ga ni viti pacific black duck, common wild duck at rivers and coastal shores. syn. (lau) p ato. idiom: sili vaka ga lit., bathe like a duck, said to a child who takes a quick, superficial bath, not bathing properly. idiom: tamata daku ni ga person who cannot listen or follow instructions. words flow off as water from a duck ’s back, an anglicism. ga . only, just, a particle used with some words to limit them: wale ga only. wale ga oqo just now. o
only you. tiko ga forever, always. in written fijian this particle is often joined to the word that follows it. the expression o iko ga! can have romantic implications.
. v. mouth open, agape, stare, usually with a blank look. ga cake! open your mouth ! (as a dentist

request). dalaga! open your mouth wide (as mother to child, giving medicine). ga balavu remain gaping, doing nothing with a blank stare into space. kakua ni ga balavu! don't gape ! don ’t stare ! (to child). mata gaga face agape. ga calucalu to be at a loose end, idle with nothing much on the mind. igaga n. spout, as of teapot.
. n. guts, intestines. . by extension, equipment, spare parts for motors, engines. syn. iwawa intestines. idiom: ivola gacagaca document, manual.
v. to walk at ease, usually for pleasure, take a pleasure trip. au na gagade tu mai kea. i will be
around over there. vale ni igagade holiday cottage. ilakolako vakagade pleasure trip.
ni igagade ni saravanua tourist spot. gade siga tolu take a three-day trip. syn. gadi. (colo east) gadea.
. (archaic) n. a type of fij ian fighting club.
. brother of one’s mother or husband of father’s sister. see below. syn. momo. gadigadi . n. object of romantic love. igadigadi . n. place to relax and pass the time peacefully .

and gadi n. a type of family relative, man , mother's brother or the husband of one's father's sister. bauans use the term vugo-na. gadre, gadreva v. to desire, want, wish for (anything). au bau gadreva tu meu lako i just wish i could go. na gagadre the desire.
n. palate, extending to the gums. mate ni gadro gum disease. gadro lala toothless.
adj . prickly, thorny (as of some trees, citrus, sago palm, some liana vines. wa gadrogadro a prickly vine, a wild raspberry, rubus moluccanus. gadro, gadrota v. to prickle.
v. to pierce, as by a needle or thorn. syn. qarota.
(lau) n. finely woven soft cummerbund of pandanus matting made by tongan procedures,
intended for formal occasions including church services. it is customary to use worn or

torn matting, to give a sense of humility. this is not worn in the moala region (yasayasa moala), part of lau province, and not in some parts of northern lau province that are more closely related to cakaudrove than to the more tongan culture of lau.
n. spout, as in small, clay pot for water to be drunk. ga refers to mouth agape, since fijians poured
the mouth, the pot being held several inches above. lip s never touched the drinking vessel and there were not cups. by ext., igaga might modernly apply to the spout on a teapot.
. adj . bitter, overly concentated, distasteful, "hot" (of chili). sa rui gaga na kari. the curry is very “hot”. sa gaga na wainimate. the medicine tastes bad.

. adj ., n. poison, poisonous, toxic, polluted. vakagaga na wai to pollute the water. vakagagai polluted. wainimate gaga ni veivaka-mateni-taki intoxicating drugs (mateni intoxicated). e na rawa ni ko ni gaga kina. it is possible that you could be poisoned by it. e rawa ni vagagai ko ira na dau kania. people who usually eat it could be poisoned. in ancient times fij ians used at least three species of plant as poisons to be consumed by their enemies.
kalou, pittosporum sp., pittosporaceae, was pounded and mixed in yaqona (capell, p. ); lobau, brugsmansia suaveolens (formerly datura candida), also mixed in yaqona in colo east as i
recorded in oral histories; and mavu ni toga, antiaris toxicaria, moraceae, for which i have
information on how it was used. antiaris spp. have long been used in asia as a poison to
humans. apparently fij ians did not usually use poison on their arrows or spears. used as an
were colourful (bright red and stark black) seeds of diridamu, abrus precatorius, but its

cyanide often killed the mother as well as the foetus. formerly, diridamu were used in necklaces, now forbidden due to the dangerous poison. so small and quick-acting, diridamu has been used in food for assassinations.
adj . to be sitting idly, not knowing what needs to be done.

n. wish, desire. a cava na nomu gagadre? what is your desire? what would you like? gagano, gaganotaka v. to desire secretly someone, usually sexually. somewhat more moderately, gano, ganova. garo, garova v. applies to lust for a person, or some thing very greatly desired.
n. deep-seated desire (usually sexual, usually futile). “gagaj” (rotuma) n. chief in one of the seven districts of rotuma. may be used as a title. there is no
chief on the island though one eccentric character has claimed to be “king”. the letter “g” is pronounced with a soft “ng”, as it is in fijian.
v. to have an excessively strong scent.
n. tetanus.
n., adj . very sharp, as of a knife or spear. syn. momoto, as applied to spears, pencils. gata sharp (and also, as a noun, for `snake).
v. desire deeply.
adj . ineffectual, useless, of a person in any endeavor. a lack of motivation or ability is implied.
. n. pet pig, or affectionate name for pigs, used to call out to pigs to come and be fed. it has been a
custom to adopt very young pet pigs, a custom discontinued in fij i. formerly, women sometimes nursed them at the breast. syn. geti.
. (vanua levu) v. do not want. au gai ni la ’o. i don ’t want to go.
(or) gaigaiya . n., adj . a colour, light or soft yellowish (can have brownish or dusky tone) usually referring to wilted vegetation or to faded, sullied cloth , not usually to human skin.
adj . free, independent, available. sa tu vagalala o seru seru is living (and farming) alone,
of the village and legally free of usual traditional obligations. na tu-galala nei viti the independence of fiji. o galala ? are you available (free)? me galala na nomu vakasama. free
mind (do not worry). by extension, may indicate that some item of clothing is too large, too
about the body. sa galala tu na nomu tarusese. your pants are loose (too big). colonial
established a system whereby a fijian individual or nuclear family could be released from
and clan responsibilites to be independent (galala). although ratu sukuna himself lived

any clan or village responsibilities, he discouraged that system for fij ians generally, believing they were not ready for it. the system failed partly because independent fijians usually lived close to their village, and villagers by custom would not release them from traditional obligations. vagalala, vagalalataka v. to make free, available, to clear off or out or away. vagalalataka na teveli clear off the table. vagalalataka na vale clear out the house (make it free, available). me vagalala na
to vacate the room. vagalalataki iko mai vei iratou stay away from them.

. have one ’s head tilted to one side and/or supported with a hand, usually indicating lack of interest, attention, relaxed sa vagalegale tu ga o seru seru has his head to one side of his shoulder (can be with head in hand). gale . n.,v . to eat, something to eat, idiom from galegale j aw. a cava na ka ni gale? what is to eat? what are we having for food? galegale-na n. molar(s), side teeth, side of the j aw.

v., adv. to be relaxed, even when doing something. e a taubale vagalegale sobu mai. he walked down here relaxedly. gale, vagaleta . v. to need, care about. au sega ni galeti iko i do not need you. au sega ni vagaleta

i do not care for beer. gale, galeta, galeleta . v. to care for, desire, to be motivated with interest. kevaka e sega ni galeleta na yalomu na cauravou oqori, kakua ni gole vua. if your heart does not strongly care for that young man, do not go to him. syn. galele.
adj . lonely.
adj . of child who is curious, independent, picking up things and leaving them somewhere else; of adult who sees things and picks them up without asking. a loner who is not properly socialised.

(colo) n. night. ma lutu mai na galo. the night is falling. vakagalo afternoon. vakagalo have dinner. galu, galuva v., adj . to be silent (of person) speechless, dumb. galu! shut up ! fijians are taught not to speak in the presence of their elders. galuva to be silent in relation to someone or something. see tiko lo.
adj . quiet, silent (person), rarely speaking.

adj . silent, as in sa dua na bogi vagagalu. it is a silent night. galu, galuva, galuvaka v. to be silent, speechless, dumb, to be silent in relation to someone, or some people, galuva . e galuvi au na ganequ. my sister may not speak with me (man speaking). galuvaka v. to be silent about it, deliberately, to clam up. vagaluya na gone to quiet down the child. na vakagalu ni gusumu! this will shut you up ! galu! be silent ! galu na gusumu! shut your mouth !
mada! quiet down ! vagagalu to make someone be silent. in the face of direct questions, a
may assume the right to remain silent. (silence, or non-response may often mean “no” to a request.) see tiko lo!.
v. to remain deliberately silent through self-interest, to avoid getting involved or found out, to avoid revealing something. e so na ka eda dau vakagaluya. some things we do not talk about.
n. silence (no people talking). may refer, for example, to the prohibition of speech between father and daughter-in-law. also, formerly, a brother and sister might not converse.

v. do something a second time to do it better. na kena igalui the second try, which will complete it. could apply to burning off garden again, or to an additional ceremony that will satisfy people that it has been done properly.

n. sibling of the opposite sex, sister (of male), brother (of female). e rau sa veiganeni. they (two) are brother and sister. na gane i siteri esther's brother. this has been a tabu relationship, no talking, looking, or any contact, unless the sister is older, acting in motherly role. na veiganeni the brother and sister. ganei n. father's sister, abbrev. from gane i tamaqu; now often further abbreviated as nei.
v. to be suitable, appropriate, match (of clothes). sa veiganiti vinaka na nona vosa. his/her
apt, appropriate. erau veiganiti na nomu vava kei na nomu vinivo. your shoes and your dress match nicely. e ganiti iko na sote oqori. that shirt really suits you. na ka o ganita! that's
you deserve ! na itotogi e veiganiti kei na cala. the punishment fits the crime. e sega ni veiganiti me kaburaki ena walesi. it is not appropriate to broadcast on the radio.

ni vatu n. peregrine falcon. syn. (northern lau) tuitui. black head, breast, flank and thighs striped black on cream. staple diet is flying fox fruit bat, finches, pigeons, some sea birds. eyrie on cliffs, - white eggs with brown blotches. watling says the long pointed wings and long tail are distinctive. gano, ganova v. to gape or stare with desire, to lust after. gara, garata v. to snarl wildly, angrily, snort. ucu gara makes a wild angry face (or, simply) have large
a flat nose. kua ni garata na gone. don't snarl at the kid(s). e garati au mai o
he shouted snarlingly at me just now. kua ni gara. don't shout angrily . syn. kara .
v. to like to eat immature fruit, as in pregnancy. syn. bati vou. garo, garova v. to have a strong desire for (a food or drink), or lust after (a person, sex).
adj . having rabid desire (a food, drink), or lustful (with sexual desire). see vorivori.

v. to want something that will never give satisfaction. na ka o gasa! that's what you yourself wanted ! (often said sarcastically). idiom: dau gasa yawa always wants the inaccessible. often said of a person who stays away from home, feeling more comfortable elsewhere.
adj . tasty, delicious, nicely sweet. mata gasagasa cute, sexually attractive (of person).
v. to make a food or beverage tasty or sweet, as in adding a condiment. igasagasa n. sweetener, condiment, such as salt.
n. reed, arrow. gasau kuro n. bomb. gasau nunu torpedo. gasau ni dakai bullet.
kinds of reeds are gasau saisai (= gasau lailai) used for multi-pronged fishing spears and
for arrows, gasau dina used for house-walls, fish-fences. reeds also served commonly as
the innovation of newspapers. (see roth, fij ian way of lif e, p. ). flowering of reeds, miscanthus floridulus, occurs around february-march , signaling a time of flies, and a time of

(cika). in western viti levu, reeds were commonly used for the walls and roofs of native houses. syn. (west) sina. (nadro) hina. idiom: daru qai laki sota ki na gasau leka . we are not likely to meet again, lit. we will meet next at
(at bua, supposedly the jumping-off place to the next world, after death).

source_text: n. bomb. na vakalutu gasaukuro. the bombing.
(archaic) n. cannon balls.
v. (vanua levu) to refuse.
adj . sharp. vagata. to sharpen (knife, axe). rui gata very sharp .
n. snake, the pacific boa, candoia bibroni, a harmless, nocturnal tree-climber that gives live birth
meter but the boa can grow to two meters. locally, the boa has its colour variations which led
to think there were several species, and the personality can become a quite snappy in some places, kabara, for example. males have tiny vestigial claspers or spurs around the cloaca. formerly,

back-bones. modernly, fijians might generally refer to all or any snakes as gata. in fij i there are no venemous land snakes that ever bite people. the small, to inch bolo, ogmodon vitiensis, is deadly poisonous but is shy, very rarely seen, and has never been
