source_text: v. to hear partially, incompletely some conversation, some account.
. n . fame. na irogorogo kei cakobau. the fame of cakobau.
. n . hearing-aid for deafness.
. n . stethoscope, earphones as for music.
. v. to make (someone, something) famous. e vakarogoya na yaca i viti ko manu. manu made famous the name of fij i. e vakarogoi viti ko serevi. serevi made fij i famous.
. v. to announce, make known, let it be heard.
v. to defame.
adj . made famous, much heard about.
n. . hearing, as in some public investigation or court case.
n. . obedience, as in paying attention to social protocol.
v. to sound, as in rorogo vata to sound the same. vaka-di rorogo silent, as of a house.
v. adj . listen to, accept advice or orders, obey; obedient. tawa vakarorogo disobedient.
v. . to publicise, advertise (a person, action or thing).
v. . to inform someone. rogoseva, rogosevata v. to mis-hear, to hear something incorrectly.
v. to hear the story of . . .
rumoured. e rogovaki tiko ni ra vakamuri kuli. it is being rumoured that they follow kuli. na kena rogovaki ni a bukete tiko. it is rumoured that she is pregnant.
(archaic) n. fijian name of a legendary ship that brought some chiefly immigrants to fiji,
the same as the lolop eau by its earlier name. lolop eau corresponds to lolovira na biau
“the waves are beneath its dignity”. (spellings of that name vary slighty.) the rogovoka is also said to have brought from uvea island stones for the tomb of the tui tonga. idiom: vaka na ivana
very tall. straight and strong, literally like the mast of the legendary ship rogovoka.
v. to hear on the fly, unverified rumours.
n. whisk, for brushing away flies, mosquitos, used by chiefs. syn. (lau) f ue.
n. pectoral fins, fins on both sides of fish, for propulsion.
n. colour. anciently fijians divided the colour spectrum at different frequencies than europeans do. there has thus been some confusion in translating colour-names though fijians now tend to follow
system. formerly, fij ians’ naming of colours was based on the colour of known objects,
by frequencies on the physical colour spectrum. duiroka of various colours. dua roka of a single, uniform colour. roka-ca off-colour, faded. oriori striped. tavu-tonotono speckled, spotted.

. n. (eng.) chilli pepper, (“rocket”), a plant introduced by indians and, probably earlier, by europeans. kana rokete a punishment of children, to eat chilli pepper. formerly, a chilli might be placed in the rectum of a naughty child. hot chilli, so popular among fijians today, originated from the americas; it was unknown in india as well as fiji. chilli has become an essential ingredient of the ever popular tongan sauce miti, with coconut cream and onion, served with fish. idiom: quru rokete be in prison, lit. crunch chilli. rokete . n. (eng.) firework s.
n. abbrev. of roko tui, the salaried, administrative head of a province.
(archaic) n. name of a legendary master boat-builder and carpenter with home village of narauyabe at the western end of the nakauvadra range in ra province. he gave protection to the ciri

who angered degei, the snake god, by their having killed his favoured pet fowl turukawa at conua, nakauvadra. these acts initiated the famous nakauvadra wars. rokola is thought to be of tongan extraction, founder of the carpenter clans mataisau in fij i. along with the ciri twins, he was
degei. his adze was stolen along the wainibuka river and he died en route in southerly travel. historian derrick wrote that he was supposedly a son of degei.
n. chiefly title in ono (kadavu), namuka (tailevu), and ovalau .
v. to show respect by one’s behaviour and attitude. idiom: rokoroko va-kanace showing disrespect, as mullet leaps up avoiding predators.
n. very minor territorial title, as at village nabouwalu, ono island, kadavu.
n. respect. na rokovi ni lawa respect for the law.

v. to show respect (more emphatic than roko). na nodra vakarokoroko vua na tamata. their respect for the people. idiom: vakarokoroko vakanace pretentious and disrespectful behaviour in the presence of one’s superiors, or elders, lit. respectful like a mullet (which jumps and splashes high out of the water over the heads of its predators).
n. persistent muscular pain deep inside the back or torso, rather like in twisted, knotted muscle. alleviated by specialists of massage.
n. prefix of traditional chiefly title that varies from one locality to another. most widely recognised is the roko tui bau of super-tribe kubuna at bau.
(or) rokotui is a title also at cautata, namata, namara (roko tui veikau), viwa, kiuva, in kadavu and also nakelo (tailevu) and ovalau .
(or) rokotui-na-mata at vukavu in naceva, kadavu, also at nacokoni in burebesaga, and in noco, rewa. rokosau is a title on totoya island, lau province.
is a title on kadavu.
is a title at naqarani and at naselai (tongan origin)
is a title at nabouwalu, ono island, kadavu province.

at naqara (ono, kadavu), namaka (bau) and daku, nasinu, at ovalau. rokotuni equivalent of rokotuinimata. rokotunimata at vukavu, naceva, in kadavu, and nacokoni and noco in rewa province. similarly, rokisi is a title at nabouciwa and naselai. some of these examples were published in the fijian dictionary na ivolavosa vakaviti, .
part of a personal name indicating high social rank for a man or woman in some parts of lau province. roko may also be a personal name with no implication of social rank.
(followed by name of a province) top fijian administrative officer appointed to a province. (in
speech locally, this administrator can be referred to politely as “the roko”.) for most

a native of the province he administers. exceptions are provinces of ra and ba, where a high bauan chief has often been appointed. roko tui bau is the traditional high chief of super-tribe vusaratu, originally the highest chief on bau island and super-tribe kubuna.
n. gastritis, persistent stomach pains. one fijian remedy is to make an infusion from the inner bark of the yalu tree. sometimes abbreviated as roko or koro.
(eng.) n. rowlock for rowing a small boat, and at the stern, serve to hold an oar for sculling.
n. v., ceremony for mother and newborn, bringing them gifts and, usually, holding the child in
(roqota). syn. (lau) kevekeve.
n. gift that is brought for newborn child. roqo, roqota v. to hold, clasp in the arms, against the chest. one might hold a baby this way, or firewood, or a bundle of clothes.
v., adj . to cross one’s arms, clasp one’s arms in front, folded on the chest.
(or) roro, rova v. to approach, usually a bird, airplane, come in to land, or approach in time of some occasion. vakaroro na waqavuka v, to land the plane.
n. perch, as of a bird, a place where it lands, a place for landing. iroro ni waqavuka aeroport, landing place for an aeroplane.

n. (nadroga) the fan palm, pritchardia pacifica, more widely called masei in fij i. leaves were used for fans and/or umbrellas for chiefs. elsewhere in fiji, roro may refer to the cycad, cycas spp., which

a food for chiefs in macuata but was used as a famine food in koro island. the nut is edible only after treatment. it can be poisonous. roroi, roroya v. to close off a fish net or fish fence (as of reeds) by attaching the final closure. iroroi n. seam or attachment where net or fish fence is closed off.
(eng.) rose (flower), introduced, mentioned in modern native romantic songs which are themselves polynesian in origin. rosi is also a female name.
(anglicism) n. edible fish , malabar blood snapper, lutj anus malabaricus, to meters. syn.

(ni radini ni bau). very similar to rosi loa, timor snapper, l. timorensis, which has slightly darker red back and fins. roso, rosova v. to squat on one’s haunches, sit on one ’s heels, for convenience or from respect for the presence of important people.
or vakarota v. to order, give orders for things to be done. ivakaro n. order(s).
v. to fart inadvertantly. rotu, rotuka, rotulaka v. to beat up (a person) usually with sticks or fists. a common revenge or
is a physical beating, usually with the victim taken by surprise, attacked by several men.
beating.
n. leaves of the taro plant that are to be used as green vegetable. certain varieties of taro are best
avoid the itchy effect of oxalic acid crystals in the plant. in coastal areas and
islands, rourou may be served in coconut cream, or used as wrapping in preparing p alusami, often including tinned fish or canned corned beef. rourou vaka-utona “stuffed” rourou, as the leaves
as an edible wrap, enclosing some other food. rourou vaka-taci-rua taro leaves wrapping
(grated coconut that has been lightly fermented in saltwater) with coconut cream lolo. rourou

taro leaf simply boiled, without coconut cream. gutu-va na rourou to cut off the leaves of rourou. sagi-ta na rourou to pluck, pick rourou leaves. syn. (lau) p akia. (kadavu) ivuso. (colo east) sovu and la . rove, rovea v. to cut up in small pieces, a root crop such as taro or yam, preparatory to cooking.

v. to sprout (teeth of baby, buds on a plant). na rovurovu the sprouting. idiom: vosa o iko, sa rovu e liu na batimu. you speak first, you are older than me (and thus i defer to you), lit. your teeth sprouted first. (this is said in humour, especially when two people begin speaking at the same time.)
(or) ruka, rukaka, rulaka v. to curse, swear. ena voso ni veiru in swear-words. iruka n. curse.
certain related peoples (veitabani or veitavu dredre) liberties may be taken , including swearing. syn. borata.

two, as in e rua. ruasagavulu twenty. e rua na drau two hundred. na ikarua the second. syn. (tonga) ua. idiom: karua now used mostly humorously, as a term of relationship or form of address, joking with a person of the same sex. it indicates that the person addressed (or referred to) is intimate with the same
sex-partner, a rival for the affections of the same mate. among intimate friends it may only imply jokingly that one admires the other’s spouse.
both. ena yasa ruarua ni gaunisala. on both sides of the road. similarly, tolu three, and tolutolu all three.

v. to repeat, to copy, to replicate, double up. rube, rubeca . v. to suspend, hang up. vakarubeci e domona hung around his neck. rube ena kauveilati v. to crucify , hang on the cross. see lili, liliva. rube, rubeca . v. to delay or defer (as in a case pending in court). rubi, rubica v . to beat or flog, as one beats an octopus kuita with a stone to prepare it for cooking. rubu . v. to pout. vakaruburubu sullen , pouting. rubu . n. type of handbasket woven of voivoi pandanus leaves.
(or) rugurugua adj . in the shade, sheltered from the sun, as in sa rugurugua na vanua nikua it is cloudy today. vakarurugua-taka v. to shelter from the sun, to put (something, someone) in the shade.

very, excessive(ly). sa rui sau levu. it is too expensive. ruku, rukuta . to leave early in the morning. rukuta na basi take the bus early in the morning. syn. sou, souta. ruku, rukuta . (rewa) v. to enter. drau ruku sara mai! you two come right in !

under, underneath. ena ruku ni teveli underneath the table. vakaruru ena ruku ni vunikau to shelter under the tree. ena rukuna underneath it. idiom: (ang.) ena ruku ni matanisiga everywhere, lit. under the sun. idiom: (ang.) ena ruku ni kuila in colonial times, under the british flag.
(eng.) room (as part of a building). rumu ni moce bedroom. rumu ni kana dining room. rumu ni
waiting room. rumu ni vuli schoolroom. rumu ni gade living room, sitting room.
adj . calm, peaceful (sea, wind), eased (of pain, sickness).
v. to take shelter (usually from rain or sun), often heard as va-ruru.
(or) ivakaruru n . sheltering place, from rain or sun, or safe and protected anchorage.
adj . sheltered, overcast, of the sky. syn. rugua.
v., adj . to shelter, overcast (sky). rusa, vakarusa v. to destroy, lasarusa is a man ’s name, implying he enjoys destroying. sa rusa ena cagilaba. it was destroyed in the hurricane.
n. famous ship built by tongans at fulaga for the tui nayau, the largest one recorded
(tonga lupe) n. pigeon, columbia spp., white-throated pigeon is native, c. vitiensis. feral pigeon
n. association of women founded by mrs. derrick supporting women ’s interests, sewing, cooking, methodist activities, later re-named isoqosoqo vakamarama.

a c, as in sici, trochus shellfish, to be heard as cici, and sucu, breast or born, as cucu. in most areas of nadroga, the s may be replaced by an h which is an influence from tonga; village sanasana would be pronounced hanahana, for example.

source_text: . particle modifying verb s to indicate definiteness, emphasis, having happened or sure to happen, or already happened, something changed or activated. sa oti. it is finished. au sa lako. i'm going now.
lako ko koya. he/she has gone already. sa kana ? have you already eaten? sa lako ? are you

(just now)? this particle stands in contrast to the particle se which can indicate present and continuing action, something that may happen or is likely to happen. sa! . interj ection of surprise, shock, disapproval, an expression often over-used by people learning the language. this same expression exists also in tonga.
. n. spear, usually now referring specifically to a multi-pronged spear for fish. the chiefly titles
and tunisa imply a warlord, from the use of spears (as told to me by the late vunisa at village weilagi, taveuni). dau vakasasa pig-hunter who uses spears (and dogs).
. n. a sp. of tree, parinara insularum, chrysobalanaceae. na vunisa the sa tree. red sap . this large
usually grows on poor soil, and itself is of little use as a timber, except for house-posts. the
cut when dry , so for firewood fijians will chop it up soon after felling the tree.

. n . a sudden frightening wind that strikes from one side, usually around september-october, near the sea on the main islands. blasts can recur or continue for several hours. in english this type of wind is sometimes called a cat ’s paw from its dangerous speed and power. isa . n. partner (marriage, tennis, business), mate, a necessary second of two things (one shoe out a pair of shoes), a gift made in exchange for another, a necessary opposite of two things, as with a rafter of a
(matching a rafter on the other side of the house).
. n. wooden rafter(s) supporting the ceiling of a house.
. (archaic) n. game of skill using four white cowry shells, rarely played today.
. n., v. women ’s exchange of traditional goods (mats, pots, etc.) for modern goods such as cutlery ,

equipment. this reaffirms social relationships and allows village women (who might have little cash) to acquire some household goods that otherwise must be bought for money. see solevu. veisa-vosa n. verbal exchange, discussion in which there are opposing sides as in a debate.
adj . flat in shape, as of some fish (sole, flounder), pancake; deflated, as of a balloon or tyre. ulu

flat-faced. sabaka, sabalaka v. to smack, slap hard with the open hand. sabalaka indicating greater degree or duration. isaba n. slap. see sabi, sabica. sabalia or vakasabalia v. to wander about pointlessly (people, cattle, dogs in the village). vakasabalia na
to waste one ’s life. vaka-sabalia na kakana to waste the food. adj . careless, inappropriate in behaviour.
v. to block, as in fending off a blow, oppose some action, take an opposing position, to be contrary, to ward off something impending. sabaya na inaki ca to ward of the evil intention. by ext.,
(in cricket).

v. to walk without ability to put a foot flat on the ground. one either drags a foot, or raises it stiffly , planting it down at each step. this is due to a birth defect or to a leg injury. sabe, sabeta v. to kick with one side of the foot, not the toes. syn. rabe.

idiom: to walk around doing nothing, wasting time, wander about. sabi, sabica v. to slap lightly, as with the open hand, to pat. ivava sabisabi (or) sabisabi “flip-flop s” (rubber sandals). see sabaka, more forcefully.
(eng.) n. sample. sabu! (or) sabusabu! interjection showing disapproval, reproach, disbelief. vakasabusabu-taka v. to abuse, misuse carelessly, wastefully (tools, equipment, supplies), to “spoil”.
n. snapper, emperor fish, one of the finer edible fish, lethrinus mahsena or l. obsoletus (longitudinal yellow stripe along each side of belly), l . atkinsoni (yellow-tail emperor, brown patch
(l. nebulosis, large yellow stripes on face, radiating from eyes). syn. cabutu. (lakeba) ika dina.
n. sweet smelling shrub, florets often placed behind the ear, in the hair, evodia hortensis. syn. uci, the much more widely known name. more commonly, the name sacasaca applies to an
closely related to the crotons, codiaeum variegatum, euphorbiaceae, noted for its highly coloured leaves.
n. a very well known tree, endemic to fiji, growing to meters, not above meters in altitude,
hornei, sapotaceae, durable hardwood timber for house-posts. white latex. late tage of
is indicated by loss of leaves, and greying bark. logging has taken a heavy toll of their existence. other timber trees in this genus are bau and bauvudi, all endemic to fiji.

n. thigh. vu ni saga-na thigh-joint. saga ni sip i leg of lamb (or mutton). the original notion has been that of a crotch. idiom : (vulgar) cabola ni sagana to fart explosively. saga, sagava (or) saga v. to strive, struggle to overcome. isasaga n. striving, directed effort. na nona

his/her effort. tamata sasaga n. striving person, person who tries hard. saga, vakasaga v. to tease, harass, persecute, cause trouble for someone. vakasagai teased, harassed, persecuted. saga-ca-taka v. to molest, harass; there can be sometimes an implication of witchcraft. sagale n. common at mangrove edge and coastal strand, lumnitzera littorea, combretaceae, often used for firewood, sometimes for building. bark mud-grey, fissured, peeling in thick flakes, revealing light grey patches. slash orange, then yellow wood. the timber is superior to the common mangrove trees
or dogo. it endures water better than most timbers, so is used for posts and piles for j etties.
fashioned it for fishhooks. clusters of bright red flowers at tip s of branches, all year. lvs narrow, tough, dark green, spirally arranged. syn. sagali.
(polyn.) n. as in rua sagavulu twenty. sagavulu is an ancient proto-polynesian word for “ten”,

changed in fiji to tini from the english word for ten. sagavulu was the name of a son of lutunasobasoba, one who remained behind at vuda. syn. (tonga) hongof ule. sagi, sagita v. to pluck off, usually leaves.
. n. amount of a bid or wager in gambling, card-playing.
. n. arrow, usually made from a hardened reed, to be shot from a bow (dakai titi), used in ancient
as a defensive weapon, by melanesian women or men. arrows also formerly used to shoot down bats for food. (tongans used bow and arrow only for chiefly sport.)

. n. see saisaia. “saijan” (hindi) n. drumstick tree, moringa oleifera, moringaceae, introduced. leaves and fruit used as cooked vegetables, and as folk medicine, by indians. the drum-stick shaped fruit is often sold in the market. excessive rain reduces fruit-set. extracts from the plant have effects that are anti-microbial, ease muscle spasms, and reduce blood pressure in experimental animals. saini, sainitaka (eng.) v. to sign (it).
v. to cry isa! with disappointment, regret, sorrow, as at departure of a loved one, or on hearing of someone’s death.
(eng.) sinai (peninsula).
n. multi-pronged spear, now used for fishing spears. such fishing spears never existed in the viti levu highlands. in early times saisai could refer to a multi-pronged spear used in war.
adj . very thin, of a person. sai n. smallest animal in a litter, often thin and under-nourished, usually referring to piglets.
(eng. cipher) zero, naught. (vulgar slang) asshole, as an insult.

sir (or) madam, polite form of address in speech or writing. i 'saka form of address used in correspondence, equiv. of dear sir (or) dear madam. sakava v. to say “saka ” in addressing some significant person.
(eng.) n. sacrament.
adj . clumsy, inappropriate in behaviour.
(eng.) v. to sack, to dismiss from employment.
n. small edible freshwater fish, kuhlia marginatus.

(lau) n. meal of chinese cabbage or mustard cabbage (mosita, lauan word for brassica juncea) cooked in coconut milk (lolo) with pieces of fish, and/or shellfish such as kaikoso clams, or trochus shellfish, with condiment of fermented coconut condiment known as kora. saki, sakita v. to marvel (at). isakisaki n. marvel, glory.

(or) vaka-sakita v. to take great personal pride in (something, someone). sakitaki koya boastful, vain, conceited. sakiki n. more than one species of palm, usually veitchia spp. trunk is tall and thin. idiom : vakavu ni sakiki marvelous something greatly admired.

n. object of admiration, usually a person, a favoured child or benificent leader or role-model; something or someone to be proud of. sako, sakoca v. to whack with a stick, usually the mash (mavu) of cooked taro held in the hand. this is
of making pudding (vakalolo). sakosako n. type of fijian pudding made this way. na
the whacking. sako may apply to whacking a person, or even a ball, sakolaka
it is done forcefully. sako-i-drauna fijian pudding of grated taro in caramelised coconut

(lolo buta), a specialty for the tui nayau as made by the people of natokalau, matuku island, and waitabu and yadrana on lakeba island. sakosako n. type of fijian pudding made usually with mashed taro and either regular coconut cream (lolo droka), or caramelised coconut cream (lolo buta).

. n. edible garfish, tylosurus crocodilis, which skims on the surface of lagoons. not highly preferred as a food. it has a pointed nose. idiom: vaka e siri na saku fast (just as the saku skims on the surface).

. n. any of the large billfish. may refer to a swordfish (saku vorowaqa) . also sailfish, sawfish (sakulaya), and/or one of the three species of marlin : blue marlin (makaira nigricans), black marlin (m. indica), striped marlin (tetrapturus audax). billfish not often caught by fijians who rarely fished beyond the reef so there is some confusion as to specific names of the various billfish.
adj . mucky, as with rotten fruit, disgusting. saku betabeta, more so.

adj . clumsy, ineffectual (person), badly done (of work) saku, sakuta v. to club a person forcefully on the head. idiom: saku vakanamara lit., club someone in namara fashion, that is forcefully, effectively. (capell

that this expression implies scalping the head of the victim as done formerly by namara people.) namara warriors of tailevu have been famous for their expert clubbing. the implication is to do a job efficiently, expertly, expeditiously .
(west) n. leper, afflicted with leprosy , hansen ’s disease. there were in several places on viti
island special stones (vatu ni sakuku), the property of certain clans (mataqali). through these stones, heads of the clans claimed they could transmit leprosy when compensated to do so; this was a
of disposing of unwanted people, mafia style. ref.: d . w. beckett, trans. fij i society , . syn. vukavuka.
n. black marlin, makaira indica, with dark upper body. there are two other spp. of marlin, m.
the blue marlin and the somewhat more slender tertapturus audax, striped marlin, both

similar with blue upper bodies; there is no tradition or consistency in their specific fijian names. marlin have often been caught inadvertantly by net fishermen; others are caught by game fishermen. they are sold as the fish in fish and chips, only sometimes identified as marlin .
n. swordfish, xiphias gladius, not trad. caught by fijians, and not common. in the deep sea,
are sometimes seen lying on their sides, sunning themselves on the surface. they are not
unless attacked or caught on a fishing line. caught only by gamefishers, as are marlins.
people (including this author) have more sympathy for these noble fish than for the game fishermen.
n. sailfish, istiophorus platypterus, to cm, not favoured as a food by europeans.
is often riddled with the holes of parasites. the name refers to its capability of breaking up (voro) a boat (waqa). the name saku is sometimes used. sailfish has a huge blue-coloured dorsal fin

along the back . it eats sardine-type fish, encircling schools of them, keeping them close-in together, then plunging into their midst, swinging their beak like a sword. sailfish are caught only by game fishermen. syn. sakulaya. laya is a noun and means “sail” in western fiji.
fij ian names of sailfish, swordfish, marlin all have the prefix saku—but any full name of
one would be known to extremely few fij ians and there is little consistency of names, some being modernisms decided by fisheries dept. reason is that fijians were not deep-sea fishermen and

never caught these fish. they rarely, in fact, ever saw them. they are not usually at the surface of the sea. sakure v. to shake, rumble, tremble, shudder, as a stomach might, or an earthquake, or a motor car out of fuel, or a house in very strong gusts of wind. see kure, kuretaka. sakulevu, sakulevutaka v. to be careless, neglectful in responsibilities.

. v., n. path. gaunisala road, trunk road. salatu highway, main road. salavata v. to go together, taking the same path. every part of fiji is criss-crossed with old paths, though they may be difficult to
today. salawai of a village, reachable only by boat. sala vaka-vanua traditional path for
between two places or people, and extremely important concept to fijian traditionalists. idiom : e tubua na sala ki na nona koro he/she has lost connection to his village, never visits it (lit.

not be so relevant as many fij ians are pre-occupied with their lives in towns or other distant places of employment. to renew relations to one ’s village is cara sala to “clear or sweep the path” to the village. it can be an expensive process, requiring gifts of goods, and time spent. a fij ian ’s village is almost always demanding support. sala . n. by extension, sala may mean figuratively, the way or means (the path) to accomplish something, or may mean to extend, as in extending the hand or leg.
v. set out on a trip in the afternoon, and thus travel or arrive at night. the personal name meli salabogi is well known in the lineage of the chiefly gonesau at nokorotubu, ra province.
n. windpipe but more generally, throat and bronchial tubes, lit. path of the breath.
n. vein or artery (human or animal body). dra blood. fijians made no distinction between a
(for blood returning to the heart) and an artery (for blood leaving the heart).
n. digestive track (human or animal body).
n. urinary tract, a newly created word.
ni valelailai n. colon (human or animal body). valelailai n. toilet, a concept introduced by europeans.
ni ivalu n. lit. path of war, meaning the specific social connections between two or more places in
for making war. formal communications should pass through various specific kingroups, tribes or villages. see also sala ni vanua.
ni vanua n. traditional approach in communicating formally with another tribe or kin-group on
other than war. communications should pass through certain specific people as a matter of formality.
n. ancient term for a traditional route whereby goods passed in tribute, and perhap s also in
a couple of the first major territories to establish such a system over an extensive area that included parts of vanua levu. bau later established such a system, as did burebesaga.
n., adj . reached by water, usually of an isolated village with no good access by road. an example
village qoma, formerly turtle fishermen for verata, located on two very small islands off the northern coast of tailevu.
ni yalo n. “path of spirits”, a legendary and real path of early migration on viti levu. it was
that after death spirits would return on this same path. on viti levu, one established

southward down from ra and the eastern highlands to the coast around veisari. this mountain range down the eastern coast of viti levu was called tualeita. some would claim it begins not far from vuda, far in the west of viti levu, and passed through the nakauvadra mountain range. sala, salaga v. to wrap around, as leaves, vines or creepers, or paper, in making a parcel, or (formerly) to
(isala) of barkcloth on the head.
head-covering, hat, formerly wrapped around the head as a type of men's turban made of fine, thin
masi, in coastal and small island areas, worn only by chiefs. missionaries caused the
to be discontinued. the use of such hats or turbans occurs these days only at the installation
n. wrapped parcel of leaves containing food such as fish to be cooked in the earth oven.
ika n. long, leaf-wrapped parcel of fish. syn. ikovu, though this is a round, bud-shaped parcel.
v. to advise. ivakasala advice. daunivakasala advisor. daunivakasala levu ni veika
solicitor general.

. n. fish, long-j awed mackerel, rastrelliger kanagurta, edible but not greatly appreciated because of the lack of meat in the head. fij ians appreciate the head of the fish as having more flavour than the other flesh ; the head will often be offered to a guest. this seasonal silver fish lives close to shore and travels in fairly fast-moving schools. idiom : ulu salala empty-headed, stupid.
. n. cultivar of voivoi pandanus leaf that has long leaves and no thorns along the edge of the leaf.
easier to handle than the regular, prickly voivoi but the quality of the leaf is not as good, so it does not displace the regular cultivar. syn. voivoi ni rotuma.

. n. a harmful wild shrub or tree of the central south seas, to meters high, dendrocnide harveyi, urticaceae, with stinging hairs on the margins of the leaves and sap that stings very irritatingly. the irritation is aggravated by water. the itching burn occurs within half a minute but the
may recur for months. veins on underside of young lvs are purple or reddish. the totem

of some highlanders where the name must not be mentioned. thrives best in secondary vegetation, identified by heart-shaped leaves with finely serrated edges, and white to cream coloured flowers, small (under cm) forming white, thin-skinned single-seeded fruit. formerly planted deliberately at perimeter of some fortified villages as defensive device. salato . n. edible small coloured j ellyfish with long stinging thread, physalia physalis.
v. to go along together. vata together. sala waqa v. to go by boat. salayame v. to have to tongue hanging out, as a dog does when too hot. (dogs cannot perspire; cooling is
by keeping the mouth open and by drinking water.) by comparison, darayame usually just refers to sticking out the tongue, as a child might do in teasing. yame tongue.

v. to extend the leg(s). yava leg(s). this may be done as a person excuses himself after a meal and shifts where his back will be against the wall, relaxing. syn. dodoyava. sali, salia (or) saliva v. to flow down (current of water), or flow through as of a narrow channel, or opening of a reef, where the tidal current flows through. also to droop down (thatching from the roof of a fij ian house). salia can be the name of a village.

n. opening through the reef of a lagoon, that serves a path or channel for the passage of boats, or for the movement of fish with the tide. isalisali-ni-wai n. gutter, or drain as passage for water flow. this is a fairly modern word.
n. traditional specialty food; for people of the warrior castes, usually inland, this is mainly pork since
are considered to have wild pig easily accessible; for coastal people it is mainly seafood, and coconut dishes. one must offer one's salu to visitors who have a different salu, and one may not eat

in their presence. the rule is still fairly strictly maintained even by urban fijians and even if the fijians live overseas. nothing need be said, and the foreigner will probably notice nothing. curiously, as people have so often moved and resettled, the traditional warriors may actually reside
the sea, the coastal people moved inland; they nonetheless retain the old customs. isasalu delicacy. veisasalu ni wai tui seafood delicacies.
adj . scented. isaluaki scent used to perfume oil. a popular fijian scent is mokosoi flowers but there are many others. crushed nuts of makita tree are also traditional.
. n. scent, fragrance; this now includes commercial perfume.
. n. condiment, spice, added to food. this is modern usage. fij ians anciently used virtually no
other than salt or a sweetener (such as sugar cane or masawe). in the highlands the

fern waruta was used and often preferred to salt that was rarely available to them. modernly, fij ians use cane sugar, chilli pepper, salt and pepper but few other condiments. saluka v. to blow the nose fijian-style, without the benefit of a handkerchief, holding a finger against one nostril. for young children, the snot (luka) will be wiped away onto the child’s clothing. adults
do the same, using the shirt or t-shirt. the handkerchief is an introduced concept. syn. wadruluka.
adj . wrinkled, loose, drooping, of human skin and flesh, usually from aging. wa-salulu extremely wrinkled. see sanuki.
n. massive and heavy garland of flowers and sweet-scented leaves, framed in woven fibre of
and/or hibiscus, presented to distinguished guests at formal occasions. the flowers often

bua ni viti. cori salusalu to string a garland. era vakasalusalu kece. they (many) all wore floral garlands. idiom: vakaciri salusalu v. to throw flowers onto the sea for loved ones departing in a boat. this

is not truly fij ian in origin. it was perhaps introduced from polynesia. as a practice, it probably reached its peak with commercial steamships, especially the matson line, in the s with the mariposa and monterey sailing through the south pacific.

(lau) v. to wear something around the neck, usually a garland. syn. taubena. vakasaluma v. to place something around a person ’s neck, usually a garland. salutu, salutu-taka (eng.) n., v. to salute. (military).

n. small tree, commersonia bartramia, sterculiaceae, wood soft like vau (hibiscus shrub), but brown colour. flowers are white, begin blooming in early december through early june. there are two varieties, sama ni vanua, and sama ni wai.
v. to clean garden of weeds, or clean house, especially by sweeping. samaka na vale sweep out the house.

. (eng.) n. “salmon”, actually mackerel, processed and packed in tins, salmon style; this is a rather oily and salty, imported fish , packed in fij i as an inexpensive food, much used by those fijians who have a modest cash income.
. (eng.) n. summons, from police, or the courts. waradi n. warrant.

(eng. submarine) n. diving goggles, by ext. one who at a meal has eyes only for meat or fish (na kena icoi), rather than rice, bread, or the starch-food that is considered "true food" (kakana dina). syn. vakakilivati, savumarini.
(eng.) psalm. fijian church women have developed a custom of singing the p salms in rhythm and tone adapted from ancient chants.
n., v. to flirt.

v., n. to lisp, to stutter ; speech defect. samu, samuta, samulaka v. to strike down with a stick, as in knocking down fruit such as dawa, mango, citrus, often with long heavy stick s. may also apply to the beating of barkcloth (masi), and beating of the surface of the water when driving fish into a net or into a fish fence. idiom : samu ni dawa. get the consequences, as with dawa falling on the person below though the
someone else. one version of the idiom is samuti koya na isamu ni dawa. lit. to be struck by the falling dawa as a result of one’s actions.

n. beating with a stick in preparation of barkcloth, or beating other thing as mentioned above. see samu, samuta, samulaka. women ’s beating of barkcloth is a frequent if not constant sound in some villages of lau and a few other places.
v. to destroy, exterminate. samuqawe, samuqawetaka v. to tattoo, mostly on men as a modern custom. young men and women
have a crude tattoo, with their own initials or initials of their school. in ancient times in fij i
women had tattoo, elaborately done around the mouth, upper thighs, rump and genitals, preparatory to marriage.
adj . thin and small, frail (person usually). syn. lila. sani, sania (or) saniva v. to pick (usually edible vegetable leaf) by pulling. sani ota (or) bele. pick ota

(or) bele leaves for eating. sani rourou cut off leaves of rourou (dalo leaves). syn. (west) sagi, sagia. sani, saniva v. to cross though an area where there is no path , through the grasslands, reeds or bush.
ni balolo n. gusty wind and bad weather that often occurs presaging the rise of the balolo (edible marine annelid), in certain locations only, away from viti levu.
(eng.) n. sandsoap. sovu n. soap.
(eng.) n. sandpaper.

(eng.) n. sandwich. named from lord sandwich , who popularised this novelty in his time. he ate them at the gaming table. sanuki, sanukia v. to crumple, crush or cause creases or wrinkles, usually of clothes, mats, pandanus leaves voivoi for weaving, paper to be discarded. sanuki wrinkled. may apply to wrinkles of elderly people. sasa nukinuki all crumpled up. syn. saloki.
. (lau) n. flat pancake made of flour, water, sugar. syn. top ai.
. (lau) adj . disorderly, untidy (clothes, household, things strewn about).
(eng. slang) “supporter”, underpants, especially men ’s. sap o ni yasana extra large underwear.
underwear.
n. edible fish, crevally, with delicious flesh, in some places formerly reserved for the chieftain. there is more than one genus and several species.
n. large traditional clay pot for storing water. such artifacts were known only around the coast,
all of polynesian or proto-polynesian origin. highland girls used bamboo tubes to carry water from the river, and to store it.
n. small clay water pot made in rewa, usually in three round sections, like three oranges (moli)

, so in slang saqamoli may refer to one dollar. saqa, saqa (or) saqava v. to cook (of the food), traditionally by steaming in huge clay pots. now the word is more inclusive and refers to any type of cooking in a pot, including metal pots. saqa does not
to grilling (tavu) on a fire or cooking in an earth oven (vavi ena lovo). cooking in clay pots

unknown among fijians of the highlands of viti levu. saqamoce v. to cook overnight, to be ready for eating the next morning, often done for cassava, via, or ivi that can be hard, almost woody. vakasaqa, vakasaqa v. to cook. na dau ni vakasaqa the cook. na vakasaqa nei losana losana’s cooking. saqa, saqata . v. to bump into, collide with. idiom: saqamua prostitute (insulting term), woman of loose morals. mua bum. saqa, saqata . v. to oppose, go against. saqata na nona vakatutu oppose his/her proposal. verb normally used the transitive form saqata. saqata . n . a space little used (part of a room, house, village, nearby bush). saqata . n. space in between two things. internode (of a plant with nodes, such as bamboo, yaqona. syn. tagau, tagona. saqata . n . road.
. n. slender palm tree sp., pritchardia pacifica, red fruit, common around november, is not eaten ,
. n. by extension, the similar areca palm nut ("betel" nut), introduced to fiji. fij ians do not
nut. that is a custom of some western melanesians, mainly solomon islanders and some
in fiji. betel is actually the name of the pepper (piper betle) leaf that is chewed with lime powder and the areca nut.
adj . withered, shrivelled, of vegetation, cloth , person ’s features.
v. to grab.

. just, which can imply "at once ", immediately, when it follows a verb. lako sara mada just go (at once). vodo sara ena waqa get on board the boat right away. nanuma sara tiko just thinking about it.
. following an adjective, sara means "very ". levu sara very big. totolo sara very fast. na ka sara
the very thing i am thinking
. absolutely, thoroughly. e sega sara ni dua e namaka. absolutely no one expected it. sa mate sara. he/she/it is quite dead.

n . boar, i.e., a male pig. sara, saramaka v. go through and under (as in the bush), push something under and through. in colo east this become saramake. wa sara a wild starch-food tuber usually eaten raw. it has a furry stem that penetrates the underbrush, growing close to the ground. this is almost certainly the same as yaka or wa yaka, pueraria lobata, fabaceae

n. small silver edible fish, atheridinae sp., that schools seasonally close to shore, often used as bait by commercial fishermen. schools scatter when disturbed and may regroup elsewhere. levuka people are sometimes jokingly referred to as bati sara, intimating that sara is one of their favourite foods. sara, sarava v. to look, to gaze at. sarasara ga just looking (with no other intention), browsing (shopping). vale ni sarasara n. stadium for spectators (for sports functions). siga ni sarasara open day, for the public to visit, as at some public institutions, university, mental hospital.
n. tourist, tourism, a modernism of course.
n. edible reef fish, small, yellow with markings on the sides. lutj anus kasmira. syn. danabe, tanabe. (lau) takabe.
(or) sarisari-na n. rib-cage, ribs (person, animal). syn. saresare-na.

adj . thin, with rib s evident (person, animal). saro, saroya v. to arrange for and set up small sticks, as for supports to yam vines, or small stick s for a fire. this word has a confusing array of meaning but all involve thin stick s.
. n. coconut-leaf midribs, or a broom made of that. fijians normally prefer the sasa broom to

brooms. since coconut did not exist in the highlands, for brooms the people there used branches of makita in colo east, and nuqanuqa or de ni ose at korolevu, navosa. in traditional exchanges between two villages, ten sasa were referred to as one ibe (woven pandanus mat). sasa . n. young barracuda that school near the shore. the school may appear almost stationary but can in an instant move very fast. sphyraena sp. sasa . n. ten woven mats as displayed to be given at ceremonial occasion. sasa . adj . erect or extended to full length or height. tu cake sasa stand up rigidly straight.
(eng.) n. saucer.
. v. to sting, as from a sharp smack , insect bite, a minor burn.
. n. main long section of fish fence by the shore.
v., n. to hunt (usually pigs), with dogs, spears, knife; na vakasasa the pursuit (animal or man) with intent to capture or kill.
v . to bat (as in cricket).
n. anything that serves as protective device: savings account as “nest egg”, insurance policy , safety helmet, bullet-proof vest, cricket bat, good-luck charm. see saba, sabaya.
n. effort, attempt.
v. to make a considerable effort (to achieve or obtain something).
n. cleaning-up, usually a house, mostly sweeping with the sasa broom but may apply to cleaning up a village. na sasamaki e loma ni vale the sweeping within the house.
n. rheumatism. sasala might also imply arthritis since it implies painful joints of the human body.
n. food delicacy, as in sasalu ni waitui seafood delicacies. certain regions are known for their
specialties, village naila, in tailevu, for example, for its bila , kaba in tailevu for the stingray (vai), rewa for its tiny prawns (moci).
n. pursuit (of person) .
v. to pursue (person, animal) in order to capture.
n. fern growing at river banks, thin black stem, edible raw, a delicacy served with prawns. there are two varieties that differ in eating quality.
(ni wai) n. broad category that includes all ferns and fern-like plants, mostly edible, including vuti,

(tree-fern), ota (small edible ferns, cultivated and marketed). sasauni, sasauni-taka v. to do one ’s personal toilet, apply cosmetics, primp. syn. sauni. e sauni koya tiko. she is putting on her make-up (doing her personal toilet). hairdressing and oiling the body were formerly the only type of personal toilet.
n. cosmetics, toilet articles.
n. territorial dependency, this word has been used to refer to the yasayasa vakara, not yet
as a separate confederacy (matanitu), but dependent on kubuna or burebesaga. lakeba
na kena isasavu lakeba and its territorial dependencies (vastly expanded since the time of ma’afu).
(eng.) saucepan.
(eng.) n. sergeant. satini metia sergeant-major.
adv. suddenly. sa vuki vakasauri. it changed suddenly.

. (tonga “hau”) n. traditional social power, as nasau or sauturaga the clan of a tribe that empowers the chief, as elders and protectors of the chief. they can play a role in the selection of the chief. also
the chief in power, the empowered chief. cola sau of a clan, to bear responsibility for
a chief. wa ni sau (or) wa tabu sinnet cord extended from serving bowl tanoa, pointed to person(s) of highest status, seated at yaqona ceremony. one must never cross in front of that cord
at very informal occasions and even then, one must touch the tanoa with the hand in passing, as a mark of respect. the notion of social ceremony serving and drinking yaqona comes from tonga.
. n. originating from tonga via lau and taveuni, a chiefly title in a very few places such as vuna
more properly have remained at kabara. sau corresponds to the tongan hau. roko sau
title at totoya island. gonesau chiefly title in ra province (though referred to as nasau in
native lands commission report that includes ra province). sauvou chiefly title at village vunikodi, udu, macuata province.
. n. a set of specific fijian maladies, unknown to foreigners; one example involves very bad breath
. n., prefix. limit, at the end or back. sauka-na n. outskirts, of village, town, garden . saula n. outside the village, in the bush . na sauloa n. the deep sea, outside the lagoon.
. v. to clap the hands, as for example, a teacher to get attention, or as part of their act, performers
at a meke exhibition dance. na isausau the clapping. this was never done as a form of applause.
. n. response, reciprocal action in response or in reaction. idiom: kemu isau, sa vuni tu. your reward (success) will come in time (though not now apparent), lit. your reward remains concealed.
. n. price. e vica na kena isau? what is the price? sau levu (or) sau dredre expensive. sau
inexpensive. sa lutu sobu na kena isau. the price has been reduced. the commercial

, above, meaning a recriprocal action. sau ni daliga n. earring. formerly, all adults had their ears pierced, often with enlarged holes plugged by a piece of wood or other obj ects. more specifically this archaic practice would now be referred to as sauciqi. missionaries eliminated the custom. modern fashions for women copy europeans: saulili n. earing(s) for pierced ears. saukabi n. earing(s) attached by a clasp. sau, sauca . v. to pierce. sauca na bu pierce the young coconut for drinking. sau, sauca . v. to prick , as in a tattoo, with a tattoo needle iqia. sau, sauca . v. to attempt an abortion by inserting a sharp stick into the uterus. vakalutu gone n. abortion. attempted abortions have been very common in fij i, some by consuming herbal medicines,
target_text: notion of price derives from isau

source_text: by physical means. most of the herbal concoctions are ineffectual or dangerous. collected by

s. certainly the use of the stick is extremely dangerous. saubulu, saubuluta v. to caulk (a boat). this has been done with fibre of coconut husk (bulu), with some glue such as the white sap of the breadfruit tree. na isaubulu the stuff used in caulking.

(eng.) south. “sauca” may be an informal form of address referring to a native of kadavu, a direct translation of naceva, a region of kadavu but also a way of referring to kadavu island which lies to the south of viti levu.
adj . expensive. sau rawarawa inexpensive.
n. outskirts (of village, town). ena sauka kei suva. in the suburbs of suva.
n. (archaic) needle for stitching sails, formerly often made of human shin bone.
n. deep sea, open ocean . syn. wasawasa.
n. hank or skein of sinnet. for formal presentation or sale such skeins of sinnet (magimagi) may be rolled into balls. kava, kavana na magimagi.
. to answer (question, letter). na saumi taro the answering of questions. na sasaumi taro the anwering of continued questions.

. to respond, as with revenge or reciprocal act of kindness. sauma . to pay (in reciprocity for something), pay with money. sauma lesu (ang.) to pay back (money usually). na itavi era saumi kina the job they are paid for (paid to do). na sausaumi vakalalai
installment payments. na matai ni veisaumi n. the first payment of wages (or other incoming money). na siga ni veisaumi n. payday. na veisaumi n. the pay, payment. na imatai ni
n. the first payment (outgoing payment, as in hire-purchase). na saumi rumu the roomrent.
. v. flip lengthwise, turn end over end, somersault. na isausaumaki the short pandanus leaves used for finishing the weaving of a mat, turning them end-for-end .
. v. to convert to religion. tamata saumaki n. people converted to religion.
v. to chew or crunch noisily. syn. namunamu.
v. to pay off a loan.
n. iguana. two species in fiji, the banded iguana (brachylophus fasciatus) and the crested
(b . vitiensis), though the two species may yet be recombined. among the banded iguana,
the male is banded, with green and grey bands, while the female is totally green. the species

only in fiji and tonga and the early origin of any iguana is certainly from the very distant continent of america. the crested iguana was discovered by john gibbons in . both species eat plants, including fruit and flowers, as well as insects. eggs are laid in damp ground usually at the
of trees, where they spend much of their time. iguanas are found in yasawa and mamanuca
and rarely on viti levu. (in the namosi jungle at wainadoi i have observed a major breeding
only ever seen the iguanas there twice.) they are often immobile, camouflaged, and may be high up in forest vegetation. a wildlife sanctuary has been established for the crested iguana

to pay the chief of the native landowners, the buli raviravi, a “goodwill” and informal lease payment of f$ a year, which was increased to $, in and formalized as a contract with the national trust. a final lease was formalized after a further necessary $, payment was
to the landowning unit in the year . syn. vokai, as used by some fij ians, but vokai
refers only to the forest gecko, much more commonly seen in the bush than iguanas are.
geckos are a smaller reptile of which there are several species in fij i, some as long as seven inches. most were commonly eaten by viti levu highlanders. the two common household lizards
to as moko. few fijians are familiar with the word saumure. fewer have ever seen one.

paid. saumi oti already paid. na rakavi saumi professional rugby. na veivacu sega ni saumi amateur boxing. na veika sega ni saumi free things. na icurucuru e sega ni saumi the entrance is free. see sauma.
n. payment(s), as in making payments for hire-purchase goods. vakadei ni sausaumi deposit on payment.
n . the payment, payroll, giving of wages.
v. to put on cosmetics, lip stick, comb the hair, use hair dye, hair grease, face powder, body oil, perfume. e sauni koya tiko. she is putting on her make-up, putting the finishing touches in her
toilet. na sasauni the cosmetics, toilet article. in early times cosmetic attention was only
given to the hair with dyes, bleaches and attention to lice. in areas of polynesian influence,
applied to a woman ’s face and body as a cosmetic for special occasions. syn, sasauni-taka.
see sauna.
v. to oppress, to force (someone).
adv. suddenly.
v . to blink (eyes), twinkle (stars), flicker (lamp).
n. physical limit or border of almost any kind, garden, compound, path.
n. record (athletics), formerly a spot where a reed might be stuck into the ground indicating the
was thrown. it indicates a limit. cavu isausau v. to beat the record.
target_text: distance a sporting j avelin itiqa

source_text: v. to clap, applaud. this is an introduced custom.
v. to flip over, tumble over.
(archaic) n. vine, rhizomorpha, formerly used for making skirts for men or women, as
by botanist seemann. before the introduction of cotton cloth, sausauwai and pieces of plantain leaf were the commonest clothing for adults. there were no undergarments. syn. waloa.
prefix implying continued motion, often from sudden energy, as in sauta-kurekure vibration (from kure to shake), sauta-ninini and sauta-ribariba.
n. chiefly graveyard. in pre-colonial times there were no graveyards or burial sites except in
of strong polynesian influence. bodies of important men were often buried within their own
for fear of body parts being taken for witchcraft. sometimes bodies were hidden away in caves. there were no elaborate funeral actions except for chiefs, when it was mainly a matter of

of wives and chopping of little fingers. for most fijians there was no such thing as a formal funeral ceremony. elderly people, disabled people, no longer productive in society were often secluded in some remote place and left to die. veisau, veisautaka v. to change, to exchange. veisau n. change, as of clothes. sa veisau na gauna. times have changed.
n. change (as of clothes); change (in coins or bills) after a purchase. veisau-vosa v. to answer back, especially as of a child, impolitely, after being scolded.
(eng.) n., v. shout (drinks). a word used only in town.
n. peace, prosperity . na veisaututaki the pacification, bringing about peace and prosperity.
n. functional role of certain clans to empower and protect the chief. these are elders of the

or tribe who have a senior function in choosing the chief and installing the chief. sau implies chiefly power. cola sau to be responsible for carrying on duties in support of the chiefly power. sauva v. to stake out some limit or boundary, as in the archaic sport veitiqa, or in gardening.
n. chiefly title at village vunikodi, udu, macuata.

(colo east) adj . crazy. syn. lialia. sava, savata v. to wash it. sovu ni savasava laundry soap. sovu ni sili bath soap. na sava isulu the laundry. vunisava functional duty of certain clans to be custodians of chiefly burials, especially the
of four nights (bogi va) in the house of the deceased. within that house they are in charge,
yaqona even before the chieftain. food, plates, blankets brought to them during this time remains their property .
n. laundry, washing (clothes, things) sovu ni savasava laundry soap . misini ni savasava washing machine.
adj . clean. the word now also applies to moral conduct.
n. cleansing, referring to conduct that fij ians often believe will gain them favour
to travel. it may also curb all smoking and drinking of yaqona. see nai lalakai, april, , p. .
adj . extremely clean, already well cleaned, village compound, clothes washed, teeth brushed.
n. a methodist notion of cleansing old devil influences by means of religious services, and yielding up of all old fijian artefacts, club s, spears, tanoa bowls, wooden food bowls,
barkcloth, whale teeth that might have been related to devilish practises. some fijians believe
a cleansing improves the school performance of their children and many other aspects of their
life, bringing them good fortune, bringing them into god’s good graces. wainibuka went

such a cleansing in the year . preacher jokatama rabukuivalu has been a leader of this movement. save n. weak child when a second child has been born too soon after the other. fijians have believed there should be a gap of at least two years between children to allow for adequate breast feeding.
. v. to hang down, as of a rope or vine, to drip, flow down of water or other liquid, oil, mucus from the nose.
. n. waterfall. savusavu set of waterfalls. bari ni savu cliff or edge of a waterfall.

. (in measurement or counting) “and then some”. na vale oqo sa katu lima ka savu na kena balavu ka katu tolu ka savu na kena kubu. this house is five fathoms long and a little more, with a gable that is a little more than three fathoms. savu is an unspecified remainder, or an additional amount. savu, savuya . v. to rinse, splash water on (some part of the body, something) usually to clean it, using the hands. savuya na yavana. wash the feet. sasavui wash the feet. see sevu, sevuya, sevuka. idiom: vakasavu liga (anglicism) uninvolved, ineffectual, idle, wash one ’s hands of any responsibility . idiom: vakasavu itukutuku pour out a story, give a verbal report.
. (eng.) submarine. syn. waqanunu, samarini.
. (eng.) diving goggles. syn. savumarini.
n. sandy shore, usually where boats are beached. sawana is a place-name of a tongan village
to lomaloma, vanua balavu island. ratu sukuna decided to incorporate these tongans as a fijian tribe, officially registered as fijians with claims for the land they occupied. by they had
adopted fijian language of lau. they are descendants of the ma’afu retinue that simply
the land. some of their land claims are disputed by fijians. sawani is a place-name on the waimanu river, location of adi cakobau school.
adj . handsome.
adj . soaking wet, drenched, as of fur or hair, leaves and other vegetation, woven mat, mattress and perhaps clothes.
n. natural fringe, of a woven mat, with the edging shredded into thin slices of the pandanus leaf. such a mat is said to be vakasavusavu.
(root-word) bright, as in serau.
(root-word) v. to flee, go astray. ise ni ivalu refugees of war. see sese, sesewa, sevaki.
. verbal particle that occurs only immediately before a verb, indicating a natural continuity of

action or state of being, present tense, or something that may continue. eratou se moce tiko. they (few) are sleeping. au se tabu tiko na tavako. i am ab staining from smoking. se . or. seu lako se sega. if i go or not. seu is sometimes written se ’u. se . whether, as in au sega ni kila se vinaka se ca. i don ’t know if it is good or bad. na nomu lako se sega e vakatau vei iko. whether you go or not is up to you. se . particle preceding cava, “what”, in certain contexts. se cava ? is it not so? (lit. or what?). e sega ni kila o seru se cava me cakava. seru did not know what to do. se . v. to flee. seba would apply usually to a group of people fleeing off in various directions. se . v. to stand on end, as in se na votona to have one’s body-hair stand on end, as in shock or fear. se, seva v . to foam, or spray, as the top of waves or wavelets.
n. (archaic ) bowl of wood or clay, usually used by priests for kava or for oil. see dari. se, sei v. to flower (of plants). senikau n. flower.
(or) seila (ni mata-na) n. cataract of the eye, glaucoma.
n. flower. se ni kau n. flower. sei n. flower of the pandanus palm, which happens to be the sacred plant totem of some highland tribes in viti levu.
(eng.) share(s), as in shares of a corporation, or co-op, owned by shareholders.
n. fan-dance by women, standing, originating from tonga.
n. pinkish edible worm thought to be found only at village tiliva, nakasaleka, kadavu, at damp places on sandy beach , cooked with taro leaves as a local delicacy.

. faded, of colour usually. sa seavu na buto. the darkness is "fading", i.e., dawn is approaching. syn. siawa, seawa. seavu . relieved, dissipated, of emotion or concern such as anger or sorrow, fog or mist. e seavu nona vakatitiqa. his doubts were relieved.
v. to cause to fade away, alleviate.
n. saltwater mist or light spray.
v. to smile openly (showing the teeth).
v. to come apart, separate, split, go their separate ways (people). erau dui seba. they () went their

ways; they parted, separated. era veisebayaki. they all scattered, went off in various directions. vakaseba, vakaseba v. to separate, take apart. secala n. a bird, kingfisher. syn. lesi. (west) lele. (rewa) semoli.

. (eng. cent) cent, and by ext. money, wages. the one-cent and two-cent coins were dropped from circulation beginning in late . e lima na sede. five cents. idiom: gunu sede social gathering for a money-making purpose with sale of cups of yaqona. a person

and names who must drink. if they do not wish to drink, they must pay. this “forces” people to drink too much yaqona and/or give money for the cause at hand. idiom: adi sede modern community festival of competitive giving to raise money among groups, each
by a “queen”. distinguished guests are invited who will presumably make substantial contributions.
. (eng. scent) perfume, as used by women.
(eng.) n. centimeter.
(archaic) n. traditional clay bowl used in certain coastal areas where clay was available and potters
the skill. virtually all of fiji pottery was inspired or made by people of tongan origin. in various areas, sedre referred to a wooden bowl. see dari traditional bowl, usually of wood.

. no, not. au sega ni kila i do not know. sega sega sara ga most certainly not. sega vakadua never. warai or wara are common regional synonyms. (kadavu) mino. (rewa) segai or sigai. (nadro.) hikai. (navosa) j ikai.
. well, . . . (an introductory word at the beginning of a sentence before expressing a thoughtful comment, usually in response to a question).
emphatically no, no, on the contrary. sei, seia (or) seya v. to tear something lengthwise, such as cloth.

adj . bright, clean stark white (colour), shiny, lustrous. applies to cloth, barkcloth, plastic, seafoam, some woven articles, teeth, the moon itself at times, and snow (if a fij ian were to talk about snow). the colour vulavula, usually translated as “white”, can include off-white and even a slightly yellowish white like the moon, vula.
v. to make shiny, glossy (as of the hair, with glycerine).
(archaic) skirt (liku) made of split leaves of plantain (vudi) as used formerly by men and women before the advent of cotton cloth.
(eng.) adj . secondary (of school). syn. sekedri.
(eng.) n . secretary.
(eng.) n. section.
n. second (of time).

n. lit. “golden flower”, flamboyant tree, poinciana, delonix regia, caesalpinaceae, that flowers brilliant red in december. this in not to be confused with the introduced african tulip tree (p isip isi)
reddish flowers throughout the year and has become a great nuisance, hard to eradicate. se flower. koula gold.

v. to have “goose pimples”, especially when one senses a spirit around, to have a tingling of the nerves, perhaps to the hair stand on end, to have an erie feeling. kutu bug. sele, seleta (or) seleva v. to cut (with a sharp instrument, formerly usually a sharp strip of bamboo or sharp shell, then a razor blade), to circumcise young boys, to operate surgically, or modernly , to castrate animals. na sele n. the steer (castrated bull), or other castrated animal. sele gutuva v. to cut off short(er), usually of a rope or vine. see sili, teve for circumcise.
n . surgery (medical).

v. cut it up finely . isele n. knife. this often means a cane knife, as used in gardening. iseleloki pocket knife. isele cariba n. j ack-knife, switch-blade knife. isele ni cici-niu n. knife for cutting copra. isele ni ta raisi n. sickle,
stalk s. aboriginal fijians had no knives other than shells or slivers
target_text: knife with curved blade to cut rice

source_text: insignia. they test it by knocking it with their knuckes to hear it ring. they speak of that ringing sound being melo, sweet-sounding at a high pitch . syn. (tonga) hele.

(anglicism) n. sword, lit. “knife used as a club”. the wooden “swords” sold to tourists are a commercial invention that have nothing to do with fijian tradition. tourists are harrassed to buy this trash. itawatawa n. sheath (as for a sword or a sheath-knife). iwau war club.
n. sherlock holmes, implying a smart detective. one fijian detective, adopted this name and
. n. patch (for joining things, parts of boat, house, clothing).

. n. joint or seam where two thing are joined, as in carpentry, clothing, human/animal body. by extension, connection between two or more events or things, people or places. isema ni sala junction (of road or path). na isemasema n . the joining. see bota-na patch. keda isema kei rotuma. our (many) connection(s) with rotuma.
n. conjunction in fijian grammar: kei and, ia ka but, ni of, etc. this word was invented by schoolteachers who teach fij ian grammar using only the fijian language.
adj . patched-up in many places. vale semasema patchwork house, made of pieces put together.
n. semi-finals of some sport tournament, such as rugby.
(eng.) semi-colon “;”, as used in punctuation.
(eng.) n. senate. seneta n. senator.
(eng.) n. century. syn. seniteneri.
n. flower.

n., adj . pink (colour), colour of the loli fig tree flowers. se ni nawanawa n., adj . dark yellow or orange (colour), like the flowers of the nawanawa tree that grows around the coast and thus a word not used by highlanders.
(eng.) n. centenary. na seniteneri refers to the centenary methodist church in suva. syn. senitenari, senij iuri.
n. hibiscus rosasinensis, malvaceae, decorative flower-bush, european introduction, many

developed, some with double or triple blooms. the hybrids are much more difficult to propagate. at the annual hibiscus festival in suva during august, a “queen” is selected, named as adi senitoa. crushed leaves are used as a gelatinous hair conditioner.
n. edible seaweed that looks like noodles.
(eng.) n. spoon. anciently, fijians had the concept of ladles but not of spoons. no utensils were normally used for eating. syn. itaki.

adj ., v. to gleam, to shine brightly, bright, gleaming (stars, reflection, lamp, but not the sun). sere, sereva, serevaka v. to sing. sere n. song. seretaka (or) serevaka v. to sing about (some person or occasion, or topic). serevi ira na saravanua sing for the tourists. sere ni meimei song to pacify a baby. sere ni moce lullaby. sere ni lotu church hymn. sere ni cumu singing of a group of men
in a circle, facing inward toward each other, face lowered, typical in the village. na dau ni
the singer (usually the person who leads the singing), or conductor. matasere choir. ivola ni
hymnbook. sere ni matanitu national anthem. same psalm(s).
(archaic) n. fijian type of verse usually commemorating some occasion or offering praise.
composed, in rhyming couplets, fij i-fashion of rhyming, in simplest form, in verses now
written in four to six lines each . traditionally recited at home, at rest, sometimes to keep
and sleep. kali refers to the wooden neck-rest that formerly served as a pillow

shop, to divorce (of married couples). na veisere n. the divorce (of a married couple). viebiu v. to be separated (of a couple). n. former spouse. sere dali v., n. to let go the mooring (usually of a boat). idiom: sa sere na koli. literally, the dog is let go (off the leash), but by extension referring to people suddenly freed from restriction or discipline who may act a little wild. sere, sereka, serelaka . v. to reveal in detail, set out the details in an explanation, to explicate.
(ni vuli) n. school holiday(s). sereki vakayabaki annual holidays. sereki ni siganisucu christmas holiday(s). sereki macawa rua two-week s holiday.
(eng.) n. soursop, annona muricata, annonaceae, introduced fruit tree, seldom eaten by fijians
n. breast, chest.

(eng. sydney) the city of sydney but also several varieties of pineapple of the smooth cayenne type, larger than the older, more familiar ripley queen types, and with fewer prickles on the leaves (and thus easier to handle). there are about three types of serene pineapple differing in size, colour of fruit at maturity, and the presence or ab sence of tiny seeds.
(archaic) n, traditional form of singing chant, now long forgotten by virtually all fijians. formerly, usually performed by one man in a relaxed position, even lying down, sometimes joined by

and unique to that occasion, thoughts that pass throught the performer ’s mind, with no rhyming necessary . there may be tacit messages in the content but nothing will be discussed later by the performer. (there might be an analogy with the concept of modern-day “rap” by predominantly black american performers, though serevasi is not performed in an excited state.) the occurence of
is after some task that required exertion, such as weeding, or digging a drainage ditch . it is
at a period of relaxation. an audience of sorts might gather around and listen, silently. the old
vasi implies a cleaning off, or peeling off the surface or skin of some food, and is thus used

or symbolically in the word serevasi. it is also used for removal of fish flesh from the bones. solo bulicokooko discusses serevasi at length with me. he wrote a small book serekali and serevasi, lotu pacifica, , pp., illustrating both concepts. semiti kaisau wrote briefly about serevasi in essays on pacif ic l iterature, fiji museum, , p. . but kaisau speaks of the serevasi as being sacred which is probably not at all a necessary component. seru, seruta (polynesia) v. to comb . syn. kava (an earlier fij ian word). serutavi, serutavia comb and pat
shape (head of hair). tavi, tavia to pat with the hand. ulu medre entangled hair (that needs combing). syn. (rewa, kadavu) vani, vania.

(polynesia) n. comb . formerly, keeping a comb in the hair was a mark of chiefly rank or warrior prowess. originally this was a single spike, partly as a head-scratcher, and means of loosening tight coils of hair. syn. ikava. iserukau n. wooden comb fiji style with long prongs, a concept introduced
in the s, according to fergus clunie. iserutaku tortoise-shell comb (lit. turtle-shell),
style for soft hair, these days made of plastic. the honorific name seru was granted to
of distinction. now it is a common first name as most fijians have adopted the english
a first name and a surname. na iseruseru the combing, manner or style of combing. syn. (rewa, kadavu) ivani.
v. to go astray, to be lost (person).
adj . foolish, scatter-brained, of a person.
n. a common coastal bird, the kingfisher, more commonly known as lesi.

adj . n. scatter-brained, unthinking, weak-willed, stupid, going astray. au sa sesewa sara koi au i have been stupid, made a bad mistake. “set!” (eng.) set ! everything is ready, everything is okay. it is as good as done. i understand what is to

done and will do it. often heard as “set tiko !” everything okay, ready. a very modern (early ), and perhaps fleeting expression is “i ’m set with digicel !”, parroting a digicel commercial slogan. this is said within the context of youngsters’ fijian speech.
(eng.) n. satan. p ielisip up i beelzebub. syn. (r. catholic) satani. seti! exclamation of mild reproach.

if i, a contraction of se au, as in a statement seu lako se sega. commonly seen as se ’u. seu, seuta v. to scratch, as a hen does, or a dog pawing the ground for a resting place. also, to scoop, as one might scoop sand with the hand. seseu such action emphatic or continued.
v. to walk hurriedly , in great haste. there is an implication of kicking up sand or dust with fast steps.
v. to scamper, run off, run away. e ra seuta ni ra sa raica na ovisa. they ran away as soon as they saw the police officer.
adj . choppy (of the sea), a word often heard in nautical weather forecasts.
v. to found, establish for the first time, initiate, as in founding a new village. new villages are sometimes named seuvou, or similarly, korovou.
v., adj . to err, to be wrong, incorrect, tangled up. rogoseva, rogosevata to mishear. wiliseva,
to miscount, misread. sa seva na noqu wiliwili. i lost count (perhaps interrupted by something). sa seva na noqu wa ni siwa. my fishing line is tangled.
v. to mislead or fool someone. seva, sevaka v. to hate, despise, rej ect totally, expel, send away . sevaki n., adj . outcast, exile.
v. to banish, banished, to avoid, as of an objectionable person.
(eng.) n. september.
. n. the first time something has happened.
. n. first-fruits, presented to the chief, formerly to priests, but modernly to the church. vula isevu
(lunar) of first fruits, around february. sevu, sevutaka v. to “break in”, to do something or use something for the first time.
n. presentation of yaqona root (waka) or rhizome (lewena) in a ceremony of introduction or greeting by a visitor. the root is stronger in lactones, more expensive, and much more prestigious. in
especially, where very little yaqona is grown, it is unacceptable to present lewena. sevusevu

v. to arrive without bringing a isevusevu of kava. sevu, sevuya (or) sevuka v. to splash water (on something), often the face, to refresh. idiom: gunu sevusevu drink from the hands by splashing water up to the face.
n. pectoral fin(s) of a fish .
or vakasewasewana v. to belittle, to demean. (from the western word for “little” sewa.)
. as in e si. i do not know (in answer to a question of fact).
. n. semen, male sperm. kaisi low-class commoner, an insult. syn. wai (ni tagane).
v., adj . to fade in colour, faded, light in colour.
n. elephantiasis of the thigh and female genital area.
. n. trochus niloticus, edible, univalve marine shellfish, conical in shape, the shell gathered
for export, used in manufacture of buttons. locally used to make bracelets. a similar,

trochus is the tovu, t . pyramsis. the name sici applies to at least a couple of edible freshwater univalve shellfish. in freshwater is the small, edible sicimoto, melanoides sp. small in long sharp shape. syn. (lau) vilivili, leru, (vuda, nadro.) tebetebe. (west) cici. idiom (children): memu sici! you got what you deserved ! syn. kemu maleka!

. n. whistle (sports, police), horn (motor vehicle). uvu, uvuca na sici blow the whistle. bitu sici n. a var. of bamboo, with very thin stem, from which children might make a whistle. in western viti levu, worn by chiefs, there existed some whistles (ikalu) made of miniature coconut shell blown from the end, with a hole on the side. see photo, f. clunie, yalo ni viti, fiji museum, page , item .
n. roll of voivoi (pandanus sp.), some leaves, that is sold in the market. it is used for weaving mats. best to check inside the roll for consistent quality.
n. piles (malady), painful sores at the rectum. sicini(dakai) n. bullet, shotgun cartridge.

n.,v. day, to be shiny or lit with the sun, sunshine, sunlight. e na siga cava ? on what day? e na siga moniti. on monday. ena siga ka tarava on the following day. mata ni siga n. sun. dausiga drought, lit. continual sunshine. dravusiga drought, parched (land). siga ni lewa judgement day.
tabu sunday, sabbath. siga tabu ni gone palm sunday. siga ni mate good friday. siga ni
cake easter sunday. siga ni sucu christmas day. vanua sigasiga sunny place. siga dakuna (lau) thursday. siga vakaoti vola (lau) friday. siga cokonaki (lau) saturday. na nodratou
their (several) best wishes for xmas. idiom: mokusiga kill time by doing nothing, waste time.
(lau, tonga) saturday. cokonaki refers to gathering food for sunday.

to continue till daylight. e sigalaka na noqu cakacaka. my work continued until daylight. syn. sigavaka. sigalevu n. noon, but in “fiji time”, extending from late morning to to mid-afternoon. sigalevu tutu high noon. sigalevu tutu donu exactly high noon. idiom: kila vakasigalevu know very clearly.

(anglicism) n. lunch. fijians formerly ate only two meals a day, one in the morning (katalau), and one at dusk (vakayakavi). there was no formal midday meal. working in their gardens, people might take snacks from garden food. vakasiga, vakasigana v. to sun out (something), set out to dry in the sun. me vakasigani sun it out.
idiom: when it is raining, to take shelter and wait for the sun. ena uca, au a laki
ena vale. in the rain i took shelter in the house. to continue doing something till daylight.
v., adj . to shine very brightly, of the sun. ulu sigasiga blond hair. mata sigasiga dazzled by

light, either the sun, when emerging from a dark place, or by a bright torch shining in one’s eyes at night. siga tabu n. sunday. sigatabu ni gone palm sunday. siga ni tucake tale easter sunday. siga-tara n . weekday , including saturday , when methodists allow work (excluding sunday). sigavaka v. begin something in the night and continue through till daytime (dancing, work).
(lau) wednesday.
n. very small, edible marine bivalve shellfish found in the shallows at sunny, sandy beaches, eaten especially by children. atactodea sp. or donax. syn. qeqe.
facial features showing the teeth, such as smiling or grimacing. could apply to a person, dog or
animal with the teeth exposed. may even apply to a corpse. the word can refer to the vagina
of this double meaning the word is best avoided. there is some sort of twisted joke in very bad taste referring to the vagina as having teeth or rather, not having teeth.
(eng.) n. cigar, usually hand-made by the smoker just before smoking it, though the custom is giving
(in town), and thin, rolled cigarettes of native tobacco with a newspaper
(in the villages). the tobacco tavako ni viti is very strong, locally grown. tibi, tibika na sika v. to roll the cigar. tobacco and the notion of smoking anything was introduced by europeans and
quickly adopted especially by men. in the solomons adult women also smoked, particularly using pipes. fij ians never adapted to pipes.

. adj . protruding, sticks out (only in certain contexts). bati sika has teeth that stick out, gusu sika has protruding mouth, and by extension an insult for a person who cannot keep a secret. idiom: maga sika! very vulgar insult, “protruding female genitals!”

. v. a root word meaning to appear, become visible as in sa basika na waqa the boat has come into sight. sika . n . grey, of hair. sa sika na ulu-qu. my hair is grey. sika droka prematurely grey-haired. idiom: sika vakabeka. old, but young in spirit. sika, sikava v . to splash , to spurt, of a liquid (water, oil, blood). tasika to spurt abruptly, suddenly, forcefully, as of a bursting water pipe.

formal traditional presentation of newborn eldest child to relatives, usually four nights after birth. sika, sikava v. to spew out, spray, splash. sikavi au mai na wai splash water on me. na sisika the splashing. na sikasika the spray (seaspray , rain , farm spray). idiom: gusu sikataka (or) dau gusu sika loudmouth, gossip, spread rumours. idiom: sa sikava na waitui idiom about the people at levuka, lakeba, as they formerly helped
to others’ goods; as saltwater sailors they were figuratively spraying their salt water on landlubbers’ goods.
v. to slip, stumble and fall down suddenly. lutu to fall.
(eng.) scrum (rugby).
n. (lau, vanua levu) candlenut fruit of coastal tree, aleurites moluccana, dried nuts formerly strung on a coconut-leaf midrib, used as lamps by fijians around the coast and on some of the islands,
not interior highlanders of vit levu. syn. lauci. polynesians introduced the notion of making
from the nut, and of eating the nut after cutting up and thorough cooking, particularly used
a condiment in the small islands. uncooked, the nut is highly purgative. the dried nuts are
to a shiny black, strung as a necklace for sale to tourists, an idea adapted from hawaii ’s tourist trade. sikele to be sleepy during daytime, usually from failing to sleep at night.

(eng.) cigarette, a very formal word, written but hardly ever spoken. normally one would say “roll”, using that english word, or the fiians version itibi tavako or some variation of that. tibi, tibika v. to roll a cigarette or cigar from pandanus-palm (balawa) leaf or plaintain leaf as suluka. koula refers to benson & hedges cigarettes because of the gold (koula) package.

adj . of bivalve shellfish, full of good edible meat. siki, sikira, sikiraka v. to shift (usually something heavy, or oneself). na sikisiki the shifting, of heavy things such as furniture, cases or boxes of food, sacks of goods. syn. kisi. siki, sikita v. to slip, perhaps by stepping on something squishy (mud, fruit), usually accidentaly.
(ground, path, road). sikiti trodden upon and squashed.
v. to slip up, to slip down. syn. tidara.
(eng.) n. scheme, plan, project.
(eng.) n., v. signal. for fijians this can be a discreet, private signal indicated with the eyes, a slight word, a seemingly casual touch. such secretive, personal signals are common.
n. type of fij ian puddin of grated ivi nut, polynesian chestnut. syn. koko.
v. to look, as in checking on people.

n., adj . grey (of the hair). siko, sikova v. to visit someone or (less commonly) some place. siko vanua visit (a place). veisiko visiting. sikova na dai visit the trap(s) to check and see if something has been caught. na siko dai the checking of traps. idiom : a siko! ah, a visitor !
