(a tiko! used when discovering that someone is already here). idiom : sa vaka na siko dai. just like checking the (animal) trap, with frequent regular visits, implying that the visitor is perhap s too pressing, too frequent. veisiko n., v. to visit, to go visiting, usually unannounced. na noqu veisiko ki jap ani. my visit to japan. na noqu sikovi jap ani. my visiting japan.
(eng.) n. scholarship. sila . n . j awbone. sila ecake upper j aw. sila era lower j aw.
. n . sheet, of a sail. sorosila (or) soro, sorova na sila v . to let out the sheet (to sail before the wind). sila, silava v. to sheet in the sail, to haul it in . sila mai! sheet in !
n.maize. originally this word referred to job's tears, coix lacryma-jobi, aboriginally introduced
edible grain with a hard shell, used as a snack by fij ians, and modernly strung as necklaces,
for tourists. no food grain was ever used as a staple by fijians. sweet corn is virtually

in fiji because it requires the purchase of imported seed for each planting. introduced by europeans, field maize is used as animal feed, but also sold boiled, unhusked as a snack food at the market or at sporting events. idiom: voci vaka-sila . to understand something by taking one step at a time, as in peeling off the skin of a cob of maize to reach the kernels. sili, silima . v. to bathe in shallow water, gather from shallow water. sili kai mussel-gathering. silima

kai to gather the mussels. sili dri to gather, dive for dri. sisili bathing . era sa sisili tiko na gone. the children are bathing. veisilimi swimming for fun (qalo swim with a purpose). wai ni sili n. bathing-water. wai ni sili n. creek used mainly for bathing. silivata to swim with (clothing worn, knife, warclub, other person). laki sisili ki na savu to go swimming at the waterfall. lai sili to go

(for fun, not purposeful swimming). purposeful swimming would be qalo. idiom: silima na gau ni dali. to interfere, to butt into a conversation. idiom: sili vakaivavalagi to bathe by rubbing the body with a wet towel rather than bathing in the water. this may be done in cold weather or when the water is very cold.
. v. to treat a woman as for fallen womb, by feeling with the hand, usually of an older woman, for a woman who is seated in a stream.
. v. to circumcise (males). syn. teve, sele. female circumcision is unknown. male circumcision is thought necessary.
(eng.) n. ceiling (of a building).
(eng.) n. silk. may be a woman's name.
(archaic) n. type of warclub that can be hidden in the loincloth when swimming, used to fight while standing in the water.
(eng. shilling) (obsolete) n. money. since metric money has been adopted, the term has become
(cent), meaning money or wages in an informal sense, as with casual workers.
(eng.) n. silver. by ext. may refer to silver medals in athletics.
adj . ashamed of wrong-doing, or failure. syn. madua, vela, dranu.
n. plaited coconut or other leaves serving to block a doorway, or other purposes of shelter or cover. fijians had no attached, swinging doors.

(eng.) n. cement, cement block. vale simede cement-block house. simedetaka v. to cement it. idiom: simede balavu n., adj . person who has not had sex for a long time. the implication is that one feels heavy, and needs to unload the burden that feels like cement. idiom: lai tala na simede to go have sex (after long ab stinence). literal meaning refers to unloading of cement. used for men or women.
(or) hina n. (nadro, west) reed. syn. gasau.
adj . quite full (of a container). sisinai absolutely filled to the brim. e sinai vutucoqa na loma ni rumu. the room is packed (with people). vakasinai, vakasinaita v. to fill it completely full.
(bau, now rare) n. dissension.

n. “true” sinu, phaleria disperma, thymelaceceae, coastal shrub to feet, terminal fls, usually solitary, fruit to inch x . inches, two seeded. sinu gaga n. poisonous sinu, excoecaria agallocha, euphorbiaceae, coastal tree to feet with white latex
adj . cheeky, naughty, interfering or speaking up in matters that are not one’s own concern, acting
of turn. mostly refers to children or people of junior status. see siova. syn. ciocio, ciqobaca. (lau) ciobilo. (rewa) qalisua.
v. to interfere in or with , to meddle in. kua ni siova na p olitiki. don ’t meddle in politics.

(eng.) n . sheep, mutton. urban fij ians today eat a great deal of n .z. mutton, tinned or frozen, usually lamb neck and lamb chops. a local breed of sheep has been developed but is not common and the meat is expensive.
(eng.) n. speaker (of legislative body). syn. sivika .

(eng.) n. singlet, men's undershirt. siqeleti domo coko turtle-neck or high neck singlet. siri v . to disappear suddenly. sa siri oti. it/he/she has already disappeared. idiom: vaka e siri na saku suddenly, lit. the way the saku, tom fish, tylosurus crocodilis, disappears.
(wainimala) v. to slip down, come apart.
"your legs will get knocked out from under you ", said to a man attracted to a highland girl, meaning he will fall hopelessly in love.
target_text: idiom sa na siri na duamu

source_text: v. to avoid someone, from dislike. syn. calata. siro, sirova v. to go down, get down from a higher place to a lower place, such as from a tree, roof, from a porch to the ground, or down a slope, often meaning to go down to the sea-front, to the water. siro mai! come down ! syn. to clamber down, perhap s implying more agility, would be kevu, kevuta. idiom: siro mai n., v. refers jocularly and impolitely to a highlander of viti levu who is in town, probably suva, having literally come down from the hills.
n . beverage such as soup or tea drunk after yaqona. modernly, young people are more likely to
a “washdown”, meaning alcohol such as beer or spirits drunk after drinking yaqona. sirovi v. to drink soup or tea after drinking yaqona.
(eng. caesar) v. do a caesarian surgical operation for a mother to give birth.

n. (lakeba, from tonga) garland (salusalu) of flowers and scented leaves attached to an hibiscus-fibre base, worn around the neck , various forms, types. syn. itaube as a general term for necklace. sisi, sisiva v. to slip (on or because of something), slide, skid, ski (as on snow). sisi-buluta v. to bury in a landslide. sa sisibuluta na vale e na uneune. the house was buried under a landslide in the earthquake.
(slang) v. to over-stay illegally in overseas country, usually for employment opportunities.
n. landslide, common on the large volcanic islands especially when the soil is soaked by rain.

are inherently unstable. landslides are a real danger in some areas. houses have been buried. great gashes may be seen in the hilly rainforest where the soil structure has collap sed. landslides are prompted by heavy rain or earthquakes. they have caused human casualties.
v., n. to bribe.
n. v. private and usually very discrete signal between the sexes, indicating attraction and interest. vakasisi, vakasisia v. to cause something to slide.
adj . abominable, as in itovo vakasisila abominable behaviour.
(or) sili v. to bathe. bathing. vale ni sili bathroom, shower-room.
(archaic) v., n. for a new mother, to daub the hair with ashes and then go down to the sea to
(bogi-va) after the birth of her child. syn. sisili e wailevu.
as full as can be. see sinai full.

(eng.) n. sister, of some christian sect, or senior nurse at a hospital or regional clinic. sisiva, sisivataka v. to be jealous. see vuvu. sisivo, as in dau sisivo competitive, envious by nature. syn. vuvu.
(eng.) n. stamp (postage, customs). kasitaba customs. vakabira na sitaba stick on the stamp. also rubber stamp.
(eng.) v., n. to strike (of labour). syn. vakabesebese. (bese refuse).
(eng.) n. staff, sometimes referring to officials, as with qualified nurses sitavu-nasi at hospitals and health clinics.
(eng.) steak, as a cut of beef.
(eng.) station (police). might apply to a petrol station.
. (eng.) n. bedsheet.
. (eng.) n. city.
(eng.) n. steel. sitili ulu n. steel wool. sitili qita n. steel guitar.
(eng.) n. steamship . sitima ni vanua train (locomotive)
(eng.) n. store, shop.
(eng.) n. stocking, sock s.
(eng.) n. stall, as at the market, selling vegetables, fruit.

(eng.) n. stove. me waqa na sitovu. light the stove. me boko. turn it off. many fijians use an inexpensive chinese-made kerosene stove. siu! an interj ection of reproach or outright rej ection. siu, siuva, vakasiuva v. to hiss (steam, owl, cat), hiss at. sa siusiu na vaivo. the pipe is hissing (as with steam).
(eng.) n. shovel. see isivi, a more common expression. see siveti.
n. types of fijian sweet pudding made usually from cassava (formerly taro) and coconut. sivaro vula and sivaro maca are the two types.
(eng.) n. spade, shovel. also applies to spades, as in suite of playing cards.
n. spade, shovel, spade, formerly an adze (only known at the coast, not in the highlands). the cutting

was a shell such as the giant clam vasua. the large bivalve shell pinna swamosa was used as shovel. na i siviyara the plough. is sivi, sivita . to carve (usually wood). na dau sivisivi the woodcarver. this is a polynesian rather than fijian skill. fijians’ woodcarving was mostly for club s and spears and wooden bowls for food or oil.
a modern trade. some warclubs for tourists are faithful copies, as are some

and neck-rests. many other tourist carvings, such as masks, are non-traditional. na isivisivi the wood-chip but also anciently, the adze. sivi, sivita (or) sivia . to go beyond, pass beyond, surpass, exceed. tu sivia n. or v. overstayers, to
(usually referring to a visitor's visa). n i sivi ga e rua na siga. . . when only two days had

. . . sivita na isausau beat the record, as in athletics. lako sivia v. to go past, go too far, go beyond. uasivi special. veisivi v. to compete. na veisivisivi the competition. idiom: sivi na koro qai kalu. do not boast or claim success until you have actually accomplished what you set out to do. lit. do not whistle till you have passed the village. sivi, sivita . to fart. sivi lo n. quiet fart. syn. ci.
too much, too far. rui sivia far too much, much too far. gunu yaqona sivia. drink too much yaqona. vakasivia excessive, excessively. katataka vakasivia excessive heat.
v., n. to compete, competition. competitiveness is a strong fijian characteristic, especially in sports. cf. dau sisivo competitive (of a person's character).
(eng.) n. spring.
n. plough, a modern concept to fijians who formerly used only a digging stick. the word
a shovel isivi being hauled along (yara). usually a bullock does the pulling. siviyarataka v.
(the field).
v. to take inventory , properly sivi iyau.
v. to dismiss, sack, fire, expel, demote (a person) from a position, rank or job. vaka-sivoya v. to
(someone). see sake.
dismissed, sent away, expelled, as of a person from a job, a government from office at a coup, schoolchild for serious misbehaviour.
n. wood chips from chopping or carving.
. n. adze, used with a chopping motion, a shell serving as a blade. the use of stone blades and
metal blades was introduced from polynesia, mainly tonga but also, especially later, samoa, with boatbuilders coming from both places.
. n. style or design, especially of wood carving. siwa, siwata (or) siwava v. to fish with a line, to fish for (a kind of fish). siwa yatu fish for tuna with

and line, trolling. siwa toni still-fishing, often leaving the line overnight, as for eels and river fish. tonia na siwa to leave the fishing line overnight. siwa bogi fish at night. siwa cavocavo to fish with fishing rod. bati ni siwa fish-hook. wa ni siwa fishing line. siwa kolokolo v., n. to fish
fishing grounds (for line fishing and trolling). qoliqoli traditional fishing grounds owned
v. to go fishing. qolilawa v. to fish with a net. the concept of hook and fishing line was
by polynesians. trolling was a specialty of early samoans and gilbertese. fishing rods

thrown from the shoulder were unknown to fijians. boi sisiwa to smell “fishy”, like stale fish. virtually all fij ian fishing was inside the lagoon or rivers, by traps, spears, fish poison, or scarelines. “snake grouper” (eng.) n. syn. kuli-ni-dovu, votoqaninubu, comet grouper, edible fish, epinephelus morrhua, with dark streak s, longitudinally along a dull greenish and white background, supposedly snake-like markings, to cm in length, depths to meters, a large, deep fish caught on line in modern times, not anciently.
v. to simmer (of water, soup), as in me so na wai instructions to simmer the water.
very, as in not very: sega so ni totolo not very fast.

v. to be abundant in clustered amounts, as of certain fruit or nuts in a heavily laden, fruiting tree (mango, dawa, ivi, tarawau). sa so na dawa. the dawa tree is bearing heavily. isoso dawa cluster of dawa fruit.
some (or) some more, as in eso tale some more. eso na tamata some people. eso vei ira some among them. ena so na gauna sometimes.
n. as in na ivakaso ni wai the reservoir of water.
(lau) v . to be apprehensive.
sa v. to be fed up, tired (of hearing), as in au sa so sa na rogoca na ulubale. i am tired of hearing excuses. also written as one word sosa.
n. species of plantain, the “upright banana”, musa fehi or m . trodlogytarum, unique in having fruit
throughout many islands from the coast of papua new guinea to melanesia and polynesia. the fruit is used more by polynesians (such as rotumans), rather than melanesians. it was
a staple in tahiti where it is known as “fe ’i”. there are many varieties, many of them with pinkish flesh. they are normally cooked before eating. syn. dra i turukawa.
n. pumice, occasionally found at sea and on beaches after underwater earthquakes. at times there
amounts. fijians use it for scaping and cleaning as in cleaning cooking pots at the shore.

also been used in upper layers of house foundations, above the stones and below the fern and mats. soba n. the bulbous, purple flower shoot that hangs down on the plantain and banana tree, and remains as
(or) so bi adj . very plentiful, of fruit on a tree or vine. applies to any fruit that is heavily laden on the tree.
down, downwards. muria sobu na uciwai. follow down the river. toro sobu get worse, decline. sobu, sobura v. get down, get off (vehicle, aeroplane, boat). sobu e tauni get off in town.
. n. formal ceremony receiving a chief who has come some distance.
. v. to lay down, as in me vakasobu na duru lay down the housepost. vakasobu na bila lay
the bila (a form of fij ian madrai “bread”) to ferment in food-storge pits (davuke) dug in the ground.
. v. to unload (truck, boat), discharge (cargo).
. v. to get off (or) to let off or to “land” passengers (from boat, plane, motor vehicle). me vakasoburi koya. let him/her off. sobu! sobu! interj ection of reproach, disbelief, regret.

n. cold wind that blows to sea off the highland hills in the very early morning. see caucau. sodo, sodomaka v. to insert, as into a sheath, or a socket, as a knife, electrical plug, or a key in a lock. syn. codo, codomaka, vakacodo.
v. to squeak , creak , a board under heavy weight, a door opening.
adj . disorderly, confused, mixed up. qaqa sodrosodro foolhardy.
n. sago palm, endemic metroxylon vitiense, growing wild in swampy places, mainly around the navua river, noted as endangered species in , cut out mainly by fiji indians for the edible heart,
by the side of the road. fijians have never eaten it. locally in serua and rewa, they used the
as an excellent, durable thatch. no one makes a sage starch powder, or pudding, as in done in
new guinea and solomon islands and northern vanuatu (of related species). this palm
around fifteen years of age, producing a huge terminal flowering panicle some feet in height, with or more branchlets. the round fruit is almost inches long and two inches wide, with

brown scales. the tree dies after fruiting, after some twenty years of age. syn. (ovalau) niu soria. (john parham has the name listed as sogo.) there is a similar, introduced species, m. warburgii that grows mainly on vanua levu island, distinguished with erectly held pear-shaped fruit on a threebranched stalk. sogo, sogota, sogolaka v. to close (it), as of a door, turn it off, as of a tap, or an engine, plug up (clay cooking pot, j ar, bottle), closed in (or out, of people or animals), to stop up (liquid flowing). era a

tu i tuba na tamata cakacaka maivei ira na nodra manidia. the workers (many) were locked out by the managers. isogo n. . plug used to close a container, such as a plug of leaves to close a clay cooking-pot, or cork or
to close a bottle. . door. syn. katuba (or) darava. there were formerly no hinged doors in
houses. entrances were closed off with various plant materials. . closure, the means of closing off something that can be opened and closed, a clasp, a lid of a pot or j ar.
adj ., v. to close up tight, as a house might be closed up. sogolati, sogolatia, sogolatitaka v. to close off (an area, a room, a flow of water), to enclose.
v. to close of a road or path. this is done fairly often by clansmen who feel they have been

outsiders who have leased some of their land, or by the native land trust board that makes lease arrangements and collects payment. sala path , road. see suguvanua. soi, soiya v. to scrape off, usually the skin of some root crop before cooking (taro, yam) or fibre-plant

as voivoi, or barkcloth. formerly this was most often done with a sharp shell (at places around the shore), or a sharp edge of bamboo (in the highlands). na soisoi the scraping (of this sort). soi, soilaka v. to scratch or prick deeply, as of coral, thorny bushes, a needle, or tip of a knife.
n. worship, religious session, meeting for christian worship.
n. crotch, knot (wood), node (on stem or branch of plant such as bamboo, yaqona, cassava). see tagau, tago-na.

v., n. to scream, shriek, squeal loudly as warriors with war cry , people in terror, bat making bat noises, rats squeaking, pig squealing in terror, child squealing with tears. sosokiki lots of shrieking, squealing. idiom: qitoqito vakoli, vuki ga, soki said of children, begin playing like puppies but soon there are
(squeals) when one has been hurt.

n . a man-hole trap dug in olden days, covered lightly with leaves; sharp stakes in the pit will injure the victim. the same technique is still used to trap wild pigs. they can be dangerous to the stranger walking inattentively on a pig trail in the bush.
n. porcupine fish, diodon hystrix, named for the shriek of pain (soki) from being pricked by the spines. length to cm, body grey back, speckled with spots, rounded fins. fish eaten by fijians but

dangerously toxic and rarely if ever by gilbertese who believe they may die from a single broken egg. syn. (tonga) sokisoki. soki, sokia v. to pick by breaking off with a twisting motion (ripe breadfruit for food). the essential
is that of twisting, often done with a pronged stick to reach the height of the fruit. soki uto pick breadfruit. yava soki lame twisted leg (person).
v., n,. adj . wrinkled (clothes, voivoi leaves, barkcloth, human brow), wavy, choppy (sea).
very wrinkled, etc. sokiki n. a distinctive, tall palm of the rainforest, with a very slender trunk and hard wood, formerly used
sail to levuka. soko kosova na toba sail across the bay. soko muria na baravi to sail along
n. a large cultivar of cassava that can be left in ground for up to a year, growing larger, a much longer time than most cassava.
v. to shiver, shake, tremble, to quake (of the body, as from cold or fear). sole, solega v. to wrap, often inside a mat or cloth, such as a sheet. also wrap, as with insulating tape or
tape. the implication is of wrapping around, as a mat is rolled. this wrapping is most

done for clothes, cloth, barkcloth, but also a human body, especially for burial. isole n. shroud, wrapper (usually in cloth or blanket). sole itutuvi to wrap up in a blanket. isolesole n. mat containing items rolled up inside.
v., n. community effort, house-building, planting crops, collecting money, often on a wide and large scale. the word may apply to small group efforts where many hands make light work. the
at any one time can be one nuclear family. the group may take turns helping individual families. this is probably one of the finest features of fij ian culture, when the people can work
at a task that might otherwise be onerous. such occasions are now becoming fewer as threequarters of the fijian population lives in towns, cities, or suburbs syn. (lau) balebale.
v. to work together on a proj ect as a community. see solesolevaki, sosolevaki, synonyms or closely related concepts.
. n . traditional exchange of goods between two villages. people in the highlands might acquire
pots and mats, or salt, while those in the lowlands receive yaqona. today the custom is much
common and its purpose is now almost exclusively social, with festivities, dancing, feasting, to
community relations. these events have been very important in re-affirming peaceful relations among different rural communities.
. n. presentation of goods at traditional ceremony soli, solia v. to give. solia mai! give it here ! solia vei iratou give it to them (few). solia na
give permission (such usage is direct translation of the english , not traditional usage).
give it as a gift. solia na matana ca to give a bad look. solia na liga-na me lululu.

the hand to shake (hands). soli bula v. to be ready to give one’s life to some cause. vakasolisolia v. to pretend to give. idiom: solisoli vakatoa give and then take back , “indian giver”, lit. give like a rooster who offers the female some food in the beak and then grab s it back. syn. (lau) solisoli vakap oip oi. idiom: solia na kesu-na to turn one’s back (in disdain), to rej ect an approach or request. idiom: mana soli gifted (as splendid singing voice, a special intelligence or ability that one may be inborn.)
n. gift, periodic contribution (money, goods), usually a payment required of each villager for some
purpose, such as repairing the village church. even when living away from the village,
are told how much money they must give. solicitation is made as well to those who have
someone from the village. collection procedures are often relentless. if a fijian fails to pay, he or she could become estranged from the village. na isolisoli mai vua na kalou the gift from god.
n. something that is given . soli ni yasana n. tax exacted by the province of people aged to .
. giving. . specifically, village collection, calling upon members and relatives to contribute for
common cause. these days it is customary also to call for contributions from families of
who have married away from the village, a class of people now referred to as vasu. formerly, only the children of such a marriage were vasu to the village, and they could demand
and goods (except not from bau), but the role is now reversed. the vasu may be expected to give rather than take from the village.
dre n., v. professional, registered moneylender, limited legally to percent interest, serving mainly civil servants, and employees of established companies.
n. exchange of goods, repeated giving.
(slang) n., v., adj . to “sweet talk”, use duplicitous behavior, trying to win favours (“marks” as
(anglicism) v. to direct traffic at busy street corners, of policeman.
ni yaca n. whale-tooth given to father of a child, asking that the child be named after the donor of the tooth.
v. to administer herbal medicine.

adj . free, normally of goods given by a merchant at no extra charge, usually on condition of some purchase. soliyate v., n. to give emotional support, as fans do in sports, cheering on their champion(s) or their team.
liver, for fij ians the source of courage, as the heart might be to europeans.

(kadavu) n. rock. syn. vatu. solo, soloya (or) solota . (lau) v . to scrape, rasp, grate, light (a match). syn. yaca, yacaraka. . to wipe, usually plates, to dry, or the body after bathing. isolo n. cloth used for drying what is wet.
v. to whisper.
v. to pack up (for travel), to wrap up (clothes, goods, baggage), to gather up one’s things isolosolo n. people added to a clan (mataqali) or tribe (yavusa) as a matter of permanent accommodation,
than kinship or related origin. such people may have been given land to use but may never
at their new location. informally, may refer to the many children of a couple. (formerly it was cause for ridicule to have a great number of children.)

(lau) n. pudding made of grated ivi (polynesian chestnut) and coconut cream, wrapped and cooked, usually in leaves of qai (cordyline terminalis, a plant also called masawe, or vasili, or in hawaii, ti). solo suggests the grating, p uli means buli, shaped or formed.

n. ankle. syn. qurulasawa. somate n. funeral ceremony. visitors gather, bringing gifts (ireguregu) such as tabua, mats, barkcloth, in the first phase of ceremony that is called reguregu. syn. (lau) sop utu.
adj . tiny. manumanu somidi tiny “animals” (e.g. bacteria).
(or) sominiwai n. moustache.

(or) somisise adj . impudent, mostly of children. somo, somota v. to soak (tonia) in mud (lolobo) to dye black, of pandanus leaves (voivoi) used in weaving, or of sinnet (magimagi), used in decorative bindings of house-timbers, or wooden clubs.

then being rinsed in fresh water, the material is cooked with certain leaves, candlenut (lauci), tavola, koka, kalabuci, to fix the colour, then washed again and dried by hanging up outdoors. there are alternative ways of blackening. see below somo.
v. to weave blackened voivoi into a mat or basket. somo n. pandanus leaf (voivoi, p. caricosus) that has been dyed black for weaving patterns into mats. the
leaf is sometimes boiled with the leaves of a wild herb called lalakai (not be be confused with ilalakai, which is a very small, woven mat used a plate for a chief’s food). today, voivoi is instead
soaked for a few days in water that has been boiled with a few old batteries from an electric torch. the resultant black colour is not the fine shiny black of the traditional technique. in the suva
somo is usually sold as bunches of individual, dried leaves, or as a small roll. the rolls often

inferior leaves inside. ibe vakasomo (or) ibe somo woven pandanus mat with some leaves dyed black. butu somo v. to soak the somo. vakacabe somo v. to dig out, bring out the somo from the mud. somuna . n. wart, mole. syn. (lau) sonusonukuita. somuna . n. sucker(s) on the arms (na qalona) of the octopus (kuita).
n. rectum. syn. icici, ivekaveka, mata ni da. (colo east) cobo.

na ua . daffy, said of a person who by nature responds in unexpected ways that amuse others. literally, in vanua levu, so na ua means the tide is full. sa so mai na ua. the tide is rising. in tailevu, mati ruku means low tide (usually referring to the early morning), which has taken on the

meaning of daffy, when speaking about an odd person. it is believed that some people’s behaviour changes with the tide, be it full or low. one may ask then, when someone acts crazily, if it is low tide or high tide. the effect of the tide on people is remarked upon particularly in vanua levu, nasavusavu district, especially villages vivili and waivunia. those locals have a reputation of being daffy in relation to the tide. this is the source of many jokes and funny stories. syn. (colo east) dale, sauvou. . not commonly, but sonaua can occasionally have vulgar connotations when referring to a person, simply because of the coincidence that the sona part of the word means rectum. vulgarity will be indicated by context and tone of voice. soni, sonita v. to pierce or to prick with a sharp object, usually a knife or a needle in these modern times. in earlier times a piece of broken glass might be used, and before that, a sharp piece of seashell. also
from edges of pandanus voivoi leaf in preparation for stretching it, prior to
(ibe). traditionally the tiny thorns were slit off using the shell of mussel qa ni kai. na
the removal of tiny thorns from edges of voivoi leaf.
n. common climbing coastal shrub, caesalpinia spp., yellow flowers and seeds, thorns and prickles
n. rivulet, tiny stream.
n. wrinkled, furrowed (of the brow), having many folds, especially of the face, in anger or sorrow.

(eng.) n. soprano. soqe n. peale's pigeon, the “barking pigeon” that bark s like a dog, endemic, ducula latrans, often shot for food by fiji indians. the hunting season is set during the last two week s of may or a few days in very
june, when hunting is done openly. same name for pacific pigeon, dacula pacifica, which
samoa, tonga, known there as lup e (equivalent of fijian ruve). in fiji the fairly common

throated pigeon, columba vitiensis, is known as ruve or soqe loa. the introduced feral pigeon columba livia lives only in larger towns and has no distinctive, separate fijian name. soqo n. meeting (of many people). e dua na soqo siga rua a two-day meeting. vale ni soqo n. meeting house. soqo, soqova v. to meet and discuss or celebrate something. na cava o ni soqova ? what are you (many) meeting about? soqona . v. to gather together, of things or people. na isoqosoqoni the gathering together.
. v. to sum up, to summarise. na isoqoni the total. soqoni n., adj . assembly. assembled.
v . jumbled together, of things; mingled together, of people.
n. association, club, group of people meeting together.
vakamarama n. womens’ association of the methodist church, founded by mrs. derrick who gave it the name na ruve.
n. trash, rubbish. tomika na soqosoqo pick up the rubbish.
make something sprout up, grow rapidly , as in building up the flame of a fire.
n. seed(s). in former times, only some fruit trees were planted by seed.
n. elephantiasis of the testicles. vuce swollen.
n. testicles. syn. p olo, sore ni qala-na, vua ni soresore. sori! (eng.) sorry ! soro, sorova, sorovaka . v. to surrender, give up, submit, or apologise. traditionally, make a formal
submission or or surrender, usually to a chief, to humble oneself, worship. after defeat in battle, a surrender offering was sometimes a basket of earth as a symbol of surrendered territory.
a frequent gift, some of them chiefly . by extension, the word may be used to say that
has eaten enough, or had enough to drink, and quits eating/drinking. or, similarly quitting a game, having had enough. na isoro the thing(s) one gives when surrendering or asking forgiveness,

as whaletooth, or ceremonially , a reed in a ceremony called matanigasau. sorovaka to soro because of . . . (whatever wrong). idiom: tabu soro! never give up ! idiom: sorosoro wale give up easily without a struggle. soro, sorova . v. (of a rope or fishing line) to slack off, let go, let it out, of a tide to slacken.

v., n. to serve a devil, wanting his service to perform evil, by presenting a gift, usually pouring yaqona for the devil. me qarava na tevoro. look after the devil. sorosoro adj . unreliable, untrustworthy, person who should atone (soro) for unfulfilled promises or duties.
n. gaggle of young chickens, duck s, who follow their mother as a troop.
v., n., adj . wrinkled (of skin, as in old age), to ripple (as of water in a lagoon). syn. sosokidikidi. see sokidi.
to be irritated, bothered, by something or someone.
v. to bother (someone), take up their time. see so sa.
(eng.) n. sausage. soseti rolo n. sausage roll.
(eng.) n. saucepan, pot.

. n., adj . mud, muddy. by extension, in ceremonial speech, soso refers very modestly to one’s own land. even in ordinary speech to an outsider, a fijian will speak modestly of his own garden-land, as

it were of little value. in the bible, soso means earth, as in the burial service. sa soso na nomu isulu. your clothes are muddy. isoso . n. cluster (fruit, nuts such as wi, tarawau, dawa, tavola), shoal or school (of fish). syn. tausoso. soso . n. (medical) carbuncle, one or more very deep , painful boils that begin with a cluster of pimples. some fij ians believe this occurs most commonly on the back and neck.
. adj . stuffed as in tiaina soso, “stuffed” bananas, as a snack or (modernly a dessert), sliced down
introduction, may be used as a substitute for bananas, a european introduction. syn. vakasoso. type of pudding.
v. of tree branches or bamboo stems, to make a sound as wind blows through and rubs

against each other. this sound of bamboo has been noted at nawi island in nasavusavu harbour, and also at qoma island off the north tailevu coast. such a sound has been thought to be significant, involving spirits.
n. bottle-stopper, cork , often improvised with a shaped piece of coconut husk
(archaic) n, food and gifts put aboard a new boat being launched. syn. ivakasoso ni waqa. soso, sosoga v. to plug up an opening, as of a bottle, with a stopper, plug or cap. sosoga na gusu ni
to close up the mouth of the bottle. isoso ni tavaya n bottle-stopper, often improvised with a carved piece of coconut husk or a rag. see sogo, sogota.
adj . concentrated, of a beverage (yaqona, coffee, tea), the opposite of waicala dilute. rui sosoko too concentrated, too “strong”. syn. soko.
n. work done together as a group, housebuilding, gardening, etc. see solevaka v . to work
as a group, helping each other in sequence. traditionally a very important fijian concept based on the notion that many hands make light work of a task. syn. sosovaki, solesolevaki.
v. to push into, through a crowd, to stuff.
v. to substitute, replace. e sosomitaki jone o seru. seru replaces jone.
n. the sub stitute, person or thing, deputy serving in an acting capacity. na kemu isosomi the substitute for you, your replacement.
v. to go in a very large group or crowd of people.
n., v. work all together first on one man ’s garden, then another man ’s. working together gets
fast, this is easier and more pleasant than each man working alone on his own garden.
has been an extemely important custom in village life and still is to some extent.
lago v. for flies, to cluster about, usually food. sa sosovilago na kakana the flies are flocking over the food.

adj . sleepy, drowsy, head nodding with sleep. syn. damule. sota, sotava v. to meet (person, people), to encounter. sota vata meet together. au a sotavi koya i met him. isotasota n. meeting, meeting place. by ext., may mean to encounter some situation: keimami
ruarua eke, na draki katakata kei na draki batabata. we (many) encounter both hot weather and cold weather here.
n. match(es), usually in sports such as boxing, rugby.
(eng.) n. shirt. in the late s, british regulations required fijian men to wear shirts in suva. at
a fair number of men owned no shirt and no sandals and most men wore a isulu rather than trousers.

a particle, not directly translatable, used to modify expressions to make them more emphatic, assertive and clear, usually in the negative, as in not at all: kua soti ni dede mai. do not then be very long in coming. e rau sega soti ni veiyaloni kei seru, o manu. manu and seru are not so much in

(not of the same mind). o cei soti? who then? who then might that be? o cei soti o iko ? who do you think you are? sega soti not at all ! a virtual synonym is so. sotia n. (eng.) n. soldier. sotia is used also as a personal name, usually female, to commemorate a relative who served in the military services. sou, souta v. to go in the early morning. in early custom, fij ians left home for garden work or for fishing
early in the morning, coming back much later for a late breakfast (katalau). their second, final
toward the end of the daylight, just before nightfall. sou i wai go down to the
(river, lagoon) very early in the morning. souta na motoka go early in the morning in the car.
very near(ly), almost, of some occurence. isou sara extremely close.
pleated, usually of cloth or barkcloth, usually of a woman ’s dress, causing a frilled effect.

n. practical, utility-basket woven of coconut-frond leaves or more carefully from vilawa, usually for carrying food, cooked or raw. by extension, a bird nest. sova v. to flock about, as with flies, bees, children. sa sovi koya na namu. the mosquitos flocked about him. sova, sova (or) sovara v . to pour out, dump out, usually with brusk motion, quantities of liquid, or rubbish, or things that occupy a container. sovara na simede pour out, dump out the cement. sa
(or kasova) na sucu the milk is spilt. (kasova may also imply the milk is poured out quickly or forcefully.) sova yaqona pour out (on the ground) yaqona as tribute to one’s devil, said of people
are vakatevoro, who have a devil they serve, in return for favours that are usually evil. sova
may also refer to pouring out yaqona into the sea as an offering to dakuwaqa, the shark god.
an offering by divers is intended to retain dakuwaqa’s protection from shark attack, though to

that protection, divers must also have restrained from recent amorous adventures. i have a scar on my leg from a shark nibble that my diver friends insist, resulted from my having violated that rule. idiom: sova wai v. to urinate (a rather coarse expression).
n. rubbish dump. sovea, soveataka (eng.) v. to survey (piece of land).
(archaic ) v., n. competitive game of two teams on a field with a sort of goal-post at each end. to score, one had to touch the opponents’ post. syn. veibuka.
n. common coastal twining vine with edible leaves, mostly eaten in lau, ipomea gracilis, convulvaceae. a lauan dish of such greens is called borovasi, often served with seafood.
(eng.) n. soap. sovu ni sili toilet soap. sovu ni savasava laundry soap. sanisovu n. sandsoap. sovu
torotoro shaving soap. sovu p outa soap powder. vakasovusovu-taka to soap (clothing usually).
formerly had no knowledge of soap (and nor did the ancient greeks). fijians cleaned with sand, fine gravel, and sometimes with body oil (as did the ancient greeks), though highlanders of viti
any body oil. fij ians sometimes used the leaves of a moderately common shrub vere (= vusolevu), colubrina asiatica, as noted by father neyret, and also by berthold seemann, who
its use for washing the hair. later, they have used leaves of the small woody introduced weed, koster ’s curse, clidemia hirta, that has several fij ian names not widely known. a froth can be
species. the tiny purple fruits of koster’s curse happen also to

source_text: tasty and edible. crushed leaves of the introduced senitoa hibiscus are used currently in hair treatment.
adj . soapy, frothy. sovu, sovuta v. to wash something by soaping.
. n . soup, as in wai ni su, fish soup, though in kadavu su refers to ripe bananas in coconut cream (lolo) sauce. fijians made no soup except with fish.
. n. dry, soft grass, fern, or leaves used to create a soft floor under the floor mats (icoco) of the

fijian house. vakasu vinaka na buturara ni nona vale. the floor of his house is softly padded. frequently used have been the ferns koukou, karuka, qato, isu n. fresh coconut-leaf basket, quickly made and disposable, made usually by men and used by both men and women, for food, garden produce such as tavioka. isu weleti basket containing papaya. isu sei n. such a basket made of young shoots of screw pine pandanus (vadra). idiom : tube isu to be an unimportant person, a simple carrier, carrying things to accompany an important person. sua, suaka, sualaka v. to spike, to stab (with spear, knife, sharp stake), by ext. to remove husk of coconut. isua n. spike of wood or metal stuck in the ground, used for husking coconuts (or) modernly, a dagger or sheath-knife. sua, suataka v. to scull (boat, with one oar from the stern , an introduced custom). idiom: sua mai, sua
rock-and-roll dancing.
v. to wobble, stagger of an infirm or drunk person, or a boat in troubled water, a tree under the weight of the wind.
n. work-clothes. the implication is that the work-clothes get wet suasua, either from sweat and/or rain. vakaisuai to dress or be dressed in work-clothes. also suwai.
adj ., n. wet, humid. via suasua adj . still damp (usually of clothes), slightly damp. idiom : sa
na yava-na. he/she is a newcomer, just arrived, not a knowledgable local. literally, his/her
(from coming ashore from a boat is implied).
(or) laki suasua v., n . to urinate (polite term). via suasua to want to urinate. sa dau dra na nona suasua. there is usually blood in his/her urine.
v. to wet, throw water on, to water (garden). vakata-suasua, vakasuasuataka v. to entertain. dau vakatasuasua entertainer(s). vakatasuasua n.

an audience. can be music, dance, or a short skit. this term is a modernism. origin probably lies with old custom that one hears about, sprinkling of water to make people laugh, done by elderly women, pretending to urinate like men, with a coconut shell full of water between their legs. subu-na n. mons veneris, woman ’s genital mound, vagina. syn. maga-na (specifically vagina). words not to be pronounced. subu-na is not a well known word.
. v. to be born. vakasucu to give birth. na isucusucu the birth. sucu dole born prematurely. sucu
breech birth. vale ni vakasucu n . maternity clinic. siga ni sucu birthday. siga ni sucu xmas day . traditionally, fij ians never counted or remembered the day or even the year of their birth.
the relative age of siblings was relevant. today many fijians celebrate children ’s birthdays,
cakes, and even place elaborate notices in classified ads of newspapers, replete with a photo of the child. a trad. ceremony four days after birth (bogi va) is a feast celebrating the probable
survival of the baby. turaga sucu born a chieftain, in contrast to the more melanesian
a chief on his qualities rather more than just lineage. fij i has had both systems.

are many disputes over that right and many vacant titles because the matter cannot no longer be settled by violence. sucu, sucuma . v. to suckle the nipple, the mother ’s or the bottle ’s. sucuma na tavaya to suck from the bottle. na sucu vei tina-na the suckling from the mother. vakasucu, vakasucuma v. to give birth (to offspring). sucu n. milk. ti vakasucu tea with milk. sucu mamaca n. dry milk (powder). sucu sosoko n. evaporated milk.

source_text: v., adj . born prematurely. gone sucudole. premature baby.
n . protruding breasts.
adj ., v. still-born. sucu-na n. breast (male or female). mata ni sucu-na nipple. sucu lodo breast with insufficient milk.
n. large type of commercially very valuable bêche de mer, dark brown, greyish brown, creamy
in colour, sometimes with blotches, with eight “breasts” (sucu) on each side, as suggested by

n. prop(s) for supporting fijian traditional clay cooking pots, usually three of them, often made of clay. syn. sori. katuba-i-sue n. doorway at the end of the fij ian thatched house, near the cooking area, used by family and people of no particular distinction. the side door was reserved for elders
place or facility, to block off (in the case of roads), in modern times, villagers sometimes block roads as a form of protest over land disputes. syn. usu, usuta.
n., v. incursion, taking control of a territory, closing off or blocking roads, commonly done
for a number of days (until village elders call for a halt). another is at the annual hindu
of holi, around april, when the splashed water is often red coloured. fij ians sometimes

splashing, though rarely understand the symbolism and religious significance. they are just having fun. sui-na n. bone. sui tu n. backbone, spine. there is no separate word for “skeleton”; one would say simply
tamata (human bones, skeleton). ora ena sui ni ika. to choke on the fishbone. suisuia adj .

skinny (person), bony, lots of bones (of a fish). by ext., midrib of a leaf of frond (palm, fern). syn. (tonga) hui. idiom : sa lauti koya ena sui ni kena. he/she got caught in his/her own trap, lit. the (fish) bone in his/her food got caught in his/her own throat.
barbed, as of speech with bitter remarks, that may be half-concealed.
adj . of a person, animal, too thin, or not filled out appropriately, considering the age or stage of growth.
ni gata n. lit. “snake-bones”, very large lycopodium spp. that resemble the skeleton of a snake. l. foliosum and l. phlegmaria, decorative foliage.
(eng.) n . switch .
tu n. backbone. also, by extension, an anglicism, the plot, as of a story, a word invented by fiji ’s education dept.
adj . very skinny, of a person, suggestive of bones showing.
(eng.) sugar. vakasuka v. or adj . to add sugar (to tea, food), sugared. previously, only fijian

sweetened, using the expressed juice from corms of masawe, after extended baking in earth oven , a practice known only around the coast. there were no earth ovens in the highlands. suka, sukava v. to return . me suka mai na noqu isele (please) return my knive. suka bera mai come back late. suka mai na valeniveivesu. get out of prison. suka mai vuli get out of school. sukanaivalu returned serviceman. sukava tale na noqu ivakamacala to turn back again to my explanation.

v. to resign (from a job or position). sa mai vakasuka na turaga mai na p ati ni p olitiki. the gentleman resigned from the political party. vakasuka, vakasuka-taka v., adj . to sugar (tea, coffee etc.) sugared (as a cup of tea), containing sugar. vakasuka, vakasuka . v. to return (an obj ect). vakasuka, vakasuka . v. to dismiss or “send down” (a person).
v. to retreat, move back.
n. returned soldier.
(or) sikau small wild tree of the forests, to m., a lowland evergreen, grows at altitudes below m., gnetum gnemon, gnetaceae, a gymnosperm. the young pink or green leaves were often

and eaten as a vegetable on the major islands and koro island. the seeds, cm diam, fleshy covering, ripening yellow to orange to red, and are occasionally eaten. fls and frts october, november. in swampy lowlands such as rewa the tree is unknown. syn. bele sukau. “suki” (hindi) fij ian tobacco, cured leaf twisted into a rope, rolled into a large ball of some to kilos,
at the market by length or weight. fij ians roll a smoke with it. they may use the expression
suki to smoke ( fijian tobacco). much of the fiji tobacco has been grown in nadroga, famously at qalimare. it is very strong.
n. knot (in wood), node (bamboo, yaqona plant, sugar cane, duruka). an internode is tagau or tago-na.

(eng.) n. schooner. adopted as a name for ratu sukuna, after cakobau ’s schooner, captained by madraiwiwi, ratu sukuna’s father. the name was held previously by one of cakobau ’s sons by a secondary wife.
(eng.) n. screw (as for carpentry).
adj . knotty (of wood), rough or bumpy (of a road), and by extension, untidy (of a person).
n. green coconut having no flesh and too young to be drinkable.
n. palm fronds woven to carry various large foods. see isu sei.
n. . n (regional) dalo, taro, colocasia esculenta.
n. . n chunks of dalo, taro, colocasia esculenta, sometimes sold at the market, cut usually to take out damage such as that of the taro beetle.
n. suckers, usually for planting (taro, banana, pineapple), sometimes abbrev. as suli. suckers grow up around the mother plant.
n. cloth, clothing. isulu tavoi simple cotton wrap-around clothing. isulu vakatoga long, anklelength wrap-around, a style introduced from tonga, first to lau, but not common around fiji till after
s. isulu vakataga man's tailored isulu with pockets (invented by ratu sukuna). isulu i loma
(a very modern concept). isulu ni yaqona cloth used to strain pounded yaqona in the
(bowl for mixing and serving yaqona). early methodist converts were given an isulu of
cotton cloth (and sometimes a metal axe) as an incentive to convert. previously coastal
a loincloth of barkcloth, but often a skirt of split plantain leaves, or waloa. women
a very brief fringed skirt liku. highland men and some mature women wore a skirt of leaves,
vava or masawe, sometimes plantain . no underclothes were ever worn . vakatara isulu
(or symbolic black ribbon) nights (bogi drau) after the death

customs. early fijians did not perform elaborate funeral ceremonies except for the strangling of widows at the death of high chiefs. vakaisulu, vakaisuluma (or) suluma v. to clothe, dress in clothes. vakasuluma na gone to dress the child.

adj . clothed. vakaisulu-taki to have been dressed up. sulu, suluma v . to grope with the hand into some covered place, blanket, basket, mud-hole of eel (to catch eel). by extension, penetrate female genitalia with the hand. wainisulubonu name of a creek at
(bonu) are caught by hand in their mud-holes.
n. octopus or squid. octopus is more commonly called kuita, except in the west, rewa, kadavu
squid travel in large schools, stay still for a while but move suddenly with great speed, caught

with nets and only with difficulty. they have excellent eyesight. squid have arms and two tentacles. giant squid, to feet in length, half a tonne in weight, are a favoured food of the sperm whale. scars on those whales indicate momentous battles at great depths, never witnessed by humans. the squids themselves eat fish especially and are also cannibals.
n. heat-cured leaves of pandanus tree (vadra or balawa) or plantain (vudi) used as a wrapper for
cigars and cigarettes, and by ext., may refer to newspaper used for the same purpose.

n. puffer fish, tetraodon sp., edible if the poison sacs are removed, but fatal if not. numbness, dis-coordination of limb s are early symptoms, then difficulty of breathing. death may occur within hours. fish is skinned and gutted immediately because toxin is in mucus of the skin
more than two tonnes. inoffensive, and unafraid of humans, the sunfish has a diet of kelp,

and plankton, small fish and crustaceans. the flesh tends to be very white or pink, but tough and lacking texture. the skin is very tough. suni, sunia v. to scald, of shellfish, by soaking in a cloth or sieve in very hot water.
n. sugary, fibreless residue of coconut, light brown in colour, eaten as a candy by children, and also rubbed on the hair of bride and groom as glittery decoration.
(eng.) snooker. sure, sureta v. to implore, invite, request. sureti au invite me. o ni sa sureti tu. you are invited. na
n. the invitation.
v. to persuade forcefully. surevaka na veivukei demand the help.
n. invitation (usually to attend some occasion). suru, suruta v. to sneeze at or on, trad. in fij i, a rejection, or an act that will bring misfortune to a
undertaking (fishing, going to war). to sneeze in the presence of a chief could be a
offense. sneezing is still somewhat impolite, but is now perfunctorily excused by the
bula!. (live !). one replies moli! to express gratitude that one’s life is spared. the

exchange is good natured. if the sneezing is repeated a few times, the humorous exclamation may be mate! die ! idiom: sa suruta na vusi. lit. the cat has sneezed on it, meaning that some plan went wrong by misfortune.

n. (hindi) food (usually seafood, small fish), fried and curried, in coconut cream, a favoured food of fij ians and indians. suruwa-taka to prepare food in this manner. susu, susuga v. to nurse, raise a child or domestic animal. au a susugi e viti. i was raised in fij i. the
susui is named for being the place to raise a chiefly child safely, away from the dangers on vanua balavu.
n. up-bringing, raising, as of a child but by extension may apply to raising a young animal, such as a calf. vakilai na yaga ni veisusu vinaka. the value of a proper upbringing is recognised.
n. guardian, caretaker for a youngster, nanny for a child. susu manumanu n. animal husbandry. susu toa raising chickens. susu bulumakau raising cattle.
n. an illness, usually of children , chicken pox. syn. korosusunu.

yago v., n., adj . nicely plump and healthy, of a young child, implying the child is well fed. by extension, this word applied to adults can imply a person who stays around the house and does very little work .

(slang, eng.) v., n . suit of clothes, and there can be an implication of getting all dressed up to impress others, particularly the opposite sex. sutu vata wearing matching clothes, such as people of a choir, or children in school uniform.
(or) suvasuva n. mound or pile of stones used to mark a place, particularly a boundary. the word
adopted as the name of a few villages, one in ra, and one at what it now suva city, now part of rewa province but formerly allied to bau. it is also the name of the tribe of the tui taveuni.
(eng.) souvenir. many of the fij i souvenirs sold in tourist gift shops originate from indonesia,
are one of the few types of souvenirs made in fiji, some of them very well done by

woodcarvers but many are crudely made imitations. carved wooden masks are fake souvenirs, not traditional in fij i. fans are often made at village daku, and fijian barkcloth, often from vatulele, is sold for souvenirs.
(or) sueia words spoken after drinking a cup of kava, preceding a wish that will be expressed.
the term vosa ni vakacivo a wish expressed on such occasion, usually for fair weather, good crops, safe voyage, something benign. (the word suveia is new to me; it is taken

ivolavosa vakaviti, p. . – r.g.) the custom is less common in modern times. suvi, suvia (or) suvisuvia v . to cut into large pieces, usually a root-crop such as yam, sweet potato, breadfruit, potato, usually before cooking. isuvisuvi chunk, as potato cut up for a for a stew.
(eng.) soup. soup is customarily slurped, even if a spoon is used. (spoon is a modernism). as a separately cooked dish, soup was known only in coastal areas, not in the highlands where there were
no clay pots. the main soup was fish broth, usually called wai buta or wai su. fish is the
food that was sometimes boiled. (the only exception is human bodies boiled in whalers’ giant
that had previously been used to reduce whale blubber.) in the lowlands, virtually all food
steamed in huge clay pots. it was not boiled. or food was grilled over a fire, or cooked in the
oven (lovo), though the earth oven was unknown in the highlands. in upper-class fijian
is now customary to serve soup in white half-shells of immature coconut (not the dark,

shells used for kava cups). soup is said to be drunk gunu, gunuva, not eaten kana, kania . like taro leaf, meat, tea, soup is considered as a garnish (na kena icoi) for “true” food (kakana dina) such as taro or yam root crops.
n . work-clothes. syn. suai.
(or) sue (ba, nadi) n. house. syn. vale. (west) were. tribe suelevu settled into the nadi area
assumed a new title they called the tui nadi. their earlier origin was in vanua levu via ba according to n. l. c. commissioner david wilkinson.
(walking stick) and midimidi = minj i-minj i (tiny). kadavu province may also use the j sound. in
sea languages it is the vowels that anchor the meaning of word, not the consonants, so these differences are not confusing to us.

the d of eastern fijian when it is the first letter of the word. thus daniva (sardine) becomes taniva in the west, and duna (eel) becomes tuna. in bua, the t is often replaced with a glottal stop which sounds a bit like a hiccup.

source_text: prefix attached in front of a word, indicating a sudden, forceful action, usually unintentional. tasere
let loose, come undone, separated, snapped (rope). taqusi suddenly smeared. tasova spilt abruptly. tamusuka cut off abruptly. takoso cross over abruptly. takosova na ikawakawa cross over
unintentionally. tadola to burst open, of a door in the wind. tadodo to stretch out suddenly, as a rope under strain. tagede bob up and down, of a fishing-line float. (see gede)
alphabetically by the prefix. the prefix tata indicates a frequent, repetitive or greater, more forceful action that the simple prefix ta.
n. two species of unicorn fish, edible reef fish with a "horn ". largest is naso unicornis. n. lituratus is more brightly yellowed. they feed on seaweed, algae.
(lau) not. bauan sega. e ta lako ki suva. he/she did not go to suva.

(or) ta-ta n . dad, daddy, as said by a child. see tama-na father. ta, tavaka v. to wait for, to meet and greet (person). ta, taya, talaka . v. to chop, cut forcibly. laki ta buka go chop firewood. taya na buka chop the firewood. taya na gaunisala cut the road. taya na waqa build the boat ("chop the canoe "). na ta
the ship-building, the building of ships. tatalaka na nona meca chop down his enemies. na

the slitting of the throat(s). na itata ni buka the chopping of firewood. e dua na ita one chop. idiom, rather obsolete: au mai taya nomu waqa. i ask to share in what you are enjoying (usually food, some delicacy), a rather archaic expression, perhaps somewhat childish . helping build someone ’s boat would normally call for some recompense. ta, taya . v. to gather up with a quick, choppy action, as with sand in a shovel, or balolo (edible sea annelids) in a net or container. ita nuku shovel-full of sand. e dua na ita balolo one scoop of balolo worms. ta, taya . (anglicism) v. in cricket, to go to bat. p ate (or) sasabai n. bat. tavi, tavia na p olo v. to hit the ball. see sabaya. taba! (slang) agreed ! from children especially one may hear sitaba!
. (anglicism) n. photograph (or) camera. veitaba sitiveni moce photo by s. m. dauveitaba or

photographer. itaba . (anglicism) n. stamp , usually referring to a rubber stamp. sitaba postage stamp. taba, tabaka . v. to press down with the hand and arm. tabaka na kato me sogo vakavinaka. press down on the box to close it well. tabaka na bulukau press the button. taba, tabaka . v. to press on with, proceed with, as in tabaka na vala to press on with the fight. taba, tabaka . v. to print, publish. iyaloyalo tabaki printed image, picture. taba, tabaka . v. to play (musical instrument such as piano, organ, accordion). taba, tabaka . v. to take a photograph. to make a film. itaba photo. taba, tabaka . v. to say traditional words of acceptance and gratitude in receiving isevusevu of kava, or receiving a whaletooth or feast food at a formal ceremony. tababoko, tababokoca v. to extinguish, of a law, regulation, or of a branch of government or business, organisation, or branch of people. not a commonly used word. boko v. to extinguish.
v. of a person, not yet matched with a partner, as in a sport like tennis. implication is that that
is “left over” for the time being. may refer to things of uneven number, lacking a corresponding “match”.
n. ministry, branch or department, usually of government or a business. t. ni vanua home affairs, t. ni vanua tani foreign affairs, t. itaukei fijian affairs, t. ni teitei agriculture. t. ni
education.
n. small edible fish at shore or reef, light-coloured body with vertical stripes, with thick, gritty skin, acanthurus triostegus.
n. epoch, period of time.
n. younger generation. tabavata of the same generation.
n. older generation.
n. generation (of people, in time). polynesian chiefs (such as ratu sir kamisese mara)
claimed to recite their lineage for up to generations, using a generous imagination to fill in

gap s with illustrious names. for chiefs of viti levu, no records extend more than about generations, usually fewer. the more purely melanesian lineages are rarely remembered for more than just a very few generations.

. n. branch or limb (tree), wing (bird), upper arm (person), branch or “side” (of a family, as in the “woman ’s side” versus the “man ’s side” in a marriage). vunitaba-na shoulder (of person), branch as of a government department. tabataba shoulder-to-shoulder. vatuvatu ni taba-na shoulder blade. traditionally, “the side” of a family has been referred to as na itataba, a term heard less commonly today. this old term presumably gave rise to “na ita”, a form of address between people of various
territories that became allied and bonded, different tribes but branches of the same people.
today know with whom they have such a relationship referring to themselves as being
those people; they know how to behave in that relationship, but normally they have no idea of the historical facts that created the relationship.
kin-groups that are veitabani are in a fiercely competitive but friendly relationship. the
is traditionally said to be that the ancestral spirits (vu) of the two groups are related as
veitaveleni. this is the case with nakelo and tokatoka in tailevu province. they may
extraordinary privileges with each other, friendly but forceful insults and even indecency. in effect it is somewhat like a veitauvu dredre relationship. see tauvu.
. n. storey (building). vale taba tolu three-storey building. ena taba rua on the second floor.
the house with multiple storeys. taba-na . n. page (of a publication). ena tabana e va kei na lima. on pages four and five. syn. drau ni veva.

. n. department (of government), branch (of company). tabana ni bula health department. syn. tabacakacaka. t. ni vanua home affairs (police, prisons, military), t. ni cakacaka labour department. tabana . n. section (publication). tabana ni qito sports section (of newspaper).

see taba-na. this is a type of kinship relation for a whole community, now often generalised to regions. in earliest times, this was based on two sets of people having ancestral spirits that were crosscousin. they may refer to each other as naita. they make treat each other impudently, jokingly disrespectful, similarly to the veitauvu dredre relationship.
v. to place hands on hips, both sides of the body. tabailago-taka v. inquire informally of a young woman ’s family, as to the prospects of approaching with
adj . short-sleeve, of a shirt or blouse, vest. e dua na sote tabaleka a short-sleeved shirt.
(archaic) v. to make a thumbprint as a signature, for someone who cannot write, mostly relevant in early history of fiji.
n. (modernism) bibliography.
v. to print (newspaper, pamphlet, book, etc.)

n. leather-back turtle with relatively soft shell having seven longitudinal ridges, and thus eight plates of carapace, as implied in the name. it does not breed in fiji and is not often seen. dermochelys coriacea. syn. tuvonu.
ni uto . v., n. idiom: have an casual affair, lover. the implication is that the branch of breadfruit breaks easily; the relationship may not endure.
. idiom: to be ineffective, unable to contribute and thus useless. a person who has no
presentation-goods to offer at a magiti is said to be vakataba ni uto. such an expression might not be known to youngsters.

n. crude matting made of split coconut branches with leaves interwoven. these serve as temporary flooring or temporary walls for a shed. may refer simply to branches of the coconut palm. idiom: dabe ena ibe qai kisi ki na tabakau. said about one who was riding high, and was then reduced to a lowered status. lit. sit on a fine mat, and than shift to the crude matting of tabakau.
adj ., adv. self-reliant, acting independently, by oneself or themselves, alone. tu tabakidua to
alone; of one kind only, as in na nuqa me ra soqo vakatabakidua implying only one kind of fish, the nuqa, collecting themselves together.
v. to proceed, but staggering or wobbling this way and that, as if drunk. see tataivatia. not to be
to walk.

n. mountain pass. tabaluvu, tabaluvuca v. to push a person down beneath the surface of the water, as in some baptisms, or children playing in the water. see taba, tabaka. tabe, tabea v. to hold or carry something with both hand supporting the burden from underneath, to support. eratou tabea toka na kumidra . they (several) have their chins in their hands. tabe ulu to
one’s head in the hand, as in heavy thought, or perhap s having a headache. tabe liga to hold one’s hands behind the back. (roqo liga to clasp one ’s hands in front of the body.)

n. fij ian form of tray, made from leaves, carried with hands supporting it underneath, such as a ilalakai, food-mat for a chief, or a tray held in this way . itabetabe n. the thing(s) such as food that is brought this way.
(western highlands) n. woman's backpack basket, usually made of split bamboo. tabetabe v., n. adj . to cater to (someone), play up to someone, flatter deceptively to gain favour, usually

. v. to press down on something, applying weight, as in pressing a rather full suitcase to close it. syn. danu, danuya, tatuva. tabika . v. to place some weight, such as a stone, to hold down say a mat, or voivoi, to keep it in place, as on a windy day . syn. danuya, tatuva. see bika, bika to press down.
n . weight used to hold something down, in the office a paperweight, in the village stones or
object to hold down a mat being aired in the sun, or to hold down voivoi that is being dried outdoors, not to be blown away.
(archaic) n. blunt-ended fij ian war canoe use for ramming enemy canoes. length about feet, the hull of single-log length.
. v. to move quickly, people rushing, pushing in a crowd. era tabili yani na laki volivoli. they (many) moved quickly in a disorderly crowd in going shopping.
. n. mortar for pounding yaqona. present versions are made of wood or of metal, metal becoming
common. the concept and word were apparently introduced from the solomon islands, according to p. geraghty. in earliest times, kava was grated on coral (at the coast) or stone such as sule
(cule in standard fijian). the notion of having youngsters chew kava before
it was probably introduced from the central south seas. it has not been a highland custom in viti levu among the “real” fij ians.
(archaic) n. v. ceremony for a new event, usually concerned with the arrival of people, a boat, or
vehicle. original concept concerned recognition of recent death of a chief ashore. an arriving
sail would be thrown in the water. gifts are brought, historically hung around the boat. hosts will compete for them. see cere, cereva.
v. disappeared, out of sight, not visible, from the view being blocked.
v. to split suddenly , as accidentally in falling, as a melon might do. syn. kabola.
v. to conceal, cover up, something physical (a stolen object, or a gift), a light, a sound, an idea or a thought or a fact.
v. to become blocked, closed off, as fallen leaves might block a drain. see bono, bonota.
. adj . sacred and (modernly) holy. sautabu village chiefly cemetery. ivola tabu holy bible. yalo

holy ghost (christian). siga tabu sabbath. siga tabu ni tina mothers’ day. duatolu tabu holy trinity. tui tabu pope. vakatabui sanctified, blessed. syn. (tonga) tap u. tabu . specially reserved (as for chiefs, priests, any special people). sa vakatabui me nomu. it has been reserved for you, for your use only.

. adj ., n. forbidden , prohibited, taboo. sa tabu na curu eke. trespassing forbidden. au sa tabu tu (of methodist youth member). i am under promise not to do something (usually smoke, drink). sa tabu vei au. that is forbidden to me. au se tabu tiko na kana tavako. i am abstaining from smoking.
n. very fine pandanus mats woven at ono-i-lau, traditionally forbidden to commoners. sa
na ta niu. cutting copra is forbidden. tabu dredre strictly forbidden. tabutabu very strictly forbidden. in villages it it forbidden to eat certain seasonal food until they have been presented
to the chief, and modernly, also to the church . this applies primarily to yams, both
and wild, but also, in places, to breadfruit, and to some fruits such as dawa. also, after the death of a chief, locally there may be a prohibition to fish or to harvest certain foods for a time.
. n. person with whom one is veitabui, with whom one may not speak. for example, formerly a
and sister were not permitted to talk together. also the relationships such as the vugona, or daku.
as a prefix, tabu-- indicates that something that is not normally done: tabusili not bathing often.
often unshaven. tabuvuli often skipping school. tabudredre strictly forbidden. tabudredre unsmiling. tabukana eats very little. tabugunu doesn ’t drink . tabuvosa hardly speak s at all.
unkempt, usually needs a haircut. tabulotu not usually going to church. tabusuka does not

sugar. tabuyaqona do not drink yaqona (as is the case of some christian sects of american origin, mormons, adventists etc.) more emphatic would be the prefix tabutabu--, as in tabutabulotu for many non-theists who might never go to church services.

(or) veitabuki in fijian custom, forbidden to talk to each other, to communicate directly, or to eat certain food in each other’s presence. certain social groups may not associate directly with each other,
as waimaro people and the people of bau. there are also food prohibitions:- in having meals together, highland people may not eat pork in the presence of coastal people, and coastal people may
eat seafoods or coconut products in the presence of highlanders. the distinction is based on the
that highlanders are traditional warriors for coastal people but in fact their geographical
switched with time. supposedly, highlanders have more ready access to wild pigs,
(no contact, no conversation) between children and the maternal uncle, and also between

and sisters (as an incest prohibition, though no such prohibition in the west). keirau veitabui kei seru. seru and i are tabu in relation to each other.(and i might therefore refer to him as my tabu.)
are ganena, vugona and one’s daku. in some areas, a son may not normally address his own father.
target_text: family relations that may be veitabuki

source_text: v. dress in mourning, black, for days after a death in the family , a custom adopted from the missionaries. vaka-tara-i-sulu ceremony after days when normal clothing may be resumed. vakatabu, vakatabuya . v. to impose a tabu, a tradtional prohibition. in fijian custom, village leaders

a tabu on something, as on coconuts or fishing grounds, preventing its use for a time, often six months. this is done ceremonially after the death of a chief or generally, to save up stock s of fish or crops for some special village purpose. vakatabu, vakatabuya . v. to prohibit, forbid. au vakatabuyi iko mo curuma na vale oya. i forbid you
by missionaries. vakatabui ena masu blessed with prayers, sanctified (as for a new church).
n. hurricane lamp fueled by kerosene, a standard item in the village.
n. very finely woven mat from ono-i-lau, “forbidden to commoners”.
v., adj . off one’s food, not eating sufficiently, under-fed, anorectic.
n., adj . express, non-stop, as of a bus, this being a modernism.
v., adj . does not usually attend church. syn. sega ni dau lotu.
v., n., adj . sleeplessness, sleepless.

adj . of a chiefly marriageable young woman, kept indoors, out of the sun, to maintain a fair skin to make her more attractive. the custom is more polynesian than melanesian. many fijians have been colour-conscious. insults to other fijians sometimes refer to them as being black . after circumcision young boys are kept out of the sun for few days. era tabusiga kece ka tiko e loma ni vale. they are all kept out of the sun and stay inside the house.
unblinking, as of a steady staring, watchfulness.
v., n ., adj . disinclined to bathe.
idiom : never give up, never surrender. this may be an exclamation.
. adj . (of a person) subject to a tabu (e.g. against a haircut or shave), usually after a death,

for nights, or one year. former, men might forego shaving, or keep shaven part of their hair until they achieve revenge. vakatatabu . n. prohibition, as in a tabu against fishing in a certain area after the death of a chief, or a prohibition against certain behaviour in the village, as carrying burdens on the shoulder, wearing a hat, or wearing immodest dress. immodest dress is a missionary notion. in earlier times, men should wear nothing above the waist unless they had chiefly status. women ’s dress barely covered the loins.
n. whaletooth, from the lower j aw of sperm whales which have about such teeth , about an inch
embedded into a massive j awbone in a straight line; all but about ten of them seven or eight
in length, suitable for fij ian ceremonial use. tabua are the most valuable of ceremonial presentation goods for fijians. such goods are referred to as kamunaga, a fijian version of wealth. in
presentations ten tabua were counted as one vulo, as a form of counting the wealth presented. previously, tabua in viti levu were reportedly carved of wood, specifically of bua, in the
shape of a plantain. no such ancient artefact has been collected other than wooden ones
impossible to know much at all of these previous customs. tongan themselves never used
in any ceremonial function; they traded them in fiji for sandalwood, used to scent their
oil. tongans and commercial whalers introduced whaleteeth to fiji, probably in the s
ship s arrived in the south seas hunting whales for whale oil to fuel lamps in the united
and europe. that industry peaked around when there were whaling ships active, four
the u.s.a . in some , whales were killed for oil but by the end of that decade the industry declined sharply, when whale oil began to be supplanted by kerosene for fueling lamps, an
the united states. whalers introduced a few huge walrus teeth which were used with
done hand-harpooning of whales themselves from small boats for the meat sold at nukualofa
until almost mid-century s. fij ians have never caught whales. some whales have been

and fij ians have taken teeth that are to be found in the upper j aw. most whale teeth have been obtained from whalers. modernly there is a considerable shortage and extremely high price on whaleteeth. it is forbidden to take them out of the country but there are no effective controls
that. the best teeth are oiled and polished, protected by wrapping, becoming an attractive
and referred to as tabua damu. colouring has been effected with the root of masawe, or of turmeric, or of the fruit of the candlenut tree. tabua are normally attached at
target_text: yellow-brown in colour that is prized

source_text: ends to a cord of plaited sinnet. presentation is always done with fairly elaborate ceremony,
the cord away from the tooth, and kneeling before the recipient. acceptance calls for more
speech. the present-day scarcity of whaleteeth and extremely high cost causes diminished
in fijian ceremonies. they are normally sold through pawn shops at prices exceeding f$ in . a large tooth can cost twice that price.
damu n. whaletooth that is highly valued for being smoked to a deep tan colour (damu), a former practice of tongans in fiji. smoke is from smouldering fire of native sugarcane or of sweet tubers of
with coconut oil and kept away from the sun, wrapped in barkcloth . tabua may be boiled with
of kura morinda citrifolia, rubiaceae, to give the desired rich tan colour. turmeric (cago or rerega or reregwa), was also used for its yellowish colour.
adj . perfect, faultless, not likely to make mistakes.
v. to stumble, stub the toe, to trip on something. caqe, caqeta to kick.
v. to become separated, unsettled as the corner of a mat, or page of a book, blown by the wind. virtual syn. tacega.
v. to babble. tacenu, tacenumaka v . to do something with vigour.
v. to come undone, as of a parcel.
n. younger sibling of the same sex. a brother’s younger brother, a sister ’s younger sister. tuakana refers to the older sibling of the same sex.
adj ., n. siblings of the same sex. na vertacini the brothers or the sisters (one of them younger than the other(s).
n. affectionate way of addressing a somewhat younger person of the same gender, ("my young brother” if the speaker is a man, “my younger sister " if the speaker is a woman). na veitacini the
of two or more siblings of the same sex. modernly, and more vulgarly, one hears young men addressed as “bro” or “baraca” (brother), mimicking the speech of some american black s.
v., n. to burst forth in a rush or gush. may apply to a sailboat under a burst of wind, perhaps to a
such as an owl pouncing on its prey , and perhaps even to a car in a drag-race. na tacoka ni wai e na tolo ni uciwai na sigatoka. the gush of water in the sigatoka river. see dobui.
v. to stretch out, extend, as an arm, leg, an implement or rope. tadoka n., v., relapse (medical). fij ians had this concept prior to the advent of europeans.

. adj ., of conversation, flowing easily, comfortably with direct speech. tadonu vinaka na nodra veitalanoa. their conversation flowed easily and directly. syn. tadrodro. tadonu . v. to cut at the exact required location. ta, taya to chop. tadra, tadrava v. to dream, dream of (usually in one’s sleep). tatadra, tatadrataka to (day)-dream, often implying a desire, a longing for something or someone. tadre n., adj . tug-of-war; tight, taut, as of a rope or binding. dre to pull.
in a face-up position (person, plate, glass, any object that has an upper and lower side).
to lie down on one’s back.
n. cleft (rocky terrain), deep gully, ditch, channel between two pieces of land. the middle area
two places. na kedrau tadrua ko suva kei navua. the area between suva and navua. the
(ta, taya), with two sides.
n. edible univalve shellfish, chiton, with eight segments of shell, clings firmly to rock s,
gemmata, polyplacophora. soaked in hot water to remove shell and hairs. syn. (kadavu) kulisolo.

v. to arrive (a formal word, usually after long voyages), or to arrive at birth . e a tadu lesu mai ki viti ena . he/she arrived back in fij i in . tadu lala to arrive with nothing, no presentation, unceremonially . (some children born out of wedlock have been given this as a name.) syn. (respectful) toka-tu.
(archaic) v., n. for a chief, to send out his matanivanua (protocol officer) to pass on his
(yavusa) and clans (mataqali). often this is an order to assemble for a formal conference to discuss or to decide on some community matters.
target_text: instructions to heads of his tribes

source_text: (lau) n. long-handled broom of coconut mid-ribs, much used outdoors. see tauf ale.
(lau) v. to sweep. itaf i n. broom. syn. sasa, itavitaviraki.

n. sack, bag or pocket (of pants, shirt, coat). pants, shirts, coats and pockets are of course, modern concepts. sulu vakataga men ’s tailored skirt with pockets, invented by ratu sukuna. taga p ep a paper bag. taga niu bag of coconuts (or copra). taga ni niu bag for copra. indigenously, in earlier times, fijian men used baskets but no bags or pockets. tagana v. to put things in a bag. tawana ena taga to fill a bag, put things in a bag.

(slang) v., adj . lit. having empty pockets, i.e., having no money. syn. nomani, from the english “no money”. taga, tagava v. to use a hand-net to catch (it), usually prawns, small fish , crab s. hand nets were not used in the highlands of viti levu. tagava na balolo to net the balolo. itaga n. hand-net. lai taga ura go netting prawn .
(archaic) n. the "horned" masthead of early fiji sailing canoes that could sail in only one direction. the halyard passed over this masthead.
n. a fij ian infectious disease, thought mostly to affect children who have visited the house of a
person, or an elderly person who has been bed-ridden for a long time. symptoms are dark pimples on the body.
v. to bag (something), put things in a bag. na kena itagatagani the bagging. syn. tawana ena taga.
n., adj . man, male (gender of human, animal or plant). na gone tagane the young man, the youth.
like a man. dabe vakatagane sit with the legs crossed, as a man does. (a woman sits with the legs to one side dabe vakayalewa.)
n . urinary bladder. syn. bolanimi.
sa v. of a place (house, school, playing field), to be empty of people, lacking the usual, familiar noise and movement.
n. node or internode (as of bamboo, yaqona plant, sugar cane). the internode is tago-na. idiom: tagau dua, in brief, . . (to express something in few words).

v. to remove the fibres kosakosa from yaqona when mixing it. this is done filtered through a cloth, or more traditionally, through a swatch of long fibres such as hibiscus or, in the highlands, fern leaves. ibo such a filter. tagi, tagica, tagivaka v. to cry, tagica to cry for something or somebody. tagivaka to cry about (something). kua ni tagi don't cry. tagi ivalu call to arms (to an ally), declare war. the cry of

animals is also indicated by this word. tagica n. soprano. vakatagi sici blow the horn (as of a car). tagi may imply a complaint, or appeal. tagitagi v., n., adj . crying idiom : sega ni tagi na toa mai nomudou me rogo mai ki ke. lit., the rooster that crows from your
