here. someone may be a powerful person in your village, but that means nothing in my village. tagicaka v. to cry (because of), to cry (for something). tagitagi n., v. continued crying,

the turtle’s eyes exude tears, appearing to cry. those tears are in vain. this applies to someone who yearns for what is impossible. (and in reality, it is a pathetic sight to see a turtle ’s tears.) vakatagi v. to play (a musical instrument, music tape or compact disc). na dau vakatagi p iano the piano player. na dau vakatagi bitu the player of the fij ian nose-flute (polynesian introduction). to play a guitar would normally be qiri, qiria as for ringing a bell, or ringing of a telephone.
n. instrumental music. dau ni vakatagi n. musician.
. v . to sing (a song, or traditional meke).
. (anglicism) n. soprano. alto alto. tena tenor. besi bass.
(archaic) v., n. declaration of war, call to war. modernly, may be used figuratively .

n. medicinal annual herb growing wild, vernonia cinerea, compositae, small herb growing about two feet high, a weed used medicinally. the tiny flowers are light blue. the leaves are rubbed in the hands, then unfolded again and plastered flat over cuts. the notion is that it will stop bleeding and accelerate healing. experience suggests this may be effective. syn. kaukamea.
(or) tagimoucia n. distinctive climbing plant, often epiphytic, famous in fiji for its white
and brilliant red bracts, medinilla waterhousei, melastomataceae, endemic to taveuni and
levu. it is the basis for several simple legends. various species, with different colouring, are found on other fiji islands, including gau island.
adj . tearful, crying. gone tagitagi crying child, cry-baby.
n. larynx, vocal chords, throat. lotu tagitagi or lotu qiriqiri, assemblies of god church, a
denomination from the u.s. that emphasises singing and playing of guitars, as well as
(unknown) tongues. tagitagikaua . v. to cry endlessly, unceasinglly.

. n. lion-fish, small very graceful fluttering-finned reef fish, dark and white, or blondbrown, not eaten, spines are poisonous, very painful but not life-threatening. supposedly more painful at low tide, hence the name.
ivalu (archaic) n. v. call to arms (or) war-cry. tribes or kin-groups often had a specific warcry, rallying their own forces, and intended to frighten the enemy.
v. to cry by howling desperately, frantically over great fear or sorrow.
n. internode (on stem or branches: bamboo, kava plant, sugar cane, duruka, etc.) see tagau n.
or internode. the word tagona has been adapted by teachers of fij ian language to mean “syllable”. thus a two-syllable word might be referred to as e dua na vosa tagoirua. outside of those
class-rooms, virtually no one would know this. tago bi n. stressed syllable (usually the
to last syllable of a fij ian word). tago mamada n. syllable that is not stressed when it is pronounced.

v. to turn around by itself, as a wind-vane might do. tagole na dakumu twist your back painfully by a sudden turn. tai . (eng.) n., v. tie (sports), equal scores. erau sa tai tu ena kei . they (two) tied to .
. n. coast, shore, river-bank. na tai kadua the other (opposite) shore. tailevu name of a province, lit. “big coast”.
(lau , from tahitian taiero) n. condiment made of crushed raw prawns fermented overnight in grated coconut, a specialty of oneata island. syn. taiyelo.
(eng.) n. typhoid fever, a danger in some rural areas of fij i where there is wet soil, infected water
people can be “carriers”. symptoms usually occur one to two weeks after exposure but can
from three days to three months. symptoms are very high fever, diarrhoea or constipation,
pain, headache, slow heart rate, diminished appetite. as many a twenty percent of infected people may die if not treated with anti-biotics. fijians had no word for typhoid fever.
(eng., slang) n. tiger, referring to a sports champion, especially in boxing.
v. to turn the body sharply while sitting to face the audience. a particular case is in the movements
in the sedentary meke dances of women. the movement should be sharp and cleancut.

n. mainland, coast (tai) of a large island, especially when it is across from a small island. kadavu island is tailevu in relation the small island ono. tailevu is a province of eastern viti levu island. taimi, taimitaka (eng.) v. to time (an event, such a boxing match, or a race).

(eng.) typewriter. taip a, taip ataka v. to type. dau ni taip a n. typist. taisau, taisau-taka v. to be assembled on opposite sides, lined up on each side (dancers at a performance, articles exhibited in a room.)
n. grandfather, mother's father.
(lau) n. a condiment, see taielo.
(eng. touch) n. touch football as a game.

(archaic) n. a very uncommon musical instrument made of bamboo, a kind of jew’s harp, resounding in the mouth when plucked with the fingers. taka, takara (or) takava v. brought, to spread, originate. vakataka v. to spread, disseminate, to originate something. e taka maivei na ka oqo ? where did this thing come from? na mate oqo taka mai vanuatu. this illness spread from vanuatu. sa takalevu e veiyasa i viti. it has spread out to all parts of fij i. takalailai found in only a few places, as with a biological species, birds, plants.
n. a minor chiefly title in some specific villages of the islands vatulele, kadavu, gau, and koro.
to as takalai gau, and pronounced that way , not takala-i-gau, as might be expected; he is
for communications from the vunivalu of bau island to people of gau island. in a sense, he is an interpreter of the chiefly will.
adj . as of a plant or animal species, of limited distribution. takalevu refers to something that is widespread.
. died (of a person, polite term), lost permanently.
. n. ocean, deep sea. ua mai takali wave from the ocean.
n. image, representation, statue
v. to drift ashore, as of a log or boat.s
. n. origin or source of something such as a word, a food, a disease that can be disseminated.
sick, refers to an infectious disease, one that spreads from a source such as flu. itakataka . n. a new usage of a word adapted by schoolteachers to indicate the correspondence of a fijian
for a foreign word taken directly into fij ian language, such as simede for the english word cement.
v. to stain.
n. centre-piece, central factor, keel (of a boat), originally referring only to part of a boat, but now generalised to be a central thing or central consideration, using the word figuratively.
v., n., adj . crooked or bent, as of a long piece of timber, or winding of a path or road. ikelo n. turn or bend or branching, as of a road or branch of a river.
(eng.) n. target, goal, aim. yacova na takete achieve the goal, reach the target. taketetaka v . to target, set a goal.
v. bent over at the end as with a faucet at the end of a water pipe. taki, takiva v. to dip (a container) into liquid. taki! serve a round of yaqona! a rather familiar idiom

at grog sessions. itaki n. ladle, dipper, spoon. na itakitaki container for carrying water, usually, from a well or source, a pool. takivaka v. to use as a container to carry water, as one uses a bucket, or a length of bamboo (in the highlands, formerly , before the introduction of buckets.)
. n. part, as of part of the body. cava taki-mu e mosi? what part of your body is in pain?
. n. social or family relationship. cava takimu o koya ? what relationship is he/she to you?
n. cooked food supplied for important visitor such as a visiting preacher. in the village, one or more families will be assigned this obligation for any one occasion. syn. itabetabe.
(archaic) n. open outrigger canoe with no deck covering for short trips and river travel even in the

levu highlands, along with dug-out canoes (bavelo) and bamboo rafts (bilibili). on larger ones, six to eight paddles might be used. tippet (p. ) reports the takia as coming from the hill counttry of the rewa valley, naitasiri, and the tributary valleys, waidina, waimaro, and wainibuka, and also the
and suva. deve toganivalu records that the takia was developed by mountain people and
adapted by coastal fijians to use for fishing. around the shore, takia might have a sail or in shallows, be pushed along by poling.
(tonga, via lau) in cricket, hit for a six .

prefix meaning “of many different sorts. takivei-roka of many different colours. e takivei-yaga na vu-ni-niu. the coconut palm has many different uses. tako n. a dualistic “moitié” division of society that defined local potential marriage partners in the western highlands of viti levu, colo north and colo west, and parts of colo east and ra. a person is either tako or lavo. one did not marry within one’s own group. if a father was born tako, all his children will

lavo, and if he is lavo they will be tako. the tako and lavo could have different totems. a person may be addressed by his/her classification tako or lavo. in a few locations colo tribes have brought the custom down to the lowlands in ba, for example, and in parts of ra. the social custom has eroded in
areas, losing a little of its significance. no careful study has been made of this social division
n. large wooden bowl trad. used for food preparation or presentation. see sedre, dari. takoso, takosova v. to go directly across, cut across. vosa takoso interrupt (speaking). sega ni dede sa

koya koso na tamana. before long his/her father interrupted him/her abruptly. sa tabu na curu takoso eke. it is forbidden to enter and cross over this place. na itatakoso n . the crossing (as of a road).
. n. hawkbill sea-turtle, eretmochelys imbricata, much smaller than the green sea turtle but feistier,
passive. its shell-parts overlap and are very valuable in contrast to the less valuable contiguous,
shell sections of the green turtle. food is mainly as a carnivore, eating j ellyfish (drose),

and shellfish. the hawkbill never attack s a person but defends itself with a dangerous beak. traditionally, turtles were caught in nets by specialist clans (gonedau) who were mainly of tongan origin. it used to be considered improper to spear a turtle. now there are attempts to preserve turtles. see vonu. taku . (archaic) adj . plastic, as in e dua na bilo taku a plastic cup. this rather dated word comes from
v., adj . scratched, abraded, as one’s arm or leg might be after a fall. syn. drakulu.

up until a certain time or event : e tala bogi na noqu cakacaka. my work will go on till night-time. tala v. to send (someone), as on an errand. talairawarawa compliant, obedient, implying they can readily be sent on errands. talaidredre disobedient. vakatalai ki tuba sent off (the field, in sports). idiom: e dua na itala ni vulagi a means of getting rid of a visitor, getting someone to leave. idiom: talai vakatoa child who is slow, unreliable when sent on an errand. (like a chicken, the child is diverted, losing track of the purpose of the mission.)
n. deportee, someone sent away. talabiu, talabiuta v. to dump, discard, or in some cases throw cargo overboard, for a ship in distress. see biu, biuta .
v. to scatter in all directions (of people, fish, birds), usually from some sudden fright. era
tiko ni sa kaila yani o seru. the people at the meeting scattered when seru yelled at them. syn. cerebu.
drodro v. to flow smoothly, together, as a swarm of fish , or water in a stream, people in a moving crowd, a story that flows along nicely, a speech that goes on and on.
kovana (archaic) secretary for fijian affairs during the colonial era. these were europeans, the last one being a. c. reid, before ratu sukuna took the post.
veivuke n. district commissioner, for one of the three administrative divisions of fiji, central, northern, and western, concerned with fij ian affairs.
n. messenger, emissary . tala, talaca . v. to unload (truck, boat). can also imply loading instead of discharging. talaca na buka
or extinguish a fire by removing firewood. talaca mai na buka bring up the firewood,

it should be dumped by the fire. (mai implies bringing it.) tala kako unload cargo. syn. (cakau.) ala, alaca or eli, elica. idiom: tala or tala simede (unload cement) may refer to having sex after long abstinence. vaqara tala
aeroport, their bus or car. it is custom to accompany someone departing as far as practicable. see talatala.
v. to send (someone) away. me vakatalai koya. send him away, have him sent away (from here).
v. to say farewell. veitalatala v. to say good-bye to each other. veitalayaka v. to send off (people or things) in several directions
n. protestant preacher. italatala qase methodist leader. from the tongan word talatala to inform, to contact.
n. yarn, story, fable, legend. (anglicism) italanoa buli fiction story, novel. na italanoa kei

the story about nayau. oya e dua tale na veitalanoa. (anglicism) that is a different story (matter). syn. (tonga) talanoa. talanoa, talanoa-taka v. to yarn, chat, relate (a story), usually for entertainment, social amusement.
n., adj . dry land burnt by the sun, scorched earth with little but dry grass, often referred to in
viti levu. this land was mostly forested in early days, the trees burned off by early fij ian settlers looking for wild yams or clearing land for gardens. grass replaced the trees.
v. to empty out, unload (things from box, trunk, bag). na italautalaucaki the unpacking, emptying out. see talaca.
v. to send, as in talavaka na ivola. to send the letter.
. v. to rise up quickly (as of a person, alarmed or an aeroplane taking off); to raise up quickly. e dau talave mai nadi na waqavuka. the aeroplane usually takes off from nadi.
. v. tilted, in a tilting position. vakatalave-taka to tilt (something). there is an implication of rising up. syn. talaqa.
adj . quite sufficient, ample. sa talavo na kakana. there is quite enough food.
v. to extinguish a fire completely, usually after cooking or camping.
. again cakava tale do it again. tukuna tale tell it again. lesu tale return. italetale n . chorus (of a song or meke). tale ga also. taletale repetitive.
. more. eso tale. some more. e dua tale na ka another (or) one more thing. sega tale ni wawa
(any more). kei na so tale et cetera.
. other, as in : e sega tale na sala. there is no other way. solia vei ira tale na so. give to some
(many). tale . else. a cava tale? what else? tale . already, as in: o sa oti tale? you have finished already ?
(eng.) n. talent.
repetitive. ua taletale n. tsunami, tidal wave that comes in several surges.
n. chorus (of a song). na italetale ni sere the chorus of the song. tale, taleva . v. to visit (a place or person). e mai talevu na noda vanua na tui tabu. the pope came
(eng.) n. telephone. qiri, qiria to ring someone. telephone numbers are spoken with
separate, as in spoken as tolu ono rua, rua lima saiva va. it is typical not readily to reveal one’s name when phoning. syn. telef oni.
also. sometimes, perhaps more properly, written as tale ga.
. adj . delightful. . adj . precious. vatu talei gemstone. fijians had no notion of precious stones. talei can now be a girl’s name.
v. to delight in . . , to enjoy.
v. to do something several times, or repeatedly.
(eng.) n. telephone, various spellings. syn. televoni
n. food provided for visiting methodist preacher on sundays. villagers may take turns in providing this food. it is methodist custom to have visiting preachers. syn. itale ni vunau.

v. to chop off the husk and remove the flesh, of coconuts. lewe-na flesh. see cici, cicia. tali, talia v. to weave (mats, sinnet). plaiting of sinnet (magimagi) is usually done with three strands (qamina). such plaiting of sinnet, or of a girl’s hair may be referred to as tobe, tobea. a girl’s plaited
(itobe) indicate that she is a virgin. (fij ians have no specific word for virgin.) in the viti levu

at naboubuco the number of locks indicated the girl ’s age. tali-sasa, talisasa-taka v. to plait coconut leaves to contain fish or meat to be cooked in earth-oven. idiom: tali magimagi chat together, lit. to plait sinnet, because men often chat together when they plait sinnet, to tell a story or report in very great detail.
v . no matter, does not matter (may be said alone). sa veitalia vei au. it is all the same to me, i

not care. whether or not this is polite depends on context and tone of voice. sometimes abbreviated as talia. tali-sasa, talisasataka v. to weave coconut palm leaves to protect food to be cooked in earth oven.
falsely.
v. to gleam, glisten, usually with reflected light. talitaliva to gleam very stongly. syn. caliva.

v. to be spilled out in a small stream. see livi, livia. taliwa, taliwa-taka v. to stitch with a needle, to sew, usually cloth. talo, talova v. to pour deliberately, controlling the liquid in small quantities as for yaqona or a cup of tea. talo! pour ! serve it ! (usually of yaqona). talotaloca v. to go on pouring.

v. to come undone, loose, let go, inadvertantly, as a knot in a rope. see luva, also tasere. tama, tamaka v. to call out formally, announcing one’s intended visit to a fijian house, a ritual call (that varies from region to region), that the host responds to, normally to welcome the approach.
. n. a call to announce one’s presence outside a house. exact words vary by region but a common
is “dua o! ” properly, one waits for a response before coming closer or entering. woman ’s greeting may differ from a man ’s.

. huge, a great deal of, used only in context :- tama ni ka levu huge big thing. tamani-ose huge horse. syn. tamatama. see tinatina mature female animal. tama-ni . huge amount of: tama ni ilavo o a rawata! huge lot of money you have earned (obtained) ! tama-na n. father. tamaqu my father. tama i seru father of seru . traditionally in fij i it was impolite to
a person by name. it is still better form to refer to a person by some term of family
or title. paternal uncles (father ’s brothers) are considered fathers, just as cousins are considered as brothers. a person may be named tamana if his namesake is a tama-na. erau veitamani
() are father and son (or daughter). abbrev. ta, tata . syn. (macuata) maqu. (nadro) vava .
n. uncle, younger brother of the father.
n. uncle, older brother of the father.
n., v. father(s) and child(ren).
n. people. mata tamata race (of people). na veimata tamata kece all races of peeple). traditionally, all but a chief should respectfully say tamata, tabuyani, not just tamata alone. tamata
healthy person in the prime of life. tamata cakacaka n. workers. see lewe.
n. mature male, of an animal such as chicken (rooster), pig (boar), cattle (bull).
v. to ring out, of a pleasant sound, a bell, or two bush knives clashing.
adj . enormous, awesome.
. v. to twist or turn sharply, revolve, turning on itself.
. n., v. to sprain , sprained, twisted (as of ankle). see moi, moica.
n. mid-section of the body.
n, see damole.

v. non-melodic noise, as of children unsupervised, clinking, scratching, may imply a continued ringing or rustling sound. tamulo v. twisted unintentionally, as of a rope. by ext. may refer to stomach cramps.
(tahiti, cook islands “tamure”) v., n. tamure, polynesian dance by young women and men,

fast hip movement of the girls, the rapid beat of the drums. danced mainly as a tourist attraction, now widely performed in many of the pacific islands. tamusu, tamusuka v. to cut off abruptly, sharply. see musu.
n. edible fish, close to shore, lutj anus fulvus. syn. kake.

n. tiny fish , young sicydiaphiinae, sub-family of gobies, spawned in fresh water, develope in the sea, then migrate upstream annually in huge numbers, in the navua river, for example. caught in nets, eaten rather like the whitebait of new zealand. syn. cigani.
(samoa - bowl) n, wooden bowl, usually made of vesi timber, for serving kava. on viti levu it

four legs and an abrupt lip ; in lau it has eight or even legs and a smooth lip. formally and properly, many tanoa have a frontal piece with two white cowries and a long, thick sinnet cord (wa tabu) laid out in the direction of the chief, with a single white cowrie attached at the end. this is
symbolic of a penis with the notion of fertility. it is forbidden for anyone to walk in front
of pottery was an introduction of tongan settlers. (the earliest, proto-polynesian settlers made pottery but those pre-millenium lapita people had no significant, continued existence in fiji.) in
places a wooden bowl (dari) with legs was used. in the highlands of viti levu a bowl was
with leaves in a depression dug in the ground. the wooden tanoa was introduced via
only in the latter half of the s. informally, these days, fijians may use a simply enamel
though still a few ceremonial words and gestures are made before serving. it is a rather firm

that when a “mix” is made in the tanoa, it must be all consumed at that sitting. the tanoa is not washed ; a prized patina forms on the surface after long use. the bowl should be hung against the wall when not in use, so that dust does not settle on it. most tanoa are made at kabara island, centre of wood-carving in fiji. wood-working machinery is now used.

. particle placed after a verb indicating direction out and away (from some place). lako tani! get out ! go away ! vakauta tani export, send (something) away. duatani different, strange, unnatural, foreign.
. particle indicating a place away mai vanua tani overseas, in a foreign country. vakawati tani married away, away from home.
. n. foreigner, kai tani, one who is not a native fijian, not a local person. vulagi is a more polite term, implying a guest or visitor.
. (eng.) ton or tonne (a measure of weight). e lima na tani five tonnes. as in english, there are
types of tons or tonnes, the old english ton, the metric tonne of , kilograms, and the maritime tonne.
v. to be caught, stuck, restrained or constrained, and by ext. can mean “tied up”, being busy with

and thus perhaps late for another appointment. au a calata na basi, au a tao vei seru. i missed the bus, i was tied up with seru. sa tao na noqu wa ni siwa. my fishing line got caught, stuck (as onto a rock).
v. to stop, impede, restrain, constrain, to make something stuck or stopped, as a rope or line.
(eng.) town. na taoni o korovou korovou town. vaka-taoni urban. tauni-olo town hall. syn. tauni.
(tonga) n. woven pandanus deep cummerbund worn around the waist by men, women and
in parts of lau. this has been customary especially in the tongan settlement sawana, by lomaloma, vanua balavu. wherever there are tongans, at formal occasions the ta ’ovala will be worn.
place by a type of belt called a kaf a, made of braided cord sinnet. different styles of ta ’ovala
used for different occasions, colourful for weddings, solemn ones for solemn occasions, tattered
to show respect and humility. instead of a ta ’avola, women may wear a kiekei, a women
belt with many strands dangling decoratively, reaching below the knees, woven in a fancy way, sometimes with shells or other ornaments attached. syn. (samoa & lau) gaf egaf e.
(anglicism) v. to spray out, as a water-pipe leaking under pressure. taqa, taqara v. to lay down, stack (on the ground, on a shelf), yams, books, dishes, etc., placing one

on top of another or on top of something (such as shelf). taqairua two layers (of things in a stack). itaqataqa place for putting somethings down. taqari, taqarica or taqaritaka v. to wipe one ’s bottom (with something) after going to the toilet. itaqari n. toilet paper equivalent, such as leaves, newspaper. syn. (lau) kavelu. cf. also quata na gone lailai. to wipe the bottom of the baby,
ni qaqa n. victory parade (as after world war ii). formerly taqa referred to the assemby and

of warriors, as a military review, only for coastal, paramount chiefs, before the combat of war. it was largely a boastful show. taqaya, taqayataka v. to be anxious about usually (some specific danger for specific people or possible events). taqataqaya constant worrying.

(eng.) n. tank, as in fuel tank. taqe, taqea v. to scoop up, as of ashes, sand, rice, money, nails, many small things. taqo, taqomaka v. to protect, keep safely (things or people). na tataqomaki the protection, preservation,
(emphatic). na veitaqomaki the protection (more generally).

v. drift, of a boat when the anchor is not holding. ququ to drag, of an anchor. taqusi . v. to be smeared, smudged. tataqusiqusi v. to scrape hard. see qusia. taqusi . v. to be erased, wipe off. see qusi. tara, tara v. to be permitted, allowed. sa tara na lako. going (there) is allowed. this is the opposite of “tabu ”, forbidden, prohibited. ivola tara licence, permit. vakatara, vakatara v. to permit (person or action). e vakatarai vei au me'u lako i am allowed to go. sa vakatarai na cakacaka e na siga tabu. work is permitted on sundays.

n. permission, the lifting of a prohibition, as in na vakatarai ni siga tabu the lifting of the sunday prohibitions. tara, tara . v. to touch, handle, to contact (person), undertake (begin doing something). vuli tara learn(ing) by experience, "hands-on " experience. veitarai children's game of "tag". e qai tatara yani

taga he/she groped, felt in (the: his/her) pocket. veitaratara touching each other. veitaratarai adj acent. idiom: tara-koro to gossip together, as an informal group, about people, relatives, news from the

(koro). tara, tara . v. to accept a presentation (usually a whale-tooth) by a ceremonial touching with the hand. idiom: tara na kamunaga in formal ceremony, reach out and touch the whale tooth offered, indicating acceptance. this will be followed by a speech of acknowledgment. idiom: tara tabua n. second oldest child. one’s oldest child is referred to as the ulumatua. tara, tara . v. to take in the hand, to catch in the hand (prawns for example). tara ura catch prawns by hand. tara na bilo ena teveli take the cup on the table. tara, tara . v. to catch (usually fish, crustacea), taking by the hand. tara nuqa to catch rabbit-fish.

kuita catch octopus. tara qari catch sea-crabs. tara lairo catch land crabs. tara duna catch eels. tara kawakawa catch rock cod. era dau tara ika ena duva. they (many) usually catch fish with fish-poison. eratou a tara na ika ena loma ni bai. they (few) caught the fish within the fish-fence (probably with the help of spears). tara ba (ni ika) to collect fish from the fish-fence. syn. tobo, toboka. tara, tara . v. to reach , to affect, to afflict. na leqa ka tarai ira kece the trouble that affected them all.

the hiv that afflicted them (few). idiom: tara reveni reach the limit, accomplish the goal (sometimes said when drinking yaqona), come to the end. raveni ribbon. tara, tara . v. to build, or make, as of a house, or a village (which can be done in a very few weeks).
adj . under-cooked, usually as of a root-crop in the earth oven, not cooked long enough, or located too far from the steam or hot rock s. may apply to other foods. syn. butadroka.
v., n. children ’s game of “tag”.
v. to stumble, to trip up. vakatarabe-taka to case someone to trip. see lalia
adj . very high, “touching the rafters” (within the house). taratarabewa extremely high (indoors).
v. to be burdensome, difficult to undertake, or do, or perform, as a duty or task. taratara-bi to be very burdensome.
v . to widthdraw money , as from a bank account.
n. hand-net, as used by one person, usually a woman, for catching small fish. syn. itaga.
v. to contact, get in touch with. veitaratara kei tukana get in touch with tukana.
adj ., n. continuous, continual, consecutive or sequential order. sequence. na vu
the continuous coughing. tuvai vakamatua vosa ena veitarataravi arranged in alphabetical order. na veitarataravi ni veika e yaco. the sequence of things that happen.
(eng.) . trump, a card game commonly played by fijians. mata ni imau cards. daimani diamonds. kalavo clubs. sivi (or) siveti spades. yate hearts. note that in playing cards fijians speak
(yate) in place of the heart (uto). for fij ians, the liver, and not the heart, are the place of
courage. . trumpet brand of cane knife, english made, often preferred by fijians though
expensive. fijians call the brand biukila for bugle. . tarabu may also refer figuratively to a
card in an argument or negotiation, as a trick up the sleeve, a winning card, so to speak, a deciding point in one’s favour.

v., n . ceremony with a feast ending days of wearing mourning clothes, after death in the family. normal clothing is resumed. tarakadru, tarakadruta v . to touch very briefly, usually very discreetly, another person as a secret, nonverbal signal with the hand, arm or foot. in mixed company such silent, secretive signals are common in interpersonal communications. sometimes a glance with the eye may suffice. kadru to scratch.
n. (hindi) v. to make a curry (fish, lamb, beef or vegetable).
(eng. “tra-la-la”) n., v. simple, shuffling dance of man and woman, side by side with arms
each other’s waist, quasi-traditional since early colonial times, invented at a school in the ba
an english tune. for a great many decades, this has been the only type of social dance
in the rural villages. a guest will be invited to participate by a local woman. (she may be appointed to that task.) slang terms butu kai, taura tale.
v. to dance the taralala with (person). tarasea or tarase n. species of sea slug (dri), actinopygia mauritana, holothuriaceae, rigid body, reddish,
and white blotches; average cm, found at - meters. has commercial value,
(loaloa). syn. (kadavu) togo.
target_text: but much less valued than the black types

source_text: (or) tarusese (eng., tonga talausese) n. trousers.
adj . damp, usually clothing, the hands, feet. see kulumaca.
(archaic) n. second child, after the eldest.
v. to feel movement of an unborn baby, by the mother; that may involve early signs of oncoming labour.
v. to follow in time (things or events), follow in order, follow in movement. vakaveitarataravi put
consecutive, next. e rua na yabaki veitaravi two consecutive years. ono na druka veitaravi
consecutive losses. vakaveitaravi consecutively. j abeni veitarataravi ena tolu na yabaki.
for three consecutive years. veitarataravi-taka to do something repeatedly, consecutively, as in catching fish one right after another.
adj . water-proof, as of a watch, a rather forced modernism, of course.
n. tree, dracontomelon vitiense, wild or semi-cultivated small fruit, rather thin-fleshed and
to non-fijians. a common snack-food in season, around june, july. legend speaks of it as a food of the gods, and hence the idiom laki tei tarawau to die, lit. go or gone planting tarawau. isoso
cluster of tarawau fruit.
(colo east) n. ceremonial presentation of goods to compensate for one’s ab sence when a relative has died in the village. syn. boka.
n. question. na nomu taro your question (the question you ask). fij ian are usually discouraged from asking too many questions. mostly they are expected to learn by observing. na biubiu ni taro the

(questions). loma tarotaro questioning mind. taro, taroga v. to ask a question. me tarogi koya ask him (the question). na veitarogi the questioning, exam. matabose ni veitarogi vanua native land commission (determines existent clans and assigns native land rights). na vakatataro n. the repetitive or continued questioning. taro ivakasala vei ira na qase ni vuli. ask advice from the (many) school teachers.

n. exam, questioning. veitarogi vakavanua n. official questioning fijian village elders on land ownership by native lands commission, usually resulting in legally binding decisions. native land is usually assigned to individual clans mataqali.

adj . to rustle as paper may do or dried leaves, see raqosa. taro, tarova v. to stop. sa tarovi koso na bose. the conference was stopped abruptly. na veitarovi the stopping. na itatarovi n. obstacle, hindrance, the thing that causes stopping, as in the case of the contraceptive na itatarovi ni vakaluveni. itatarovi ni cagi windshield (of a car, boat).
v. to cut a new path or road. sala path. gaunisala road.

(rotuma) n. specialty food, flesh of young coconut bu cut up and left to ferment for four days in the sun, often served with some garnish na kena icoi. tase, tasea v. to split lengthwise, as of a log, to make planks, deliberately and more forcefully than se,
to split or tear lengthwise. tasei split. sei torn, though the words are almost synonymous.
v . to become untied (unexpectedly), as in sa tasere na buke. the knot came undone.
(eng.) n . task, task-work, piece-work in labour agreements, in contrast to day-labour (murisiga).
workers usually perform better with short-term, well defined task s with immediate cash payment.

n. very thin partial moon. tasi, tasia . v. to peel (taro, yam, cassava). tasi, tasia . v. to sharpen by scraping, shaving (spear, pencil). tasi, tasia . v. remove the surface hair (pig, human head, body). tasi shaved (of the head), bald, as in
shaved head. tasili, tasili-taka (eng.) v., adj . to tar-seal, tar-sealed. gaunisala tasili tar-sealed road. tasina, tasinataka v. to paint design on barkcloth without the use of a stencil.
v. to spurt ahead, usually of a person or animal running, or of a boat. see siri.
v. j etsam, flotsam washed ashore. tasoro v. to become slack, as of a rope. see soro, sorova.
spilt, usually water or milk . see sova .
n. dad, daddy, sometimes abbrev . as ta. the relationship includes the father ’s brothers. such a
is referred to as tata levu if older than the father, and tata lailai if younger. tata or ta are affectionate abbrev. of tama-na, father. syn. (nadroga) nahuna (or) nana, vavai.
v. to spread, disseminate, be evident or known (usually news, stories, rumours). often used in the
form vakatata. sa noqu inaki me vakata-taki na vuna. it is my intention to make known the cause. sa vakatata na we ni mauwena . his footsteps are clearly visible.
n. crossroad, where two paths meet.
v. to stutter. syn. gusu-tata n., v. dau tata-cemeceme n. stutterer.

prefix to a verb, implying repeated, vigorous or great amount of an activity. tata-sei to split. tatalaka to chop down. tata-melamela na rorogo ni qiri kava. noise of the banging on tins. tatagedegede battered about, as a boat in heavy seas. tata moce to babble with sleep-talk . tata-balebale v. to fall here and there, staggering, as when drunk. era tata-mosamosa na lairo e loma ni dramu kava. the mud crabs scratched around noisily inside the metal drum. tata-qiriqiri sound like chipping rust off metal. tata, tatataka v. to rub the body vigorously with a wet cloth, especially the face. syn. (lau) tataf i (or) tatavi. tatadra, tatadrataka v. to dream, to dream of while awake (often with a sense of longing). tadra,
to dream (in one ’s sleep).
(lau) v. to wash the face.
n. wooden paddle used by potters to shape pots. no pottery wheel has been used in fiji.
v. to press the arm against something, the wall, the floor, the table, perhap s for support. taba-na n. arm.
v. to stagger, falling here and there, usually of a drunk.
v. to stagger. syn. tatabalebale. itataviraki n. broom. syn. sasa, when made of coconut palm-leaf midrib s.
v. to chop with (something). e tataka na matau. he chopped with the axe.
v. to warm oneself by a fire. tatalaka v. to chop repeatedly (big things usually , trees, people) with force, chop up (little things, though less commonly applied to little things). see ta, taya.
v. to be simulating, going through the motions, acting out, pretending to be doing something (children playing at adult activities like cooking, workers slacking off, idling at their work and
little). vakatatalo-taka na cakacaka go through the motions of work. dakai ni
toy gun. iyaya ni vakatatalo toys.
v. make a lot of noise, of many objects ringing out, such a tins being banged with a stick . (children do this around new year’s eve.)

v. to make a lot of repeated sounds, as in era tatamosamosa na lairo e loma ni dramu kava. the land-crabs scratch about, making a continued or repetitive sound, in this case a rustling, inside the metal drum.
v. to catch eel, prawn, crabs, octopus, fish, reaching, groping, snatching with the hand, often by women. tara implies some action of the hand by touching, catching hold of something.
n. in an earth oven (lovo), a protective layer of vegetation between the hot rocks and the food to be cooked. this is often coconut leaf with midribs, or stems of banana or plantain.
or itaratara . n. protective layer or cover generally, to prevent something from being damaged,
as food, or a book. this may be a form of bag, of woven material, cotton cloth, paper, sheet of plastic.
. n. (anglicism) lingerie, specifically a woman ’s slip or half-slip. (the implication is of a protective layer.) sulu i loma underwear. syn. liku e loma

v. to intercede, as in a dispute between others, and by ext., to flag down a passing vehicle, to hitchhike or catch a bus. to stop a car or bus one pats the air with an extended and lowered arm, raising it no higher than the waist. (it would be rude or threatening to show a raised hand.) tataro motoka v. to wave down a car, to hitch-hike.
n. ob stacle, hindrance. see tarova to stop, prevent.
n. contraceptive. luve child. tatau, tatautaka v. to request politely (for some permission, especially to take one’s leave). au sa
lako i request permission to leave, to go. a u sa tatautaki au meu sa lesu ki na noqu vale. i have asked permission to return to my house. caution: this word is often confused with

n . formal polite request, almost invariably to take one ’s leave. tataunaka v. to assign or give responsibility for the care of someone or something, often as a request. au tataunaka na cakacaka oqo vei saba. i give responsibility for this work to saba. au tataunaki iko vei seru. i leave you in seru ’s care. o tataunaki tu vei cei? who is supposed to be looking after you? (to a child, often said reproachfully). au tataunaka vei seru me kauta mai. i ask (asked) seru to bring it.
v ., n. to babble or talk in one’s sleep. see tetewai. tatawasewase adj . fragmented in many pieces. tawase divided. see wase, wasea.
n. crevice under a ledge, as at a coral reef. teba implies a spreading out above and undercut below. ulu-teba refers to hair that is long, combed to spread up and out.
v., adj . tilted, as in sa vaka-tatiki na vula. the moon is tilted on its side. (for fijians this may be a sign of impending rain.)
. v. inadvertantly to bump the head on something hard or be struck on the head.
. v. to make a throbbing, drumming sound, as with a fij ian drum (lali).
n. swollen testicles, elephantiasis of the testicles (ceke). in the central and eastern viti levu
is matuku, a legendary power of super-tribe waimaro, and source for the name of
and some clans named matuku. huge testicles were prestigious symbol of strength and
for which the waimaro highlanders were famous. tuku implies a lowering of something that hangs, as from a rope. see ceke, tauna, waqaqa.
v. to place some weight, such as a stone, to hold down say a mat, or voivoi, to keep it in place, as on a windy day . syn. danuya, tabika.
prefix for numbers, as in taudua one alone, single, taurua two at a time, etc.
n. friend. syn. itokani. vakaitau to have a friend, chum, boyfriend, girlfriend.

. adj . to be or to have friends, chums, friendship. eratou veitau. they (several) are friends. au sega ni veitau. i have no boyfriend (girlfriend), with romantic implications, these days often said even by very young teenagers. itau n. friend. veitau . v., n. competitive race. veitau-cici running race, track race. veitau ose horse-race.
n. friendly form of address between people of certain different regions who are veitauvu (related

either by having the same ancestral spirit (vu), or by ancient chiefly marriage that united them). see tauvu. tau, tauca . v. to fall, especially of rain. sa tau na uca. it is raining. sa tau bi na uca. it is raining hard (heavily). sa tau bi. it fell (or falls) heavily (rain, heavy object). biuta na senikau ituba me tauca na uca. put the flowers outside so that the rain can fall on them. sa suasua na isulu ni tauca na uca. the clothes got wet when the rain fell on them. tau, tauca . to set down, to put down, to let fall. . tau! drop it ! let it fall ! me tau na icolacola drop (let fall, put down) the burden (that is carried on the shoulder). sa tau mai nadi na waqavuka. the
(landed) at nadi. tau, tauca . v. to speak, pronounce (words, speech), make a pronouncement or judgement, a set of
words such at at a isevusevu ceremony. tauca na vosa to speak the words, make the speech, pronounce the words; to pass, pronounce (judgement), pronounce, to impose (court sentence).

impose the penalty. itautau n. pronouncement tau, tauca . v. to pick (breadfruit, orange, mango, tarawau, etc.), cut and gather leaves such as voivoi for weaving. tauca mai! pick it !. itautau n. stem (of leaf, flower or fruit), the part of the plant where it is picked or plucked. by ext., may imply winning a prize. tau, tauca . v. to obtain. tauca na kakana to obtain the food. tau, tauca . v. in sailing, to turn into the wind, to luff.
. n. ends, fore and aft, of a boat. syn. mua-na.

(archaic) n., adj . type of boat like a takia but having both ends covered to impede the inflow of surging waves or spray, sometimes referred to as a waqa vakatau. taubale, taubaletaka . v. to walk. to walk on (a path, road, beach). itautaubale n. walkway , path , and modernly a pavement or sidewalk.
v. to eat starch-food (kakana dina) with no relish (na kena icoi). keitou taubale dalo tiko. we (few) are just eating taro, with no garnish.
n. necklace or garland hung around the neck. some chiefly ones were made of shells, cowry, for example, as a fertility symbol, later, of pearlshell that was inlaid, some composed of fashioned pieces
and the waseisei. waseisei, made of strips of whaletooth, were used by bau to reward some
for their cooperation (and betrayal of their fellow highlanders). the small white
was traditionally worn around the neck only by a chiefly female. taube civa n. pearlshell necklace.
v. to wear (necklace or garland, usually of fragrant leaves, flowers, or of shells). vakataubena
such a garland on (someone), as for a guest of honour at a ceremony. distinguished guests are always so honoured at formal receptions.
v. tauca to put down, let down, as of some burden. taucoko . whole, all, entire, entirely, complete. taucoko . j am-packed, full of people, as a meeting room might be.
(ni koro) n. outskirts (of town, village), outside. vakawati ena taudaku ni lotu married outside the church . ena taudaku kei ovalau beyond ovalau , on the other side of ovalau (from viti levu).
timely, on time, at the right time, apt. appropriate at the occasion.
alone. taurua only two, both, for both. au sa lako taudua ga. i’m going quite alone. tautolu only three, for three people.
(tongan) n. whisk-broom of coconut-leaf ribs (sasa) bound to a wooden handle, usually with
sinnet cord. formerly, most fijian whisk-brooms (sasa) had no attached handle. both
of broom are sold at the public market. itaf i similar broom but with longer handle, more for outdoor use.

n. (archaic) wooden hook with rat-guard rail used for storing food, hung from house rafter, safe from rats, dogs, ants. now seen only in fij i museum and sold as handicrafts in tourist shops. itaukei adj . native fijian, as in sotia itaukei native fij ian soldier.

n. owner of some thing, itaukei ni motoka owner of the motor car. na kena itaukei its owner. originally, this word referred to a person who maintained usage rights over something, and might have rights concerning its disposal, not strictly speaking an “owner” in the european sense of that word. itaukei n. fijian native (of a place), these days often capitalised as itaukei, referring to indigenous fij ians in general. the word has become a polite way of referring to fijians as in e dua ni cauravou itaukei a fijian youth. gone itaukei native fij ian. turaga itaukei fijian gentleman (polite term for mature adult fij ian man). the new term itaukei may refer only to officially registered fij ians. itaukei dredre hardline itaukei, belligerent in politics, asserting rights of fijians versus indians, europeans and other ethnic/racial groups. traditionally the term itaukei ni qele refers only to original settlers of an area,
the clans or tribes that joined the settlement later (though, often the case, the later settlers force
way to takeover the chiefly position.) as a modernism, the word has come to include all native
who own native land. o ira na itaukei ni qele the (many) landowners. in fact, some fij ian

own very little land and some clans own none at all. these days quite a number of fij ians are not even registered as fij ians in records of the native lands commission. the n.l .c. has estimated at least ten percent.

(followed by place-name) title of traditionally appointed chief in various places of western viti levu island. the word taukei being followed by the name of the people, chief of . . ., as in the taukei nakelo, chief of nakelo people (as at village viseisei), or the taukei sawaieke, chief of sawaieke, a
of title at vuda for head of the tribe tububere at village viseisei, spokesman for the tui vuda.
examples: taukei navo at dratabu, taukei werenidri at nasigatoka, and the taukei vidilo at namoli.
v. to own (something, house, boat, land); to have usage rights by traditional custom. ownership
such might have a very different meaning to fijians, as compared to european notions of ownership . individual ownership is less common. e rau taukena na sitoa. they (two) own the store.
the owner (literally , its owner).
n. nail, as in itaukuku ni liga-na fingernail, itaukuku ni yava-na toenail. also hoof (horse, cow), trotter (pig), claw (bird, cat). ivako n. carpentry nail.
v. to give birth (a very respectful word), taulaki born. syn. vakasucu.
first (before something else in time), first in importance, firstly, first of all. a vosa taumada
(of book), prologue.
n. elephantiasis, particularly the grotesque swelling of certain parts of the body (legs and arms
but also testicles and scrotum), and sometimes causing blindness, that follows from
infection (waqaqa), with symptoms of fever, fatigue, weakness and swollen lymph glands.
any one of thread-like nematodes in the lymph glands. different vectors affect
parts of the body. infection is transmitted from person to person usually by the bite of a mosquito, a culex sp. (one species) or aedes spp. (three species), or possibly, a fly . there was an
% in the fiji population in . there is a national programme to provide free
annual pills (not advised for pregnant women and children under two years of age). continuing, repeated infection over a ten-year period can bring about elephantiasis. syn. (lau) f ua. see tatuku.
n. mosquito net. originally, this was made of barkcloth (masi) but did not exist in the most of
(except in navosa, brought by tongans) and just
target_text: the viti levu highlands where there was no barkcloth

source_text: (namu).
target_text: smoke was used to avoid mosquitos

source_text: v. scattered, to scatter in disorderly fashion, such as tools in a tool-room.
. v. to take, take hold, to hold in the hand, to accept. taura! take it ! (anglicisms) taura

take the advice lightly. taura vakabibi take it seriously. idiom: taura tale v., n. dance (man and woman as a pair), lit. “take again”. syn. n., v. taralala (a specific type of social dance, as a european influence). idiom: tauri lisi to receive lease money for native land leased to tenants.
. understand. o taura na noqu vosa ? do you understand what i am saying? taura cala to misunderstand.
v., n. to dance with a partner, as at a village taralala dance, a dance derived from european custom, not indigenous.
v. to hold hands. syn. veiqumi liga. rau veitauriliga ena sitoa na veitinani. the mother and
each other ’s hand in the store. by ext. to work together co-operatively, to help one another.
da veitauriliga ena cakacaka vakoro. let us (many) work together on the village work. young
may walk together holding hands. there is no sexual implication to that. it would be thought improper for male and female fijians to to be seen holding hands romantically.
(anglicism) v. to take the minutes of a meeting.
v. to take the helm of a boat or wheel of a car. uli helm, rudder.
v. to use. syn. vakayagataka.
alone, of two people together. taudua alone (one person). tautolu just three people, and so on for any number of people.
v., n. collection of money for community purpose.
n. bunch or cluster as of hanging fruit (such as mango or wi) or coconuts. syn. isoso but tausoso implies hanging down of clusters of greater substance.
. n. enunciation of rhythm (of music), of words (in speech), distinctiveness of movement (in gestures, motions of dance).
. n. pronouncement.
. n. implication, innuendo, of something said. e veibeci dina na itautau ni nomu vosa. your words really have despicable innuendo.
. n. stem (of leaf, flower or fruit), the place on the plant where it is picked or plucked.

n. a very large grey-coloured freshwater river eel that nests in rocks and suns itself. when disturbed it can be aggressive and attack, and often goes on land, even flinging itself at an aggressor. it sometimes lies under leaves, giving rise to the false impression that it is a snake. this eel has ample fat
n. handle (as of basket, bucket, box, cup), not of a knife, axe or hand-tool where the proper word would be dia-na.
. same, even (sporting score, level of ground). tautauvata kei same as, equal with, equivalent to.

. level, smooth, physically even, flat. vakatautauvata, vakatautauvatana v. to compare. sa mai na iwiliwili ni vakatautauvatani kei na ena yabaki sa oti. the count has reached , compared with last year. syn. vakatauvatana.
n. outside (of house, building).
. v. to afflict by (usually some infectious illness). sa tauvi koya na mate. he/she has been
by a sickness. rerevaki ke tauva na gone lalai dangerous if it inflicts little children.
v., n ., adj . sick. syn. taka, takava. tauva . v. to stain (a person, clothes, wood) as from a dye, paint, fruit juice). syn. taka, takava.
n. commoner, common people, usually with no specialized traditional function for their clan,
as priest, warriors, fishermen. syn. lewenivanua implies simply that the people are not chiefly or significant elders.
compared with, in comparison to, as in ni vakatauvatani kei na . . . as compared with the . . . syn. vakatautauvatana. see above.
in a question, how many people? also applies to fruit, asking how many. na kavika, tauvica qori? how many kavika fruit are there there (where you are)? syn. le vica ? (how many people?).
n., adj . sick. tautauvimate sickly. syn. (lau, kadavu) baca.
n., adj . people of certain geographically separated tribes who in legend derive from the same
spirit (vu), or have been united anciently by chiefly marriage. one says that the people are
(related in this way). one may address one’s tauvu as “tau”. they are inclined to make jokes, play tricks against each other, playful insults, sometimes obnoxious. for relationships where the
can be extreme, they are tauvu dredre, “hard” tauvu. similar mutual behaviour occurs in the veitabani relationship . these days this relationship may extend to whole territories or even provinces
than specific localities or specific tribes that was the older tradition. nayau island in lau and

territory in rewa are veitauvu, based on an ancient marriage of a lauan lady into noco. see tau. taba-na. veitabani. tauyavu, tauyavutaka v. to establish, to found, to lay the foundation for. yavu foundation, basis. tava, tava v. to slice, cut off or cut into with a knife (formerly this was often a sharp strip of bamboo).
to cutting open a mature boil, castrating animals (not traditional), removing skin of cassava
arm. tavatava slicing, which may imply child punishment or bleeding for fij ian medical purposes. see tavatava.
having many tiny holes, as a mosquito screen does, or a sponge. this is very probably a modernism.
. v. to wait for (people). tavaki au. wait for me. syn. waraka.
. v. to “possess” in the sense that a devil possesses a person.
. v. to yank, as in tavaka na wa ni siwa! jerk the fishing line ! yank it ! this to ensure the fish is well hooked after it has bitten the bait.
(eng.) n. cigarette, tobacco. kana tavako (or) vakatavako to smoke (tobacco). sa tabu na
smoking is prohibited. tavako ni viti is grown in fij i, wrapped tightly in coils the size of
own smokes. covers (suluka), as for home-made cigars, are usually dried leaves of plantain or
(wadruca) between the fingers. idiom: itibi tavako (or) itibi a “butt”, literally a “roll”, slang for a cigarette.
n. cross-cousin, ie., child of one’s father’s sister or of one’s mother’s brother. veitavaleni adj .
as cross-cousins, or as n., the set of two or more cross-cousins. this is an extremely close relationship, very supportive and essentially members of the same family. those of opposite sex are
candidates to marry each other in fiji though first-cousin marriages are prohibited among europeans. tavale are usually addressed as “tavale ”, rather than tavalequ. these days one ’s tavale
same or opposite sex. more traditionally, two tavale would both be male cross-cousins, and in english be referred to as “cousin-brother”. cross-cousins of different sex would be veidavoleni.
is the “correct” term. when both cross-cousins are female the relationship is vei-dauveni,

each other as dauve. when two separate kin-groups have gods (kalou) that are veitavaleni, those two groups are said to be vetabani and they may address each other as naita . in effect, this is similar to a veitauvu relationship, a close familiarity that allows hard joking, harder perhap s than that of two groups that are veitauvu. see tauvu.

v. to pass before, or go across, one’s field of vision. vuki tavali to go back and forth across one’s field of vision. au a raici koya ni tavali ena noqu matanivale. i saw him/her go past the front of my house.
n. unexpected sound, not always immediately identified, usually a rustling, cracking or crackling (twigs broken by a person walking, plastic being shuffled about, or being folded). au rogoca e dua na
etuba. i hear a strange noise outside. sa tavasa na veikau. there ’s a strange sound in the bush.
. n., v. to punish a child by slicing parallel, superficial cuts on the back or arm. the scars may remain for life. see tava slice.
. n, v. as a native medical remedy, to apply a series of usually small cuts to a painful part of
(ni uto) v ., n. rapid beating (of the heart), usually at some excitement.
n. bottle. qa ni tavaya chip or piece of broken glass, formerly used for cutting, and for shaving.

was introduced by europeans. tavaya bia bottle of beer. gourds (vago), lagenaria siceraria (formerly l. vulgaris), aboriginally introduced vine, now naturalised, the fruit ’s wooden pericarp formerly used as bottles for water or coconut oil, only at lower elevation areas of polynesian influence.
seemann noticed they were in widespread use in the s. glass and plastic replace them.
in the viti levu highlands, the only liquid containers were segments of bamboo. coastal people sometimes used shells of mature coconuts or clay pots.
adj . unsettled, confused, uncertain, anxious.
n. task, duty, function.
v. to participate, serve, be occupied with or assigned to some task , involved. era sa vakaitavi e
soli itukutuku they are involved in the release of the report. na nodra laki vakaitavi ena yadrava

veisaututaki their (many) going to serve in guarding for the pacification (as for the united nations.) tavi, tavia v . to hit, whack hard, usually a ball, as in tennis, cricket. tavia na volo hit the ball. itavi (or)
n. bat (as in cricket). itavi ni tenisi n. tennis racquet.
v. to slap or tap with the open hand.
v. use the hand to pat, pet, (a cat, a baby).
v. in forming clay pots, to whack to the outside with a paddle (itata) with a stone held inside the pot.
v. to sweep, sweep out (usually house). this is normally a vigorous work, using a traditional

called a sasa, made of the mid-rib of coconut leaflets. fijian women usually prefer this to european-style brooms. formerly, highlanders had no sasa; they used branches of the makita tree that retain their leaves.
v . to proceed very quietly, with hardly any noise. idiom: e tavidi na vusi proceed quietly, as a cat moves. e tavidi na vusi na nodra cakacaka. they went about their work quietly
(eng. tapioca) n . cassava, manioc, manihot esculenta. originally from tropical america,
by europeans, it is now the most frequently eaten starchy root-crop. a reddish-skinned
called new hebrides is commonly exported. for ceremonial food presentations, cassava is not
taro. eager for quick yields, fij ians sometimes talk
target_text: a prestigious root-crop like the traditional yam or

source_text: variety exists. seven months is minimum time to maturity. sokobale is a very slow maturing variety and need not be harvested promptly.
n. broom. sasa usual fijian broom of coconut-leaf midrib s. syn. (lau) tauf ale, itaf i, both types with wooden handles. syn. itataviraki. see taviraka, above.
v. entangled, as in e tavivi na me. the goat is entangled (in its tether). tavo, tavoca v. to beach a boat or to launch it into the water. by extension modernly it can mean to

some new proj ect. a public programme, a new product. tavo ki wai to launch a boat in the water. tavo ki vanua to beach a boat. itavotavo place at the shore for beaching a boat. tavo, tavoraka v. work too hard, sweat for it, to over-work or over-use something. tavo, tavoya, tavoitaka v. to wipe the face, especially when wet or damp. me tavoi na matamu wipe your face dry. tavoya na wai ni matamu wipe away your tears.
n. handkerchief (an introduced concept), or small cotton towel, mostly used for wiping the face.
tavoi cloth used to dry a person after bathing. presumably, in lowlands, barkcloth (masi) was used as towelling before cotton cloth was introduced.

n. fiji almond, edible nut, like an almond, from a common coastal tree, terminalia catappa, combretaceae. it has conspicuouly horizontal branches with lvs spirally arranged at tip s of branches, very large colourful red, leathery falling deciduously around the shore. fls small, white, on racemes to cm. the nut is difficult to crack. it is eaten mostly by children, or as a casual, occasional snack, not
sold in the markets. the nuts (along with coconuts and fish) once helped this author stay
when castaway on an atoll called cakau ni sici (lit. “trochus reef” but called bird island in english). geraghty speculates that the name tavola is borrowed from a solomon island language; the
talice (fij ian dalice). syn. (nadro, serua) tivi or j ivi. tivi is also

(eng.) n. tub. tavu ni sili bathtub. tavu, tavuna v. to grill, roast on embers. this was formerly the commonest way of cooking in the highlands of vit levu, where there were no clay pots (kuro), and the earth-oven (lovo) was unknown. see tavuteke to fry, a relatively modern term, formerly unknown in fiji. no cooking in oil or fat was
by fijians. idiom : tavu vudi. wishful thinking, as might be exclaimed by one boy to another who is looking wistfully at a desirable girl. the expression is heard mostly in that context.
v. rise to the surface after sinking. see vude. tavukadiridiri adj . spotted, speckled finely, freckled, mildew(ed).
v. overturn. the name of a few villages, memorialising the overthrow of an early chiefly lineage, a common occurence.
v. to throw forcefully, as a stone, or in boxing, a hard punch.
knocked down, dropped (a person dropped by a blow, a heavy parcel dropped hard, or a a boat
(as in a storm). by ext., veitavulaki ena rakavi knocked down (defeated) at rugby (of a team). tavutavulaki more forceful knock-down.
(eng.) n. tarpaulin. today these are commonly made of cheap blue plastic rather than canvas. several spellings.
v. to cover or wrap something with a piece of cloth or barkcloth. me tavuloni na wai ena dua na tiki ni isulu. cover the medicine with a piece of cloth.
n., v. to make decorative marks burned onto a person ’s body, shoulder, chest, or the back,
a palm leaf (sasa) pricked into the skin. these are often short parallel lines with no special meaning, done to a child for punishment, or an adult as decoration. syn. tuboko.
v. to relate (a story) gushingly. vuso froth , foam.

v. to fry , a method of cooking previously unkown to fijians. itavuteke n. frying pan. in towns, lard is widely used because it is cheap. popularity of frying is partly due to the speed of preparing fried foods, and the shortage of firewood, a severe problem in suburb s. tavutoka n. threespot reef crab that has three dark spots on its shell at back. syn. kavika.
spotted. this applies to a rash on the human skin, fungal spots on a plant leaf, spotted or speckled design on a shirt, blouse or dress, or an animal. see tono.
(or) tovuto n. whale. though this term has been mostly understood to mean the sperm whale, it
applies to both the major species. seen most often is the humpback whale (megaptera nadosa) that migrates from antarctic, past new zealand, to fiji and then tonga in june, july, august,
is harmless, quite friendly and unafraid of humans or boats. it is possible to make eye-toeye contact. the carniverous, dangerous, predatory sperm whale, pyseter catadon, is source of all
(tabua), used as ceremonial gift kamunaga of great value. fij ian obtained the teeth
by trade, or from the lower j aw of the occasional dead whales found on the shores. (the upper
is virtually toothless.) this fijian use of whale teeth is not much older than a couple of centuries,
any other such symbolic, ceremonial gift. previously , mainland fijians used wooden tabua, and
whale oil for lighting lamps. ambergris (“grey amber”) was not named or used by fijians,
it has been used since ancient times in malaysia and china for spicing wine. its use in the
perfume industry is as a fixative, to prolong the fragrance, and a couple of the essential
add their own perfume. the fine, sweet fragrance is obtained only after the very smelly, greasy, lump s of grey raw ambergris have been dissolved in cold ethyl alcohol. ambergris is rare, with
to pounds found in the head of just a very few sperm whales, but smaller amounts
be found floating at sea, or at the seaside strand. fij ans have been unaware of ambergris and never made use of it.
there was a tribe ra tavuto, as one of the five or perhaps eight social groups of the butoni(vanua) fishermen who live on the flatlands of bau islands before the incursion of super-tribe
around , an incursion that soon after, displaced the butoni, as well as the korolevu (levuka) sailors and fishermen who lived on the hill. the butoni then settled mainly in lomaiviti,
on koro island but also elsewhere. on bau island the butoni had constructed the council house called naulunivuaka, with a separate door for each of their tribes.

v. describes a sharp, strong motion that comes to a sudden end, as in a boat striking a reef, or bumping one’s head, usually inadvertantly, stub one’s toe, push something hard as far as it will go (as a post in the ground). vutu suggests banging, pounding, and “ta” suggests a sharp action. tavuwai, tavuwai-taka v. to cook quickly by throwing into water that is already boiling, as one might do with shellfish. this is not traditional. grilling was traditional.
as a prefix, without, indicating an absence of something. tawa mudu infinite (without end). bulatawamudu n. “live forever”, name of a plant, kalanchoe pinnata, crassulaceae; the succulent leaves

form rootlets around the edges, and remain alive a long time. tawayaga useless. tawa donu without right, unrightful(ly). tawa guilecavi unforgettable. na itovo tawa kilikili improper behaviour. vakatawa dodonu unrightfully. tawamalaca uncertain, uncertainty.
without, un- . vakatawa dodonu unrightfully. tawa, tawana v. to fill (container), populated (land), loaded (gun) vakatawana fill it, populate it. sa
na taqe. the tank is filled. sa tawa na vanua. the country is populated. tawana na koro

the village. na tawaqele the populace, inhabitants. tawa-vanua v., n. to populate, first immigrants, first settlers. for a place or territory, tawa, tawana may indicate that there is a presiding chief. tawa implies the process of being filled whereas sinai refers to the state of being completely full. idiom: sa tawa na matana. she is pregnant. idiom: tamata tawa n. person who has a devil, and serves that devil, a person “possessed”, who must pour a yaqona to his devil and gains favours for that.
adj . canned, as in kakana tawaitini canned food.

(ni benisini) n. filling station, petrol station, bowser. syn. bausa (eng.) a much more commonly used word. vakatawa, vakatawana . v. to fill (container). tawaip akete-taka to package (in packages, usually commercially). vakatawa, vakatawana . v. to populate. vakatawana na vanua vou. populate the new land. idiom:
get married (move into a house of the husband). vakatawa, vakatawana . v. to keep watch. na ivakatawa guard, person on watch, wesley catechist.
acting president.

(archaic) n. pennant, small flag. syn. drotini. kuila flag. vatanitawake was a famous shed on bau island, conceptually and originally having shelves (vata) for the drying of the nautical pennants of the high chief, especially the roko tui bau.
n. (lau, from tongan “ta’ovala”) traditional tongan binding of sinnet that serves as a belt
(gaf igaf i) woven of pandanus voivoi (called kie in lau). it is worn at church, and at any ceremonial occasions.
adj . undependable, untrustworthy. tawase, tawasea v ., n. split, torn apart, divided, separate. e tawasei ira na kaicolo. they are divided
themselves, the highlanders. na yalayala ka tawasei rau na yasana o tailevu kei ra the
separates the two provinces of tailevu and ra. see wase, wasea to divide, often to share out. na tawase ni yabaki vou the new years day.
(anglicism) n. new years eve and may imply new years day as well. siga ni vakatawase new years day.
v., n. first immigrants or settlers to populate a place. tawa to fill.
useless. tawa without. yaga useful, usefulness.
limitless, infinite. boundless.
v. to march, as in a parade. yabe to walk about unencumbered. tayana v. dis-arranged, scattered about carelessly.

n. foamy scum found on the surface of coastal waters some days before the rising of the balolo seaworm (an annelid, palolo viridis), which will be gathered as food. when the scum is sighted, locals stay alert to the arrival of the worm. the rising usually occurs twice a year, october (balolo lailai) and
(balolo levu), according to the phase of the moon, but only at certain places and not always regularly, and not at viti levu island. see balolo.
v. to plant (to grow). sa tei oti. it has already been planted. teivaki planted, as in sa teivaki na qele
the piece of old planting stock that remains; it can be used, making a much weaker beverage. traditionally, in farming, fij ians planted only from corms, sprouted seedlings, and suckers. they
seeds except for a few fruit trees. their only gardening tools were a club to knock down bush for clearing by burning, and also a digging stick (doko) that is still commonly used.
food garden . fijians planted some ornamentals but never had ornamental gardens.
n. alluvial flatland, such as at nakelo, tokatoka, noco, rewa. the place-name tebara is recent, a far-out suburb of suva city.

n. edge (thick), as in tebe ni gusu lip(s), tebe ni maga-na labia pudenda of a woman. tebe, tebeka v. to chip, break off, of something brittle, such as pottery, plate or cup. itebetebe n. chip(s) off something brittle, sherds. katebe chipped.
(eng.) n. tender (as in the commercial term, a formal offer to buy, or to carry out construction).
to make a tender offer.
n . dew. syn. bite.
. verbal modifier adding the meaning of “first of all”, "just", "just now", or "for just now". offered

say sa tei rauta mada, that's enough for now thanks, or au tei kua mada i won't (take more) just now, thanks. ni sa tei moce toka mada good-bye for now. more elaborately, ni sa tei toka saka tale mada. tou tei kana mada, qai lako. let’s (several) eat first, then go. idiom: sega ni ura me sa tei damu. where there is smoke there is fire. there must be a cause for that to happen, and the cause is yet to be known. lit. no prawn just turns red (unless someone has cooked it) – there is a reason for it turning red.

. planted. see tea, to plant. dau tei dovu n . sugar-cane farmer. itei . n. segment of a plant that is planted to propagate it, such as a section of yam tuber, or a section of yaqona stem that would include a node.

n. food garden. dau teitei farmer, planter. around villages, food gardens are usually far away from the houses. teivaka . v. to plant (the land). teivaka na noqu qele. to plant my land. teivaka . v. (modernism) to set, establish (as a new record, in sports). e teivaki e dua na isausau vou. a new record was established.
n. a sp. of freshwater crab, common on viti levu, usually no more than inches across, a light
colour. the left claw is large and orange-coloured. it may be caught in hand prawning nets. grilled on an open fire, it is sucked on and chewed, and the shell-parts are spat out.

n., v. a specific, brief challenge enacted out and chanted by the fiji national football team before a major match. though now “traditional”, the custom dates only from the lates. the custom was inspired by an abbreviated version of “haka” war-dance performed by n.z. all black rugby team. the
version was composed by a vusaradave chief at the request of the vunivalu of bau, ratu george cakobau. teivovoi is probably an abbrev. of tei voavoa, with voavoa referring to a field that is

after use as a garden. (in early days, fij ian gardeners rotated the land, not the crops. some still do that.) tei refers to something being planted or struck into the ground. here the implication is a war-fence. teke, tekea v. to kick backwards, as a horse does. by ext. refers to the “kick” of a handgun or rifle when fired. idiom: tekea na vokete (anglicism) to kick the bucket, to die. interesting that fijians have this as a backward kick, rather than a forward kick, as assumed by most europeans.
(eng.) n. taxi. syn. tekisi. itekiteki n. flower or other decoration stuck in hair, usually behind the ear, by women or men. a sprig of
uci is commonly used. this is often a matter of whim rather than any special occasion. one

that a flower behind both ears means you are married, a flower behing the right ear you have a romantic partner, and behind the left ear, you are looking. this was invented as tourist talk, and is not traditional. the usually red, ornamental hibiscus (senitoa) is introduced, not a traditional tekiteki. it is contrary to custom that a itekiteki be worn casually in a chiefly village area. teki, tekia, tekilaka v. to stick a pole, post or stake, cricket wickets, into the ground. tekiteki-vaka to thrust hard, stick forcefully (something such as a stick), usually into the ground. teki, tekina v. to stick a itekiteki, flower or scented plant, at the side of the head.
v. to bow the head in a fixed position. cuva implies leaning forward.
v. to kneel. duru-na knee.
(eng.) n. taxi. syn. tekesi.

n. beginning. na itekitekivu the very beginning. tekivu, tekivuna v. to begin, to begin it. idiom: tekivu e jerusalemi (biblical) lit., begin at jerusalem, i.e., begin by making changes at home, oneself before trying to change others. by a curious twist this can imply doing favours for
own people before anyone else, implying that nepotism is justified. helping one’s relatives is a firm custom in fiji.
v. to start it.
n. genesis. vakatekivu mai . . . beginning with, as in vakatekivu mai na gauna beginning with (or from) the time . . .
(eng.) n. television. syn. retio ni yaloyalo. these days one is more likely to hear an exact copy of the english abbreviation tv.

v. to tempt, entice. kua ni temaki au. don't tempt me. na veitemaki nei seru vei vani the tempting of vani by seru . that is a rather formal, archaic kind of expression. itema n. enticement, lure, that which tempts someone. veitemaki n. temptation, enticement. see above.
n. calf of the leg. may sometimes refer to the forearm temo ni liga-na.
(eng.) n. tenor. tene, tenea v . to seat or set down on the lap, usually of a child. na itenetene the lap.
(eng.) v. to stand at attention (military).
(eng.) n. tennis.
(eng.) n. tape (as in recording tape). na tep i ni lagasere the tape(s) of recorded song. katokatoni n.
(as of music). teqa . adj . deformed, of a person ’s limb. yava teqa n. bow-legged. (syn. yava veqa). teqa . n. vanity . teqa-taka v. to be vain (about something).
n . adj . posture or stance of a person showing off with proud bearing, often with new clothing.
(eng. terror) n., adj . fearsome (person), formidable, domineering, brash, overly forceful and “pushy”.
v. to try to appear tough.
v. to show off. tere, terega v. to touch lightly in passing, to graze by. such a movement may be used by fijians as a
people. terema v. to clear the throat, with a sort of cough. this may be a way of catching someone ’s attention.
(eng.) v. to train, physically by exercise, a custom adopted at advent of jogging, much spoken of in modern times.
n. comb on the head of a chicken.
n. purple swamp hen , porphyrio porphyrio, on main islands virtually extinct due to mongoose and
cats, but still reasonably common on some other fiji islands and very common in new zealand. the species also exists in europe, africa, asia, central america and florida according to paddy ryan.
live in social groups and may include two or three males, each mating with each female. the
in incubation and feeding of the young. partly nocturnal and not at all restricted to wet or
places. watling says it may be a nuisance in some fruit and vegetable gardens, damaging bananas, plantain, taro. i have not observed that. syn. (lau, kadavu, nadro.) kitu. (vanua levu) qala.
(rewa, verata) no, not. au teri kila. i do not know. syn. tara. idiom: sa teri! no way ! nothing doing !

adj . slack or loose, as of a rope, not taut. vakateruya v. to slack off, of a rope, cord, belt, or the sail of a boat, or by ext. to speak slowly and meaningfully. tete, tetea (or) teteva v. spread out, disseminate (seeds, rumours, disease). vakatetea na vosa to spread
v. to spread, disseminate, as with propaganda, or gossip.
v. adj . babbling, self-centred in speech. syn. (colo east) tatawai. cf. tatawai to talk in one’s sleep.

(eng., lau “table”) n. pulpit (often used figuratively). teve, teveka v. to circumcise (males). veiteve circumcision. this takes place usually from age six to nine. the process is usually called tiko e bure and requires a few days of isolation. the coming-out
(four nights). teve vakabeka circumcision that involves only a slicing on top
target_text: feast is known as bogi va

source_text: (eng.) n. table. ena teveli on the table.
(tongan tevolo) satan, the devil, best perhaps capitalised as tevoro; also dangerous indigenous spirit(s) which fijians have commonly believed to be nearby, especially at night, formerly just known
kalou spirits. spirits that came to be called the tevoro in christian times often possess people and

may be exorcised by the victim being made to believe he or she is "eating" them. some people are believed to have a tevoro do evil for them, by serving the tevoro, and pouring yaqona to honour it. if they cease to so honour the tevoro, they themselves may fall victim to it. this usually means seizure,
and even death. there is analogy with the european legend of faust. belief in both satan and in traditional fijian spirits is quite current. tevoro may refer to the j oker in a deck of cards.
adj . bewitched, possessed by a devil. tevu, tevuka v. to lay out, spread out (usually mats, sheets, blankets), also open out (as a book).
n. part of a marriage ceremony, formerly only for people of high rank, the presentation and symbolic laying out of mats where the marriage is to be consumated.
n. mats or other gifts given to a newly married couple by the wife’s side of the family. this custom is falling into disuse around urban areas. the word implies the laying out of mats.
(eng.) n. tea. as a substitute, fijians are often quite content to use mature leaves of lemon tree or other citrus leaves.

(or) jaina (eng. “china”) n. banana, introduced cultivars. ikau tiaina hand or small bunch of bananas. ikaukau tiaina whole stalk of bananas. cf. vudi plantain . liga ni marama lady fingers (tiny) bananas. the plaintain vudi is an aboriginal introduction, as is the soaqa, the upright banana
fehi. the introduced “china” banana was brought to fiji by rev. george pritchard in ,
cultivar was hardly six feet tall, and thus resistant to wind damage according to seemann.
varieties, introduced later, have been known as cavendish and sitivenu (“stephen”). bananas
been grown mostly in the eastern viti levu highlands and floated in bamboo rafts down the
river. the commercial export industry was formidable in its day but came to an abrupt end
quality control was abandoned by fijian growers after fiji ’s independence from colonial

(e. polyn. “tiare”) n. gardenia, the national flower of tahiti. fiji has some ten species of the genus gardenia, nine of them probably native. gardinia taitensis was most likely a polynesian introduction, not common in fij i. tiare is the general maori word for flower. tibi, tibika v. to flash, as of lightning. sa tibi na liva. the lightning flashed. tibika v. to strike something
(of lightning). idiom: tibi na liva quick as lightning tibi, tibika v . to roll (something). tibika na sika. roll the cigar.
n. “roll”, cigarette. more completely, itibi tavako. tibio! exclamation of child who opts out of a game such as “hide and seek” (veivuni) or a game of “tag” (veitara).
n. fruit of the mangrove tree, an emergency food.
n. small fish, mud flipper or skipper, to inches, of no economic use, dark coloured, lives in swampy places.
v. to slip (of person or animal), in a slippery place, walking or running. titidara very slippery , as of a muddy path. syn. (colo east) sikidara.
n. kin relation, as in:- a cava takamu o seru? what relationship is seru to you?
n. a common variety of edible wild yam, dioscorea nummularia, sold in the market. this was a

food of highlanders. syn. (colo east) dasi. around the nasavusavu area tikau may refer to any of the several types of wild yam. tikidua n. leaflet, pamphlet, page. tiki, tikica v. to separate apart, to cut off or break off a piece, often said of some food such as bread, or cooked root crop. tu vakatikitiki v. to stand next to something, to stand aside.
. n. part, piece. e dua na tiki ni keke a piece of cake. tiki-ni-siga n. date of the month. tiki ni
part of the body. tiki-na . next to, beside. dabe e tiki-mu sit next to you. ena tiki-na kadus on the other side. syn. tikiva v. to be next to. tikiva na vale next to the house.
. n. subj ect matter. na noqu vakasama ena tikina oqo my thoughts on this matter (about this topic).
. n. administrative district of fiji. na tikina o noco the district of noco. to some extent

are designed to encompass traditional territories (vanua) but that goal is far from being achieved. the numbers of districts and their boundaries have varied greatly through fiji’s modern history . at various times the administrative title buli has been used for district administrators. in the districts, called “old districts” (tikina makawa) were combined into larger groups called
districts (tikina cokovatai). in the old system was restored. the old districts of
of viti levu, colo east, colo west, colo north, were abolished and merged with other districts to suppress the feisty, independent spirit of the highlanders, the kaicolo.
partly. tikitiki kai viti part-fij ian. tikitiki jaina part-chinese.
apart, to one side. biuta vakatikitiki e yasaqu. put to one side, at my side. tu vakatikitiki stand aside.
(or) tikiti (eng.) n. ticket.
