next to, alongside, to one side, adj acent to. na valelailai ka tikiva na makete. the toilet next to the market. e dua na yanuyanu lailai ka koto tikivi ovalau. a small island that lies next to ovalau.

to be next to each other. eratou toka veitikivi. they (several) stay next to each other. tikivili n. nectar-eating parrot, red-throated lorikeet, charmosyma amabilis, favours red-flowering vuga trees.

. v. to be (but only used where necessary, much less often than in english , and only used in specific contexts). tiko lo! be quiet, shut up ! (to a child). e tiko eso na suka ? is there any sugar? io, e tiko. yes, there is some. tiko, tikora . v. to reside, to stay, to be (at some place). e tiko mai suva. he/she is in suva, stays in suva. itikotiko n. residence. syn. (west) no.
. particle that follows a verb to indicate continuity of action. sa moce tiko. he/she is sleeping. lako tiko! lako tiko! keep going !

. n . existence, or being, as in tiko yavavala disturbed existence, social unrest. na tiko vinaka. the well-being. tiko, tikora . v. to set down, oneself, a person, an object such as a pot. vakatiko, vakatikora v. to place (it). but note: tikovata to stay by someone, to remain with a person.
together.
(or) tiko ga still, in the sense of a continuity of a condition or an action. e cakacaka tikoga. he/she is still working.
n. aide-de camp of governor (prior to the military coup), or to the president of the
(since the military takeover).
. . . idiom: once upon a time (there lived, there was) . . . -- as said in beginning to tell a story.
n. residence, place where one stays, address. (a relatively modern word.)
v. to stay by someone, remain with a person. the usual implication is that of a couple living together as partners in a quasi-married state. vata together.

v., n . well-being, a modernism. tila, tila, tilaka v. to strike with a wooden club, the top of a stake, or the human head. tilo, tiloma v. to swallow (food, beverage). (anglicism) to “swallow” a tall story.
v. to gobble (food), to guzzle (beverage), swallow in haste.
n. after-taste, as when tasting yaqona, one’s first impression may be modified by a somewhat later taste-effect in the mouth.
v. to swallow whole, without chewing.
n. adam ’s apple, fore part of the throat, throat.
(or) tulou excuse me (said when passing close beside, behind or above someone). syn. tulou. the
is never modified (one cannot tilou “very much”). in fiji it is bad manners to have one ’s head
a chief, or to walk or stand close behind a person of rank. vakatilou to make the gesture of
“tilou ”. syn. (tonga) tulou.
n. mother or mother’s sister, maternal aunt. also father’s brother’s wife.
n. mature female animal.
(eng.) ten. vakatini ten times. tini ka dua eleven ("ten plus one"), tini ka rua twelve, etc. tini na
ten pots. tini na udolu ten thousand. the thing counted is named with its definite article na.
a few more than ten. na ikatini one-tenth, tithe (as in some christian sects). legendary
(tribe) tinitini involved ten children (numbered and named dua, rua, tolu etc.) of the ancestral spirit of village nasilai in tailevu province, with a mother from kaba.
the various tribes that migrated here from vanuatu and the solomons with their different languages.

(eng.) n. tin (of food, such as canned beef). vakatinitaka to can (food). kakana tawaitini canned food. syn. kava. tini, tinia v. to end, to end up, conclude, terminate, finish. used only in specific contexts, perhaps not
as often as vakaotia or cava. e tinia ena nona kaya . . . he/she concluded by saying . . . tini
end abruptly. tini dole to end prematurely, before its proper time. tini botoilevu to end abruptly (harsh implication).
. n. the end, the last (usually as an abrupt transition). a last child may be named itini, and that name
are not a last child. itini yara “train” of barkcloth that trails behind a man in traditional formal chiefly costume.
target_text: may be passed on to others though they themselves

source_text: n. ending, as of a story or action completed. itini . (eng.) n. commercial agent.
v. a transitive form of the verb tini, tinia, meaning to finish off, or put a stop to something. may include “tuck in” a sulu wrapped around one’s waist.
(archaic) v., n. of a chief, to wear a barkcloth form of dress with a long trail behind. yara to drag.
n . sporting j avelin formerly used seasonally in competitive games (veitiqa). the handle (dia) was
(gasau), the blunt head (ulutoa) usually of a very hard wood. the j avelin skimmed and
to its final stopping place which was then marked by a reed stuck in the ground. the
was distance, not accuracy of aim. there still remain remnants of old playing grounds
with stones. itiqatiqa playing ground for veitiqa. tiqa, tiqava to throw the itiqa. most commonly, competitions were between different villages. in may the sport was exhibited at
on the occasion of the birthday of ratu sir kamisese mara. traditionally, women were attracted to the champion. tiri, tirima v. to drip, as with a leaky roof or faulty faucet. syn. turu.
(or) tiriwai n. red mangrove, with red sap and creamy wood, rhizophora mangle (= r. samoensis),
half-submerged salt water marshes, vitally important breeding places for many species of fish, and home for crabs. many drooping prop roots, long thin fruit, and flower calyx with four lobes.

tabua n. tall mangrove tree growing on the sea side of tiriwai, and is distinguished by white flowers and leaf tips that do not curve down, rhizophora stylosa. tiri vanua n. an endemic sp., small tree of the bush, crossostylis seemannii, rhizophoraceae, deriving its

from similarity to mangrove tiri in its aerial roots as buttresses (though only at the base of the trunk) and bark. the timber is soft, hardly useful even as firewood. fls white, tiny, cm diam., finely hairy. lvs opposite, brown hair on underside. the wood is orange. bark and root used by women as an

for conception. this “land mangrove” tiri vanua, usually grows in a damp place but may be well inland from the sea. all mangroves make long lasting, hot fires as excellent firewood. tiro, tirova v. to look into a mirror (iloilo) or water, more traditionally, at a reflection, usually checking one’s own appearance. na titiro n. the looking at a reflected image on the water or in a mirror. this is
iloilo for fij i’s president; his mother in taveuni used to see her reflection in a
(by his own account).
(eng.) n. disciple. syn. tisaip eli.
(eng.) n. december. ena i kalima ni tiseba on the fifth of december.
tip-toe. vava titeqe high-heel shoes.
as in dakaititi, bow (to be used with arrows), branch or bark of mangrove. originally, the word for

as simply dakai. with the introduction of guns being called dakai, the word for bow became dakaititi to make the distinction. the arrow is sici. bow and arrow were used only in war (by men or women), never as a chiefly sport, as in tonga, and never in fishing.
v. to ooze, squish out slowly, to seep out, as pus from a sore, resin from tree-bark, saliva from the mouth.
v. to doubt something or someone. e a vakatitiqataka o seru na isau ni taro nei mela . seru doubted mel’s answer.
adj . mouth-watering, flavorful. weli saliva.
adj . deep (as of water, a pool or the sea, or a hole).

n. walking stick. fig. used for a last drink, customarily yaqona, before departure, “one for the road”. fij ian walking stick s were never carved decoratively or elaborately, as they were in vanuatu. vakaititoko v. to use a walking stick. syn. itoko.
n. bare branches (as of vau, or masi) after bark is stripped off for fibre or barkcloth (masi).
v. to go off or turn aside suddenly, with alacrity, as an animal frightened, or a car swerving sharply on the road, a person ducking into the bush to avoid someone.

(slang) v. to change the subj ect of conversation. tivi n. timber tree, terminalia litoralis, combretaceae, similar to t . catappa, but nuts not edible. caution: tivi or variations of that name refers to t. catappa in parts of vanua levu, rakiraki and the west.
n. edible reef-fish, yellowish colour.
sideways.
n. wild or semi-cultivated variety of yam, dioscorea nummularia, a common source of food
(february to march). an aboriginal introduction, as were
target_text: available long after the regular yam harvest

source_text: all the yam species. smooth round stem, spiny near the base, not angled like the cultivated uvi, but like the uvi, the stem twines to the right, clockwise. good-size tubers grow deep and take two
in the ground to ensure continuance of supply, but these days that custom is often ignored.
(dalo) and yam (uvi), tivoli plays no part in ceremonial food presentations. it is sometimes
in the market. tivoli ni toga a very large-rooted tivoli. tikau and rauva are quite distinct,
varieties of this species. they also are sometimes sold at the public market. these wild

of yam, and to a less extent cultivated taro, were the staple root-crops of viti levu highlanders. cultivated yam (uvi) was important as food and prestigious presentations only at the coast and on small islands where also, it marked the passage of the year with its annual harvest (yabaki).

(eng.) n. teapot. syn. tip ote. it is common custom to serve tea with sugar and milk already added with a considerable amount of both. to, tovaka v. to contain liquid, as a water-well, a bucket or other container, a woman ’s breasts with milk).
to na sucuna her breasts are full of milk. toevu n. well (for water). sa to nawanawa na matana. he/she has watery eyes (emotion, age, sickness). e tovaki wai na matana. his/her eyes are full of
(but not falling much).
n. associate, peer, partisan, party (political). na ito ni veisaqa the opposition party. au tovaki koya

. n. chicken, orig. the aboriginally introduced jungle fowl, gallus gallus. a few still exist in remote areas. most have now interbred with chickens introduced by europeans. in olden days the eggs of the

fowl, very difficult to find and were not commonly eaten by fijians. some thought them disgusting, like mucus they would say, though some ate snake eggs and some polynesians ate turtle eggs. male jungle fowl have flamboyant colours. they were sometimes caught by tying up a female

an attractant. genetic evidence with mitochondrial dna seems now clearly to indicate the protopolynesians brought jungle fowl to chile in long-range voyages. (science news, vol. , june , p. .) they also brought back the sweet potato kumala and retained the name from the americas. idiom: kana yava ni toa lit. eat chicken feet said to a child who is hyper-active, unable to sit still. idiom: solisoli vakatoa lit. giving like a rooster, that is, giving a gift and then taking it back, as a

gives grain to a hen and then pecks it back, what in the u.s.a. would be called “indiangiving”. idiom: toa makawa. impolitely refers to a woman, no longer young, who affects continued youth and thus makes a fool of herself. lit. “old hen”. idiom: moce vata na toa to be extremely tired and go to sleep early, lit. to go to sleep at the same time as the chickens. toa . n. champion, warrior. toa ni vala champion (as in sports). toa ni valu champion warrior.
. as in ulutoa head of j avelin used in the sport of veitiqa. it was usually made of very hard wood and attached to a shaft made of a reed stem.

n. bay (inlet of the sea), harbour. na toba o laucala laucala bay. idiom: sa dui cagi ni toba lit. each bay has its own different wind, i.e, your authority is effective in your territory, but is irrelevant here in this territory . each can be a chief in his own land. tobe, tobea v. to plait (human hair, basket). cf. tali, talia to weave (mat).

. n. traditional “curls” of hair hanging down on one or both sides of the head as a sign of a virgin girl. tobe . n. by extension, pigtail or ponytail as worn by man or woman. tobo, toboka v. to catch, seize, capture (person, animal). na lairo, tobotobo rawarawa ena bogi buto the land-crab lairo, easily caught in the dark of night. as an anglicism, one speaks of catching the bus. idiom: tobo koki try to “pick up” girls, lit. catch parrots. vakatobo-i-cu, vakatoboicu-taka v. to turn up side down, bottom up, so to speak . tobu n. pool, pond, bay. torobu very small pond or tidal lake. tobu ni qalo swimming pool, tobu ni sisili bathing pool, swimming pool. titobu deep. toci, tocia v. to smooth off with sharp blade, as tocia na voivoi to cut off spines from the edges of

leaves preparatory to weaving, usually using a sharp shell such as drivi or kuku, referred to as itoci. the best voivoi for mats has such spines, while what is called rotuman voivoi has none, but is only used for inferior mats, or baskets. by ext., toci refers in carpentry to plane some wood.

n . plane (carpenter ’s tool), also the sharp shell used in stripping voivoi leaves of spines, preparing the leaves for weaving mats. todi, todia, todilaka v. to squeeze, usually between the thumb and forefinger, as in squeezing a boil that is mature.

adj ., v. extremely hot (weather), to scorch (of the hot sun). todrou, todrova v. to lap up (liquid) without use of cup, bowl, as a man or dog might drink from a stream. this was the fijian manner of drinking from a stream, without the use of one’s hands. in rural
this is still the custom. in the viti levu highlands, no cup of any form was ever used though
sometimes served as a temporary substitute to carry water a short distance. the yaqona cup (coconut shell) was introduced from the coastal areas.
n. well (for water). sa to na toevu. the well contains water.
(archaic). n. early large twin-hulled proto-polynesian sailing canoe with a huge deck, used for
voyages between fiji, tonga and samoa. the outrigger side lay to starboard. it could not
direction of the sail and had very poor ability to sail to windward. this brought tongans to
southeast tradewind, but made fiji to tonga travel very difficult. it was displaced during
s by tongan development of the drua or kalia ocean-going outrigger canoes which could

to windward by interchanging of bow and stern. while the boat-building skill was tongan and most particularly samoan, the timber was more available in fij i, where the boats were made. the sailplan was probably inspired from micronesian concepts according to fergus clunie.
v. to force. tongans were considered a forceful people and the word tonga was often transformed to togo as in togoraka, and in the place-name korotogo.
n . clitoris. syn. toitoi, cui, words not usually spoken.
. now, just for now, or at that particular time (indicating a change, or temporary situation, espec. in
with a preceding sa). keitou sa lako toka. we (few, exc.) are going now. sa vinaka toka. it's good now (the way it is now). sa moce toka mada. good-bye for now.
. v. n. to be (location, condition), location (at the time), in the sense of “staying” for a while. sa dede na noqu toka e suva . i have been staying in suva a long time.
. v . to sit down, as on a mat, or the grass. toka, vakatoka v. to proclaim, announce. vakatoka, vakatoka or vakatoka yaca v. to name, give a name (to a person). this is a ceremonial matter

names as surnames did not exist until recently adopted, following the european custom. formerly, a person might be accorded a new name at a different stage of life, and even after death . in villages, the major house-sites (yavu) all have formal names. properly, in referring to a family, one uses the name of their house-site, not their own name. place-names have been ubiquitous in every part of fij i, though many are lost to memory .

refers to leftover cooked food to be eaten the next day. vakatoka ua v., n. the action of surfing on a wave, a polynesian recreation, especially anciently at vuna, taveuni. no ancient surfboard has been preserved. the custom is now a modern sport, mostly european. some tourists come to fiji for that purpose.
idiom: to practice songs or meke.
n. prop, something used to prop up another obj ect.
(ni gone) n. placenta.
n. extended family within a clan (mataqali), type of kin-group in some parts of fiji and now applied throughout fij i by the native lands commission. the word implies a place where the family

staying. where the concept exists, this is usually the “true” occupant of the land, the people entitled to use the land. there was never any concept of land ownership in the european sense. land was held
unit in official records, as if the clan were the owner. in lau a rough equivalent of
the bati-ni-lovo. in nadroga/navosa there are bito or beto and in ba, kete or nalewe. on
sometimes hears kausivi, according to roth. members are always related by marriage
in, coming from elsewhere. the itokatoka is literally a family, and is considered as such. all
are intimately related by birth and marriage. there can be fifty members or more of the family. the distinction of nuclear family was formerly less emphasized than the itokatoka.
n. mountain ridge. as a formal name tokaitua refers to an extension of the nakauvadra range.
from ra down into tailevu followed this ridge part of the way . on vanua levu island a significant ridge extends out to udu, separating out macuata province from cakaudrove. syn. tuatua.
n. northeast wind. original fijian names of directions were based on typical wind directions. there was no notion of north , east, south, west and, of course, no compass. syn. vualiku. (tonga)
north.
cevaceva n. southeast (or) southeasterly wind, the prevailing trade wind. this is a modernism,
to european names of directions. above the equator, above the doldrums, the tradewind is from the northeast.

n. middle east (lebanon, sinai, kuwait, etc.). tokalau here implies an easterly direction but fijians had no notion of an exact east. tokalulu, tokalulu-taka v. to peer, as from a position of concealment. lulu owl. toka, toka-vaka v. to proclaim, announce.
n. declaration of war. syn. tagi ivalu.
n. companion, chum, colleague. implied is one who is protective, supportive. na nona itokani dredre. his/her close friend.
v. to put on (kettle on stove, pot on fire, clothes such as a coat). tokara na vinivo put on the dress. also vakatokara. see daramaka.
v., n. to move or go (from one place of residence to another), (resepctful) to arrive.
n. roof-thatch. toka-ulu, tokaulu-taka v. to attach or fix thatching on a roof. syn. bevu, bevuya.
n. whirlwind, which is always extremely dangerous. houses are swept away, boats lifted out of

n. beak (bird, certain fish), hooked protuberance (warclub). toki, tokia, tokilaka v. to peck. this may be very forceful, as by a hawk. toko, tokona v. to prop up, support (a point of view, another person ’s cause), be protective toward. idiom: gone ni toko favourite child; “apple” of the parent’s eye.
n. prop or pole to hold something up or out (such as a sail). ititoko walking stick.

n. bayonet (because it protrudes and protects). toko, tokoca v. to steep or sop something in a liquid, usually a starch-food in tea, or fijian pudding (vakalolo) in coconut cream. cf. toni, tonia to dip, steep , soak. bolomo, bolomona to steep.
adj . hollow. vaka-tola-taka to hollow it out.

n. vehicle, now almost any vehicle, but formerly , and to some extent still today, implies a new vehicle, one to be admired. possibly this notion originates from weapons or articles of value hung about the house, to be admired.
n. stem (plant, tree), trunk (tree, human). tolonikau tree trunk. see gau.
three. vakatolu three times. tolusagavulu thirty. tolutolu all three. tolu na drau three hundred.
third. e rua na ikatolu two-thirds. syn. (tonga) tolu.
(or) toluwa (or) qolua n. (rare) bamboo water container, three to five feet long with leaf-plug, or

of leaves tied at top when used to add water to yaqona bowl. used formerly to carry water, mainly in the highlands where pottery was unavailable. girls normally fetched water. toma, tomana . v. to accompany (person). keirau a vetomani tu kei seru ki na koro. i accompanied seru to the village. toma, tomana . v. to continue (story, report, letter, one ’s studies). lai tomana na noqu vuli go and continue my studies.
n. the continuing part, sequel.
n. name of highest mountain in fij i, m, near nadarivatu in central viti levu, named mt.
by adolph brewster. residing nearby at nadarivatu for many years, he was one of the first
to climb to the top. many people incorrectly believe the name is tomanivi and think
the oddity that from different faces of the mountain flow sources to the major rivers

(sigatoka river), the wailevu (rewa river) and the ba river. located in naitasiri province, it is near the borders of three other provinces: nadroga/navosa, ba, and ra. nearby are villages nasoqo and navai. the mountain is home to two tree species, vugayali and vugayalo, not yet
as to scientific name, though both are on exhibit at wainadoi gardens. vugayalo is totemic
wars of degei, the snake-god, and also in the origin of the vugalei people of tailevu province. they are distinct from the well known vuga, usually said to be metrosideros collina, though
applies to two species of geissois because the name suggests a tree with bright red blossoms.
(biblical) n. doubting thomas, as in the idiom: au tomasi kina. i doubt that is true, i wait to see concrete evidence. see vakatitiqa to doubt.
(eng.) n. tomato, an introduced plant. tomi, tomika v. to pick up, gather up (many small, scattered things, fruits or flowers fallen from a tree,
around a compound). itukutuku tomiki rumour. na tomitomi the task of picking
such things. na cava o cakava ? what are you doing? tomitomi. picking up things (from the ground).
n. selection of scattered items, as with diverse essays or stories in a book, or things gathered up from a scattered condition.
adj . dirty, usually said of a child, whose face or nose need wiping or washing.
n. plant, leaves sweet smelling, ocimum basilicum, lamiaceae, florets white or purple, used in perfuming coconut oil. syn. domole, tamole and other variations.
. n. sexually transmitted disease (std), gonorrhoea. there has been no separate fijian word for syphilis. the english word is used. syn. mate-ca .
. (lau) n. yaws, formerly a very common ulcerous disease among children throughout the south pacific, caused by a spirochete very closely related to the spirochete that causes syphilis. syn. coko.

(eng.) n. metric tonne. toni, tonia v. to dunk, steep. fij ians often dunk or sop their starch-foods in a liquid, especially biscuits in tea. biscuits may thus be eaten without butter or j am, and are softened and easier on the teeth. toni somo soak in mud in process of dyeing black some pandanus leaves for mat-weaving or sinnet cord for decorative binding. toni moce to soak overnight. see bolomo. tono, tonoka, tonolaka v. to poke, as with the pointed fingers, or a sharp instrument. itono poker, stick or any long, pointed thing used to poke. idiom: vosa tonotono mata talk accusingly, poke one’s nose in the affairs of others, or one's finger in another's face, direct talking, lecturing other people on their behaviour.
(eng.) n. torpedo. top ito niukilia nuclear torpedo.
n. a type of fij ian pudding, boiled or fried, mostly just wheat flour, leavening and water, sometimes
(lolo). common breakfast food. toqa, toqa v. to cut with an incision as on wood, stone or metal, to pierce, to make a sharp marking,
as on a questionnaire form or to underline something written , as emphasis. na vosa ka toqai na rukuna. the words that are underlined. see tosi, tosia.

. n . (anglicism) check-off, “tick”, as on a questionnaire filled out, something checked. itoqa . n. (anglicism) a typographical accent associated with a vowel, as with itoqa leka hyphen. itoqadela macron. itoqa-ruku underline. itoqa cabe acute accent, and itoqe siro accent grave.
v. to carry something over the shoulder, hanging from a stick, as with a bunch of bananas.

something carried in this manner. toqi, toqina v. to coil up (rope, weaving material). toqitoqini coiled, plaited (of hair, usually considered a feature of indian women). itoqi . n. coil or roll. itoqi ni dali coil of rope. itoqi ni f ilimu roll of film.
. n. coil of woven pandanus leaf used as a prop or "seat" for fijian clay pots which all have had only rounded bottoms.

n. specific, rather minor title, of dreketi (tora dreketi), and also lomaiviti (tora i bau at batiki). the title originates from verata. it implies a standard-bearer. the title has been used for the head of the mataqali sauturaga, the clan that empowers the chief. also used as a man ’s personal name.
v. to prick up the ears, as of a dog alerted.

n. pig pen. some fijians keep a pig pen near their house where it is convenient to feed them and supply water, though it may not be very sanitary. toro, toroya . v. to move, shift. toro sobu to decline, decrease, often in a critical sense, as in sa

na nodra ivakarau. their (many) behaviour has taken a turn for the worse. torocake built up, increased, improved as with company profits or improved behaviour. idiom: ivakarau toro sobu despicable behaviour. toro, toroya . v. to shave, person ’s beard or soft body hair. yame ni toro razor blade. torotoro shaving. to shave the head is tasi, tasia na uluna.
. n. razor. in the highlands, early fij ians used the sharp edge of a bamboo sliver. in coastal areas
a broken shell. broken glass then became popular. almost all now use razor blades. village
have sometimes resharpened blades by rubbing inside a cup or glass. itoro livaliva n. electric shaver.
. n. rasp (carpenter’s tool) to smooth out wood. formerly, fiji boatbuilders used the tail of a stingray. itoci is a carpenter’s plane, or formerly, a shell used as a plane for smoothing wood. see
to saw (previously, to rasp , before introduction of saws.)
cake v. to move up, develop, increase, improve. toro sobu decrease, decline, shift downward. na
higher education. see toro, toroya, above.

(anglicism) v. to develop (the economy, the land), a modern concept. veivakatorocake-taki n. development (usually economic), a modern word. tosi . (eng.) n. toast, as served at an urban breakfast. tosi, tosia . (eng.) v. to toss, toss up, as of a coin, heads or tails winning. tosi, tosia . v . to make a marking, scratch with pointed object ; modernly, to check off, to “tick ” as on a questionnaire. tositosi vulavula white marking(s). syn. toqa, toqa.

n. “tick” or check-off, mark or streak. na tositosi the checking off. syn. toqa which is rather more forceful. originally meaning was simply to mark distinctively. toso, tosoya v. to shift along, move along (of things or people). toso! get moving ! toso tani mai! come
(from there to here) ! na veitosoyaki the moving about, the travel, getting around, the moving here and there. toso, tosova v. of a person, to shift toward (someone, something)
v., n. to give support to (another person ’s views or position, or an ideal), go along with. na noqu
my sticking by the truth. see to.
v. to turn away , in refusal or rej ection.y
n. small deep pool surrounded by shallows, at swampy land or reef. see tobu.
n. feeling by touch , smoothing. see toci.
n. well known, wild and common creeping herb with semi-circular leaves on erect stems,
asiatica, umbelliferae, tends to grow in wet places, often around houses, probably aboriginal
to fiji. in india, an ayurvedic medicine, brahmi (brahma-manduki), and used

in tonga (called tono) and samoa (called tongo). in fiji, used externally on cuts, internally for aches of the joints, stomach ailments, general weakness. some use the leaves to alleviate diarrhoea. occasionally served as a vegetable.
n. penalty, fine, punishment. totogi mate n.,v., death sentence, sentenced to death, discontinued in fiji. (there was formerly an official hangman.) syn. (tonga) totongi.
v. to penalise, punish, to fine.
adj . beautiful.
(archaic) n. so-called pineapple war club, a beaked battle hammer with heavy swollen head and

intended mostly for quick j ab to the skull. this club did not require the wide sweeping blow of many other clubs. it was often intended for assassinations with one quick short blow but it was a large club, difficult to conceal, often used for display in ceremonial duties.

quick . totolo! be quick ! lako vakatotolo go quickly . vakatotolotaka to speed it up. me vakatotolotaki! speed it up ! syn. kusa. (lau) remo. idiom: (anglicism) na kena totolo na kena vinaka the quicker the better. vakatotomuri, vakatotomuria v. to imitate, follow the example of (someone). muri, muria v. to follow.
n.plant, three-leafed shamrock, yellow flowers, oxalis corniculata, oxalaceae, grows in damp areas, near houses or wherever people urinate (wiwi), as implied in the name. medicinal uses, unproven.
v. to glue together sections of barkcloth using a vegetable paste, a starchy product such as cooked

(dalo), cassava (tavioka), or arrowroot (yabia). properly, the use of such pastes should not be necessary. tovaka v. to take the part of, support, defend. e tovaki seru o tukana. tukana takes the part of seru. na
the political involvement. tovisi n. ribbon fish, trichiurus haumela, edible, silver colour, seasonal. syn. tovici, beleti.

. n. customary behaviour (of person, animal), habit. itovo vinaka good behaviour. itovo vakasisila abominable behaviour. syn. ivalavala, ivakarau. itovo . n. manner, regular way (of doing something). na itovo ni veiqaravi the manner of treatment (as in medical care). na itovo ni rai attitude. itovo . n ethnological custom(s). itovo vakaviti fij ian custom(s).
v. to try, to attempt.
n. testing, testing out. na vakatovolei iyaragi the testing of weapons.
n. the testing period, trial run, practice trial.
n. testing, practice.
v. to practice (for testing or to improve).
. (eng.) top, as a child ’s toy.
. (eng.) n. top shell, trochus (or) techtis pyramis. a smaller version of the commercial trochus shell. see sici. tovure v . to overflow. tovure noqu bilo my cup overflows (an anglicism). see vure.
adj . brackish, of water.
. to be, indicating a state of being, to exist, implying it has been that way for a while, or has been in
a while. e lako tu. he/she is gone. tu vakai koya independent. e vinaka tu na waqa. the boat is in good condition. evica na vosa ka sega ni tu eliu some words that did not exist before.

located here and there in a rather scattered fashion. cf. toka, which indicates a changed condition or state of things. see also tiko that refers only to the present. idiom, exclaiming an announcement, surprise or discovery: a tu! there he/she/it is ! sa ra tu na turaga! the chief has arrived !

. v. to have. sa tu vei au e dua. i have one. tu ga e lomana have thoughts, feelings kept to oneself, unexpressed, where open expression of opinion would be considered intrusive or rude. it is not customary to express opinions in front of someone senior.
. v. to stand tu! tu cake! stand ! stand up ! na tucake tale the resurrection (of christ). matanitu
vakawawa interim government. tu vakarau be prepared, stand ready. tu vakatikitiki stand aside. syn. wavu = tu cake stand up.
n. see below, tuatua.

n. mountain ridge. tokaitua principal mountain range, usually referring to the one on eastern viti levu, course of the spirit path (sala ni yalo), and of many migratory travels south from nakauvadra mountains, more specifically named the tualeita. also, the mountain chain along the length of vanua levu, separating macuata from cakaudrove. tu lo v. to attack under cover of darkness. fij ian attacks are almost always unexpected. in combat, fij ians are direct and confrontational only as a last resort or when they are fairly certain of victory. they excel at making an ambush.
(or) e tuba outside (usually of house, the immediate vicinity outside). tuba! laki tuba! go outside !
(of the house) ! tautuba completely outside (usually outside the house compound). curu yani

tautuba go outside. na daku ni tuba n. outside the lagoon, outside the reef. gusu ni tuba n. local name for the lower reaches of the ba river. (gusu mouth). idiom: lasa e tuba have an affair outside of marriage. tube, tubea v. to hold in the hand, often said of offering a whaletooth. idiom: tube tabua to bring a presentation of whaletooth.
n. handle (as of a bag, basket). kato vakatubetube handbag. tube, tubera . v. to lead, guide with the hand, as with a child, to take by the hand, and by ext., to guide
(archaic) n., v. formal marriage, to marry. this is an old, properly traditional word used mostly
(tongan fakamau) more traditionally , a man would formalise marriage by
a house for the woman (vakavaletaka na yalewa). lotu ni veitube church marriage ceremony. bride price, so important in parts of western melanesia, was not common custom in fij i.
the late s, a whaletooth sufficed in many cases, several teeth in the case of important women. wives and concubines were often given by a defeated tribe. anciently, lower-class

little if any ceremony in taking a wife. in many cases taking a woman for one night meant you had just taken her as a mate. her relatives would normally enforce that. “tubelight” (eng. slang) of a person, slow on the uptake, slow to react or understand, as with the hesitation of a fluorescent lamp to be lit.
(archaic) v., n. tono buka, to burn scars on the human body, chest, shoulders or back , prodding it
a burning coconut midrib sasa . this was done as body decoration or sometimes as punishment for a child. syn. tavusasa .
v. to grow in size or amount (plants, animals, people). tubu ni dra (anglicism) n. high blood pressure, hypertension, formerly unknown to fijians.
n. interest (on money), profit (of business), growth.

n., v. increase, to increase. vakatubu, vakatubura v. to give rise to, to make grow, to cause, to set up vakatubura na rere to cause fear. vakatubu leqa v ., n. to cause trouble. me vakatubu na lovo. set up the earth-oven (a request). see tubu, tubura.
(anglicism) n. baking powder. leavening was unknown to fijians though european-style bread and cakes are now eaten frequently.
sudden, suddenly.

. n. edible vegetable plant, amaranthus sp., probably an aboriginal introduction of polynesians or proto-polynesians, semi-wild, a virtual weed, the leaves cooked and eaten by coastal fij ians (not highlanders), and also by indians, who introduced their own varieties and cultivate them. syn. moca , driti. (hindi) chauraiya. interestingly, some amaranthus species yield edible seeds, a common food in africa but no grain was every grown or eaten as a basic food by fijians before the introduction of rice. tubua . adj . overgrown with weeds, of a garden or path. idiom: sa tubua na sala ki na nona koro. he/she no longer visits the village. i.e., has not maintained
relationships with village kinfolk, suggested by the path (sala) being overgrown by vegetation. maintaining the relationship can be expensive for urban fijians who may be expected to
for their rural relatives. also, some fijians have left their village due to internal disputes,
differenes, shortage of land or simply that their village is remote from their employment, their children ’s schooling or medical clinics and shops or markets for their farm produce.
n. grandparent. tubu i seru seru ’s grandparent, which may serve as a name.
n. our forbears, our forefathers, our ancestors. tubu-qu my forbears. tubu, tubura v. to grow upon or within, particularly an emotion. e tuburi au e dua na cudru. l am becoming angry.
n. parents (as of schoolchildren).
n. growth (usually of a plant or creature, but could apply to the economy.
n. middle finger (of the hand).
(anglicism). resurrection.
permanent. vunivola tudei permanent secretary. dei firm.
as in tamata tudonu adult person.
n. chiefly title at village dravo, tailevu province.
n. chiefly title at wainikeli.. tuga, tugana v. to put away in its place, to put aside carefully, to place in memory , keep in mind.
(or) tu galala n. independence. also refers to a fij ian who has formally arranged to live independently, usually on his own personal farm, separate from his clan, and not owing traditional
community. this system was introduced by the british but opposed by ratu sukuna. he himself lived totally separate and independent of any clan or village but he believed that
for that type of freedom that he insisted to have for himself. this system

hardly succeed when the independent fij ian remained living close to his village, say as in leasing land from his own clan. relatives are accustomed to impose traditional and family obligations that most fijians could not bring themselves to refuse for fear of being socially ostracised and despised by their own kin.
n. small, silver, edible crevally-shaped fish, schooling seasonally around november, selar crumenophthalmus. on lakeba island, village yadrana, and at fulaga island, village naividamu, the
of this fish is celebrated as an annual “balolo ”, a festive occasion. syn. (west, kadavu, rewa) yatule, (nadro) j ule.
n., adj . usually of a child, dirty face, runny nose, etc.

. (west) n . dog. tui . n. king or chief, chiefly title followed usually by place-name or tribal name. tui nawaka chief of nawaka. roko tui bau chief of bau. tui sabeto chief of sabeto. many such titles were relatively
adoptions, since colonial times, inspired from verata, adapted from tongan titles. the tui

has become very popular in usage, displacing many of the older, properly fijian titles such as vunivalu, vunisa, momo, or is added to them as an additional title. in formal ceremonies both types of titles may be cited. tui king. vakatui royal. na matavuvale vakatui the royal household. tuina is a

at nacamaki, koro island. only in cakobau ’s time did the newly invented tui viti title come to be used by europeans. cakobau conceded any claim to that title to queen victoria and her successors. tui also means dog around western viti levu. itui n. string (of crab s, small fish etc., strung together). tuitui strung together (of crabs, fish, etc.) na ituitui
(crabs, fish) hung in the string. syn. idoi.

boto (anglicism) n. lit. “king frog”, referring to the european dance, the conga, often done for tourists, a long line of people each holding onto the one in front of them, the line weaving around the room with a sort of hopping motion, suddenly reversing direction. lots of laughter.
n. pope (roman catholic). the pope actually visited fij i in .
. n. village steward who apportions feast foods at food-presentation ceremonies. this is a delicate
with the recipients watching closely to see if they get their fair share. he will sometimes have

acceptable portions. idiom: wasewase o tuirara. said of one who keep s a large portion for himself when his duty was to divide the portions into fair shares. wase divide. syn. votavota vaka tuirara. vota v. to share out. tuirara . n . local warden of the methodist church.
target_text: assistants who help guide him in allocation

source_text: n. (polyn.) candlenut tree with useful oil nuts, aleurites moluccana, formerly used for lamps and for hair dye in coastal areas. syn. lauci, sikeci.
n. goshawk. syn. latui.
adj . very salty (water, food). rui tutuina much too salty. wai tui saltwater. syn. konakona.
n. grandfather on the side of either father or mother. na tukai seru vakarua seru ’s great grandfather. tukai is the usual abbreviation for grandfather, but may be applied respectfully in
to other elderly gentleman. like several other terms for family relationship s, tukai (or)
may be used as a personal name if one has been named after a grandfather. tukadra vakarua
(many) great grandfather(s). na tukaqu vakatolu my great great grandfather. na veitukani n. the grandfather(s) and grandchild(ren) together.
n. grandfather. syn. (lau) tua.
n. our forebears, ancestors, always preceded by “the”, as in na tukada. tuki, tukia . v. to knock, to hammer. tatuki, tatuki-taka na uluna to strike (someone) on the head. tukia
knock on the door. tuki, tukia . v. to punch. syn. vacu.
n. cape gooseberry, husk tomato, peruvian origin. very small edible fruit. children knock
gooseberry against their forehead to make a popping sound, hence the fij ian name. yadre-na forehead. many local names for this annual plant.
n. hammer. na itukituki the hammering, knocking on something hard. tukituki, tukitukia v. to hammer it.
(ni qio) n . dorsal fin of a shark that may appear above the surface of the water. tuku, tukuca v. to lower something by loosening, usually something suspended by a rope. tukuca na
lower the dory, rowboat.

v. to tell (it). sa tukuni it has been told (referring to legends, prophesies). tukuna vei au tell me. kua ni tukuni au. don ’t tell on me. tukunataki related, already told. syn. (nasavusavu) avola. tukuni, tukunitaka v. to recount traditional folk stories, legends. (
n . traditional tale, folk story, legend.
n. report. itukutuku tomiki rumour. dau-vola-itukutuku reporter for the news media, reportwriter. itukutuku raraba official reports on tribal (yavusa) background, prepared for the native
commission from signed testimony of local elders known as the veitarogi vakavanua.
ni leqa obituary, announcement of death(s). itukutuku saumi n. advertisement. tabana ni
information department (govt).
adj . tells stories about others, gossipy.
n. communications.
v. to boast. e tukutukuni koya tiko. he/she is bragging.

v. to pass judgement, to judge, determine. tuli, tulia na kuro v . to shape and make the clay pot. qele ni tuli kuro potting clay. dau tuli kuro n. potter. the potter ’s wheel is not known. syn. (nadro.) voca.
(or) tilou (tonga) interj ection of apology for passing too close or above another person. it is

stand above a person of high status, or to pass the hand above their head. there is an implicit possible threat to such a position or motion. “tulsi” (hindi) n. basil, holy herb-plant grown around indian houses, naturalised as a weed. this is the potherb basil, ocimum basilicum, labiatae, used as such by europeans in fiji. similarly, sage grows virtually as a weed. neither is normally used by fij ians. tuna, tunaka v. to gut (fish, eel, chicken , pig) usually before cooking.
(west, kadavu) n . eel. syn. duna.
n. conger eel, conger cenereus. syn. baku (west).
n. a minor chiefly title at village vanualevu, tokatoka territory. culturally this is of rewa, but is assigned politically to tailevu province.
n. a minor chiefly title in verata, village navuruvuru, and in bureta, at tai.
n. a minor chiefly title of tribe dewala at villages nagigi and nacavanadi, near nasavusavu, cakaudrove. the origin is near nakorotubu, ra province.

n. title of the spokesman (matanivanua) of the chiefly vunivalu, tui kaba at bau island. he heads clan matanivanua with five extended families and some ten house-sites on bau island. tunu, tunuga v. to warm up food that was previously cooked. vakatuna (causative) to make it warm.

(or) tunudra n. ceremony celebrating the fourth night after a birth. formerly, at coastal locations, blood from the birth was washed off and excretia from the baby washed away in the sea. dra blood. feast is prepared for the grandfather and relatives of the new baby who have attended the
ceremony to which they brought gifts at the birth of a baby. the fourth night tunudra ceremony implies the baby will probably survive since it has lived through the first few days of life.
n. temporary shed, usually erected for special occasions in the village and at suburban homes, often made for marriages, ceremonial feasts. modernly, fijians often rent the corrugated iron
used for temporary roofs. supporting posts may be decorated with branches of coconut palm and flowers.

n. open, outdoor fire-place for grass or bamboo fire that hardens pottery and makes it resistant to water. all firing of pots is done outdoors with no furnace. pottery made for tourist trade is not always heated sufficiently for use as a water container, flower vase or cooking pot.
adj ., n. hot and humid (the air, the weather), humidity .
(eng. obsolete.) n. tuppence, two pence. (there used to be such a coin.) occasionally used as a personal name tupeni, the only way one hears the word today.
v. to propose, or move a motion in a meeting. au sa vakatura me sogo na bose. i propose that the meeting be closed.
n. gentleman, chief. long ago adopted from coastal areas, turaga was anciently an unknown word
the indigenous melanesians. (the same applies to marama, lady). na turaga bale the high chief. na gone turaga the high chief.
n. supervisor, man in charge of the work or task.
ni koro n . village headman, an administrator, usually not of high rank, paid a small stipend. he
government regulations in the village, and collections of money but has no chiefly status. word and functions created by colonial officials.
n. judge, magistrate (of court).
n. man in charge of cooking a lovo earth oven.
n. police officer (polite term).

n. military officer, soldier (polite form). turi, turia v. to prepare washed, starchy mash from grated roots of arrowroot yabia or some wild yams kaile, for food. turu, turuma (or) turuva v. to drip, drip on (as rain through a roof, hair-dye on the face, tea from the spout of a teapot). sa turumi au na uca. rain is dripping on me. e dua na ituruturu one drop.
n. menstruation, menses.
(ni vale) n. eves (of a house).
buto v. to become covered (of sun or moon) by sudden clouds, darkening the sky. vale
shade-house (nursery for young plants). tusanaka v. to confess, to talk truly of important matters. a lai tusanaki koya vua na bete. he/she went to confess to the priest.
(eng.) tuesday. syn. tusite.
v. to support, be supportive, as people may be to their elders, their chief.
. n. corner (building, playing field), column (written by media correspondent). na tutuna nei
mesake’s column (in the newspaper).
. n. dorsal fin of a fish.
. v. to beat bark-cloth in order to join the pieces and smooth out the texture.
. exactly, as in sigalevu tutu, exactly midday, noon. bogilevu tutu midnight exactly.

. n. title. itutu vakaturaga chiefly title(s). na keni itutu his/her title. some tribes yavusa have no formal title for their chief and some do. some require a formal installation ceremony, and some do not.
have varied considerably and some have changed with time. in the west, there are momo or
levu. vunivalu and vunisa are old titles concentrated perhaps on viti levu (there is also a
at weilagi, taveuni island). vunivalu is the classical title on most of viti levu. sau exist at
and lakeba (or perhap s more properly, kabara) and ra, and a roko sau at totoya,
to the tongan hau . other titles, outside viti levu, include ra malo, ra masi, and takala.
(followed by a place-name), usually gives a form of address “ratu” to the chief, a
that originated in verata which had extremely early contact with tonga. many if not most
adopted the tui (with place name) and ratu form of address. this dates only from colonial times. the widespread use of ratu has no justification in tradition outside of verata. the

source_text: roko might precede the tui, as in the rokotui bau, and there are rokotui also at cautata, namata, namara, viwa, kiuva, kadavu, nakelo, and ovalau . rokotuni is an alternative.
. n. position, stance, as in na itutu ni lotu me baleta na siga tabu the position of the church on the issue of sunday.
. n. stand, where something is placed. itutu ni tv n. television stand.
n. position or “stand” (on some issue), point of view expressed, proposal. na cava na nomu vakatutu? what is your proposal, point of view?
v. to propose.
adv., adj . sideways (as a crab walks), on its side. davo vakanatutu lie down on one’s side. syn. vakababa.
v., adj . to be unsteady on the feet, as a person dizzy or drunk.
v. to light (a fire, lantern, matches).
v. stand up for (someone, something). tutaki koya stand up for him/her vaka-tutu-taki proposed.

(colo) n. any family relative who is older than the person speaking. term of reference or term of address. most commonly used for one’s father's father. itutuvi n. blanket, a covering, modernly of cloth, formerly of barkcloth or woven matting. itutuvi kuta nei
name of cakobau ’s warclub, lit. “sedge-blanket of the queen of bau”, sometimes
as a i tutuvi ni ranadi i bau ”, dropping the reference to sedge. originally a namosi club, it

given at cession for queen victoria, and later returned to fij i and used as mace for legislative council, more recently for parliament. tuvi, tuvia v. to cover over. tuva, tuva (or) tuvana v., n. to arrange, arranged, array, to stack (boxes, stones for a fish fence).
v. to arrange in detail, carefully .
n. arrangement, classification, array, programme.
ni ilavo n. government budget. tuva-ilavo v. to set out a financial plan, usually an annual budget for a company or organisation.
v., n. have a fit, possessed (by a devil) usually , or having an epileptic fit, “interim, waiting state”. the notion of a devil possessing a person for a while serves as an acceptable, understandable
for temporary, erratic behaviour that would be otherwise reprehensible or socially unacceptable. it can be a kind of safety valve in an extremely closely controlled society.
(anglcism) n. na tuva itutu ni koro ni vuli the school graduation ceremony, when degrees and prizes are handed out. tuva to arrange or stack. itutu title(s).
n. plant, tephrosia purperea, leguminosae, formerly used as a fish poison in quiet ponds. pounded, released underwater. fish float to the surface, dead but edible. a totemic plant at village
in the colo east highlands, where the name is not to be mentioned. duva, duva v. to poison fish. duva n. derris sp., another fish poison, two species.
n. condition, state. na ituvaki ni bula the standard of living, conditions of life. na ituvaki ni

the condition of my body. na ituvaki ni gaunisala the condition of the road. ituvaki ni draki condition of the weather. tuvi, tuvia v. to cover over, to conceal by placing something on top ; of an earth oven lovo, to cover it

n. leatherback, also known as tabaiwalu, largest of the sea turtles, often kg but may attain kg, one to two meters long, dermochelys coriacea, uncommon in fiji waters, seen mostly in open ocean, around shore only if deep water. breeds at australian north coast, solomons, papua and migrates to indian ocean. during five years of fishing and diving around fiji i have seen it only once.
around malaysia, borneo, and visits but does not breed in fiji. back is leathery with seven long ridges, black spots with white blotches, without a shell, and the flippers are huge with no claws.

mostly j ellyfish. fast swimmer, to mph according to the late rob wright, authority on fiji fishing. other sea turtles mph. leatherback can dive to almost , ft, deeper than other sea turtles. while most fij ians may have hear the word tuvonu, they have no knowledge of it. there is
confusion with the equally elusive loggerhead turtle, ceretta carette gigas, the larger of two subspecies, the one that inhabits the pacific. it is much smaller than the leatherback, weighing kg
jellyfish , but also clam and mussels, squid and flying fish . unlike the leatherback the
a massive head and very powerful j aws. its carapace is reddish brown, formerly useful in commerce, as has been the shell from the hawkbill turtle, now however a forbidden trade.
n. freshwater spring that seeps up, as on a sandy beach.

n. (rare) very tip or top of a long obj ect such as a tree trunk or ship ’s mast. tuvu, tuvulaka v. to wash wet clothes by beating with a stick against rocks. tuvutuvu-laka v. to keep beating (drum, laundry). na katuvu ni lali the beating of the drum.
n. giant, man of giant size. stories of fijian gods and founding spirits often tell of giants. some
still occasionally reported as seen. today the term is used more figuratively, meaning a very big
i, the personal pronoun, as an abbrev. of au when that pronoun follows a vowel, as in e dina, seu lasu? that is true, or am i wrong? (commonly, one might see seu written as se ’u.)

. n. wave, tide. uaua adj . slight, of the sea. vakaua adj . moderate, of the sea. ua lokaloka tidal wave, tsunami. see sonaua. ua levu high tide. sa lo na ua. it has become the quiet period just before change in tidal flow.
v. to ride the waves, to surf. syn. vakadavo-ua. surfing was a sport little known to fijians
at vuna, introduced by polynesians but discontinued in the early s. after mid-century

was re-introduced as a sport, from hawaii. in fiji most surfers now are europeans or parteuropeans. qalova uaua swim with the tide, waves, or current. idiom : kakua ni qalova uaua na moka. do not try to do something before you have the appropriate
or experience. this might be said to a child to discourage smoking, or pre-marital sex . moka stone fish-fence.
v. to make a judgement, decision. syn. vakataulewa.
(archaic) v., n. recitation of genealogy, mainly in areas of polynesian influence, that may

back generations. a fair amount of the lineage is usually imaginative, of self-serving importance. there are often some gaps and discontinuities. in areas of melanesian origin, recounted lineages would normally be limited to about four generations, not more than about eight. ua . n. vein, muscle. ua dradra. n. varicose veins. dra blood.

n. paddle, stick used especially for laundry, beating wet clothes against a rock. ua, uaca or ua v. to beat with stick, clothes in washing, mash of root crop for pudding, pandanus leaves for weaving. v. uaraka to beat forcefully
adj . of people, in a productive, adult phase of life.
to the extreme, to the fullest, a word rarely used. vuabale to overflow.
n. varicose veins. syn. uasala.
swell (of the sea).
(or) ualokaloka n. tidal wave, tsunami. there is a famous meke in rewa, celebrating a major ualoka that created great devastation. these are caused by an undersea volcano.
n. flood. syn. waluvu. see luvu.
special, exceptional. sivi, sivita v. to pass, to go beyond.
especially. uasivi, uasivita v . to surpass, to excel. o sa uasivi ganemu ena veitarogi. you have done better than your
in the exam. o sa uasivita na nona na cakacaka na tuakamu. you have done better than the work of your elder brother.
choppy or rough of the sea.
n. drumstick s (formerly used only for signaling and for exhibition dancing).

having prominent, bulging veins, of a person. ubi, ubia v . to cover over, conceal by covering. iubi n. cover. idiom: were ubiubi to pretend to work, literally to fake the work of cutting grass, weeds, by just
vegetation down to lie against the ground. by extension, this idiom may imply that someone is not telling the whole story, that they are concealing some truth.
n. eyelid(s). syn. dakudaku ni mata-na. eyelash(es) n. bekabeka ni mata-na. yaloka ni
n. eyeball. vacu-na n . eyebrow.
(eng.) n. home-brew (alcohol). there are various spellings of this word.

n. rain. sa tau na uca. it is raining, rain is falling. sa ucauca na draki. it is rainy weather. uca bi heavy rain. kote ni uca raincoat. uca tokavuki rainy squall. uca waicevata n. hail, that does occur,
at certain highland locations. the hailstones can be quite large and even somewhat dangerous to people. syn. (lau, rewa, kadavu) lagi.
n. small shrub, evodia hortensis, rutaceae, known to all fij ians, semi-cultivated, often growing near houses, leaves and flower shoots used as a fragrance, placed behind the ear by women or men. the
flowers themselves are not conspicuous. seeds appear in july. the shrub grows best in partial
and does not thrive standing alone in the full sun or in places where the roots remain in wet ground. the leaves are edible and tasty, but rarely eaten. small shoots grow from fallen seeds around
n. river or stream.
. n. nose. ucu gara broad-nosed, of person. ucu rava has a flat nose, of person (those
not widely used). ucu cega turned–up nose. dokaniucu n. bridge of the nose.
n. nostril(s). ucu bi n. blocked or stuffed nose, as from a cold. idiom: ucuucu ni kalavo or ucukalavo bloody nose, blobs of stringy congealed blood and mucus that

from the nose during a nose-bleed, and may be pulled out. they are preceded by fast dripping of blood. when the blobs pass, fijians believe that the nose-bleed is coming to an end. my observation suggests they are correct. idiom: “ucui cei? ucui lei.” “chip off the old block”, looks like the parent. idiom: ucu mai duru unbelievable “tall yarn”, “if you believe that you will believe anything”, lit. nose growing out of the knee.
. n. protrusion, protuberance. ucu ni vanua n. cape, point of the lands-end, as in suva point,
(of land). idiom : dui mate ena noda ucu ni vatu. each die defending our very own territory. ucu, ucuya v. to resemble, have similar features, said of people, usually related as parent and child.
v. to proceed out, come on the scene, as of dancers, or people making ceremonial presentations, proceeding out in a procession to the arena.
v. to draw out (knife from sheath , reed from within a stack of reeds, book from a shelf of books, etc.).
n. promintory (land).
thousand. e rua na udolu two thousand.
v. to land, come ashore from a boat, to approach the shore and anchor. this can become a placename.
n. hermit crab, often used as bait, common at the shore, edible but not commonly eaten. kasikasi smaller hermit crab, useful only as bait.

vule n. the very large coconut crab, burgo latto, rare except on a few remote islands such as katafaga. easy to catch by hand though they have formidable pincers. they actually open coconuts with their pincers though this in not often observed since they are nocturnal feeders.

n. (eng.) n . ukulele, introduced by europeans, from hawaii, via portugese sailors. fij ians had three musical instruments: a nose flute, polynesian in origin, rare in fiji, a j ew ’s harp of bamboo, also

rare, and a simple section of bamboo thumped against the ground for rhythm, which is still common. wooden gongs or drums were used only for signals and communications. the use of small wooden gongs for music was introduced from polynesia.
(eng.) n. hookworm. (slang) big eater, gourmand.
adj . of clouds, become black, heavy with rain about to fall.
n. decoration, ornament, adornment. uku, ukuta, uku-taka v. to decorate, add embellishments, to adorn, to dress grandly, as with special clothes, flowers.

adj . attractively dressed up , “all decked out”. ula, ulaca . v. to jump, jump over. syn. lade, rika. sa ula tiko na kanace. the mullet are jumping, skimming. dau ula n . jumper (sports, long jump, high jump). idiom: sa ula! fantastic ! (food, dance, a delightful experience).

. (hawaii) n., v. hula dance, modern introduction of hawaiian hula, a sensual, undulating dance of women, formerly a quite different type of dance of men in old hawaii. ula! . interjection of sudden delighted admiration
(archaic) n. throwing club for use in fighting, often carried thrust through a man ’s waist-band.
(or) vaka-ulaka v. to hurl (something) at someone, something, or to somewhere. syn. kolo, kolotaka.
. n. tiny jumping frog, the fij i tree frog, barely more than two inches long, platymantis vitiensis,

lives only in trees, usually in wet canopy forest, and thus rarely seen. no free-swimming tadpole phase. sometimes found close to the ground in pandanus palms, near streams or wet places. it is different from the much larger fij i ground frog boto or dreli in having large, adhesive well padded feet and highly varied coloration. it can jump amazing distances. highlanders kaicolo grilled the ula over embers of flame, and ate it whole with the intestines. see also boto fiji ground frog, but also an adopted name for the toad, unfortunately introduced, now a pest. ulabale, ulubaleta v. to over-step, figuratively, as in acting above one’s station. ulala! interjection of surprise and admiration.
v. to somersault. syn. sausauvesu, ulu-sauvesu.

n. parrot fish , mainly scarus harid, dull reddish colour, but several species at the reef, edible. in various places, this name applies to bolbometopon spp. uli, ulia, uliraka . v. to stir, as of sugar in tea, milk powder and water. uliraka to stir fast, forcefully, as in whipping eggs. na iuli n. stick or spoon used to do the stirring. uli, uliva . v. to comment on a speech when it is finished, often summarising and complimenting the speech in ceremonial reception of it. uliva na noqu vosa to receive respectfully and comment on my speech. uli, ulia, uliva . v. to steer (a boat, vehicle). uliva na waqa ki na matasawa to steer the boat toward the shore. ulia na motoka to steer the motor car. iuli n. rudder, helm.
n. maggot.
(colo east) n. ceremonial presentation to a village after a death of a woman or her offspring. the gift is made to the woman ’s people.

(polyn.) n. head, head of hair. traditonally in fiji the head has been sacred, not ever to be touched. a few decades ago this was strictly observed and in some situations still today . formerly high chiefs had a special individul to trim their hair and colour it. fijian hair is not naturally black ; in
situations it is often dyed black. in preparing for war, various colours were used. ulumatua

child. ulu dina “real” fij ian hair, crinkly. ulu kabi very tightly crinkled fijian hair of the highlanders; sometimes laughingly compared to steel wool. syn. ulu manj i or ulu maquru. ulu wai soft hair. ulu waiwaiya very soft hair, usually falling down the back. ulu damu red-head, gingerhaired, a common natural occurence in fij i, but may be simulated by bleaching or by dye. ulu
blond hair, light-coloured (no red). ulu kaukauwa intelligent. ulu tawa knowledgeable person. ulu lala ignorant ("empty-headed "), ulukau stupid ("wooden-head"). ulu ca wrong-headed.
buki with hair knotted, as in a bun. ulu qali with plaited hair (sometimes an indirect way of
to an indian woman.) ulu balavu having long hair. ulu p ori or ulu cou or ulu drika bald.
tasi shaved head. ulu maquru short, tightly curled hair that cannot always grow long (it breaks).
se scattered spikey hair. bui ni ga “duck-tail” hair style. ulu viro long hair, curled. ulu vula white-haired. drau ni uluna hair. mala ni uluna single hair(s). syn. (tonga) ‘ulu.
prefix indicating the high part or upper part of something. ulu-ni-vanua high point of land, mountain. ulu-toa head of tiqa j avelin.
(or) ulu mate n. wig, traditionally often made of human hair, later of horse hair after europeans introduced horses. fij ian men sometimes wore wigs, in case of natural baldness, or hair removed as a
at the death of someone close or chiefly. men were formerly proud of their head of hair,
elaborate care of it as a main feature of male vanity. that was still quite common fifty years ago, but is now quite rare. missionaries discouraged this. military service also required shortened

style. there are a couple of clans (mataqali) called ulucavu, a major one at village nakorosule, colo east. their ancestral spirit is a white man. when he removed his hat, fijians considered he was removing his wig.
(or) naulunivuaka n. an early place name of bau island, referring to the fishermen by that
who occupied the low flatlands that were also known as butonivanua, and the people also as

large tribal house ( ’ x ’) with five doors (some say eight), one for each clan: tunidau ni bau, yavusa ra tavuto, taurisau , bale i nasinu, and sanisamu. it was used for church services th -, when the methodist church was completed, later named ratu cakobau church. the
of bau, penaia kadavulevu, (died ) removed the building to make room for playing cricket. it was replaced by a public toilet.
n., adj . sleepy-head.
v. head for, head towards, go toward. vakanaulu i baravi. head for the coast. ulubale, ulubaletaka v. to offer an excuse.
n. excuse. iulubale lokiloki lit. “lame excuse”, an anglicism.
n. head hair grown long and combed out straight, usually trimmed neatly, and under-cut sharply in men ’s tradition, common till the mid-s.
n. edible fish, also called “bedford” because its face is shaped like the front of a bedford truck,

snapper, paracaesio kusakarii, with four dark yellow patch on its sides, against a sight silver background. there is a very similar species, somehat smaller, p. stonei, cocoa snapper, that has three or four dark patches on each side, against a yellowish background.
n. an edible parrotfish, chlorurus microrhinos, blue back , then pink and belly yellowish. blunt head. same genus as the karakarawa parrotfish .
v. to go head over heels, somersault. syn. sausauvesu.

source_text: vakaviti n. hair let grow out, dressed neatly in early fij i-fashion, formerly proudly worn by fijian,
only very rarely seen among men, and only occasionally among women. men now crop their hair closely.
n. promintory , rocky peak, literally rock-head. nauluvatu is a major super-tribe from the waidina highlands, now, widely dispersed.
n. deliberately curled long hair, as some men do, rasta fashion.
n. . a body, lot, pile, or bar of something, soap, ingot, tobacco, brick, block (as of traditional sea

umea for colouring bark-cloth). na veiuma qele the parcels or lots of land. uma tamata n. bunch or group of people. veivoli umauma (modernism) wholesale. uma n. . lead (the metal). uma n. . weighted ball used in the european game of bowls. viritaka na uma to hurl the weighted ball.

(lau) . red ochre pigment from a certain soil for staining bark-cloth , a specialty of komo island, lau province, which supplies the pigment but itself makes no bark-cloth. made into spindle-shaped blocks that are given, traded or sold. dry reddish powder is scraped from the block.
(lau) . n. rust. syn. veveka.

n. earthquake, tremor, common in fij i, causing landslides (sisi ni qele), especially in the red latersols, acidic, infertile soils that are amorphous in structure, and thus unstable when soaked in rainwater. landslides are visible in the hills and mountains as red gashes in the verdure. they can be quite dangerous, burying houses suddenly and leaving great gashes, crevices in the ground.
(eng.) n. university . there are now two in fiji. uqe, uqeta v. to move swiftly the mid-section of one’s body, mostly as a dance movement. this is rather
swamp s. it is believed that crevally (saqa) eat them. prawns are the aquatic totem
are jumping. (in rivers and streams they are often trying to escape the eels that feed on them.)

are often sold by the roadside, but not always safe to eat, since some are killed with stolen, poisonous paraquat. a weed-killer. idiom: sega ni ura me sa tei damu. where there is smoke there is fire. the truth will come out. i.e.,

must be a cause for it to happen, and it will be known. lit. no prawn just turns red (unless someone has cooked it). idiom: moce vakaura. lit. to sleep like a prawn , ready to rise to instant action from apparent sleep .
buta n. prawns that are naturally red; this requires a very specialised alkaline environment, with
water, connected underground with the tidal effects of the sea. at vatulele island the best
species is parhyppolyte uveae, held sacred, and may respond to ceremonial calls. (they also

to a simple stirring of the water but that is not traditional.) the same species is known at naweni, cakaudrove province, and at a one-hectare limestone island in the philippines where they are called pulang payasan. there are other species at vatulele, smaller ones, that local fijians assume
simply the young ones. in fiji the red prawns are serving as a tourist attraction. at naweni a fee

charged for sighting them and one is told of the prohibitions: no touching, taking, and no photographs. the ritual call: “ ‘eitou qo na marama ni vuna, ‘eitou mai via sara ura buta. e tuba, e tuba, e?” this is said to recall that people here supported the tui wairuku in aiding the tui cakau
the tongan forces of wainiqolo.” it is unclear how those fij ian words
support but such is oral history. (ifereimi nadore, “na ura buto ni naweni ”, nai lalakai, august, , p. .)
n. banded prawnkiller, slipper lobster, lysiosquille maculata.
n. large crayfish, “spiny lobster”, palinuri dae, most readily caught at night by torch-light, but now
more scarce. when the moon is shining they go into hiding and are harder to find. when
to escape they dart backwards very quickly. best and freshest when caught alive by hand, as
and tuvalu people, and cooked while alive. fij ians normally spear them and sell
dead to hotels, resorts, where often they become tasteless and rubbery . iseru (or) lawe-na
of crayfish. tara urau to catch crayfish by hand. several type of crayfish : urau dina

versicolor, large, green with white and black markings. urau bola or urau tamata, p. ornatus, very large and greenish with markings. urau vatu, urau kau or urau kula, the golden rock lobster, p. pencillatus, short and dark. quite different in appearance is the vavaba, slipper crayfish, parribacus caledonicus, flat and small, lacking antennae. syn. (lau) ura. ure, urea v. to shake, as of a tree branch, to bring down fruit. fruit bats are caught, especially by highlanders, shaking a tree where the bats are resting. the bats fall in their confusion and are easily picked up. syn. kure, kurea or sakurea.

boil down lard to use cooking fat because it is cheaper than commercial brands of

v., adj . heavily laden, over-loaded (usually of boat, vehicle, horse). uso, usora v. to poke, usually with a stick , usually speaking of stones in a fire for grilling food, or stones for an earth-oven , to arrange them. usoraka refers to the stick or other instrument used for poking.

n. breadfruit, artocarpus altilis, moraceae. there are some forty varieties which now extend the

season much longer than the mainly two months of harvesting in early times, march and april. the tree is native to coastal fiji which has had a large gene-pool of breadfruit. some varieties have seeds, some none, and in certain areas the seeds are eaten. fiji varieties were taken as far east as

of uto was used for cloth in coastal areas if there was little masi barkcloth . (neither was available in most of the viti levu highlands.) leaves of uto formerly used as plates. the breadfruit is sacred, totemic at vuda, not spoken of freely, though it is eaten there, which is unusual for a totemic plant. at vuda one must eat it if it is presented at a meal, and should eat the skin as well as any seeds. there, it would never be cut with a knife. syn. (west) kulu. kulu, kuru, ‘ulu or ‘uru are names that extend through polynesia. idiom: vakataba ni uto n. or v. someone who is ineffectual or unreliable, dependant on others, not to

depended upon. also to have a brief love affair that could not become a dependable, lasting relationship. (the branches of breadfruit tree are fragile and breakable). idiom: drau ni uto lutu i wai. useless (usually of a man). idiom. vuki na uto. sudden, unexpected change. when uto is roasted on a fire, it is turned around in a sudden action to avoid burning. cultivars: uto dina, round, dark green fruit, smooth skin, no seeds. balekana, excellent taste, small round fruit. bokasi, early maturing. (gives the name to wainibokasi river.) buco, long fruit, rough skin, excellent eating. koqo, small fruit, rough skin, firm flesh, no seeds.
ni idia n. j ak fruit, artocarpus heterophyllus, eaten mostly by indians. the huge fruit grow directly from the tree trunk. syn. (hindi) katari.
n. heart. modernly, the word is often used in direct translation from english as in: uto kavoro broken heart. traditionally fij ians never thought of the heart in relation to emotions.

(anglicism) n. heartwood, of a tree. uto-uto . n. green jobfish, aprion sp. uto-uto . n. float, as used for fishing lines or nets. utu, utura . v . to place end-to-end. utu buka v. to light a torch by touching it to a firebrand. utu

to furl sail. idiom: utu boko v. to chain-smoke, lit. lighting one cigarette from another, then extinguishing (boko) the butt. utu, utura . v. to shift logs or branches in a fire, better located to burn well. utu . n . path that pigs travel in the bush. these can be recognised, distinct from paths used by humans.

n. cultivated yam, dioscorea alata, a most noble starch-food for ceremonial food presentations in coastal areas. this is a strictly seasonal, annual crop planted in june or july, harvested when the vines die back, around march, the earliest ones in february. the only starch food that can be stored above
for many months without fermentation. (cassava can be kept in the ground for a time.) this
been mainly a food of the coastal areas and smaller islands and its harvest (yabaki) marked the
of the year, though years were never counted. highlanders of viti levu, certainly in the eastern
(colo isiti), have no great tradition for cultivation of yams though in modern times that is
more common. they much more often ate the wild species of yam, and taro that they
and grows much more quickly. popular early yam varieties are vurai balavu and vurai dra.
maturing varieties are uvi ni futuna, kivi, taniela vulaleka. planting of yams requires more
knowledge than most other crop s. the top section (na uluna) of the yam is cut off for planting. in a well matured yam, that can be quite thin, and it is often dried out by being placed on a
of ashes before planting. the bottom part of the yam (dromuna) is cut off where it is soft, sometimes only one cm. section, when the yam is at the right stage, and that part will be for food. the
(na kobena) supplies planting material (na vacina) that is cut off in vertical
to include a good layer of outer skin and those pieces may have a notch cut to indicate the
side that will be planted down. vacina can be no thicker than an inch or so. the inside
eaten. some farmers have the notion that a little salt on the planted mound (buke) may help the growth . some sprinkle a handful of sand so that theft of the planting material

be revealed if the sand is disturbed (and the sand itself is thought to have salt). theft can be a common problem since the planted vacina is perfectly edible. a hand can easily dip into soft earth of the planted mound. without the disturbed sand, the farmer might wait in vain for his harvest from the empty mound. uvu, uvuca v. to blow out air or tobacco smoke from the mouth or nose. me uvu na sici! blow the whistle ! (whistles were known anciently in colo west, now displayed in the museum, though

or function is not known). uvuca na biukila to blow the bugle. na dau uvu biukila the bugler. uvu bitu vakatagi (archaic) to play the nose-flute. uvu davui blow the triton trumpet-shell horn. that horn is blown at the death of polynesian chiefs, but also regularly, by fishermen returning
n. newly sprouting leaf of coconut or plantain, not yet opened.
wai n. a word unfamiliar to most fijians. harmless, and even quite friendly, the humpback

from the antarctic past new zealand, through fijian waters, then to tonga, june through august, in breeding season, before returning to the antarctic after the birth of their young in tropical waters. fij ians have seen it in coastal waters. it is capable of spectacular leaps out of the sea,
associated with giving birth to the young that may be a third the length of the mother.
fijians tend to use the word tavuto, referring to any kind of whale. though few have seen the

sperm whale, all know this as the source of the whaleteeth used as symbolic wealth for ceremonial gifts. there is no regularly used word for the pilot whales or blackfish , the much smaller whales that school in these waters but are usually seen only by sailors at sea.

n. spindle-shaped fish trap usually made of mangrove roots, by the sea. where polynesian influence is considerable, the v of fijian is often pronounced and spelled as a p or an f. thus vuaka, pig, may be heard as p uaka. fijian vale house, is f ale in tongan.
list here omits in most cases those many words with the prefix vaka (or its abbreviated form va),
an action, a verbal or adverbial form, or a similarity. those words that begin with the prefix

are listed under their root-meaning. thus vakatotolo adv., meaning fast, and vakatotolotaka, meaning hurry it up, are listed under totolo adj , fast. also, the many words beginning with vei, indicating plurality, or reciprocity, are in most cases listed

their root-word. thus veitalanoa, to yarn together, is listed under talanoa. some words combine both prefixes, as veivaka. still, in this dictionary, the word would appear under its root, not the prefixes. similarly, names of plants are often preceded by vu ni as a prefix, such as vunidakua for the dakua tree,

named by adding a prefix vua in front of the root word for the plant. vuanikau fruit. vuaniivi nuts of the polynesian chestnut. in this dictionary they would be found under the root word, not the prefix.
four. ikava fourth ; vasagavulu forty; e va na drau four hundred; vakava four times. syn. (tonga) f a.

n. eyebrow. na vacumu your eyebrow. contrast with nomu ivacu your fist. vacu toso waggling eyebrows. deguvacu to indicate agreement by raising both eyebrows slightly, usually with an expressionless face. syn. becuru.

(archaic) concubine and maidservant of chief, a term only very rarely used today but understood by many fij ians. can refer to an unmarried woman. vadi, vadiga v. to pick with the fingers, as in picking a guitar or ukelele, or to check something like food, by squeezing it between the fingers. me vadigi na qita. play the guitar. vadivadi strumming (as of a guitar).

n. pandanus pyriformis (or p. odoratissimus or p. verus) that grows in damp, coastal places,

in poor soil. fruit is edible, eaten mostly by micronesians, who have varieties best suited to that. a flour can be made from the fruit, cooked as a mash. edible nut inside very hard shell. colourful ripe fruit used in floral garlands. leaves used for weaving coarse mats. dried leaves used as
(suluka). syn. balawa. historical significance in the famous “first landing” immigration

called vadravadra, land of the original, indigenous kainadi, melanesian people, earlier settlers here. later, some of lutu ’s people settled in what is now ra province, at the mountain range nakauvadra, again named for the pandanus. legend relates that after death a man wishing to reach the
a whaletooth and hit a pandanus tree. the legend cannot precede the s, with the introduction from tonga of whaleteeth as a prestigious symbol. na sei the flowers of vadra.

n. stingray, skate. large ones may be seven feet across the wingspan, small ones just inches. they nestle in the sand, almost invisible, and if stepped on, disturbed, or caught on a line, may be dangerous
and their spike. (a very large one almost killed this author. it had been caught on a shark line from a dory .) that tail was used formerly to shape wood because of its granuated skin,

six men from a boat, usually at high tide, their leader throwing the spear. voto ni

n. spike of the stingray. kaba people provide stingray to the vunivalu of bau as traditional food, when requested. if they have offended the vunivalu, they may beg forgiveness with presentation of a stingray spike.
. (eng.) n. vine, sometimes spelled out as vu ni vaini, indicating that it refers to a plant that is a vine.
. (eng.) n. wine. few fijian ever drink wine and this word is hardly ever used outside of european hotels or restaurants. beer is the common alcoholic beverage. syn. waini.
n. several species of tree, mimosaceae family, many introduced by europeans for decorative
and urban planting, one species local, now called “bush vaivai” (vaivai ni veikau) or vaivai ni viti, serianthes melanesica. vaivai ni vavalagi usually refers to the raintree (= monkeypod tree),
saman, native to central and south america, to meters high, often planted at roadsides but invasive in dry, western parts of viti levu. favoured for carving of handicraft bowls for tourists,

also as flooring. fls white or cream to pale yellow in branched inflorescences, stamens very long and pink. woody, flattened pod to cm long with seeds embedded in pulp. similar species, albizia lebbeck, has yellow-green flowers and flat pods that lack pulp.
