. such as (when preceded by the particle me) e levu na matanitu me vakataki mereke, jamani, varanise many governments such as america, germany, france. vaka-ta-medroka v. to masturbate (of males).
depend, in this sense only:-- e na vakatau vei iko. it will depend on you (on your behaviour, your reaction, your decision).

v. to put, to put on, as in me vakatoka na kuro. put on the pot (put it on the stove or fire.) me vakatoka na wai. put on the water (put it on the stove or fire, as for making tea). vakatoka, vakatoka v. to name, give a name to. vakatokai named. vaka-totovo, vakatotovotaka v. to practice, to try out, to make a trial. vakatubu- prefix; to cause, as in vakatubu-leqa v. to cause trouble. syn. vakavu-. vakatubu n. baking powder. idiom: (slang) kua ni vakatubutaka. don ’t exaggerate, be pretentious, blow things up out of proportion. syn. “baking powder” as a verb ; syn: vakay isi-taka. yisi yeast. vaka-vu, vakavuna v. to cause. vu-na n. cause, origin. vu-vakavu n. newly invented word by language teachers to signify causation, as by the prefix vaka or va.

n. nail (carpentry), horn (cow, goat). originally, i believe, the word applied to a sharp protuberance on a warclub. ivako wiri n. drill bit. vako, vakota v. to nail (it), a modern concept, of course. vala, valata, valataka v. to fight, fight for it. era a vala mai bokanivili. they fought at bougainville.
na meca fight the enemy. valataka na yaca i viti compete, fighting for (or in) the name of fiji. na valataki ni bula galala the fighting for freedom (which is a modernism, of course.) valataki
fighting for the cup. idiom: na valataki vanua fighting for the country, representing the nation (usually in team sports these days).
(tongan palagi) as in kai valagi, european. valagi is a common abbreviation for vavalagi, polite term for european.
(lau) v. to do it, make it. syn. cakava.
n. conduct, behaviour, used today often in a negative sense. ivalavala ca bad behaviour,
referring to some specific behaviour. ivalavala kaukauwa forceful behavious, violent behavious.
n. house. vale vakaviti fijian thatched house. it is incorrect to refer to a fijian house as a bure. vale
wooden house. vale vatu (or) vale simede cement-block house. vale tabatolu three-storey building. vale vakenani lean-to, shack, camp-house, temporary house (biblical, canaan house,
shelter). vale ni wawa basi bus shelter. vale ni itukutuku maroroi n. national archives.
the housing. size of traditional houses is indicated by the number of fathoms of length, e.g., e dua na vale katu rua a house two-fathoms in length. the traditional fij ian measure katu
approx. one fathom (six feet), the span of a person ’s outstretched arms. in principal, a man provided a house for his wife, or one for each wife, where she would raise their children. normally, in

days, the man did not regularly sleep in the house of a wife. a high chief would have his own house. in the highlands, men all slept in a large bure, a men ’s house. the women and children slept quite separately. idiom: vale katu dua burial grave, lit. house six-feet in length. idiom: mate vale dua, bula vale rua. literally, you might die if you eat at only one house but you can
if there are two houses where you can get food. the implication is that you should feel comfortable eating meals or staying at a relative ’s or friend’s house. often said in good humour to one
has declined a meal. fact is, it is a social strength in fiji that a person who does not feel well

in one house of the extended family, may usually move in with an aunt or uncle or cousin where there is a more welcoming attitude. idiom: vale drauna fruit of the ivi tree, polynesian chestnut, an edible starch-food (this preciosity derives from the fact that the fruit grows almost hidden in a small bower of leaves).
n., v. toilet, to defecate (polite term).
(or) voleni (eng. fall in !) v., n. military : fall in !, also used as a noun for a parade formation. often this word is pronounced just as in english.
n. hospital, formerly known as vale ni mate, “house of illness (or) death”.
n. national archives, an old building built in in suva, originally for
printer, now with an extension. it houses old issues of newspapers and a substantial
composed of the libraries of sir alport barker, harold gatty (including books of dr. ronald gatty), and james borron snr.

ni veivesu (anglicism) n . prison. korovou is the holding prison in suva as a convenience to the courts. (it is named after the earliest but temporary prison of fij i, after gordon ’s little war.) at naboro valley, km west of suva, is the largest prison of fij i with some acres of land.
n. lavatory , out-house. the concept is introduced. fijians formerly went into the bushes or to

fij i, human excrement was normally concealed to avoid witchcraft so no one identifiable place was used as a toilet. valenivo dre n. flush toilet. valenivo keli n. pit toilet. vale ni yaya makawa n. fiji national museum, located in suva. the museum benefitted from the early care of george barker, and later, until , the leadership of fergus clunie and kate hindle. visiting research scholars are helped by the local staff who have field experience. vali, valia v. to extract with the thumb, and by pulling and pushing as in removing a mussel from its shell, or fishhook from mouth of a fish.
n. war. a ivalu! it is war ! war is begun ! na ikarua ni ivalu levu the second world war. buca ni

field of battle. idiom: toa ni ivalu warrior, champion. the concept of the rooster symbolising a warrior derives from tonga. valu, valuta v. to fight, wage war, fight for. na veivaluvaluti the fighting, battle(s), warring. na valuti ni
the combating of corruption.

v. to have a miscarriage. e a valutu o mere mary has a miscarriage. vakalutu yaloka v. of a chicken, to lay eggs. vana, vana v. to pierce, to shoot (arrow, gun) at it. vanataka na dakai to shoot the gun.
n., adj . piercing, pierced, pocked with small holes or depressions.
v., n. shooting. dau vavana marksman, shooter.
. (tonga, fana) n. mast (of boat, ship). vana-rua two-masted. may also imply antenna, as for broadcasting or reception, radio, tv or mobile phones.
. n. wooden shuttle used to pierce thatch of a house, when binding it in place.
(ni namu) . (modernism) n. mosquito spray. vanataka to spray (it).
v. to vibrate or tremble with sound, to twang, tremulo. could be the vocal chords, could be the rhythmic rumble of marching feet, or a wire strung tightly. nini suggests the notion of trembling.
n. comb. this is a “true” melanesian fij ian word, common in some regions as in burebesaga.. the
usual word today is iseru, a word of polynesian origin . vani, vania v. to comb. syn. seru, seruta. vanivani v., n. to comb (the hair), combing.
(eng.) n. varnish.

n. territory, land (but not soil itself or any specific piece of land), country, nation, place. vanua tani overseas. tauvanua (or) lewenivanua n. ordinary people, commoners, in contrast to chieftains or others of high function. na vanua o tiko kina the place where you are. na vanua cava e mosi vei iko ?

do you feel pain ? (i.e., in what place of your body?). na vanua o wailevu the territory of wailevu. the concept of a large territory (vanua) under a paramount chief is an introduced polynesian notion, first established in fiji at verata and perhaps laucala and later, by the immigration
and his people at vuda. this imposed hierarchical system enabled indirect rule by
it is convenient for purposes of national administration. m inisita ni vanua minister for home affairs. idiom: wai ni vanua n. yaqona for drinking, a term of preciosity, used pompously in speeches.
adj . traditional, customary. veiqaravi vakavanua traditional ceremony. the word can be used facetiously. asked how or where he acquired something, a modern fijian may reply vakavanua. in
words, he simply took it. fij ians may take things freely from relatives especially but also from
if the person has such things in abundance and is not carefully on guard, or is not under the chief’s protection. this may not be considered stealing.
v. to make a traditional approach , usually for something desired, as in la ’ki
go make a traditional approach for the woman to become his wife.
target_text: vakavanuataka na marama me la ’ki watina

source_text: n. food supplies for a voyage, “viaticum” (in latin terminology, as used in english). christian
speak of ivaqa vakayalo, their notion of inspirational quotations from the bible. they see this as food for the soul.
(slang) to show off, put on airs impetuously.
n. search. vaqara, vaqara v. to search for, investigate.
n. investigation. vaqe n. taro suckers that grow by the mother plant. these are better planting material than the cut tops of the taro corm, which yield a root that is truncated flat.
abbrev. of vaka oqo, like this.
v. to do it like this.
n. young sprouting coconut. the spongy inside of the nut is a sweet delicious food eaten raw or
over a fire. that spongy material replaces the water and flesh inside the coconut as it starts to sprout and form roots.
adj . deaf. syn. didi vara, didi.
(eng.) n. verandah.
n ., adj . france, french.
. n. onion, an introduced vegetable, greatly liked by fijians but almost all imported, not grown locally. there are also some unimportant indigenous plants bearing this name.
. n., adj . (eng.) brass. vaivo varasa brass pipe. metali varasa or varasa bronze medal (in competitive sports).
n. scale(s), of fish. vari, varia v. to scale (a fish). na varivari ika the scaling of fish.
n. ringworm, red fungal lesions on the body, usually of children. pharmacists usually suggest
cream. some fijians treat with external application of macerated papaya leaves, which are
(and can be used as a meat tenderiser.)
n. edible fish with delicious white flesh, humphead wrasse, giant wrasse, cheilinus undulatus,
a heavy snout and a huge hump over the head, and very large, tough scales (hence the fijian name), and sharp, powerful fused teeth. though it is carniverous it has not been readily caught by
and line, but by spear or fish poison. usually found in reef passages and crevices but now rare.
grow to seven feet in length, weighing several hundred pounds, body colour greenish. range is

to impose. syn. (burebesaga) dagava; ulurua (a name shared with another species, a parrotfish chlorurus microrhinos), varevoce (as listed by rob wright.) varo, varota v. to saw. kabani ni varovaro lumber company, timber mill. varovaroa rough, unplaned, of wood, planks, bumpy of skin, as of some breadfruit. de ni varo n. sawdust. varomusu, varomusuka v. to saw across the grain (rather than with the grain) of the wood.
(or) vakarota v. to order, to command (that something be done). direct orders bluntly stated are not characteristically fij ian unless the person in command is extremely angry.
(ni kau) n. saw. ivaro gata n. sharp saw.

adj . rough to the touch, as of skin (shark, some breadfruit varieties), bark of a tree. vasa . n. white muscle of the vasua giant clam, delicious raw. no point in cooking it. the black mantle is very tough and is best minced and heavily marinated if it is eaten at all.
. (or) vasa damu n. small shrub, euphorbia fidjiana, often planted at the border of gardens to
it from spirits and from human theft. it is no longer very effective as protection against theft
it is still usually planted. red purple stems and leaves, with bright pink flowers that begin blooming in early december. syn. vasa kinikini, rewa.

. n. medium-sized, soft-wood tree to meters of the shore and bush, cerbera manghas, apocynaceae, leaves dark and glossy green, with white fragrant flowers ( cm diam.), sometimes pinkish centre, growing at tip of branches, used for garlands. fruits egg-shaped, reddish, dark purple or black when mature, to inches in diam. white poisonous latex . syn. (lau, west, rakiraki) rewa. (polyn.) reva or leva. vasi, vasiga v. to scrape off, clean off the surface or skin of food, such a grilled starch-food. can include skimming off slime from a seafood.

(or) masawe (or) qai n. the “ti” plant (ti is a polynesian name), cordylene terminalis or c. fruticosa, agavaceae. now mainly a decorative garden plant. the corm of a tall indigenous, greenleafed wild var. was used as a source of sugar after being cooked in the earth oven for a few days.
is a red-leafed ornamental variety with a polynesian name. syn. masawe, (lau, nadro, west) qai. (kadavu) kokoto or masawe.
v. to take a step and slip down from slippery or unsteady footing. syn. tidara.

. (modernism) n. a person from outside a village who has married a person of the village in question. in this modern sense, it usually refers to the person of outside origin who does not live in the village, but may include the spouse if the outsider is a man. today such an outsider is expected
to contribute money and goods for village purposes. formerly, a couple almost always settled in the village of the man.
. n. traditionally, in the mother’s village of origin, it is the offspring who are called vasu and they

make demands for services or goods from the village, especially from their mother's brothers (momo), who might be addressed as momo or mudrau (abbrev. of kemudrau a polite form of “you”.) formerly, chiefs had extraordinary vasu powers to make demands. this custom of making such demands is falling into disuse to have his children recognized and accepted in their mother's village, a
(kerosene, food, mats) and whales' teeth for a ceremony called kau na mata

gone ("bringing the children's face”). today the tendency is to bring several siblings at the same time, often waiting for years till some of them are virtual adults. the children must not be seen at the village until the ceremony is performed. na cauravou oqo e vasu ki bau. this youth ’s mother is from

island. e vasu ivei o iko ? to what place are you vasu? i.e., what village does your mother come from? vasu, vasuta v. to ask for (something), as in the kerekere custom, where it is virtually impossible to be refused. a special form of demand is that of the traditional vasu (see above) who could in former times, take anything from the maternal uncle without even asking for it. a chiefly child might make very great demands. remnants of this custom persist. vasua or vasua dina n. giant clam, tridacna derosa. e dua na matau vasua ten vasua clams offered at a

food presentation. sa dala tu na vasua. the vasua is agape. qarauni iko de qamuti iko na vasua. be careful lest the vasua clamp on you. (it is a real danger. one came close to killing this author.) vasa muscle of the vasua, delicious part, usually eaten raw. the black mantle is very tough
the cega, the fluted giant clam, t. squamosa, and the katavatu, the rugose giant clam, t. maxima.
. n. shelf (usually in a house, office or copra shed). vatanivola n. bookshelf.
. together. lako vata v. to go together ; salavata v. to travel together. kalavata matching (in colour, as with clothes). vata kei au together with me.
. same, as in kaivata fellow countryman. tautauvata same, equal, flat, even .
(archaic) n. alternatively navatanitawake, name of house-site (yavu) for a large building
mai bulu, as a human manifestation of this ancestral god. vueti was also referred to as ko mai vatanitawake. after the tui kaba became dominant, after over-throwing the roko tui bau raiwalui,
also used to serve the kaba god of war, cagawalu. the vatanitawake was destroyed in when tanoa was being restored as vunivalu. tanoa replaced the building. cakobau was installed
same year. calvert published an illustration of the temple drawn in the s.
at kaba point in , when forces of the king of tonga defeated rewa and the bauan dissidents.
v. to imagine, to concentrate on or set one ’s mind to (something).
n. riddle, puzzle. vati, vatia v. to lash together, as of reeds for a fish-fence or wall of a fij ian house. the items so lashed are usually long and thin.
n. small medicinal epiphyte, phymatodes scolopendria, polypodiaceae. in lau and cakaudrove
or boreti, which has edible young fronds and grows in brackish swamps according to j. parham.
n. blessing and good wishes, usually expressed by a host who is receiving a formal presentation
in an isevusevu ceremony that introduces the guest. also veivatonaki. before drinking, it
also been custom to express good wishes, as for a fair wind, for a guest’s safe return. spitting has been part of this formality, a custom now falling into disuse.
. n. stone, rock. veivatu stony (of a piece of land). vale vatu concrete-block house. matau vatu
(adze was the only form of stone axe), as a n. or adj . today it usually refers impolitely to
villagers considered ignorant and backward by the younger generation. stone axes were
to viti levu highlanders. na uluvatu the rock-face (cliff), or promintory. bearing
as a name, there is a village in waidina district, naitasiri province, and some tribes as in
and the islands tuvuca, cicia, and vanua vatu in lau province. there is an amazingly

dispersed diaspora of nauluvatu people. none remained at village nauluvatu. syn. (kadavu) solo. vatu(ni-yayani) . (anglicism) n. iron for ironing clothes, sheets. vatu livaliva n . electric iron. yayanitaka to iron (clothes, sheet).
v, to cause trouble, create bad feelings.

v. to turn over (person being given massage, of some object to turn it over, to turn it upside down.) cu v. to show one ’s bottom. vatuka, vatukana v. to shape, give form to, as in arranging the hair or setting the sail of a boat.
adj . well shaped. vatukaica badly shaped. vatukailailai shaped small. vatukailevu of large form or shape, big in appearance.
n. form, outcome, appearance. vakavatukana-taka v. to fulfill. vakavatukanataka na nona gagadre. to fulfill his/her wishes.
n. (archaic) stone sinker perforated in the middle, used to weight down a drag net in
river fishing. these are the only known stone artefacts of the viti levu highlanders, a
who were essentially pre-stone age in culture. such fishing in the highlands was mostly for
loa cestraeus picatilis, and was a boisterous community effort that might involve more than one village. it is not known if these stones were ever made in pre-european times.
ni ceva (archaic) n. special stone that was used to call up a favourable wind, notably at beqa island, and levuka. vatu ni sakuku stones used to transmit leprosy (sakauku in some western speech),
adj . stony, of a piece of land or small island.
adj . (anglicism) rich, influental. this derives from a fanciful notion of wealthy people having jewels as precious stones vatu talei, a foreign concept to fij ians.
n. shoulder. taba-na arm, limb, of a person, wing of a bird or aeroplane.
n. native hibiscus shrub or small tree that grows near the shore, hibiscus tiliaceus, malvaceae, the

as a fibrous cord, and as a dye, and as a filtering sponge when mixing kava, and in coastal areas was formerly used for the brief fringe-skirt worn by women. flowers are yellowish with maroon centre. in farming, this small tree is sometimes used as living fence or as a windbreak. there is a
variety, vau leka, that grows to only about m. and has darker green, lobed leaves. the taller var., to m. height, is called vau balavu. upper leaves of the short var. are applied externally, shiny
against the skin, to alleviate sprains and swelling of arms or legs. leaves are often used as
paper. the wood is very light, burns easily, and used to be used as a base for making fire by friction. syn. f au (tonga, samoa, tahiti).

n. (archaic) turban of thin fine barkcloth formerly worn only by some chiefs. missionaries eliminated the custom. vakaivauvau adj . wearing a turban. the custom has been revived only for the installation of a few high chiefs.

. n. cotton shrub, gossypium hirsutum (one variety native to the south pacific), or g. barbadense, two -chromosome american species. cotton grows only around present or past human settlements. it is quite possible that some variant of cotton was an aboriginal introduction from america brought back by early polynesians. it extends right up into the highlands of viti levu. the
is used by coastal fij ians (not melanesian highlanders) for stuffing soft pillows (lokoloko),
is an introduced polynesian concept, not known to early fij i melanesians. the chewed leaves
applied medicinally to wounds and sores. vauvau ni valagi is the term often used for the

cotton varieties, gossypium arboreum, a -chromosome species from asia, was introduced by europeans. commercial growing of cotton in fiji ceased by with revival of cotton production in the u.s.a ., after the american civil war.

. (rewa, suva, colo east, namosi) n. regional syn. for bele, a common green cultivated vegetable, abelmoschus manihot. vauvau . n. introduced kapok tree and its “cotton”, ceiba pentandra, bombacaceae that grows in coastal areas. fij ians never plant it but occasionally use the “cotton” to stuff pillows.
. n. cotton wick (for kerosene lamp or stove), mantle (coleman lamp).
n. board, as in vava ni yayani n. ironing board, vava ni savasava n. washing board. around nasavusavu i heard this as p ap a.
n. shoe(s). ivava ni cici n. track shoes. ivava laca n. canvas shoes.
n. a wild species of ginger family, alpinia spp. zingiberaceae, with broad leaves, to feet height,
a favoured food of pigeons and parrots. flowers and fruiting clusters appear at the top of the plant near the leaves, above the tall bare stem.
n. woman who is occasionally possessed by a spirit, and through whom the spirit speaks. this is still all quite real to some fij ians, and a common occurence.
n., v. to carry piggyback. rau a veivava toka o seru kei na buna. seru ’s grandmother was carrying seru on her back. vava! or vava mai! climb on (my back) ! vava, vava v. to carry on one’s
(especially babies).
n. slipper crayfish, rather flat, lacking antenae. paribacus. there are many regional synonyms.
v. to reach a place. e ratou sa vavaca yani na sau tabu. they (few) have reached the sau tabu.

n. cultivar of dalo, known and highly favoured from ancient times. it has small corms, divided in two. the colour is a little yellow, and the taste and texture magnificent. young fijians may not know of this.
n. congregation (church), gathering of people. for fijians this is now a very major social grouping that involves strong allegiance to their denomination.
n., adj . thickness, thick, of solid things (timber, cardboard, metal sheet, etc.), not liquids.
(tongan palagi) n. european place overseas. kaivalagi white person.

n. blackboard. syn. vavanivolavola. j oke n. chalk. vavi, vavia v. to roast (formerly only in earth oven lovo), usually taro, yam, breadfruit, pork, chicken, fish, palusami. this is done by men, most often these days on the sabbath, or for some feast. before modern
the earth oven was unknown in the highlands of fij i. vavi moce bake overnight in the earth oven. eratou a vavavi. they (few) did some baking. na vavavi keke cake-baking, the baking of

(not an early custom of fiji). vavi kulikuli v. to bake (root crop) with the skin on. kuli-na n. skin. vaya! (slang) an interj ection: yeah, maybe ! might happen ! could be ! there may be an element of disbelief in this interjection.
adj . overly ripe and soft, of a breadfruit (uto). veata or kotia n. sea-hare, an edible creature of the reef, seen on sale at the suva market. unsightly when
open but exquisite in taste, usually eaten raw. dolabella auricularia (d. auriculata?) and perhap s
species. the usual one is somewhat greenish in colour and another type is dark-coloured, called
or kotia-ika. syn. (nadro.) baga, kosia. (kadavu) samu. (lau) mone. (nayau) qaqawe. at nayau island this is the seasonal, annually harvested “balolo ” celebrated locally.
v. to flatter, or “butter up” someone. there are several synonyms. vecu. vecuka v. to kill an octopus (kuita) by turning its head inside out. requires great experience, with
octopi to three feet in length. it can be dangerous. the octopus does not cooperate. it has a sharp beak. veiba, veiba-taka v. to dispute, argue, oppose.

v., n. to wrestle, wrestling, a very minor former fijian sport, mostly polynesian in origin, now forgotten. veibo liga “indian” wrestling with the hand to contest strength of the arm. vei . to or from, as in solia vei au give it to me. vei . of (or) among (as of people), as in e dua vei rau one of the two of them.
. as a prefix, indicating collectivity or plurality : veikau forest, bush. ena veiloga ni dalo in the taro
(in the gardens).
. prefix indicating all, each and every one: ena veisiga every day. ena veigauna kece at all times.
veimotoka kece all motor-cars. na veikoronivuli kece all the schools. a multiplicity may be indicated by repeating the vei, as in ena vei-vei-gauna kece. at all the many times.

. prefix indicating interaction or reciprocity. veivacu boxing (punching). veimaliwai n. social ambiance, human environment. veimau v. play for stakes, as in gambling. veicai v. to have sex together, a blunt word, but perhaps socially acceptable in certain contexts. (veicai is a swear word). keirau sa veikilai. we (two) are known to each other, know each other, have already met each other. erau veilomani. they () love each other.
. prefix indicating a relationship, such as family relation, as in veitinani mother and child(ren)
father and child(ren) veitacini brothers or sisters, of the same sex . veiwekani related,
(people). na veiwatini the married couple(s).
. prefix, indicating a change. veisau, veisautaka v. to change. noqu veisau n. my change (usually

(and sometimes, implicitly the notion of reform). -vei . where? e vei? where? (where is something, someone). o lako maivei? where do you come from? where have you been? kivei? to where? idiom: mai vei! no way ! out of the question ! -vei . whom (preceded by ki - or mai-, indicating a direction to or from, as in kivei to (person named) as in addressing a letter. maivei from (person), as on an envelope. -vei . how (preceded by e-), as in vaka-evei? how is it going? what about it? what ’s up? vakaivei na veidigidigi? what about the election? how is the election going? (the prefix vaka is often abbreviated as va.) vei-(verb)-yaki this way and that way, here and there, as in veilakoyaki to go here and there, veiqaloyaki
swim around here and there. vei-raiyaki to look here and there.

opposite, across from (in location). e toka veibasai kei na sitoa. it is located opposite the store. veibasai kei na cowiri ni liga ni kaloko. counter-clockwise. ibasa n. may refer to a person holding a corresponding position on an opposing team.
v. to become separated, of a married couple. veisere v. to divorce.
(archaic) n. cat’s cradle, string figure made in the hands, a girl ’s game of yore.
opposite each other. see donuya.
v., n. idiom: to compete fiercely. dresu to tear up. qanibulu coconut husk.
brackish, of water. syn. tovutovula. veileti v., n. dispute. veileti na hindu kei ira na itaukei. dispute of the hindu(s) with the (many) native fijians.
n., adj . half. ena ikarua ni veimama in the second half (sports). veimama na lima half past
(o’clock).
n., v. game, as in playing cards such as poker, bridge, or for chess, checkers. veimau(ilavo) gambling for money , as with cards or games of chance.

v, n., adj . to be competitive, sometimes said in an unfavourable context. suva kei nadi na veiqatitaka na bilo ni farebrother. suva and nadi will compete for the farebrother cup. veisau, veisautaka v. to change, exchange.
n. change, exchange (often referring to a change of clothes, or change meaning money).
v. divided, especially of people not in agreement.
v. to divorce. tasere separated, of a couple (but also to come untied, of a cord or binding). veibiu v. to become separated, of a married couple. see veibiu.
no matter ! it is a matter of no concern. just as one wishes. vakaveitalia any way, any which way, casually, without due concern.
v. to relate as friends (itau). the implication may be that of boyfriend or girlfriend in a romantic sense.
see tauvu.

n. type of wild yam, often preferred. veiwali n. v. joke. au sega ni veiwali tiko ena tikina oqo i am not joking about this matter. joking is a strong characteristic of most fijian conversation. no conversation proceeds long without some quip or witticism. idiom: veiwali vakanavaga to fight instead of pleasantly joking with horse-play. lit. to joke like the

of navaga. village navaga in magodro district, ba province is peopled by highlanders of colo west, defeated by bau ’s troops and exiled to koro island where they established a village also called navaga. like most viti levu highlanders they have been tough fighters.
n., v . sexual intercourse (correct and polite term). lit., to come together. veka! . (vulgar) exclamation of surprise, usually pleasurable.
. n. excrement ; disgusting mess. veveka rust. ivekaveka n. anus. idiom: vakamici na gone qai veka. treat someone nicely then they treat you badly. lit. have a child urinate then the child defecates.
. v. to defecate (ordinary term, polite enough). vekabiu v. to leave a disgusting mess, specifically in failing to clean up and put things away after use.
(or) vela vela expression of surprise, mild disgust, or disbelief at what is asserted.

. adj . tasteless, of food or of a person ’s behaviour. velavela ! . awful ! (reproaching someone's behaviour, often jocularly), disgusting. tone of voice indicates the degree of displeasure. veleko n. hard, polished part of a tool or weapon, tradionally a stone or shell, modernly a metal surface or blade. (no such tools existed in the highlands.)
(eng.) n. plate. veleti kava tin plate (usually enameled metal, made in china). syn. disi n. dish.
n. porcelain dish.

n. type of fijian forest gremlin , very short, and very strong, with long unkempt hair. they may play tricks on people but are never evil. their yaqona is supposed to the the yaqoyaqona (in fact a virtually
weedy shrub), and their coconut the niu sawa. to some fijians they are quite real and are
as still seen and encountered. they are associated particularly with highlanders of colo east in viti levu, especially at serea, solo-ira. they have been reported around wainadoi in recent years.

clearing parts of the forest for planting, workers have called out to the veli, asking politely for their permission. see leka, a different kind of legendary dwarf in fiji though not having extraordinary strength, eccentric features or any unusual behaviour. may refer to earlier memories of a pygmy people.
n. rowboat, dory. this may be propelled with a pole, or by sculling with one oar, a technique learned from europeans.
adv. as in duka veluvelu extremely dirty.
v. to play with sex organs. lauan vakatamemeno.

(eng.) van, now sometimes referring to almost any commercial vehicle (but not a bus). small truck s may be called veni. large truck s are called lori (lorry). veno, venoka v. to bore a small hole, as on shells to string a necklace. see qiva. venu, venuka v. to clear one ’s nose of mucus by squeezing with the fingers. fij ians did not use handkerchiefs of any sort. see wadruca.
n . trap, literally, but often referring to trickery. idiom: vere vakabau typical bauan trick of deception and treacherous behaviour for which they are infamous.
v. to deceive, trick, betray (people).
adj . complicated (any situation, problem), entwined or entangled (rope, cordage). syn. (lau) f ij ia. idiom: lako vaka-vereverea have affair(s) outside of marriage.
n. decorative arm-band or ankle-band of vegetation worn by dancers, or by chiefs on ceremonial occasions. made of barkcloth, the vesa vakavanua is in some places tied ceremonially on the arm of a
being installed. for dancers, the vesa is often strung together or woven leaves, often of the ti
sp., discarded after the one-time use. syn. (tonga) vesa. vesa, vesa or vesana v., adj . deliberately to expose to the sun, as in ika vesa fish that has been smoked
over a open fire; can apply to sunbathing, exposure of a person to the sun. sun-dried fish is first salted before drying and has a lighter texture than smoked fish.

n. noble tree-timber of the forest, intsia bijuga, caesalpinaceae, used for large boats, yaqona bowls, war clubs. the wood does not float. it is one of the useful plants with symbolic significance for some
especially of eastern fiji. many tongans came to eastern fiji to build boats with this timber.

the arts of building ocean-going vessels. the tree grows at beach and coastal forests below m. fls white or yellow turning purple, to cm diam., one showy petal, falling easily. pods flat x cm, - seeds, orange, mealy inside. idiom: sa ciri saka na vesi! good night ! said only to a paramount chief of eastern fiji. the implication is that of the chief’s canoe, made of vesi timber, would be drifing off from shore.
wai n. seashore timber tree, milleta pinnata, fabaceae (formerly pongamia pinnata, papilionaceae),

samoa, superficially similar to the vesi intsia bijuga, though unrelated. vesi wai is a very dense wood. pink fls, cm diam., pods in clusters, peaked apices. seasonally, may lose all its leaves. syn. (lau) vesivesi. vesu, vesuka . v. to capture (escaped prisoner), tackle (rugby). na veivesu the tackling (rugby). vale ni

n. prison. kaivesu n. prisoner. vesu, vesuka . v. to bind, tie up firmly. ivesu n. bundle. ivesu dalo bundle of dalo. veta n. as in na veta icake the upper hands of bananas in a bunch, which are the best ones. this can be

to people na veta icake are the uppermost, influential or important people. na veta ira the lower ones, the lower classes of people. vetao or vetau n. tree, mammea odorata, clusiaceae, sap was used by fijians to dye their hair an orangebrown colour. p. geraghty says that vetau is an ancient word for the related dilo tree, calophyllum inophyllum.
n. type of edible worm that lives in the sand, siphonosoma spp. or sipunculis spp. may be eaten raw. syn. vurai. see ibo.

adj . crooked, bent. a veiveveyaki na sala eratou muria. the path they followed was winding and curved. e veiveveyaki na kava ni vale ni oti na cagilaba. after the hurrican , the corrugated roofing iron of the house was cooked and bent.
n. rust (a concept unknown till the introduction of metal). a word derived from veka excrement. syn. (lau) umea.
adj . sad-looking, sorrowful, close to tears. vaka-mata-veveku glum.
(eng.) february. traditionally the first month of harvest for yams. first-fruit tribute (isevu) is offered to chief and church. syn. (archaic) vula i isevu.
n. manta ray, huge and harmless, unafraid and beautiful in motion. the word may be unknown to many fijians. syn. lelebo, vaivukivuki.
. v. to want (followed by a verb) au via lako. i want to go. au via kana. i want to eat. (but au
i want it.) viavia levu pretentious, wanting to be important. syn. (west) mata.
. almost, nearly or tending to be, as in via loaloa almost black.
. should be, or needs to be done. sa via bulu na benu. the garbage should be buried.
. n. swamp taro, very large edible plant with starchy corm, cyrtosperma chamissonis, araceae,
in wet, lowlands areas, a specialty of rewa but also in relatively dry areas like vanua balavu island, where it is a staple. though not a prized food of most fijians, this is a specialty of rewa,
people know the right stage of harvest, and best cooking techniques – not a simple matter. it
as a “true food” (kakana dina), but is not considered a prestigious presentation food for ceremonial feasts. not widely sold at the markets. syn. via kana, via kau.
mila (or) via gaga n. alocasia macrorrhiza, araceae, plant with starchy corm, usually considered
shortage, by islanders who know how to treat it to become edible.
target_text: inedible except in times of extreme

source_text: . n. a small decorative plant in sandy, coastal areas, grown in lines near dwellings, crinum asiaticum, amarillidaceae. the long leaves are a shiny green on a stout stem, the flowers graceful and white. shiny white sections of the leaves have been used by europeans as trolling lures. trolling is not a native practice of early fijians. it was mostly a specialty of samoa.
. (before an adjective or noun) very nearly, almost, tending to be, wanting to be. viavia loaloa very nearly black . viavia turaga acts pretentiously like a chief (though he is not).
adj . pretentious.
. how many, how much (in a question). preceded by an “e” at the beginning of a sentence. e vica na kena isau? what is the price? lewe vica ? (or) e vica na tamata ? how many people?
. a few, several (may appear as a separate word or as a suffix). me toni bogi vica ena wai. let it
a few days in water. eratou levica ga. they are only a few people. e vica ga. only a few.
the house with serveral storeys.
a few times, several times. vakavica ? how many times?
n. flesh, as of meat, in contrast to fat (uro). in early times this applied only to pigs, where the flesh is not usually marbled. pork and fish were the only large mammals in the diet.
n. several species of large grass, especially erianthus maximus. as a bush food, the small fruit may
eaten rather like a tiny duruka fruit (“fijian asparagus”). totemic plant of some of the waimaro
people and iconic name for some people of dravo, tailevu. vico leaves have been commonly used as thatching for houses.
n. navel, belly-button. syn. (tonga) p ito. vida, vida, vidaka v. to split, split up, split apart (wood, coral, piece of food, marriages, partnership s),
up (land sub-division, writing into sections). kua ni balata na ikelekele vakaveitalia de kavia
lase. don ’t throw the anchor any which way, lest the coral be broken up. na vidavidai the splitting up, the dividing up.
split up. sa vidavidai tu na vanua the territory is divided up (into many parts). the verb
would imply a deliberate division with a notion of sharing (though the shares might be quite unequal for some acceptable reason.)

v. to spring out suddenly, water from a leak, blood from a wound, an animal from hiding. jumping may be implied, and/or a sudden sound such as a clicking or ticking. idiom: vaka e vidi na ura conveys the notion of something that jumps suddenly into action, as the prawn does.

n. feast on the fourth night after a burial. the implication is that by this time worms (ulo) will be jumping around the buried body. (this entry is suggested by rosiana lagi of moala.) vidi, vidika v. to flick with the fingers, finger pressured against the thumb, suddenly released, as against the ear of a child in punishment. may refer to snapping the fingers, as in getting someone’s attention. idiom: vidika na yadremu! wake up your mind ! (usually accompanied by a flicking gesture of the finger against one’s own forehead), coming suddenly to a realisation.

. v. clicking or flicking noise, as in era vidividi na daniva. the sardines are skipping at the surface, making a clicking noise as they try to evade their predators. prawns also make such a clicking noise.
. n. common square board-game of wood with counters that are flicked. a women ’s game,
precursor of this modern game, often used segments of reed that were flicked to a distance. syn. veividi.
n. (medical) ulcerous sore. “vidio” (or) “video” (eng.) n. video (pronounced just as in english). rental of videotapes has been
among fijians and a significant substitute for the cinema. videotapes are usually referred to as tep i. dvd discs have largely replaced the tapes. pirating has been prevalent.
(eng.) n. arithmetic, calculation. vika kau tani subtraction. vika soqoni addition. vika vakalevutaki multiplication. vika wase division. vika kakavorovoro fractions.
n. whirlwind, whirlpool, a word now sometimes used figuratively. whirlwind can destroy a boat or
n., v. traditional fire-walking of beqa island. feet of locals are impervious to heat of the hot
said to be recompense for sparing the life of a certain spirit rere that had been caught by their ancestors. outsiders may be invited to join it, unharmed, but very few do so. this act is now largely
entertainment for tourists. science has not yet determined how it is that the firewalkers’ feet are
when they walk on the stones. there is no good explanation for this phenomenon. when

stand still on the stones the feet are protected by a layer of green vegetation. these are special stones, considered sacred. one speculation is that a very thin layer of ash separates the stones from the feet, serving as a kind of insulation. firewalkers freely invite foreigners to join them, holding their hands to prevent a fall. this author has not accepted the invitation. vili, vilika v. to gather, of certain foods such as wi fruit, dawa, ivi (polynesian chestnuts), mature coconuts, mango, and mussels or small clams. mai vilivili! come, pick them up ! idiom: vili wi vakaca to be beaten by a large margin in some sport or game, lit. to gather wi fruit unsuccessfully.
good. vinaka vakalevu very good. it is a modernism that these words have also come to mean a simple thank you, and thank you very much, following european custom. in ceremonial speech, trad.
and appreciation but traditionally they never said vinaka “thank you” in
target_text: fijians do say words of praise

source_text: a simple and direct manner, though malo might be said by a lauan. appreciation of a substantial

a gift was, and still is, properly indicated by a few soft clap s of the cupped hands, usually done from a seated position, or with a bowed back. gifts may very often be taken for granted as if they were
so that gratitude would be superfluous. verbal expression of appreciation or gratitude is
considered necessary for simple acts of giving. in some sense, the ceremonial words a muduo
indicate acceptance and appreciation in very formal circumstances. syn. (bua, vanualevuiloma) re, as in bula re (= bula vinaka) good day ! hello !
(west) good, thank you. vina du riki thank you very much.
n. thanking, thanks.
(anglicism) v. to thank.
(eng.) n. vinegar. vinakata v. to desire, wish for. syn. gadreva.

(eng. pinafore) n. dress (as female clothing). viri, viria v. to tie up, set up, throw together, establish , as of a fence, bamboo raft, type of bridgecrossing, or a defence. viri, virika, viritaka v. to throw (usually a stone) at person, animal, house. fijians throw with great
from long experience. usually, stones are thrown from a position of concealment. stones

thrown at houses or cars of people with whom there is dispute. for the throwing of sticks or clubs, the word kolotaka applies, not virika. virika na tamata to throw at the person. viritaka na vatu to throw the stone. viriviri throwing (things, usually stones). viriba, viribataka v. to set up fencing, as around a garden, to keep out pigs. lit., throw up or tie up viri a fence ba. idiom: viribai v. to get ready for imminent war, setting up defenses, specifically war fences around a settlement.
v. to establish, enact, as in lawa virikotori act of parliament.

v. to throw it forcefully (stone, ball). viritaki uma shot-put (athletics). idiom: sa viritaki na kena vatu. it is already decisively rejected, lit. a stone has already been thrown at it. can also mean that the decision has been made to quit something, such as a game. a child may
a stone and throw the stone into the bushes to indicate that he is quitting a game. the notion is that if you found the stone he would be forced to stay. actually, nobody much would try to find it.
n. spider. lawalawa suggests the spider’s web as netting. visa, visa v. to burn hot, of a fire, cause the flame to rise, build up a fire by adding wood. cakobau ’s
tanoa earned the name visawaqa for burning boats of the roko tui bau raiwalui at vuna, taveuni island.

n. mangrove heron, small, dark, secretive, difficult to observe, common on most coastal areas of islands, excluding yasawa archipelago and southern lau. solitary nests, to pale blue eggs. syn. (rewa, kadavu) sako. viti, vitika . v. to push apart (vegetation) to peer ahead, in the bush. this is sometimes said to be the

of the fij ian name "viti" for fiji, "fij i" being the english spelling for the tongan pronounciation of viti. viti, vitika . v. to break something. vitika na taba ni kau. break the branch of the tree. ka viti broken.
n. seven. syn. (tonga) f itu. tini ka vitu . vitusagavulu ka dua .
n. umbrella. original proto-polynesian form of the word meant fan-palm, and ip iu still does mean
n. shellfish. qa ni vivili shell of the shellfish. la ’ki vivili go gather shellfish. koda, koda na vivili
shellfish. gunu, gunuva na vivili eat cooked shellfish (gunu drink). freshwater shellfish are not eaten raw. vivili tebe i rua bivalve shellfish (lit. “two-lips”).
good, better (plural or emphatic form) e vica na ivacu vivinaka a few very good (better) punches.
several sp. of edible river fish, mudfish, eliotris spp. vo loa a somewhat darker coloured vo.

n., v. remainder, what is left over, to be left over. na kena vo what is left over. sa vo e dua. there is still one more, one remaining. na vovo ni yago-na the remains of his/her body. na ivovo that which is
over, the remains. vale ni vo n. toilet, lavatory , out-house. the concept of an outhouse was
by europeans. fij ians formerly used the bush and usually concealed their excrement, mostly from fear of witchcraft. leaves or reeds were the only toilet paper.
(archaic) n. field, usually abandoned that is held under certain property rights, that may now be forgotten, left aside.
except, except only, excepting, excluding. see vo.

v. leave some. me vakavo na sucu! leave some of the milk ! (don ’t drink it all !). vakavo, vakavoca v. to exclude, to leave out. kau kece na ika lelevu vakavoca na ika lalai me baca. take all the big fish and leave the small fish as bait. vobo n. wild and semi-cultivated medicinal shrub or small tree, mussaenda raiatensis, the branch-bark and
an infusion especially for children to drink. syn. bovo. it is easily identified by
conspicuous very large white calyx tube that has the appearance of huge flower petals. flowers, less conspicuous, are yellow.

v., adj . wrecked, as of a boat crashed on the reef. kama voca completely burnt. voce, vocea v. to row or paddle (boat). vocea to row it. vocera to paddle (to a place). fijians paddle facing the bow, traditionally using only one oar and no rowlock. it was actually paddling. they never
with two oars. they still do not favour the european custom of rowing facing the stern.
ivoce (archaic) n. canoe song, usually sung by only two people, in rhythm with the movement of oars a specialty of the yasawa archipelago.

n. paddle or oar for rowboat, blade of aeroplane propellor or electric fan. voci, vocia v. to peel a skin-fruit (with the hands, as with banana, plantain, citrus), when the peel slip s off easily. idiom: voci vakavudi to relate everything fully and clearly. let is all out, speaking freely. lit. to peel off the skin as with plantain, easily and completely.
n. puffer fish that contains deadly poison to be removed before eating, but best avoided by the novice.
n. anus. syn. icici.
adj . shallow, of a pool, lagoon. also modernly, figuratively shallow, as of discourse, argument, the mind.
v. to fail to penetrate, usually of a spear, knife, arrow, nail, but may be used figuratively: tamata e

na vosa. person(s) to whom words have no effect, fail to penetrate his/her/their mind(s). syn. sega ni coba. highlanders of vitilevu were made by their priests to believe they were invulnerable to weapons. they used the word vodivodi for that invulnerability. it gave them courage and helped them be fearless in war. vodo, vodoka v. to board (boat, bus, car), mount (horse).
n. fare to pay for passage on bus, boat, aeroplane. vakavodo, vakavodoka v. to put on board (boat, bus, etc.). vodre n. grasshopper. this is a sacred or symbolic animal of batiki chiefs of verata.
n. a cultivated shrub, pandanus sp., leaves used for weaving mats. propagation: grows best in
areas around damp soil. roots are removed from the corm, which is planted shallow. later

suckers should be removed if plant is to grow tall, with long leaves. plants are often knocked over when four or five feet tall to encourage more rooting, and longer leaves. leaves are cut, boiled in water, then sun-dried. the thorny leaf-edges are stripped off (toci) with a shell (kai), or a knife. smoothed, the leaves are often then coiled for storage, sale or transport. unlike mats made of sedge (kuta), voivoi mats can be washed repeatedly in water. voivoi ni valagi introduced varieties, green
striped or streaked with yellow or white, some with no leaf thorns. voivoi may be listed
p . caricosus, p. thurstoni, p. joskei (all endemic to fiji), or p . whitmeeanus, which is the most
prized species for weaving mats. p. whitmeeanus probably originated in vanuatu and was
aboriginally to fiji. voivoi was not formerly grown in the highlands of viti levu, where
leaves are spoken of as being one buto. approximatel one buto of voivoi is needed to
(idavodavo).

n. low tide. sa kui vakaukauwa na voka the outgoing tide flows swiftly. sa gole na voka. the tide has turned. sa tekivu di sobu na mati. the tide has begun to fall. na vokavoka the tidal movement. vokai n. forest gecko, gecko vorax the babies hatch unattended. i found a baby one, five inches long,
month of may on the lower branches of a tree. their feet with adhesive discs help them climb. in captivity they can be encouraged to eat by hand feeding. they accept finely cut fruit, wet leaves and
of hibiscus (se-ni-toa), and wet leaves of the bele vegetable. with gentle handling, vokai become accustomed to humans but their bite is very painful and they have an edgy temperament. they
found from three inches in length to inches. they can move with startling speed to avoid danger, or to catch an insect. viti levu highlanders frequently ate them after grilling (tavu) over fire
seen a vokai. similarly, the iguana is almost never seen due to predation
(eng.) n. bucket. (anglicism) tekea na vokete to kick the bucket, to die.
v. to shift direction suddenly, of the wind.
n. marking, sign, indicator. ivolasiga planet venus, the morning “star”.

n. book, letter, marking. indigenous fij ians never developed any system of writing or complex signing. ivola (of the body) birthmark. ivola vakavula monthly magazine. ivola-ni-vuli n. schoolbook. ivolavosa n. dictionary. ivola-ni-baqe bank book. ivolatara n. permit (as for driving). na vale
volavola the office. vunivola tudei permanent secretary (of a ministry, the top civil servant).
ivola ni kawabula the register of fij ian descendants, and official record maintained by the

lands commission. it is said that a fijian is “written down” volai as a member of one clan mataqali, usually the father’s clan. the n.l .c once estimated that ten percent of fijians are not registered. vola, vola v. to write. volai written, “written down”, as a fij ian may be written down as a member of a

clan in the official registry vola ni kawa bula. european missionaries introduced the concept of writing. previously this version of the word vola referred only to markings or an indicator or sign, as in ivolasiga, the planet venus, morning star that indicates the coming of dawn. (appearance of that planet can also indicate the recent setting of the sun.)
v. to surround, as in surrounding fish with a net. vola na qele ni kanace. encircle, surround the school of mullet.
(anglicism) n. writer, reporter, journalist.
(anglicism) n. writing.
(anglicism) n. correspondence, letter-writing.
n . planet venus (“morning star”). this has been the name of a fijian-language weekly newspaper. no other planets are commonly known by name by fijians today.
(anglicism) n. writing, dictionary.

(polyn.) n. boat-shed. volau ni ta waqa ship-building yard. idiom: vakasa tale na waqa ti na kena volau there is a recurrence, as of an old problem ; also an analogy like the prodigal son, returning home.
(anglicism) n. permit, as for driving licence, ticket.
near, nearby, almost. vovoleka sara very near(ly). idiom: voleka na vanua e buli kina na matau. something that is not accessible, as remote as the place
(unknown to early fijians)
near to (place, people, thing). na baravi volekata na tauni. the coast next to the town. o viwa e volekata na yanuyanu ko bau. viwa is next to bau island. volekati suva. next to suva. volekati ira
(many).
closeness (in a physical sense).

(eng.) n. volcano. (none is active in fiji, and none within memory .) the word is rarely seen in print. this is one example of its speliing. voli, volia v. to trade, buy, sell, exchange for things of equal value. volitaka to sell it. volia mai to buy.
the buying of papaya. volivoli shopping. such trading could be done only with people
(solevu), still occasionally carried out. dauvolivoli shopper, buyer.

volitaki weleti the selling of papaya. volivolitaki n. marketing. dauvolivolitaki seller, salesperson, marketer. veivoli commerce, trade. isoqosoqo cokovata ni veivoli consumer cooperative. volivinaka to be a bargain. volica to be a bad buy. voli-rawarawa inexpensive. voli-saulevu expensive, pricey, “dear”.
v. to buy wholesale, then sell at retail (usually farm products). most fij ians who sell in the market and by the side of the road have bought the produce that they are selling at retail.
v. to sell it. dauvolivolitaki n. salesman, sales woman, seller.
n. v., shopping. dau volivolitaki sellers, vendors. dau volivoli buyers, shoppers, consumers.
vakadinau hire-purchase, installment purchase. volivoli is an old place-name in a few
locations; it signifies the collection of fijian goods submitted as tribute in olden days.

paths from place to place were known as sala volivoli. verata and laucala were early centres that had a system of sala volivoli. veivoli n. sales, marketing, as in manidia ni veivoli sales manager. veivoli umauma wholesale. voli, volita v., n. to go around, to follow around noqu voliti viti my going around fiji. e a soko wavoliti viti levu ena waqa o seru. seru circumnavigated fiji in the boat. see wavoki.
around, go about. veilakoyaki voli go around here and there. qalo voli swim about. in some cases the word is not directly translatable.
v. to surround. era sa vakavolivoliti koya they(many) surrounded him.
(eng.) n. volleyball.
v. to dig for wild yams such as tivoli, tikau, rauva out in the bush. idiom: (taveuni) lai volo! get out of the way, get out of here ! yelled at a child who is a nuisance.
n. v. (tongan, samoan fono) formal village meeting in polynesian tradition.
n. shrub, alyxia spp., apocynacea, known for attractive flowers, usually white or cream-coloured.

a pink var. that gives the name to adi pateresia vonokula, roko tui waimaro. her names comes from lau from an ancient marriage into the waimaro super-tribe. vono, vonotaka v. to inlay, to inlay with (perhaps shell, whaletooth into wood such as a warclub). or to
pieces together, as in assembling something. civavonovono (archaic) chiefly breast-plate of
pearlshell with whaletooth, made by tongans, some given by bau to compliant lesser chiefs
power.
target_text: who cooperated with the extension of bauan influence and

source_text: n. giant sea-turtle, usually referring to the green turtle. unlike the smaller hawkbill turtle (taku),
is docile and usually does not defend itself by biting. it is vegetarian, favouring sea grass.
takes place only at very specific sandy locations to which the turtle returns after a long absence. sex ratio of newborn turtles depends on ambient temperature at incubation of eggs; higher

around degrees c. yield females while lower temperatures yield males. the name vonu also refers to the much rarer leatherback, dermochelys coriacea, ika dina, which is occasionally seen in fiji waters, usually at sea rather than right by the shore, for apparently it does not breed here,
at midday, gathering body heat. at other times it dives very deep, to at least thousand feet,
mainly on jellyfish and zooplankton, as they rise and fall in a daily cycle. adults are more

(° f or less), except when they are breeding. the loggerhead turtle, one of the world ’s oldest species, is rarely seen in fiji waters, mostly in the open ocean, lazing on the surface. spending five years at sea as a diver and fisherman, i have seen one only once. weighing pounds or more, it has a huge, broad head with very powerful j aws that can

through heavy clamshells that are almost two inches thick. it is carniverous but never wilfully attacks humans. this tuvonu never breeds in fiji. its main breeding grounds are very far away, mainly along beaches from texas to north caroline, and also at the coast of oman. eggs are laid in the sand, and covered, to hatch after about two months.
a chiefly food, and social groups called gonedau existed to catch turtle with nets (never spears), for their paramount chiefs at verata, bau, cakaudrove. for the chiefs of verata, the people of
island were traditional turtle fishermen. turtle fishermen, and concept of paramount chiefs
of tongan origin. much ceremony attended the fishing for turtles. turtle fishermen were
also naval warriors, such as the lasakau of bau. carving of the portions was a skilled occupation. at bau, the turtle was killed by poking a sasa (coconut leaf midrib) up the turtle ’s nostril.

anyone to witness. cutting up the turtle was a very specialised occupation, carefully done, with the various parts given out to various people. the blood solidifies by clotting. put in a bowl, water accumulates above the clotted blood, and is discarded. the clotted blood is then cut, more or less in cubes, and is cooked with the meat and fat. it is is an extremely rich food.
chiefs ate turtle eggs, often raw, sometimes cooked. other than the eggs, the tui
was specially given the fatty part from inside the back of the turtle, a part called the p ito,
a navel in tongan language. the shell and some leftover parts were reserved for the people of benau, a seafaring people originally from tonga, expert divers, fearless of sharks. as with whales,
fat, so a sauce or coconut cream are required, or the addition of fat. the fat congeals on cooking and turns a dark green colour, extremely rich in taste and can be eaten only in small quanitities.

source_text: of the turtle, and the calling of turtles to the surface has been traditional at village nacamaki, koro island, and at village namuana, vunisea harbour, kadavu island. turtles are now an
species. their main enemy is man, and also sharks. a large tiger shark can swallow a green turtle whole. qoli vonu fish for turtle (using nets). syn. (tonga) f onu.

sp. sailfish , istiophorus sp. or swordfish xiphia gladius. most fijians are familiar with neither. sailfish is sometimes sold in the market but parasites have often made holes in the flesh. waqa boat. vosa n. word(s), talk, language. na vosa vakaviti the fijian language. vosa ena vosa vaka neitou. speak in
language (our dialect). vosa-ni-vanua n. dialect, communalect, local language. daunivosa (or)
spokesperson (as a modern concept). daunivosa n. now adopted at univ. of south pacific

the dictionary . yavu ni vosa root-word, often modified, made transitive, by adding a suffix or prefix. dewa ni vosa alternative form of a verb, such as a transitive form, made by adding a prefix or suffix to the intransitive root-form. yatuvosa n. sentence (grammatical). cai-vosa (vulgar) v., adj . cheeky, too outspoken. a vosa taumada n. foreword (as to a book). vosa ena domo mamasu speak in a pleading voice. vosa veibasai n. antonym, a word with opposite meaning. malanivosa n. part of speech. matua-vosa n. alphabet, script of a language. wa ni vosavosa n. telephone. vosa ni susu n. “first” language, one ’s primary language, spoken in childhood. syn. (west) tata. idiom : vosa vutubati lit., speak s as if suffering from a toothache, i.e., reluctantly , unpleasantly, in a surly manner.

v. to speak. vosa vei koya speak to him/her. vosa taladrodro speak fluently, flowingly. vakalutu vosa v., n. to wisecrack. veisau vosa v. to talk back . na vosataki ni noda vosa the speaking of our (many) language. idiom: vosa tagau dua speak briefly, lit. speak just the short length of one internode (as of bamboo, or yaqona); toward the end of a speech, the speaker may say “tagau dua . . .” meaning “in brief” or “in summary” and summarise his main points.
n . expressions (in language, dialect). vosa-vaka-ibalebale n. proverb.
v. to talk excessively.
n. idioms, verbal expressions. na ivosavosa vakaviti eso some fijian idioms. syn. veivosavosa .
n. verbal expression, idioms, types of speech . syn. ivosavosa.

of refusal, the offered tooth is taken but another tooth given to reciprocate,( dirika to respond

v . to discuss it, talk it over. veivosakitaki discussed.

matua ni pasifika e cake n. branch of austronesian language spoken by the migratory lapita
from , b.c. that is the basis for the later development of fij ian and the polynesian languages. a language first evolved from that in the central pacific, later forming fij ian, samoan and
as separate languages. cognates from that language persist today with many dozens of words
understandable. the word vosa matua was invented by paul geraghty. he has thought it
to create a very great number of modern fijian words, particularly concerning fij ian grammar.
v . to mutter hardly audibly, as when angry.
muri, vosa muria v. to criticise, speak against, as of some decision or command, after it has been announced.

(or) vosanisucu n. first language (that one spoke as a child).

v. to say bad things (about something or someone), to speak ill of . . .

chief justice. this was also a name or quasi-title used by one of the prominent fijian “prophets” (dissidents). vosa-vinaka, vosavinaka-taka v. to express thanks graciously. this is a rather modern expression.
. v., n. to grumble, grumbling, to complain.
. v., n. speaking, talk. vosavosa duadua talking to oneself, as elderly people might do, or a delerious person.

. n. saying, expression, slogan , motto.
v. to talk to oneself. syn. vosavoa duadua. vosavosa wale v. idle talk. dau vosavosa wale n. idle talker, gabbler.
adj ., influential (person), one whose words have effect to make things happen.
v. to propose marriage, usually in a formal sense, this done by elders for the prospective
after they have been given to understand that the proposal will be accepted. such formalities might only apply for high chiefs.
n. patience, forgiveness. dauvosota patient, forgiving.

n. profound, emphatic forgiveness with mutual understanding. vota, vota v. to distribute, share out, often said of a magiti where the food and goods are shared out. (careful judgement is required so that no people feel slighted ; they certainly watch carefully.) e vota

na kabani distributed by the company. votai shared out, distributed (often in ceremony, according to custom). na nomu ivotavota (or) ivota your share. idiom: votavota o tuirara criticism of a person ’s greed, implying that a village steward who
food at a formal distribution of food magiti could be favouring himself or his own people with a large share for himself. votivoti adj . irritating, annoying (a problem, a person, physical abrasion).
n. thorn, spike. votovotoa or veivotoki thorny, prickly (lemon tree, sea urchin etc.) na voto ni
the spike of the stingray.
v. to prick, prickle, pierce, as a thorn or needle might do.

. v. to appear, become visible. e votu mamaca it appears clear(ly). e laurai votu it is clearly visible, apparent. geraghty believes this is the origin of the place-name votua, suggesting a location that has appeared after a lowering of the sea level or a rise in the level of the land. votu . n. vowel. this word is a modern invention of teachers of fijian language, unknown to the general public. similarly, the new fij ian word koso has been invented to mean “consonant”. and tago-na refers to “syllable”.
v. to make apparent, cause to appear, reveal.
. adj . new (singular form). vovou (plural form). ravouvou n. “prince”, young chief who is likely to
a traditional title other than in fij i, though the word is used in children ’stories. vou vei au (anglicism) new to me. idiom: (anglicism) sucu vou born again (among evangelical christians).
. adj . immature, green , of fruit. idiom: bati vou adj ., n. one who likes to eat immature fruit (especially women and children). jocularly, may be said of an older man who prefers younger girls.
(anglicism) v. to renew. na vakavoutaki ni laiseni the renewal of the licence. ivovo n. leftovers, what is left over, as for food after a meal, or timber after construction.
adj . new (plural form).
. v. to be the cause or origin, to be caused, to originate. vu-na . n. origin, cause, reason. yavu house-foundation (a named house-site). yavutu place-name where

(yavusa) was formed. na vu ni noqu biuti suva the reason for (or cause of) my leaving suva. vakavuna v. to cause. vu . n. ancestral spirit of one or more tribes (yavusa), originally a person who founded that social group,
may have become deified in a sense. in some cases the spirit could take the permanent or
form (waqawaqa) of an animal, or reside in a rock or tree. that representation (rock, tree, living creature) would be respected with avoidance or some respectful behaviour, perhaps even gifts, a
branch of leaves, or even a whaletooth in the case of degei. but for the vu there is no supplication for special favour such as success in war. among fijians themselves, the term kalou vu is

synonym for vu. and this is a topic one may not always discuss openly. only some of the vu have names, or the names are forgotten probably because one is usually not encouraged to pronounce the name. by contrast, for kalou vu, temples were built and attended by just a few select people, services with offerings and solicitations, advanced through a priest bete, who would take care
human form. an authority as great as the late solo bulicokocoko referred to the spirit tui
at village nacamaki, koro island, as a kalou vu, yet in the formal chants calling the turtle, the
themselves refer to it as their vu. there has thus come to be some confusion among fijians themselves as to usage of the terms vu and kalou vu.

same ancestral spirit (vu), they are said to be tauvu to each other. for example, in fij ian, era veitauvutaki kina na vanua o noco kei na vanua o lau. in english :- the territory of noco (in rewa province) is tauvu with the territory of lau. they have an

and they are said to be tauvu dredre. formerly such relationships were often between two very

in time this often becomes a relationship between both regions. in early times, for example, the relationship of noco did not extend to all of lau but only to nayau if i remember correctly , and perhaps only to part of nayau. such relationship s can become established after a very high level chiefly marriage between two places. details are often forgotten .
. (anglicism) n. verb. vuwale intransitive verb. this fijian word for “verb” has been invented and
