n. pupil (of the animal or human eye).
n. (anglicism) moving pictures, movies.
v. to wave (the hand, in greeting, farewell, etc.). yaloyalo vei koya . wave to him/her.

n. a common, wild, leafy-vine epiphyte that grows on trees, dumb cane, toga plant, epipremnum pinnatum, araceae, used by europeans as a decorative plant in fiji and elsewhere. the sap is poisonous and even small quantities have a numbing effect on the skin. (more is seriously dangerous.) a pet parrot died from pecking at the leaves next to its cage. yalu dina var. with very large leaves, the
fibre of stem called wa me, twine for weaving baskets (sova). yalu tagane var. with entire leaves, yalu yalewa var. with leaves having holes.

(archaic) n. ancient var. of yaqona, much prized for ceremonial presentations. the root is very large and grows horizontally in the ground, making it easy to harvest. yalu, yaluma v. to reach out the arm to grab, grasp (something). yaluyalu-lala v. to reach out to take, but fail, empty-handed. lala empty . yaluma . n., v . grief, to grieve, anguish, in agony, mental or physical. yaluma . v. (archaic) to retrieve, take, pass over to someone. usually heard as yaluma mai get for me, retrieve for me. yamaraka . v. to smash, knock down, as of a tree in a gale, a house in a hurricane. yamaraka . v. to beat up, give a beating to someone. syn. buturaka.
n. military scout sent ahead to check the situation, spy (wartime). yamata vuni secret spy, an anglicism sometimes seen in translated novels.
. n. tongue. yameleka n. tonsils. dara yame or salayame v. to stick out the tongue. yame ni

n. flame, or “tongue” of fire. idiom: yame-sa "sweet-talk ", liar. yame-na . n. blade (knife, razor, axe). yameyame . v., adj . talkative, voluble, glib , liar, smart and rapid talker. yameyame . n. flames. na yameyame ni buka the flames from the fire. yameca . v. to light up something, with light from a lamp, or flame from fire. yameca . v. to deceive with clever, ingratiating words.

v. to be very unsettled in manner and feelings. yamo . v. to go about at night, feeling one ’s way in the dark. yamo . v. to fight at night in the dark. yamoraka beat up people under cover of darkness. fij ians would often attack from a concealed position, using the element of surprise. yamo, yamoca, yamoraka v. to stroke with the hand, to massage with the hand, to grope for something with the hand. by extension, to “feel” a sexual partner.
v. to toss and turn, as in unsettled sleep.
v. to use one ’s hand(s) to find one’s way around.

n. small patch of submerged reef separate from the main reef. motu is an ancient polynesian word for “island”. idiom: sa vakaua ga na yamotu. said of a powerful person with great strength or great appetite. lit. the reef-patch has waves. yana, yanaka v. to wash off, clean off, especially shellfish, swilled about in water to separate them and remove sand or dirt. yanaka v. to grope around with the hand, feeling for something, perhaps furtively. see yamo, yamoca. yanaraka v. to scatter around as in flapping out a mat to remove crumbs, or dust. also as in spreading out
of yaqona drying out in the sun. yanaraka na lewe ni yaqona ena vata. to spread out the pieces of kava on the drying-platform.
away (from the speaker, following a verb). lako yani go away (from where the speaker is located).
(in the direction of the speaker).
n. small island, now used only as a place-name for small islands, such as the tiny island where the shangri-la fij ian resort is located at the nadroga coast of southwestern viti levu.

n. small island (not normally used for large islands like viti levu). yanu is an ancient protopolynesian word for “small island”. occasionally yanuyanu might appear as the name of an island. there is one such just offshore of lomaloma, vanua balavu island. yaqa, yaqava v. to sneak along crouching, usually to attack. fijians are expert at such attack s, excellent as jungle fighters, exemplified when they were fighting communists in malaysia.

root presented to host by a visitor to his host as a way of formal introduction.

the formal serving of the yaqona (or) the one who serves the cup of yaqona to the chief or honoured guest. rabe, rabeta to drink the next cup following the more important person, as a supportive gesture.
last round of serving, “one for the road”.

bulu yava round of yaqona served after departure of guest, when last comments and memories will be discussed. memories may then be set aside. ititoko, last cup before a person quits the session of yaqona drinking, lit. a walking stick.
n. a common weed, macropiper aduncum (piper timothianum and p. vitiense), piperaceae,

(or) yaro (eng.) n. harrow, as used in farming, usually hauled by a steer, but some powered by diesel engine. siviyara v ., n. to plough, an introduced concept. yara-taka v. to haul, drag behind oneself. by extension, modernly, language teachers use the word yara
a vowel or syllable that is drawn out in pronounciation, like the “o” in the word for cloud.
“o ”. they sometimes indicate this by placing a macron above the vowel. idiom: yara benu ceremonial clapping when a chief has finished his meal. lit., haul away the refuse. (benu garbage, refuse).
v. to keep on delaying, deferring, to prolong.
n. dry dock, place where a boat can be hauled out (yara). formerly referred to a low-lying
of land, place where a boat might be hauled across the land to reach the opposite sea. both vanua levu and kadavu have such places.

n. weapon. tagane vakaiyaragi armed man. na biu yaragi the laying down of arms, the disarmament. originally, this word referred only to indigenous weapons such as the club or spear. yaraneke n., v. to cheat, as at playing cards, such as in the card game tarabu (“trump”). such cheating is commonly done, considered playful and clever. caught, the cheater will usually laugh. syn. eraneke.
. here and there. kacivaka yarayara yani vei ira call out here and there to them. me tevu
ena veico spread it out on the grass. e dau kele yarayara na motoka. the cars park here

(wherever they can). moce yarayara to sleep in various different places. yarayara . to continue doing something. tagi yarayara to keep on crying. vosa yarayara to keep on talking. talanoa yarayara to yarn on and on.
(lau) n. small mat made specially for new born baby.
n. sp. of endemic tree, mainly premna protrusa (formerly p. taitensis), verbenaceae, valued for
of the timber, often used for house-posts, one of the best timbers for that purpose. creamcoloured to yellow flowers, corollas to mm in length, clusters of small (to cm) -seeded globose

near mangrove areas; its corollas are much smaller, only to mm in length. dried heartwood

scent body oil in the lowlands. (there was no body oil in the highlands of viti levu.) syn. (lau) waro. yasa . v. to move about silently, usually secretly, with ulterior purpose (theft, violence, evesdropping). yasa . n., adj . person who remains away from his village. after a long absence, returning even for a brief
requires bringing of gift goods: kerosene, cloth , food. this costly custom keeps many fijians from restoring close contact with their village when they have been long absent.
ni at the side of. e dua na vu ni niu e tiko ena yasa ni vale. there is a coconut palm beside the house.

n. side (physical location), part or section. ena yasana kadua on the other side. e na veiyasa i viti in all parts of fij i. ena yasana vakara on the western side (of viti levu island). tu e yasana to stand aside, stand to one side.
n. province. fij i has fourteen provinces, aside from rotuma. ena yasana o namosi. in namosi province.
n. region. yasayasa vakara western region.
n. lightning. na lidi ni yaseyase the lightning strike.

n. sandalwood, santalum yasi, santalaceae, endemic in the central south seas, vanuatu , fiji and tonga. greatly valued in the orient, which led to an influx of u.s. trading ship s for only ten years in
at wainadoi, some km west of suva. it is not easy to propagate because the young
and becomes a parasite on the roots of nearby trees. (commercially, lemon
are often used.) fijians had never cultivated it and they never used it in body oil before contact
florescence in the axils of leaves, tiny white florets turning pink, then rich red at maturity. fruit round and small, . cm diam., green turning purple to black, with sweet pulp, seen
around august but exist throughout the year. wood of the living tree has little of its fragrant
that develops when it is dried. the tree grows to more than twenty feet, with a trunk up to six

in diameter, the bark distinctively grey. quite another, unrelated species of forest tree is also called yasi, from some similarities. to distinguish this other species, the term used is yasi ni veikau
"sandalwood", or yasiyasi. see below. this counterfeit sandalwood sometimes raises false hopes for windfall money.
n. a forest tree, syzygium spp., myrtaceae, with extremely durable, springy, tough hardwood,
used for house-posts and for bows (for war) by highland fijians. bows were not used by
anything but war (not for sport, not for hunting or fishing). lowlanders were more likely to

made from branches of mangrove tiri. by contrast, in tonga bows were only ever used by chiefs, and only in sport such as shooting at rats. yaso, yasova v. to howl, to yowl (dog, cat, person). tagiyaso v. to howl with grief, tears, crying, typically at funerals. yatayata v., n. trembling, quiver usually of voice, incoherent mumbling as of a delirious speech.

n. liver. idiom: yate lailai coward. yate levu courageous. the liver is considered to be the principal organ of the body and the focal point of one’s courage. (the notion of the heart connected to romance or sentiment is a novel idea borrowed from europeans.) yate dei firm, unyielding in spirit. idiom: na yatemu e vaka na yate mai lagi! lit. your liver is like liver from heaven. this is exaggerated flattery to impress a potential romantic partner.
suits in a deck of cards, the hearts are known as livers yate. kalavo clubs, siveti spades,
diamonds.
n. lung(s).
v. to move slowly, or clumsily, with effort, now a rarely heard word except in the idiom : e na qai
mai na colo: we will get there eventually, our persistence will be rewarded. lit. implication is

a saying of vutia people who travelled up into the interior to trade their clay pots and mats for such items as yaqona. carrying their heavy goods, this was an arduous climb. yato, yatova v. take something by stealth, to snitch, grab. na ka e yatovi rawa mai. what can be grabbed.
. n. row, and by ext. archipelago, as in na yatu lau or na tu-i-cake the lau archipelago. yatu eliu

row, in football the forwards. yatu emuri back row, in football, backfielders. alternative is iyatu, though not for archipelago. yatu . n. tuna, sometimes heard as atu. this may include the skipj ack (yatusewa, with long stripes along belly), albacore (yatu loa, for its black back), yellow fin tuna (yatu ni toga), and much more rarely the
tuna (yatu levu, or dog-tooth tuna). anciently, little distinction was made in fijian languages
any of these species; they did no trolling and hardly ever fished outside
migrate in a clockwise direction from south of kadavu, around fiji. they often follow lines of
temperature (even a degree or two change), and lines of change in the current. december to
are often times of heavy catches but then a month may go by with very little catch at all.

of the lines is a vital matter. yellow fin are found at to feet, with the big-eye somewhat lower. largest catches are often at to feet. in waters less than feet deep, one finds walu, crevally, and sharks, fish that are not valuable for export. over-fishing and oriental competition, some of it illegal, has devastated the industry. yatu, yatuna v. to line up in rows.
n. (anglicism) sentence (of speech, writing). this is of course a modern term, as are all words of grammar.
. n. goods, wealth . vutuniyau rich , wealthy. all fijian goods were perishable, usually food, mats,
sinnet, salt, coconut oil. they represented power or prestige only as they were used, as in
(magiti, etc.) or ceromonial trading (solevu). durable wealth such as whaleteeth were
innovations, only in the s, but only used in ceremonial presentations. presentation wealth
also includes kerosene in liter drums, bales of cloth . vutu ni yau rich, having many possessions.. yaubula n. wealth, precious goods. vakayauyau plentiful, abundant, in great number.

(ang.) treasurer (as of an association, bank, organisation). yau . n. dew. syn. tegu, bite. yau, yauta . v. to bear (carry), take, bring (of many things or people together), go together (of many people). vakayayau burdened, charged with burdens, carrying things around, plentiful, plentifully sa
mai na tamata a lot of people are coming here together in a bunch. e yauti ira mai na lewe ni koro o tukana. tukana is bringing the villagers here.

(eng.) n. yacht. syn. iota. fiji traditional calendar
lived by a lunar calendar with a climax of human activity around february, when they

begin to harvest the cultivated yam harvest. this is a “noble” crop, yams being prestigious at ceremonial food presentations. cultivated yams were also the only basic food that could be stored in their
state and kept for use much later in the year. all other vegetables and fruits were perishable. the
yabaki signified the annual yam harvest and that has been adopted as the word for “year”. first

isevu of some crops were presented to chiefs or priests, and more modernly also the christian church. fijians never counted the years and had no concept of a weekly cycle. there were no dates on their calendar and no names of days, only lunar monthly cycles. they simply followed a seasonal calendar

signalled by the flowering or fruiting of certain plants, or by the sea, with the changes in the available seafood. highlanders of viti levu are of a different culture. they did not cultivate or honour yams to the degree of coastal fijians. and they had no seafood, only aquatic life from the rivers. much of this calendar does not apply to them. all too often when people speak of fijians they are talking only of fij ians around
in history and biology, and the practical matter of what fruits, vegetables or seafoods may be found at the market.
calendar. when we name the equivalents in european months it is only approximate. also, in fact, the tropical climate has inherently variable seasons, not dependent only on the phase of the moon.
